{"DRAMATIS PERSONAE":{"1":{"play":"1.  Priam, king of Troy:","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"2.  Hector,","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"3.  Troilus,","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"4.  Paris.     his Sons.","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"5.  Deiphobus,","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"6.  Helenus,","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"7.  Æneas,     Trojan Commanders.","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"8.  Antenor,","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"9. Calchas, a Trojan priest, taking part with the Greeks.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"10. Pandarus, Uncle to Cressida.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"11. Margarelon, a bastard son of Priam.","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"12. Agamemnon, the Grecian General:","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"13. Menelaus, his brother.","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"14. Achilles,","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"15. Ajax,","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"16. Ulysses,   Grecian Commanders.","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"17. Nestor,","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"18. Diomedes,","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"19. Patroclus,","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"20. Thersites, a deformed and scurrilous Grecian.","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"21. Alexander, servant to Cressida.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"22. Servant to Troilus; Servant to Paris; Servant to Diomedes.","notes":[]}},"ACT 1, SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus and Troilus.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"TROILUS: Call here my varlet; I’ll unarm again.","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"Why should I war without the walls of Troy","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"That find such cruel battle here within?","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"Each Trojan that is master of his heart,","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"Let him to field; Troilus, alas, hath none.","notes":["Troylius] MALONE (ed. 1790): Shakespeare, it appears from various lines in this play, pronounced “Troilus” improperly as a dissylable. [See v.ii.186 and note.]"]},"7":{"play":"PANDARUS: Will this gear ne’er be mended?","notes":["Will this geere, etc.] Steevens (Var. ’78): There is somewhat proverbial in this question, which I likewise meet with in the Interlude of K. Darius, 1565 (sig. E r ): “Will not yet thys gere be amended Nor your synfull actes corrected?”—[“Gear” is, or was, one of those vague, popular words which have very elastic meanings. Here it means matter, affair, business, and the thought is close to that of II Henry VI, iii.1.91-92: “But I will remedy this gear ere long, Or sell my title for a glorious grave.” I have not been able to substantiate Steevens’ guess that “Will this geere ne’re be mended?” is proverbial, but it seems probable.—Ed.—See Misogonus, IV.4, “Alas, Misogonus! wilt thou never leave this gear?” and J. Heywood (woorkes. A dialogue ... of ... proverbes, 1562, sig. H r ), “nay ware that geare.”—B.] 12, 13. to] In addition to. See Franz (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §523). But Abbott (Sh. Grammar, 1872, §187), although he allows the same meaning in some instances, interprets “to” here as meaning “up to, in proportion to, according to.”"]},"8":{"play":"TROILUS: The Greeks are strong and skilful to their strength,","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"Fierce to their skill, and to their fierceness valiant;","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"But I am weaker than a woman’s tear,","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"Tamer than sleep, fonder than ignorance,","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"Less valiant than the virgin in the night,","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"And skilless as unpracticed infancy.","notes":["skilleffe] Johnson (ed. 1765): Mr. Dryden, in his alteration of this play, has taken this speech as it stands, except that he has changed “skill-less” to “artless,” not for the better, because “skill-less” refers to “skill” and “skilful.”"]},"14":{"play":"PANDARUS: Well, I have told you enough of this. For my","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"part, I’ll not meddle nor make no farther. He that will","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"have a cake out of the wheat must tarry the grinding.","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"TROILUS: Have I not tarried?","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"PANDARUS: Ay, the grinding; but you must tarry the","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"bolting.","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"TROILUS: Have I not tarried?","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"PANDARUS: Ay, the bolting; but you must tarry the","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"leavening.","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"TROILUS: Still have I tarried.","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"PANDARUS: Ay, to the leavening; but here’s yet in the word","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"hereafter the kneading, the making of the cake, the","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"heating the oven, and the baking. Nay, you must stay","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"the cooling too, or you may chance burn your lips.","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"TROILUS: Patience herself, what goddess e’er she be,","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"Doth lesser blench at suff’rance than I do.","notes":["lesser] An anonymous writer in Gentleman's Magazine (LX, 1790, 215) finds that the text states the opposite of the intended meaning, which is that Troilus is more resistant to suffering than Patience herself, and suggests therefore \"not less\".—THISLETON (Nolulae Criticae, 1907, 63-71, pp. 20-21) cites a parallel case from Faerie Queene, v.vi.26: \"Ne lesse did Talus suffer sleepe to seaze His eye-lids sad, but watcht continually,\" where we should expect \"no more.\" He is \"inclined to think\" that \"lesser\" is equivalent to \"worse,\" the thought being that Patience is worse than Troilus in blenching. \"Even at the present day 'less' and 'worse' are frequently interchangeable in many cases without the slightest variation in meaning.\"—In both cases, however, a tele-","blench] A word with a confused history. It is derived from OE. blencan, to deceive, but \"the sense-development is involved, from confusion of blenk [the northern form] and blink, of blench and blanch, probably also of the past tense blent with blent past tense of Blend v.1, and other causes\" (N.E.D.). From the original meaning \"to deceive, cheat\" was derived the senses \"to start aside, so as to elude anything ... to flinch, shrink, give way.\" In Sh. the word invariably means to flinch or shrink. Compare below, ii.ii.69-70: \"There can be no euasion To blench from this, and to stand firme by honour.\" The still-current blench in the sense \"turn pale\" is a variant of blanch from F. blanchir."]},"30":{"play":"At Priam’s royal table do I sit","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"And when fair Cressid comes into my thoughts—","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"So, traitor! “When she comes”? When is she","notes":["So ... thence] THISELTON (N.Q., 3 June, 1899, p. 423): [There is a material difference between the F reading and the modern. See Textual Notes.] The modern version makes Troilus accuse himself of treachery towards himself on the ground that it is not really true that Cressida is ever absent from his thoughts; the original makes him accuse himself of treachery towards Cressida, since, on his own admission, she must be at times absent from his thoughts, or it could not be said she came into them. As the latter is, I submit, the more natural position for a youthful lover, like Troilus, to take, I would certainly advocate a reversion to the original text.—PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910): Rowe's change ... is like other modern improvements, not very suitable to the original structure. Troylus is complaining, not that she is never absent from his thoughts, but that she is really thence, bodily away from him, present in his thoughts only. Pandarus interrupts him, while he was going on to say how vividly her presence came in his mind only to torment and tantalize him.—TATLOCK (ed. 1912) and PARADISE (ed. 1927) are exceptional among editors in keeping the Folio reading. PARADISE thus explains: \"Troilus, breaking off his original train of thought, calls himself a traitor for admitting that Cressida is ever absent from his thoughts and says that when she is absent for a moment she instantly returns.\" [The \"then-when\" rhetorical device is conclusive for the authoritative reading.—B.]"]},"33":{"play":"thence?","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"PANDARUS: Well, she looked yesternight fairer than ever","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"I saw her look, or any woman else.","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"TROILUS: I was about to tell thee: when my heart,","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"As wedgèd with a sigh, would rive in twain,","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"Lest Hector or my father should perceive me,","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"I have, as when the sun doth light a-scorn,","notes":["a-scorn] KEATS (note in his copy of Sh.; Spurgeon, Keats's Sh. (1928), p. 149): 'Tis certain that the Commentators have contrived to twist many beautiful passages into common places as they have done with respect to \"a scorn\" which they have hocus pocus'd in[to] \"a storm\" thereby destroying the depth of the simile—taking away all the surrounding Atmosphere of Imagery and leaving a bare and unapt picture. Now however beautiful a comparison may be for a bare aptness—Shakespeare is seldom guilty of one—he could not be content to the \"sun lighting a storm,\" but he gives us Apollo in the act of drawing back his head and forcing a smile upon the world—\"the Sun doth light a-scorn.\"—HALLIWELL (ed. 1864) cites a \"curious note in an anonymous manuscript [MS. additions to Junius],—'Quasi illudens, a particula otiosa more veterum praeposita, as when the sun doth light a-scorn, i.e. hiding himself behind a cloud, and sometimes peeping out for a moment, as it were in mockery: scorning etiam exponitur changing, a Fr. escorner, deformare i.e. vultum mutans in pejus'.\"—PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910): Rowe's change here, also, obscures the lover's thought. Troylus finds his imagination of an unpresent happiness galling. He makes a' pretence only of mocking at his woe with a forced wrinkle of a smile when he thinks Hector or his father is looking at him, and yet is in the dense shadow of his grief all the time. And this gleam only intensifies the gloom, which he compares to the sun lighting up that which it is \"a-scorn\" or averse toward. So decided a metaphor as that of a storm is not in point.—HAZLITT (Sh. Himself, 1912, p. 476): The modern editors print \"light a storm,\" which is evidently nonsense. The figure in the next line should have guarded them against such a deviation from the original copies, as the aspect of the sun slightly veiled in cloud or mist is apt to be not dissimilar from that of the features puckered into a smile. But in fact a superior reading would be \"ascaunt,\" i.e. across or athwart—a word easily misheard or misread as \"a-scorn.\"—[N.E.D. cites only one instance of \"ascorn\" as an old adverbial phrase meaning in scorn or mockery, from the Digby Mysteries (c. 1485).]"]},"40":{"play":"Buried this sigh in wrinkle of a smile;","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"But sorrow that is couched in seeming gladness","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"Is like that mirth fate turns to sudden sadness.","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"PANDARUS: An her hair were not somewhat darker than","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"Helen’s—well, go to—there were no more comparison","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"between the women. But, for my part, she is","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"my kinswoman; I would not, as they term it, praise","notes":["praise it] THISELTON (Notulæ Criticæ, 1907, 63-71, pp. 21-22): The Folio reading is not so absurd as to justify its being ignored. \"Praise it\" may be equivalent to \"pile on praise,\" \"it\" being used indefinitely; and may even be preferred to \"praise her\" as more consistent with the context. The parenthesis \"(:-- they tearme :~:),\" implies an allusion to some proverb about being economical in praising one’s kindred.—PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910) also think that \"a phrase of the day, ‘praise it,’ seems indicated by the parenthesis,\" and that the parenthesis would have no point if we should read \"praise her.\"—[The objection is that Q reads \"her.\" The probable explanation is that the second \"it\" was carried over in the F compositor’s mind from the first.—ED.—Good!—A.—Pandarus will not praise because he does not intend to sell. See IV.i.84-85, and Malone’s note at IV.i.87.—B.]"]},"47":{"play":"her, but I would somebody had heard her talk yesterday,","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"as I did. I will not dispraise your sister Cassandra’s","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"wit, but—","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"TROILUS: O, Pandarus! I tell thee, Pandarus:","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"When I do tell thee there my hopes lie drowned,","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"Reply not in how many fathoms deep","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"They lie indrenched. I tell thee I am mad","notes":["indrench’d] The text does not need THEOBALD’S defense (ed. 1733) against Rowe’s \"intrench’d.\" \"Indrench’d\" has been found ranging from Nashe (1596) to Fenning’s Dictionary (1741), where it is defined \"to soak; to drown.\" See N.E.D. 57-67. Powr’ft ... made it] BRINSLEY NICHOLSON (N.Q., 1 Sept., 1866, pp. 164-65): The metaphorical language here used is drawn from the surgical treatment of an old wound. ... From \"pour’st\" to \"voice\" is one clause ...; and from \"handlest\" to \"ploughman\" is a second and similar one, the former having reference to the pouring in of would-be soothing oils and balms; the second to the handling or healing use of such instruments as the chirurgical knife and the like. If, for \"O that her hand\", we substitute \"her beauteous"]},"54":{"play":"In Cressid’s love. Thou answer’st she is fair;","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"Pourest in the open ulcer of my heart","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"Her eyes, her hair, her cheek, her gait, her voice;","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"Handiest in thy discourse—O—that her hand,","notes":["Handlest ... Hand] MALONE (ed. 1793): “Handlest” is here used metaphorically, with an allusion at the same time to its literal meaning; and the jingle between “hand” and “handlest” is perfectly in our author’s manner. ... We have the same play of words in Titus Andronicus [iii.ii.29]: “O handle not the theme, to talk of hands.”—[Also in II Henry VI, v.i.7: “This hand was made to handle nought but gold.”] O that her Hand] THEOBALD (Sh. Restored, 1726, p. 149): I have always ... suspected this odd Interjection of Rapture,—“O that!” and cannot help thinking it is an inelegant Break, as I am sure it is an ill-sounding one. Without departing very widely from the Letters of the Text, I must own I should like it better, if it stood thus; “... how white her hand!” And then, methinks, by the Repetition of the Term, the Verse immediately following acquires a double Beauty. “In whose Comparison all whites are Ink,” etc.—KNIGHT (ed. 1841): We do not receive this passage as an interjection beginning “O! that her hand”; for what does Troilus desire?—the wish is incomplete. The meaning we conceive to be rather,—in thy discourse thou handlest that hand of hers, in whose comparison, &c. [O what a hand is that!—B.] 59-63. O that ... Plough-man] STAUNTON (ed. 1860) considers “that Troilus is repeating, or pretending to repeat, what Pandarus had said in praise of Cressida’s hand; and the lines should be marked as a quotation.”—LETTOM (in DYCE, ed. 1865): I must express my utter dissent from those critics who take the part [as above] for a quotation from Pandarus. “O, that her hand,” &c. is evidently a lover’s burst, and the whole passage is as remote from the low jar-"]},"58":{"play":"In whose comparison all whites are ink","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"Writing their own reproach, to whose soft seizure","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"The cygnet’s down is harsh, and spirit of sense","notes":["[spirit of Sense] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 3 March, 1729/30): In a former of yours, you objected to “spirit of sense” as unintelligible. I believe, our Poet means by it, that most exquisite sensation which can be communicated by the touch; and I am very apt to think the text sincere, because the Poet, speaking afterwards [III. iii. 112a–b–113] of the powers of the eye, uses the same expression: “Nor doth the eye it selfe That most pure spirit of sence, behold it-selfe Not going from it selfe,” &c.—WARBURTON (ed. 1747): Read, and (“spite of sense”) in a parenthesis. The meaning is, tho’ our senses contradict it never so much, yet the cygnet’s down is not only harsh, when compared to the softness of Cressid’s hand, “but hard as the hand of ploughman.” “Spite,” I suppose, was first corrupted to “sprite,” and from thence arose “spirit.”—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I think this passage more forcible and elegant without an alteration. “In comparison with Cressid’s hand,” says he, “the spirit of sense,” the utmost degree, the most exquisite power of sensibility, which implies a soft hand, ... is hard as the callous and insensible hand of the ploughman. ... It is not proper to make a lover profess to praise his mistress “in spite of sense,” for tho’ he often does it in “spite of the sense” of others, his own senses are subdued to his desires.—CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 115): “And” therefore he [Capell] does pronounce a corruption, and that for “in”; and by—“in spirit of sense,” understands—in estimation of a sense truly purify’d.—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 308): [Hanmer’s emendation is necessary] for I cannot agree to Johnson’s explanation. I admit that the spirit of sense may signify the utmost degree, the most exquisite power of sensibility ... but how the utmost power of sensibility can mean the subject that is to be felt, I cannot well conceive.—The spirit of sense may be used, in poetry, to express the organ by which we feel; as in the third act of this play, Achilles says ... “the eye it selfe, That most pure spirit of sence”. ... But in order to adopt Johnson’s explanation, we must go still further, and suppose that it implies the thing to be felt.—WHITE (Sh.’s Scholar, 1854, pp. 349–50): [None of the commentators has been able to explain the passage, and for a good reason.] There has evidently been a compositor’s transposition; and we should read, “to whose soft seizure And spirit of sense the cygnet’s down is harsh, Hard as the palm of"]},"61":{"play":"Hard as the palm of plowman. This thou tell’st me,","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"As true thou tell’st me, when I say I love her.","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"But, saying thus, instead of oil and balm","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"Thou lay’st in every gash that love hath given me","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"The knife that made it.","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"PANDARUS: I speak no more than truth.","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"TROILUS: Thou dost not speak so much.","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"PANDARUS: Faith, I’ll not meddle in it. Let her be as she","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"is. If she be fair, ’tis the better for her; an she be","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"not, she has the mends in her own hands.","notes":["ha's the mends] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. she may paint and mend 'her complexion.—STEEVENS (Var. '78): I believe it rather means—\"She may make the best of a bad bargain.\" So, in Woman is a Weathercock, 1612 [1.2, Hazlitt-Dodsley, 1875, xi, 24-25]: \"I shall stay here and ha' my head broke, and then I ha' my mends in my own hands.\"'—PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910): Pandarus, as Chaucer and Shakespeare represent him, is full of saws and proverbs. He recurs to an already used proverbial expression, 'meddle nor make' ..., at the beginning of his speech, and falls into a similar one at the end, meaning Make the best of a bad bargain.—[The expression was proverbial, and the sense must be interpreted from the context. N.E.D. seems to be right in applying, for the present instance, the meaning \"remedy.\"]"]},"71":{"play":"TROILUS: Good Pandarus—how now, Pandarus?","notes":["How now Pandarus?] TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., vii, 1932, 72): Troilus ... says, according to modern editors: \"Good Pandarus, how now, Pandarus!\" It is evident that Pandarus made a pretence of going away and leaving Troilus to manage for himself. In consternation Troilus calls after him, \"Good Pandarus!—how now? (i.e., what shall I do now?)—Pandarus!\" Thereupon Pandarus returns—with a great show of reluctance."]},"72":{"play":"PANDARUS: I have had my labor for my travail, ill thought","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"on of her, and ill thought on of you; gone between","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"and between, but small thanks for my labor.","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"TROILUS: What, art thou angry, Pandarus? What, with","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"me?","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"PANDARUS: Because she’s kin to me, therefore she’s not","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"so fair as Helen; an she were not kin to me, she","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"would be as fair o’ Friday as Helen is on Sunday.","notes":["faire on Friday] HUDSON (ed. 1881): That is, as beautiful in her plainest dress as Helen is in her finest. Alluding to the old Christian custom of wearing fasting attire on Friday and festival attire on Sunday.—CRAIG (ed. 1905): Friday, a gloomy day; Sunday, a bright day.—N.E.D. quotes Greene's Groatsworth of Wit (1592): \"The Foxe made a Fridayface, counterfeiting sorrow.\""]},"80":{"play":"But what care I? I care not an she were a blackamoor;","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"’tis all one to me.","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"TROILUS: Say I she is not fair?","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"PANDARUS: I do not care whether you do or no. She’s a","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"fool to stay behind her father. Let her to the Greeks,","notes":["stay behinde her Father] Priam had sent the priest Calchas to consult the oracle of Apollo at Delos. The god commanded him to abandon the Trojan cause and ally himself to the Greeks. See pp. 166–69 and Appendix, pp. 436–38, 444."]},"85":{"play":"and so I’ll tell her the next time I see her. For my","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"part, I’ll meddle nor make no more i’ th’ matter.","notes":["meddle nor make] WRIGHT (1903) gives this as a widespread idiom, most often used in the negative, meaning to interfere in matters which do not concern one.—[There is an old proverb: \"Quoth the young cock, I'll neither meddle"]},"87":{"play":"TROILUS: Pandarus—","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"PANDARUS: Not I.","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"TROILUS: Sweet Pandarus—","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"PANDARUS: Pray you speak no more to me. I will leave","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"all as I found it, and there an end. He exits.","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"[Sound alarum.]","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"TROILUS: Peace, you ungracious clamors! Peace, rude sounds!","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"Fools on both sides! Helen must needs be fair","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"When with your blood you daily paint her thus.","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"I cannot fight upon this argument;","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"It is too starved a subject for my sword.","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"But Pandarus—O gods, how do you plague me!","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"I cannot come to Cressid but by Pandar,","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"And he’s as tetchy to be wooed to woo","notes":["teachy] A dialectical variant of \"tetchy,\" itself of uncertain origin."]},"101":{"play":"As she is stubborn-chaste against all suit.","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"Tell me, Apollo, for thy Daphnes love,","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"What Cressid is, what Pandar, and what we.","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"Her bed is India; there she lies, a pearl.","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"Between our Ilium and where she resides,","notes":["Ilium] CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 115): Meaning—Priam's palace: for so was that palace call'd, according to the marvellous writer [Caxton] whom the poet thought fit to follow in this play; his expressions here, and elsewhere ... shew him to have conceiv'd of this palace—that it stood apart from the city, as our castles do now.—A. A. HILL (M.P., xxx, 1932, 95): In Dares occurs the following: \"Priamus ut Ilium venit, ampliora moenia extruxit ... regiam quoque aedificavit.\" This short passage was expanded by Benoit into a long description of the new building, in the course of which for the first time he uses the word Ilium. What is more important, the word is used here, as well as in all other occurrences of the name in the Roman, in reference to the palace."]},"106":{"play":"Let it be called the wild and wand’ring flood,","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"Ourself the merchant, and this sailing Pandar","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"Our doubtful hope, our convoy, and our bark.","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"[Alarum. Enter Aeneas.]","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"AENEAS: How now, Prince Troilus? Wherefore not afield?","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"TROILUS: Because not there. This woman’s answer sorts,","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"For womanish it is to be from thence.","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"What news, Aeneas, from the field today?","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"AENEAS: That Paris is returnèd home, and hurt.","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"TROILUS: By whom, Aeneas?","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"AENEAS: Troilus, by Menelaus.","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"TROILUS: Let Paris bleed. ’Tis but a scar to scorn;","notes":["[scar to scorne] HUDSON (ed. 1881, reading “scorse”): The use of “scorse” in the sense of “bargain, payment, exchange, equivalent, or offset,” occurs repeatedly in the writers of Shakespeare’s time [i.e. the wound of Paris is a fair offset for the seduction of Helen.] ... The word “scar,” I think, cannot properly mean anything but a cicatrice or mark of a healed wound,—a meaning that is utterly unsuitable here].—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Does this mean “it is but a mere trifle which Paris can afford to treat with contempt,” or “it is but a scar in return for the scorn with which Paris regards Menelaus?”—[Or “it is but a scar to be scorned, a contemptible scar?” a meaning congruent with the general attitude of the play toward the rape of Helen.—ED.—Or “a scar to be regarded with scorn, since it was caused by the horn of Menelaus, and hence is to the glory of Paris”—A.—It is only fitting that Paris should"]},"118":{"play":"Paris is gored with Menelaus’ horn.","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"[Alarum.]","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"AENEAS: Hark what good sport is out of town today!","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"TROILUS: Better at home, if “would I might” were “may.”","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"But to the sport abroad. Are you bound thither?","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"AENEAS: In all swift haste.","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"TROILUS: Come, go we then together.","notes":["togither] Sister Miriam Joseph (Sh.'s Use of the Arts of Language, 1947, p. 53): The exchange of one sound for another in a word ... was called antisthecon.—B. lii.8. as a Vertue fixt] Theobald (ed. 1733, quoting Warburton): What's the Meaning of Hector's Patience being fix'd \"as a Virtue?\" Is not Patience a Virtue? What Room then for the Similitude? The Poet certainly wrote, as I have conjecturally reform'd the Text [see Textual Notes]; and this is giving a fine Character of it, to say, \"His Patience is as stedfast as the Virtue of Patience itself\"; or the Goddess so call'd: for the Poets have always personaliz'd"]},"125":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 1, SCENE 2":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Cressida and her man Alexander.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Who were those went by?","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"ALEXANDER: Queen Hecuba and Helen.","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"CRESSIDA: And whither go they?","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"ALEXANDER: Up to the eastern tower,","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"Whose height commands as subject all the vale,","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"To see the battle. Hector, whose patience","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"Is as a virtue fixed, today was moved.","notes":["virtue fix’d.] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I think the present text may stand. Hector’s patience was as a virtue not variable and accidental, but fixed and constant. If I would alter it, it should be thus,—“Hector, whose patience Is all a virtue fix’d.”—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 492): That is, whose patience appeared incapable of being moved, as, when it really is a virtue, and not a sluggishness of constitution, it generally is.—CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 115-16): [Approves the emendation of Theobald.] “A virtue” is tame and unpoetical: the definite article makes a person, a goddess, of the virtue call’d—patience, and the “patience” of Hector as “fix’d” as that goddess; who, both in painting and statuary, is presented sitting and motionless.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): A “virtue fixed” may, however, mean “the stationary image of a virtue.”—BECKET (Sh.’s Himself Again, 1815, II, 231): “Is as a virtue” means not, as Warburton supposes, “like a virtue.” The poet would insinuate that Hector’s patience (being a virtue) is, as a virtue should be, fixed. There is here an ellipsis, which is very common with Shakespeare.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Is of the nature of a fixed, unshakeable virtue. [I.e. “fixed” is an adjective of “virtue,” and so it is now taken.]—CRAIG (ed. 1905) cites Cymbeline, v.v.174: “He was as calm as virtue.”"]},"9":{"play":"He chid Andromache and struck his armorer;","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"And, like as there were husbandry in war,","notes":["husbandry] Economy, careful management, alluding to the early rising of the prudent man of business. Compare Henry V, iv.i.6-7: “For our bad neighbour makes us early stirrers, Which is both healthful and good husbandry.”"]},"11":{"play":"Before the sun rose he was harnessed light,","notes":["harness[t lyt] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): Why, harnest light? Does the Poet mean, that Hector had put on “light Armour”? Or that he was “sprightly” in his Arms, even before Sun-rise? ... A very slight Alteration makes all these Constructions unnecessary, and gives us the Poet’s Meaning in the properest Terms imaginable. “Before the Sun rose, he was harness-dight,” i.e. compleatly drest, accoutred, in Arms. It is frequent with our Poet, from his Masters Chaucer and Spenser, to say “dight” for “deck’d”, “pight”, for “pitch’d”; &c. [First proposed in Sh. Restored, 1726, p. 188.]—WARBURTON (ed. 1747): “Does the Poet mean,” says Mr. Theobald, “that Hector had put on light armour?” mean! what else could he mean? He goes to fight on foot; and was not that the armour for his purpose? So Fairfax in Tasso’s Jerusalem, “The other Princes put on harness light As footmen use.”—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 492): That is, harness’d ready for action. For it appears from this very play, that the heroes, whether they fought on foot, or in their chariots, were always in heavy armour, and indeed wore the same armour in both cases indifferently, unless they equipped themselves merely as archers, which Hector is never represented to have done. One would imagine Mr. Warburton had","light of foot.] never so much as dipped into the Iliad.—SINGER (ed. 1826): The commentators have all taken “light” here as referring to armour. ... “Light,” however, here has no reference to the “mode” in which Hector was armed, but to the “legerity” or “alacrity” with which he armed himself before sunrise. “Light” and “lightly” are often used for “nimbly,” “quickly,” “readily,” by our old writers.—COLLIER (ed. 1842): Some corruption may be suspected here; for first the connection and meaning are not very intelligible, and next the word “light” in the folio and quartos is spelt lyle; an unusual orthography, “light” being then generally printed as at present. “Lyte” or “lyte” formerly meant “little,” and it is so used by Chaucer and our elder poets. The common explanation of the passage has been, that Hector was lightly armed.—DYCE (Remarks, 1844, p. 146): I see no necessity for quarreling with the reading, “light”: it is evidently used adverbially for “lightly”; and perhaps it may be employed here in a sense which the adverb frequently bears in the works of our earliest writers, viz. “quickly, soon.” ... If “lyte” be an error of the press, qy. is it a misprint for “tyte-tight,” i.e. tightly? [That is, adroitly.]—CRAIG (ed. 1905): “Light” probably means “quickly,” with a quibble on the sense “brightly.”—TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., vii, 1932, 72) thinks that “tyte” is the right word, i.e. tight, meaning “skilfully, competently, securely.” In other words, Hector was well armed. “The letter f, made with a loop, was easily mistaken for an l in the secretary script in which dramatic dialogue was written in Shakspere’s day.” [Compare “smile” for “smite” (v.x.10), “surely” for “surety” (ii.ii.14, 15), and “will” for “witt” (i.iii.88).]"]},"12":{"play":"And to the field goes he, where every flower","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"Did as a prophet weep what it foresaw","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"In Hector’s wrath.","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"CRESSIDA: What was his cause of anger?","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"ALEXANDER: The noise goes, this: there is among the Greeks","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"A lord of Trojan blood, nephew to Hector.","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"They call him Ajax.","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Good; and what of him?","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"ALEXANDER: They say he is a very man per se","notes":["per se] N.E.D.: By or in himself; intrinsically, essentially; without reference to anyone else. [Compare the citation from John Harris, Lexicon Technicum, 1704: “We say a Thing is considered Per se, when ’tis taken in the Abstract, and without Connexion with other things.”] Hence in this instance, an extraordinary man, a man apart from other men.—[V.E.D. (A IV Phrases, 1): The word a was formerly spelt ‘a-per-se, a,’ that is, ‘a by itself makes the word a,’ ... Hence ... the first, chief, most excellent, most distinguished, or"]},"21":{"play":"And stands alone.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"CRESSIDA: So do all men unless they are drunk, sick,","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"or have no legs.","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"ALEXANDER: This man, lady, hath robbed many beasts","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"of their particular additions. He is as valiant as the","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"lion, churlish as the bear, slow as the elephant, a","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"man into whom nature hath so crowded humors","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"that his valor is crushed into folly, his folly sauced","notes":["crusht] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): “Valour crusht into folly” is nonsense; but it is of the first editor's making; who seeing “crouded” go before, concluded that “crusht” (which is of it indeed the consequence) must needs follow. He did not observe that the poet here employs a Kitchen-metaphor, which would have led him to the true reading, “His valour is crusted into folly, his folly sauced with discretion.” Thus is Ajax dished up by the poet. The expression is humourous. His temper is represented as so hot that his valour becomes over-baked, and so is “crusted” or hardened “into folly” or temerity: yet the hardness of his folly is “sauced” or softened with discretion, and so made palatable.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): This emendation does not want ingenuity or humour; but I cannot see so clearly that the present reading is nonsense. To be “crushed into folly,” is to be confused and mingled with folly, so that they make one mass together."]},"29":{"play":"with discretion. There is no man hath a virtue that","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"he hath not a glimpse of, nor any man an attaint","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"but he carries some stain of it. He is melancholy","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"without cause and merry against the hair. He hath","notes":["against the haire] STEEVENS (Var. '78): A phrase equivalent to another now in use—“against the grain.” The French say à contrep oil.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) cites Merry Wives, II.iii.35-36: “if you should fight, you go against the hair of your professions,” and Romeo and Juliet, II.iv.91-92: “Thou desirest me to stop in my tale against the hair.”"]},"33":{"play":"the joints of everything, but everything so out of","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"joint that he is a gouty Briareus, many hands and","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"no use, or purblind Argus, all eyes and no sight.","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"CRESSIDA: But how should this man that makes me","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"smile make Hector angry?","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"ALEXANDER: They say he yesterday coped Hector in the","notes":["cop’d] N.E.D.: From OF. colp, cop, coup blow. Hence come to blows with, engage, encounter, fight with."]},"39":{"play":"battle and struck him down, the disdain and","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"shame whereof hath ever since kept Hector fasting","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"and waking.","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus.]","notes":["Enter Pandarus] Mackenzie (Women in Sh.’s Plays, 1924, p. 189): The clipped flat prose of the dialogue has a curious cheapness about it that is not likely to be unintentional. “... Cressida says nothing in it at which one need feel offended, and yet, in the long run, we are uncomfortably aware of the ironic difference between her and Troilus. It may be, perhaps, that although she snubs her uncle, we are left with the impression that it is out of mere contrariness rather than from any objection to what he is or says, and that the two are familiar associates.—Snider (System of Sh.’s Dramas, 1877, II, 200): The adroit Cressida listens to the encomiums bestowed by her uncle with a complete penetration of their object, parrying his questions, tormenting him with a feigned opposition, uttering words of detraction against Troilus. ... Her character comes out plain in this interview; she is shrewd, witty, and wanton; no person of the caliber of Pandarus can touch the depths of her mind—the cool understanding effectually controls the emotions."]},"43":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Who comes here?","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"ALEXANDER: Madam, your Uncle Pandarus.","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Hector’s a gallant man.","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"ALEXANDER: As may be in the world, lady.","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"PANDARUS: What’s that? What’s that?","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Good morrow, Uncle Pandarus.","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"PANDARUS: Good morrow, Cousin Cressid. What do you","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"talk of?— Good morrow, Alexander.—How do you,","notes":["Alexander] Pope (ed. 1723) solemnly declared this to be an error, because in Homer Alexander is the other name of Paris. But as Theobald (ed. 1733) pointed out, “Why might not Alexander be the Name of Cressid’s Man? Paris had no Patent, I suppose, for engrossing it to himself.”"]},"51":{"play":"cousin? When were you at Ilium?","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"CRESSIDA: This morning, uncle.","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"PANDARUS: What were you talking of when I came?","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"Was Hector armed and gone ere you came to","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"Ilium? Helen was not up, was she?","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Hector was gone, but Helen was not up.","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"PANDARUS: E’en so. Hector was stirring early.","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"CRESSIDA: That were we talking of, and of his anger.","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"PANDARUS: Was he angry?","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"CRESSIDA: So he says here.","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"PANDARUS: True, he was so. I know the cause too. He’ll","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"lay about him today, I can tell them that; and","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"there’s Troilus will not come far behind him. Let","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"them take heed of Troilus, I can tell them that too.","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"CRESSIDA: What, is he angry too?","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"PANDARUS: Who, Troilus? Troilus is the better man of","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"the two.","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O Jupiter, there’s no comparison.","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"PANDARUS: What, not between Troilus and Hector? Do","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"you know a man if you see him?","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Ay, if I ever saw him before and knew him.","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"PANDARUS: Well, I say Troilus is Troilus.","notes":["Troylus is Troylus] H. ISAAC (Sh. Jbch., XIX, 1884, 239) parallels this mode of expressing admiration with Sonnet 84: “which can say more Than this rich praise, that you alone are you?”; Romeo and Juliet, II.ii.39: “Thou art thyself, though not a Montague”; and Antony and Cleopatra, III.ii.13: “Would you praise Caesar, say ‘Caesar’: go no further.”"]},"73":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Then you say as I say, for I am sure he is not","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"Hector.","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"PANDARUS: No, nor Hector is not Troilus in some degrees.","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"CRESSIDA: ’Tis just to each of them; he is himself.","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"PANDARUS: Himself? Alas, poor Troilus, I would he were.","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"CRESSIDA: So he is.","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"PANDARUS: Condition I had gone barefoot to India.","notes":["Condition] WHITE (ed. 1883): On that condition; that is, if Troilus were"]},"80":{"play":"CRESSIDA: He is not Hector.","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"PANDARUS: Himself? No, he’s not himself. Would he","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"were himself! Well, the gods are above. Time must","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"friend or end. Well, Troilus, well, I would my heart","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"were in her body. No, Hector is not a better man","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"than Troilus.","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Excuse me.","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"PANDARUS: He is elder.","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Pardon me, pardon me.","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"PANDARUS: Th’ others not come to ’t. You shall tell me","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"another tale when th’ other’s come to ’t. Hector","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"shall not have his wit this year.","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"CRESSIDA: He shall not need it, if he have his own.","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"PANDARUS: Nor his qualities.","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"CRESSIDA: No matter.","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"PANDARUS: Nor his beauty.","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"CRESSIDA: ’Twould not become him. His own ’s better.","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"PANDARUS: You have no judgment, niece. Helen herself","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"swore th’ other day that Troilus, for a brown favor—","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"for so ’tis, I must confess—not brown neither—","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"CRESSIDA: No, but brown.","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"PANDARUS: Faith, to say truth, brown and not brown.","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"CRESSIDA: To say the truth, true and not true.","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"PANDARUS: She praised his complexion above Paris’.","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Why, Paris hath color enough.","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"PANDARUS: So he has.","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Then Troilus should have too much. If she","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"praised him above, his complexion is higher than","notes":["higher] More vivid, intense. N.E.D. quotes from Cooper's Thesaurus (1565-73): \"Ardentissimus color ... a very high or glisteryng redde colour.\" The explanation would scarcely be necessary, had not Craig (ed. 1905) defined \"higher\" as \"more intensely dark.\" The word \"flaming\" in the next line shows that \"glisteryng redde\" is the complexion meant."]},"108":{"play":"his. He having color enough, and the other higher,","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"is too flaming a praise for a good complexion. I","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"had as lief Helen’s golden tongue had commended","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"Troilus for a copper nose.","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"PANDARUS: I swear to you, I think Helen loves him better","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"than Paris.","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Then she’s a merry Greek indeed.","notes":["merry Greeke] A common slang phrase in Sh.'s time for a merry fellow, or person of loose habits. Under grig (sb. 5) N.E.D. has this note: \"The relation of merry grig [of much the same meaning] to the earlier recorded synonym merry Greek is obscure; no doubt one of them must have been a perversion of the other, but the difference of recorded date is too slight to afford ground for saying that merry Greek is the original. The probability seems indeed rather on the other side, as it is not easy to explain why Greek should be used in this sense.\"","merry Greeke] A common slang phrase in Sh.’s time for a merry fellow, or person of loose habits. Under grig (sb. 5) N.E.D. has this note: “The relation of merry grig [of much the same meaning] to the earlier recorded synonym merry Greek is obscure; no doubt one of them must have been a perversion of the other, but the difference of recorded date is too slight to afford ground for saying that merry Greek is the original. The probability seems indeed rather on the other side, as it is not easy to explain why Greek should be used in this sense.”"]},"115":{"play":"PANDARUS: Nay, I am sure she does. She came to him","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"th’ other day into the compassed window—and","notes":["compaft window] Compass-window, or compassed-window, a semicircular bay-window. A \"compassed\" line or arch meant formerly a rounded one, as though drawn by a pair of compasses (N.E.D.).","compact window] Compass-window, or compassed-window, a semicircular bay-window. A “compassed” line or arch meant formerly a rounded one, as though drawn by a pair of compasses (N.E.D.)."]},"117":{"play":"you know he has not past three or four hairs on his","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"chin—","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Indeed, a tapster’s arithmetic may soon bring","notes":["Tapsters Arithmetique] This was a favorite joke. DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) cites Love’s Labor’s Lost, I.ii.40-41: “I am ill at reckoning; it fitteth the spirit of a tapster.” And see below, III.iii.263-65: “ruminates like an hostess, that hath no Arithmatique but her braine to set downe her reckoning.”"]},"120":{"play":"his particulars therein to a total.","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"PANDARUS: Why, he is very young, and yet will he within","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"three pound lift as much as his brother Hector.","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Is he so young a man and so old a lifter?","notes":["old] N.E.D. (Old 1, sb): In various colloq. and slang phrases: ... a person who has become knowing through experience, spec. an experienced thief.—B. lifter] STEEVENS (Var. ’73): The word “lifter” is used for a “thief,” by Green[e], in his Art of Coney-catching, printed 1591: on this the humour of the passage may be supposed to turn. We still call a person who robs the shops, a “shop-lifter.”"]},"124":{"play":"PANDARUS: But to prove to you that Helen loves him: she","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"came and puts me her white hand to his cloven","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"chin—","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Juno have mercy! How came it cloven?","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"PANDARUS: Why, you know ’tis dimpled. I think his","notes":[]},"129":{"play":"smiling becomes him better than any man in all","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"Phrygia.","notes":[]},"131":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O, he smiles valiantly.","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"PANDARUS: Does he not?","notes":[]},"133":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O yes, an ’twere a cloud in autumn.","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"PANDARUS: Why, go to, then. But to prove to you that","notes":[]},"135":{"play":"Helen loves Troilus—","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Troilus will stand to the proof if you’ll","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"prove it so.","notes":[]},"138":{"play":"PANDARUS: Troilus? Why, he esteems her no more than","notes":[]},"139":{"play":"I esteem an addle egg.","notes":[]},"140":{"play":"CRESSIDA: If you love an addle egg as well as you love","notes":[]},"141":{"play":"an idle head, you would eat chickens i’ th’ shell.","notes":[]},"142":{"play":"PANDARUS: I cannot choose but laugh to think how she","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"tickled his chin. Indeed, she has a marvellous","notes":[]},"144":{"play":"white hand, I must needs confess—","notes":[]},"145":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Without the rack.","notes":[]},"146":{"play":"PANDARUS: And she takes upon her to spy a white hair","notes":[]},"147":{"play":"on his chin.","notes":[]},"148":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Alas, poor chin! Many a wart is richer.","notes":[]},"149":{"play":"PANDARUS: But there was such laughing! Queen Hecuba","notes":["maruel’s] Dyce (ed. 1865) compares Hamlet, II.i.3: “You shall do marvellous wisely,” where Q2 has “meruies” and F1 “maruels.”"]},"150":{"play":"laughed that her eyes ran o’er—","notes":[]},"151":{"play":"CRESSIDA: With millstones.","notes":["With Milftones] The expression was proverbial, meaning apparently, as Schmidt (1875) says, not to weep at all, to be as unfeeling as a millstone. It occurs twice in Richard III, e.g. I.iii.354, where Richard says to the First Murderer, “Your eyes drop millstones, when fools’ eyes drop tears,” and elsewhere in the literature of the time. Here it is used idly, for no other reason than the proverbial association."]},"152":{"play":"PANDARUS: And Cassandra laughed—","notes":[]},"153":{"play":"CRESSIDA: But there was a more temperate fire under","notes":[]},"154":{"play":"the pot of her eyes. Did her eyes run o’er too?","notes":[]},"155":{"play":"PANDARUS: And Hector laughed.","notes":[]},"156":{"play":"CRESSIDA: At what was all this laughing?","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"PANDARUS: Marry, at the white hair that Helen spied on","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"Troilus’ chin.","notes":[]},"159":{"play":"CRESSIDA: An ’t had been a green hair, I should have","notes":[]},"160":{"play":"laughed too.","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"PANDARUS: They laughed not so much at the hair as at","notes":[]},"162":{"play":"his pretty answer.","notes":[]},"163":{"play":"CRESSIDA: What was his answer?","notes":[]},"164":{"play":"PANDARUS: Quoth she “Here’s but two-and-fifty hairs","notes":["two and fifty] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): The Copyists must have err’d here in the Number; and I have ventur’d to substitute “one and fifty,\" I think, with some Certainty. How else can the Number make out Priam, and his fifty Sons?—KNIGHT (ed. 1841): This is an exactness which Priam and his chroniclers would equally have spurned. The Margarelon of the romance-writers, who makes his appearance in Act V, is one of the additions to the old classical family. We leave the text as we find it.—DYCE (ed. 1857): [Believes that “two and fifty\" is an error “which probably arose from the Ms. having had the numbers in figures.”] It is not to be doubted that Shakespeare knew the exact number of sons which from the earliest times had been assigned to Priam, ... and it is utterly improbable that here he would needlessly deviate from the Homeric tradition. [Knight is wrong in thinking that Margarelon counted as an extra son.] ... Margarelon is not to be considered as an addition to the family ...: the romance-writers merely bestowed that name on one of the fifty sons whom antiquity had left unnamed.—THISLETON (Notulæ Criticæ, 1907, 63-71, p. 22) suggests that Helen playfully counted the forked hair as two.—PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910): According to Caxton’s account, to make up the tally of Priam’s sons to fifty, we must not be too particular as to gender, and, strictly speaking, Caxton gives him fifty children: first are named “fyve sones and thre doughters of grete beaute”; then it is added that “Virgile recouneth” that he had two other sonnes by hys wyf making ten children; finally, it is said, “yet above these chyldren here to fore rehersid Kyng Pryant had threttty bastard sones by dyverce women that were valyaunt Knyghtes noble and hardy.” ... Lydgate pointedly contradicts such accounts of the number of Priam’s sons, declaring that he had “ten sones and no moe.” [This is wrong; Lydgate likewise gives Priam “thritty sonys. ... That callyd wern his sonys natural.” See Bergen’s ed., E.E.T.S., Bk. II, lines 376 ff.—No one has as yet offered a generally accepted solution of the fifty-one sons. DYCE is right in saying that Sh. must have known the tradition to be fifty, but his theory of a copyist’s error is weak, in view of the repetition of two and fifty. There is, however, a good deal in Thiselton’s suggestion: Helen counted fifty-two hairs, but one of them turned out to be forked and was counted as two. Inasmuch as the whole joke leads up to the forked hair, this is not improbable.—ED.]"]},"165":{"play":"on your chin, and one of them is white.”","notes":[]},"166":{"play":"CRESSIDA: This is her question.","notes":[]},"167":{"play":"PANDARUS: That’s true, make no question of that. “Two-and-fifty","notes":[]},"168":{"play":"hairs,” quoth he, “and one white. That","notes":[]},"169":{"play":"white hair is my father, and all the rest are his","notes":[]},"170":{"play":"sons.” “Jupiter!” quoth she, “which of these hairs","notes":[]},"171":{"play":"is Paris, my husband?” “The forked one,” quoth he.","notes":[]},"172":{"play":"“Pluck ’t out, and give it him.” But there was such","notes":[]},"173":{"play":"laughing, and Helen so blushed, and Paris so","notes":[]},"174":{"play":"chafed, and all the rest so laughed that it passed.","notes":["it past] HANMER (ed. 1744, note on Merry Wives, II. i. 270-71, “the women have so cried and shrieked at it, that it passed”): “It passed” and “This passes” was a way of speaking customary heretofore to signify the excess or extraordinary degree of any thing. The sentence compleated would be, “It past” or “This passes all expression,” or perhaps (according to a vulgar phrase still in use) “It past” or “This passes all things.” The participle of the same verb is still in common use and in the same sense: “passing well, passing strange,” &c. 177-78. Harke ... Illium] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): This Conduct of the Poet, in making Pandarus decypher the Warriors as they pass, seems an Imitation of Homer's Helen on the Walls, where she shews the Greeks to Priam. This Incident was borrow’d by Euripides, in his Phœnissæ; and again copied by Statius, in the 9th Book of his Thebais, where he makes Phorbas shew to Antigone the Chiefs of the Theban Army."]},"175":{"play":"CRESSIDA: So let it now, for it has been a great while","notes":[]},"176":{"play":"going by.","notes":[]},"177":{"play":"PANDARUS: Well, cousin, I told you a thing yesterday.","notes":[]},"178":{"play":"Think on ’t.","notes":[]},"179":{"play":"CRESSIDA: So I do.","notes":[]},"180":{"play":"PANDARUS: I’ll be sworn ’tis true. He will weep you an","notes":[]},"181":{"play":"’twere a man born in April.","notes":[]},"182":{"play":"CRESSIDA: And I’ll spring up in his tears an ’twere a nettle","notes":[]},"183":{"play":"against May.   Sound a retreat.","notes":[]},"184":{"play":"PANDARUS: Hark, they are coming from the field. Shall","notes":[]},"185":{"play":"we stand up here and see them as they pass toward","notes":[]},"186":{"play":"Ilium? Good niece, do, sweet niece Cressida.","notes":[]},"187":{"play":"CRESSIDA: At your pleasure.","notes":[]},"188":{"play":"PANDARUS: Here, here, here’s an excellent place. Here","notes":["an excellent place] DELIUS (ed. 1856): Pandarus and Cressida go up to an elevated point, in the Shakespearian theater to the balcony at the back of the stage, and from there watch ... the homecoming Trojans pass over the stage, without themselves being seen.—[They hardly went to the balcony or"]},"189":{"play":"we may see most bravely. I’ll tell you them all by","notes":[]},"190":{"play":"their names as they pass by, but mark Troilus","notes":[]},"191":{"play":"above the rest.","notes":[]},"192":{"play":"They cross the stage; Alexander exits.","notes":[]},"193":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Speak not so loud.","notes":[]},"194":{"play":"[Enter Aeneas and crosses the stage.]","notes":[]},"195":{"play":"PANDARUS: That’s Aeneas. Is not that a brave man? He’s","notes":[]},"196":{"play":"one of the flowers of Troy, I can tell you. But mark","notes":[]},"197":{"play":"Troilus; you shall see anon.","notes":[]},"198":{"play":"[Enter Antenor and crosses the stage.]","notes":["Enter Antenor] LAWRENCE (Sh.’s Workshop, 1928, p. 43): The fact that Antenor ... comes on the stage, in all, three times, and on no occasion condescends to open his mouth, is fairly good proof that, whatever his earlier office, in the later version of the play, he had absolutely no place. To admit as much, however, is likewise to concede that Pandarus’s description of him in the first act must also have gone by the board; otherwise we have the absurdity of a character distinguished as “a shrewd wit” and demonstrating his expertness of tongue by his silence. If Antenor really remained, he must have been the enviable possessor of a most sagacious nod, a quality that made him lineal ancestor of Burleigh in The Critic. But, so far from being able to take that"]},"199":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Who’s that?","notes":[]},"200":{"play":"PANDARUS: That’s Antenor. He has a shrewd wit, I can","notes":[]},"201":{"play":"tell you, and he’s a man good enough. He’s one o’","notes":[]},"202":{"play":"th’ soundest judgments in Troy whosoever; and a","notes":[]},"203":{"play":"proper man of person. When comes Troilus? I’ll","notes":[]},"204":{"play":"show you Troilus anon. If he see me, you shall see","notes":[]},"205":{"play":"him nod at me.","notes":[]},"206":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Will he give you the nod?","notes":["Youl Deighton (ed. 1906): After the word \"nod\" ... I believe we should insert \"Ay,\" as the commencement of Pandarus's answer. The pun on \"noddy\" will then be complete, as in The Two Gentlemen of Verona, I.i.106 ff.: \"Pro. But what said she? Speed [first nodding]. Ay. Pro. Nod—Ay—why, that's noddy.\" 196-98. Warburton (ed. 1747): To \"give one the nod,\" was a phrase signifying to give one a mark of folly. The reply turns upon this sense alluding to the expression \"give,\" and should be read thus, \"The mich shall have more.\" i.e. \"much.\" He that has much folly already shall then have more. This was a proverbial speech, implying that benefits fall upon the rich. [Warburton's emendation has had no favor. In support of it, however, a proverb listed by Thomas Fuller, Gnomologia, 1733, might be adduced: \"Much would have more; but often meets with less.\"—Johnson (ed. 1765): I wonder why the commentator should think any emendation necessary, since his own sense is fully expressed by the present reading. ... That \"to give the nod\" signifies to \"set a mark of folly,\" I do not know; the allusion is to the word \"noddy,\" which, as now, did, in our author's time, and long before, signify, \"a silly fellow,\" and may, by its etymology, signify likewise \"full of nods.\" Cressid means, that \"a Noddy shall have more\" nods. Of such remarks as these is a comment to consist?—Steevens (Var. '78): To \"give the nod\" was, I believe, a term in the game at cards called Noddy. This game is perpetually alluded to in the old comedies.—Capell (Notes, 1780, II, 116): To \"give the nod\" ... was never any phrase, as has been asserted, for \"to give one a mark of folly\"; 'tis a meer extempore archness of that speaker, and a laying-out for that proverbial expression which follows ..., importing—being a noddy now, you shall be more noddy then.—Singer (ed. 1826): Cressid means to call Pandarus a \"noddy,\" and says he shall by more nods be made more significantly \"a fool.\""]},"207":{"play":"PANDARUS: You shall see.","notes":[]},"208":{"play":"CRESSIDA: If he do, the rich shall have more.","notes":[]},"209":{"play":"[Enter Hector and crosses the stage.]","notes":[]},"210":{"play":"PANDARUS: That’s Hector, that, that, look you, that.","notes":[]},"211":{"play":"There’s a fellow!—Go thy way, Hector!—There’s a","notes":[]},"212":{"play":"brave man, niece. O brave Hector! Look how he","notes":["braue] CRAIG (ed. 1905) defines as “handsome.” But that is too precise; the word was used, as N.E.D. says, “loosely, as a general epithet of admiration.” Perhaps the nearest modern equivalent is “fine.” Compare As You Like It, III.iv.36–38: “O, that’s a brave man! he writes brave verses, speaks brave words, swears brave oaths and breaks them bravely.”"]},"213":{"play":"looks. There’s a countenance! Is ’t not a brave man?","notes":[]},"214":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O, a brave man!","notes":[]},"215":{"play":"PANDARUS: Is he not? It does a man’s heart good. Look","notes":[]},"216":{"play":"you what hacks are on his helmet. Look you yonder,","notes":[]},"217":{"play":"do you see? Look you there. There’s no jesting;","notes":[]},"218":{"play":"there’s laying on, take ’t off who will, as they say.","notes":[]},"219":{"play":"There be hacks.","notes":[]},"220":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Be those with swords?","notes":[]},"221":{"play":"PANDARUS: Swords, anything, he cares not. An the devil","notes":[]},"222":{"play":"come to him, it’s all one. By God’s lid, it does one’s","notes":[]},"223":{"play":"heart good.","notes":[]},"224":{"play":"[Enter Paris and crosses the stage.]","notes":[]},"225":{"play":"Yonder comes Paris, yonder comes Paris! Look you","notes":[]},"226":{"play":"yonder, niece. Is ’t not a gallant man too? Is ’t not?","notes":[]},"227":{"play":"Why, this is brave now. Who said he came hurt","notes":[]},"228":{"play":"home today? He’s not hurt. Why, this will do","notes":[]},"229":{"play":"Helen’s heart good now, ha? Would I could see","notes":[]},"230":{"play":"Troilus now! You shall see Troilus anon.","notes":[]},"231":{"play":"[Enter Helenus and crosses the stage.]","notes":[]},"232":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Who’s that?","notes":[]},"233":{"play":"PANDARUS: That’s Helenus. I marvel where Troilus is.","notes":[]},"234":{"play":"That’s Helenus. I think he went not forth today.","notes":[]},"235":{"play":"That’s Helenus.","notes":[]},"236":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Can Helenus fight, uncle?","notes":[]},"237":{"play":"PANDARUS: Helenus? No. Yes, he’ll fight indifferent","notes":[]},"238":{"play":"well. I marvel where Troilus is. Hark, do you not","notes":[]},"239":{"play":"hear the people cry “Troilus”? Helenus is a priest.","notes":[]},"240":{"play":"[Enter Troilus and crosses the stage.]","notes":[]},"241":{"play":"CRESSIDA: What sneaking fellow comes yonder?","notes":[]},"242":{"play":"PANDARUS: Where? Yonder? That’s Deiphobus. ’Tis","notes":[]},"243":{"play":"Troilus! There’s a man, niece. Hem! Brave Troilus,","notes":[]},"244":{"play":"the prince of chivalry!","notes":[]},"245":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Peace, for shame, peace.","notes":[]},"246":{"play":"PANDARUS: Mark him. Note him. O brave Troilus! Look","notes":[]},"247":{"play":"well upon him, niece. Look you how his sword is","notes":[]},"248":{"play":"bloodied and his helm more hacked than Hector’s,","notes":[]},"249":{"play":"and how he looks, and how he goes. O admirable","notes":[]},"250":{"play":"youth! He never saw three and twenty.—Go thy","notes":[]},"251":{"play":"way, Troilus; go thy way!—Had I a sister were a","notes":[]},"252":{"play":"Grace, or a daughter a goddess, he should take his","notes":[]},"253":{"play":"choice. O admirable man! Paris? Paris is dirt to","notes":[]},"254":{"play":"him; and I warrant Helen, to change, would give","notes":[]},"255":{"play":"an eye to boot.","notes":[]},"256":{"play":"[Enter Common Soldiers and cross the stage.]","notes":[]},"257":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Here comes more.","notes":[]},"258":{"play":"PANDARUS: Asses, fools, dolts, chaff and bran, chaff and","notes":[]},"259":{"play":"bran, porridge after meat. I could live and die in","notes":[]},"260":{"play":"the eyes of Troilus. Ne’er look, ne’er look; the","notes":[]},"261":{"play":"eagles are gone. Crows and daws, crows and daws!","notes":[]},"262":{"play":"I had rather be such a man as Troilus than","notes":[]},"263":{"play":"Agamemnon and all Greece.","notes":[]},"264":{"play":"CRESSIDA: There is amongst the Greeks Achilles, a better","notes":[]},"265":{"play":"man than Troilus.","notes":[]},"266":{"play":"PANDARUS: Achilles? A drayman, a porter, a very camel!","notes":[]},"267":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Well, well.","notes":[]},"268":{"play":"PANDARUS: “Well, well”? Why, have you any discretion?","notes":[]},"269":{"play":"Have you any eyes? Do you know what a man is? Is","notes":[]},"270":{"play":"not birth, beauty, good shape, discourse, manhood,","notes":[]},"271":{"play":"learning, gentleness, virtue, youth, liberality and","notes":[]},"272":{"play":"such-like the spice and salt that season a man?","notes":[]},"273":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Ay, a minced man; and then to be baked with","notes":["mince'd] SCHMIDT (1875): Affected.—[Certainly affectation is implied in the forms \"mincing,\" \"mincingly\" and even in \"to mince.\" Compare Lear, IV.vii.178-200: \"yond simpering dame ... That minces virtue.\" But I am not persuaded that such meaning would carry over into the passive form. Cressida's mind leaps at once from spice and salt to mince pies. At best her joke is pretty labored.—Ed.—SISTER MIRIAM JOSEPH (Sh.'s Use of the Arts of Language, 1947, p. 115): Cressida recognizes her uncle's description as a figure of division and thereupon with quick wit caps his speech with the pert, completely apt pronouncement that Troilus is \"a minced man.\" The naturalness and spontaneity of such comment, while it marks Shakespeare's awareness of the figure he is using, contrasts with the more obvious manner in which his contemporaries introduce references to the precepts of art.—B.]"]},"274":{"play":"no date in the pie, for then the man’s date is out.","notes":["the mans dates out] CRAIG (ed. 1905): The man is past his best. A legal term.—[But need it be more than a turn of the common phrase \"out of date\"?]"]},"275":{"play":"PANDARUS: You are such a woman a man knows not at","notes":[]},"276":{"play":"what ward you lie.","notes":[]},"277":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Upon my back to defend my belly, upon my","notes":[]},"278":{"play":"wit to defend my wiles, upon my secrecy to defend","notes":["wiles] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): So read both the copies; yet perhaps the authour wrote, “Upon my wit, to defend my will.” The terms “wit” and “will” were, in the language of that time, put often in opposition.—MALONE (ed. 1790): So, in The Rape of Lucrece [line 1299]: “What wit sets down is blotted straight with will.” Yet I think the old copy right."]},"279":{"play":"mine honesty, my mask to defend my beauty, and","notes":[]},"280":{"play":"you to defend all these; and at all these wards I lie,","notes":["ward] SCHMIDT (1875): Guard made in fencing, posture of defense.—[The play is upon “watch and ward.” N.E.D. (watch, sb., II, 7): The action of ‘watching and warding’ ...; the performance of the duty of a watchman or sentinel, esp. as a feudal obligation. Now only (as often in earlier times) a rhetorical and more emphatic synonym of watch in sense 6; also fig.—B.]"]},"281":{"play":"at a thousand watches.","notes":[]},"282":{"play":"PANDARUS: Say one of your watches.","notes":[]},"283":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Nay, I’ll watch you for that, and that’s one of","notes":[]},"284":{"play":"the chiefest of them too. If I cannot ward what I","notes":[]},"285":{"play":"would not have hit, I can watch you for telling how","notes":[]},"286":{"play":"I took the blow—unless it swell past hiding, and","notes":[]},"287":{"play":"then it’s past watching.","notes":[]},"288":{"play":"PANDARUS: You are such another!","notes":["such another woman] I.e. such a rascal, such a devil of a woman.","such another] DELIUS (ed. 1856) suggests that Pandarus was about to add “woman” but was interrupted by the Boy. The supposition is not necessary; “such another” was a self-contained idiom."]},"289":{"play":"[Enter Troilus’s Boy.]","notes":[]},"290":{"play":"BOY: Sir, my lord would instantly speak with you.","notes":[]},"291":{"play":"PANDARUS: Where?","notes":[]},"292":{"play":"BOY: At your own house. There he unarms him.","notes":[]},"293":{"play":"PANDARUS: Good boy, tell him I come.    Boy exits.","notes":[]},"294":{"play":"I doubt he be hurt.—Fare you well, good niece.","notes":[]},"295":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Adieu, uncle.","notes":[]},"296":{"play":"PANDARUS: I will be with you, niece, by and by.","notes":[]},"297":{"play":"CRESSIDA: To bring, uncle?","notes":["To bring] DYCE (Remarks, 1844, pp. 149-50): The modern editors appear not to have understood this passage ...; and, in opposition to the old copies, erroneously put a break, as Mr. Collier does, at the end of Cressida’s speech, supposing it to be incomplete. ... The expression, “to be with a person to bring,” is one of which I can more easily adduce examples than explain the exact meaning. [He cites three examples, to which several others are added in DYCE-LITTLEDALE’s Sh. Glossary, 1902. See e.g. Spanish Tragedy, iii.xii.22-23 (ed. Boas, 1901, p. 62): “And Balthazar, Ile be with thee to bring, And thee, Lorenzo.” One instance combines “to bring” with “know,” namely Beaumont and Fletcher’s Cupid’s Revenge (ed. Dyce, 1843, II, 419-20): “If he prove not yet The cunning’st, rankest rogue that ever canted, I’ll never see man again; I know him to bring, And can interpret every new face he makes.”]—SCHMIDT (1874): “To be with a person to bring” [means] to give him a sound lesson, to bring him to reason, to overcome him; with a lascivious sense, when spoken to women. “To be with a person,” without that apposition, is an ambiguous expression, as it may mean “to join” in a friendly sense as well as to fight, to combat. ... The addition of “to bring” gives it expressly the latter signification.—SKEAT and MAYHEW (Glossary of Tudor and Stuart Words, 1914): A phrase of various applications, but usually implying getting the upper hand in some way.—[The origin of this idiom seems to be completely lost, and its sense must be deduced from such applications as can be found. “To bring” appears to have had an intensive force, equivalent to “with a vengeance.” Combined with “be with you” and in the future tense, it expressed a threat, serious or playful. In the example from the Spanish Tragedy above the meaning is, “I’ll be with you with a vengeance”; in that from Cupid’s Revenge it is, “I know him through and through.”—ED.]"]},"298":{"play":"PANDARUS: Ay, a token from Troilus.","notes":[]},"299":{"play":"CRESSIDA: By the same token, you are a bawd.","notes":[]},"300":{"play":"[Pandarus exits.]","notes":[]},"301":{"play":"Words, vows, gifts, tears, and love’s full sacrifice","notes":[]},"302":{"play":"He offers in another’s enterprise;","notes":[]},"303":{"play":"But more in Troilus thousandfold I see","notes":[]},"304":{"play":"Than in the glass of Pandar’s praise may be.","notes":[]},"305":{"play":"Yet hold I off. Women are angels, wooing;","notes":[]},"306":{"play":"Things won are done; joy’s soul lies in the doing.","notes":["ioyes ... dooing] MASON (Beaumont and Fletcher, 1798, Additional Comments, pp. 54–55): This is the reading of all the editions; yet it must be erroneous; for the last six words of the passage are totally inconsistent with the rest of Cressida's speech, and the very reverse of the doctrine she professes to teach. I have, therefore, no doubt that we ought to read, “Joy’s soul dies in the doing,” which means, that the fire of passion is extinguished by enjoyment.—SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 415): There is no need of change: the sense is, the supreme enjoyment of lovers is during the time of courtship; but possession once obtained, puts an end to that enjoyment.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): The very spirit, essence, of delight, lies in the act of doing, and perishes when the act is complete.—[Mason, along with some other commentators, has evidently taken “doing” to have the sense, common enough to Sh. and his day, of performing the sexual act, and so does Schmidt. But the meaning is clearly fixed by the first part of the line: “Things won are done.” The antithesis is between the thing done and the thing doing or not yet accomplished. This supports the whole tenor of Cressida's speech. Deighton is right.—ED.]"]},"307":{"play":"That she beloved knows naught that knows not this:","notes":[]},"308":{"play":"Men prize the thing ungained more than it is.","notes":[]},"309":{"play":"That she was never yet that ever knew","notes":[]},"310":{"play":"Love got so sweet as when desire did sue.","notes":[]},"311":{"play":"Therefore this maxim out of love I teach:","notes":[]},"312":{"play":"Achievement is command; ungained, beseech.","notes":["Atchieuement ... beseech] RANN (ed. 1789): The language after conquest is peremptory; of courtship, submissive.—[HARNESS is credited by COLLIER (ed. 1842) with the “very easy and plausible change,” “Achiev’d men us command.” But this reading does not appear in Harness’ edition of 1825, or in any later edition I have seen.]"]},"313":{"play":"Then though my heart’s content firm love doth bear,","notes":["Contents (content)] HANMER (ed. 1744): By “Content” here is meant “Capacity.”—CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 116) interprets “content” to have the same meaning as “continent” in Antony and Cleopatra, IV.xiv.40–41: “Heart, once be stronger than thy continent, Crack thy frail case.” That is, “heart’s content” means bosom or breast.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): My “heart’s content,” I believe, signifies—“the acquiescence of my heart.”—SINGER (ed. 1826): “My heart’s content” ... probably signifies my “will,” my “desire.”—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): My heart in the fulness of its contentment.—PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910): Cressida confesses that although the contents of her heart include, that is “beare” or hold within it, “firme love” for Troylus she will not let what her heart contains appear in her looks. The Quarto reading does not show the meaning clearly and should no longer be followed in the modernized texts."]},"314":{"play":"Nothing of that shall from mine eyes appear.","notes":[]},"315":{"play":"[She exits.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 1, SCENE 3":{"1":{"play":"[Sennet. Enter Agamemnon, Nestor, Ulysses, Diomedes,","notes":["iii.1. Diomedes] WHITE (ed. 1865): The folio brings in Diomedes with the rest of the Grecian leaders; it being plain that there is a general council. But because he has nothing to say, modern editors hitherto have omitted his name."]},"2":{"play":"Menelaus, with others.]","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Princes, what grief hath set the jaundice o’er your","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"cheeks?","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"The ample proposition that hope makes","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"In all designs begun on Earth below","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"Fails in the promised largeness. Checks and disasters","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"Grow in the veins of actions highest reared,","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"As knots, by the conflux of meeting sap,","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"Infects the sound pine and diverts his grain","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"Tortive and errant from his course of growth.","notes":["Tortive] TYRWHITT (Var. ’78): There are more hard, bombastical phrases in the serious part of this Play, than, I believe, can be picked out in any other six Plays of Shakespeare. Take the following specimens:—Tortive, —persistive,—protractive,—importless,—insisture,—deracinate,—dividable. And in the next Act,—past-proportion,—unrespective,—propugnation,—self-assumption—self-admission,—assubjugate,—kingdom’d, &c.—COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868, re “oppugnancie,” line 171): It is worthy of observation how frequently Shakespeare uses his own specially coined words here; not only in this speech, but throughout this play. It is as if he were in a peculiarly minting vein at this period.—[M. D.: Twisting, twisted, tortuous.—B.]"]},"12":{"play":"Nor, princes, is it matter new to us","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"That we come short of our suppose so far","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"That after seven years’ siege yet Troy walls stand,","notes":["seven yeares siege] HERTZBERG (ed. 1877): That Shakespeare’s chronology does not agree with the Homeric, is to be expected; but he has also permitted himself material variations from his medieval sources, for dramatic purposes. It is true that according to Le Fèvre the death of Hector falls in the “seventh year” of the war. But also according to him Patroclus is killed by Hector early in the siege … and Achilles’ inaction from love of Polyxena first begins in the year after Hector’s death. … Of the leading motif of the Iliad, the “wrath of Achilles” for the rape of Briseis, Dares knew as little as his followers and Shakespeare, himself. As to the vain attempt of Agamemnon, Nestor, and Ulysses to rouse Achilles from his apathy, there is, to be sure, much said from Benoît and Guido on: But the attendant intrigue,—the excitation of Achilles’ jealousy by ostensibly favoring Ajax,—is Shakespeare’s own invention."]},"15":{"play":"Sith every action that hath gone before,","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"Whereof we have record, trial did draw","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"Bias and thwart, not answering the aim","notes":["Bias and thwart] HUDSON (ed. 1881) takes both words to be nouns, explaining “bias” (literally the weight in one side of a bowl) as “any wayward impulse or preference” and “thwart” as “hindrance or defeat.” He does not explain their construction in a sentence whose subject is “trial” and whose object is “action.” ROLFE (ed. 1884) takes them, correctly, to be adverbs,"]},"18":{"play":"And that unbodied figure of the thought","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"That gave ’t surmisèd shape. Why then, you princes,","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"Do you with cheeks abashed behold our works","notes":["works] SINGER (Sh. Vindicated, 1853, p. 191): The alteration of “works” to “wrecks” [in Collier’s Folio] ... has, it must be confessed, some appearance of probability, and would be a good conjectural correction of a misprint very likely to occur; “wracks,” as written, might easily be taken for “works,” and yet “works” may have been the poet’s word. [In his edition of 1856 Singer offered as his own emendation “mocks, i.e. our frustrated attempts by which we are mocked.”]—COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868): “Works” here has been suspected of error, and has been changed to “wrecks” and “mocks.” But Shakespeare elsewhere uses “works” for “acts,” “deeds,” “proceedings,” “doings”; and here “works” is intended to express “what we have done,” while the preceding argument gives to be inferred “the inadequate amount of what we have done,” “the insufficiency and unsuccessfulness of what we have done,” which need not cause shame, being but a trial of our constancy sent by Jove. 22–25. But ... love] CARTER (Sh. and Holy Scripture, 1905, p. 384) cites Hebrews xii, 6; Job, xxiii, 10; Zechariah xiii, 9.—B."]},"21":{"play":"And call them shames, which are indeed naught else","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"But the protractive trials of great Jove","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"To find persistive constancy in men?","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"The fineness of which metal is not found","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"In Fortune’s love; for then the bold and coward,","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"The wise and fool, the artist and unread,","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"The hard and soft seem all affined and kin.","notes":["affin’d] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Joined by affinity."]},"28":{"play":"But in the wind and tempest of her frown,","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"Distinction, with a broad and powerful fan,","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"Puffing at all, winnows the light away,","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"And what hath mass or matter by itself","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"Lies rich in virtue and unmingled.","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"NESTOR: With due observance of thy godlike seat,","notes":["Nestor] SNIDER (System of Sh.’s Dramas, 1877, ii, 205): Nestor is not the man who creates, but is the man who appreciates and gives utterance to the thought of others. The new plan is laid before him; his opinion is decisive. Too old for invention, his powers of judgment have increased with age; ... his mind grasps the thing as it is, without the least taint of prejudice. But the thought must first be brought before him—he cannot originate it. godly feat] NOBLE (Sh.’s Biblical Knowledge, 1935, p. 213): In the Bishops’ “ seat ” is continually used instead of “ throne ” for the Deity. See Matt. v, 34: “for it is Gods seat ” (Geneva] and R[heims] “ throne ”), and Matt. xxiii, 22: “the seate of God” (G and R, “ throne ”).—B. 34-35. apply ∞ words] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): What were these latest words? A common-place observation, illustrated by a particular image, “that opposition and adversity were useful to try and distinguish between the valiant man and the coward, the wise man and the fool.” The “application ” of this was to the Greeks; who had remained long unsuccessful before Troy, but might make a good use of their misfortunes by learning patience and perseverance. Now Nestor promises that he will make this application; but we find nothing like it. He only repeats Agamemnon’s general observation, and illustrates it by another image; from whence it appears, that Shakespear wrote, “—Nestor shall supply Thy latest words.—” And it must be owned, the poet never wrote anything more in character. Nestor, a talkative old man, was glad to catch at this common place, as it would furnish him with much matter for prate. And, therefore, on pretence that Agamemnon had not been full enough upon it, he begs leave to “ supply ” the topic with some diversified flourishes of his own. And what could be more natural than for a wordy old man to call the “repetition ” of the same thought, a “supplial.”—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I suppose the reader is long since contented rather to take either word than read the argument. Nestor “applies ” the words to another instance.—SINGER (ed. 1826): To “apply ” here is used for to “bend the mind,” or “attend particularly” to Agamemnon’s words. [He cites in evidence Baret’s Dictionarie (1580), which does indeed give as one definition adiungo animum, with supporting illustrations, “to bende or applie his minde to a thing,” “to applie"]},"34":{"play":"Great Agamemnon, Nestor shall apply","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"Thy latest words. In the reproof of chance","notes":["reproofe of Chance] \"NINGHA\" (N.V.Q., 2 April, 1921, p. 269) asks if the phrase means \"the resistance offered to chance, or the blow or buffet inflicted by chance? Something may be said for each interpretation.\"—F. L. WOOD (ibid., 16 April, p. 318) thinks it means \"the retesting of chance,\" that is, trying your luck again after defeat.—W. E. W. (loc. cit.) approves \"the resistance offered to chance.\"—SCHMIDT (1875): confutation, refutation."]},"36":{"play":"Lies the true proof of men. The sea being smooth,","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"How many shallow bauble boats dare sail","notes":["bauble Boates] Twelfth Night, v.i.48, has \"bawbling vessel.\""]},"38":{"play":"Upon her patient breast, making their way","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"With those of nobler bulk!","notes":["With those of Nobler bulke] STEEVENS (Var. '03; the first form of the note, in Var. '78, lacked the parallels from Sylvae): Statius has the same thought, though more diffusely expressed: Sic ubi magna novum Phario de littore puppis Solvit iter, jamque innumeros utrinque rudentes Lataque veliferi porrexit brachia mali, Invasitque vias; it eodem angusta phaselus A quore, et immensi partem sibi vendicat austri. Again, in The Sylvae of the same author, Lib. i.iv.120:—immensae veluti connexa carinae Cymba minor, cum saevit hyems— —et eodem volvitur austro. Mr. Pope has imitated the passage.—B."]},"40":{"play":"But let the ruffian Boreas once enrage","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"The gentle Thetis, and anon behold","notes":["Thetis] Tethys, the wife of Oceanus, would more properly stand for the sea than Thetis, a mere sea-goddess, famous only as the mother of Achilles. But both names were used, by metonymy, for the sea even in Latin times, and"]},"42":{"play":"The strong-ribbed bark through liquid mountains cut,","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"Bounding between the two moist elements,","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"Like Perseus’ horse. Where’s then the saucy boat","notes":["Perseus Horse] MALONE (ed. 1790) is the first editor to remark on this association of Perseus and Pegasus. He thought that Sh. was following the Recuyell (ed. Sommer, i, 196; ed. 1596, p. 155), which tells of the birth of the horse Pegasus from the blood of Medusa, but which then rationalizes the whole business: by the killing of Medusa is understood that Perseus deprived her of her kingdom and banished her, and by Pegasus is understood that from her wealth he made a ship of that name. “And this shippe was likened vnto an hors fleyng.”—STEEVENS (ed. 1793) thought this explanation more curious than pertinent. “Unallegorized Pegasus might be fairly styled ‘Perseus’ horse,’ because the heroism of Perseus had given him existence.”—DOUCE (Illustrations, 1807, II, 57), however, agreed with Malone that Sh. was thinking of Pegasus as a ship and got the idea from the Recuyell. But he then adduces evidence to prove that authorities before Sh. had mounted Perseus on a horse. “Boccaccio, in his Genealogia Deorum, lib. xii. c. 25, has quoted Lactantius as saying, that when Perseus undertook his expedition against Gorgon, at the instance of king Polydectus, he was accompanied by the winged horse Pegasus. ... Boccaccio adds that others were of opinion that he had a ship called Pegasus. The liberties which the old French translators of Ovid’s Metamorphoses have taken, and their interpolations, are unaccountable. Some have caused Perseus at the instant of his birth to bestride Pegasus, and travel away to Helicon. In the cuts to many of the early editions of Ovid, the designers have not only placed him on Pegasus in the adventure with Andromeda, but even in his attack upon Atlas.”—ROOT (Classical Mythology in Sh., 1903, p. 96), refers to Spenser (Ruines of Time, lines 645 ff.): “I beheld where stood A Knight all arm’d, vpon a winged steed, The same that was bred out of Medusaes blood, On which Dan Perseus borne of heauenly seed, The fair Andromeda from perill freed”; and remarks that “in Rubens’ painting of Perseus and Andromeda in the Royal Museum at Berlin, a winged horse stands at the left of the picture.”—DOUGLAS BUSH (“Sh.’s Classical Mythology,” P.Q., vi, 1927, 298) adds to these citations Rabelais ii.24: “Et ne crains ... cheual tant soit legier, & feust ce Pegase de Perseus”; Stephen Hawes’s Pastime of Pleasure (Percy Soc. ed., ch. i, p. 8): “Pegase the swyfte ... Whiche sometime longed ... To kyng Percius ..., On whome he rode by the worlde so farre”; and Stephen Scrope’s translation of Christine de Pisan’s Epistre d’Othea à Hector (Roxburghe Club ed., ch. 5, p. 15): “And poeytis seide that he roode the hors that flawe in the eyre, the which was called Pegasus.” Bush"]},"45":{"play":"Whose weak untimbered sides but even now","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"Corrivaled greatness? Either to harbor fled","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"Or made a toast for Neptune. Even so","notes":["Tofte for Neptune] Toasted bread immersed in wine, ale, or (for weak stomachs) water was considered a delicacy. Hence, as SCHMIDT explains, a \"toast for Neptune\" would be a tasty morsel for Neptune to swallow.—[Can it be a toast in the sense of a salutation to?—A.]"]},"48":{"play":"Doth valor’s show and valor’s worth divide","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"In storms of Fortune. For in her ray and brightness","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"The herd hath more annoyance by the breese","notes":["Briese] Gadfly. Compare Antony and Cleopatra, III.x.10–15: \"Yon ribaudred nag of Egypt ... The breese upon her, like a cow in June!—Hoists sail and flies.\""]},"51":{"play":"Than by the tiger, but when the splitting wind","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"Makes flexible the knees of knotted oaks,","notes":["knees] CRAIG (ed. 1905) remarks that \"timber naturally or artificially bent and used in shipbuilding was called 'knee-timber' \"; which is true, but I think not pertinent here. Nestor has left sea and ships for land. The winds are strong enough to make even an oak bend."]},"53":{"play":"And flies flee under shade, why, then the thing of","notes":["Flies fled under shade] MALONE (ed. 1790): Flies are fled.—WHITE (ed. 1865): But why should a splitting wind drive flies “under shade”? I suspect that “flies” is the true verb, and that there is irreparable corruption.—[White apparently was not aware that in Sh.’s time “shade” was used for almost any shelter from the elements, especially for a shelter from the wind. See N. E. D., ii. a., and the citation from Smith’s Virginia, 1624: “To keepe vs from the winde we made a shade of another Mat.”]"]},"54":{"play":"courage,","notes":["Thou] HUDSON (ed. 1881, p. 340) suggests that the poet wrote \"Tho.,\" intending \"Though,\" but neither he nor Dyce gives any reason for adopting this emendation, first proposed by Hanmer. There is in fact no reason. Ulysses addresses Agamemnon and Nestor; the parenthesis is a vocative; and the distinction between the greatness of the one and the wisdom of the other has been clearly made in lines 66-67. By omitting the comma after \"great\" Dyce and Hudson destroy the sense and the proper elocution. 79-80. These lines are based upon Chapman's translation of the Iliad. A fairly literal translation of Homer's passage is, \"only Thersites chattered on, the uncontrolled of speech, whose mind was full of words many and disorderly\" (Lang, Leaf, & Myers, Iliad, 1883, p. 28). Chapman based his verse translation of these lines upon the Latin verse translation found in Spondanus (Homeri quæ extant omnia, Basle, 1582, p. 33), the edition from which he is known to have translated: \"Thersites adhuc solus immoderate verbosus crocitabat Qui verba mentibus suis inornataq; multa; sciebat.\" Chapman translates this as: \"Thersites sole except, A man of tongue, whose rauenlike voice, a tuneles iarring kept, Who in his ranke minde coppy had of vnregarded wordes\" (ed. 1598, sig. Evi). There is no suggestion of a raven in Homer, but the Latin translator put one over Chapman's chamber door with his verb crocitabat, the reduplicated form of crocito, which Cooper (Thesaurus, 1565) defines as \"To croke, or crie lyke a rauen.\" Similarly, the verba ... inornataq; multa; sciebat is summed up as \"coppy had of vnregarded wordes.\" These words"]},"55":{"play":"As roused with rage, with rage doth sympathize,","notes":["with rage doth sympathize] HANMER (ed. 1744): It is said of the Tyger, that in storms and high winds he rages and roars most furiously.—[This trait is not mentioned by Pliny or Bartholomew. I have not yet found Hanmer’s authority, if indeed he had one.]"]},"56":{"play":"And with an accent tuned in selfsame key","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"Retorts to chiding Fortune.","notes":["Retyrés] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): For “returns” [Pope’s reading], Hanmer reads “replies,” unnecessarily, the sense being the same. The folio and quarto have “retires,” corruptly.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793) cites in support of Pope, Richard II (III. iii.127): “Northumberland, say thus the king returns.”—WHITE (Sh.’s Scholar, 1854, pp. 352–53): Mr. Dyce, in his recently published Few Notes &c. [1853], p. 107, asks: “did not Shakespeare write ‘Retorts to chiding fortune’?” Unquestionably, in my judgment. The conjecture seems to me to be one of the best among the many good, which have received the sanction of the taste, learning and discrimination of that gentleman. “Returns” is tame and meagre as applied to “to the thing of courage, roused with rage;” especially after the vigorous preceding lines. About four years ago it occurred to me that “retorts” was the only word in the language, which would at once worthily fill the place and correct with probability the typographical error.—THISELTON (Notulæ Criticæ, 1907, 63–71, p. 23): On the assumption that “Retyres” is due to a mis-reading of hand-writing, and knowing how easy was confusion between “c” and “t”, and between “d” and “r”, while I have myself at first sight taken “h” for “y” in the old style of writing, I strongly incline to Lettsom’s conjecture (“Rechides”).—The COWDEN CLARKES (ed. 1868)"]},"58":{"play":"ULYSSES: Agamemnon,","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"Thou great commander, nerves and bone of Greece,","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"Heart of our numbers, soul and only sprite,","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"In whom the tempers and the minds of all","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"Should be shut up, hear what Ulysses speaks.","notes":["Vlysses] LEWIS (Lion and the Fox, [1927], p. 212): In a play like Troilus and Cressida the weakness of the grand style and of blank verse becomes peculiarly apparent. ... It transfigures everything at once, monotonously heightening it, so that it is impossible, in the midst of its splendours, to convey anything but the most elevated and dazzling perfections. ... With Ulysses, for example, the intention is to convey a feeling of craft and “policy”; and you would expect his utterance to be correspondingly circumspect, rather insinuating than grand. You would not expect organ notes to issue from his mouth as you would were it the mouth of Roland or Renaud. Yet ... the moment he opens his mouth the organ begins, and no one, whatever his theme, could speak more grandly. 68-74. [speeches ... tongue] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Ulysses begins his oration with praising those who had spoken before him, and marks the characteristick excellencies of their different eloquence, strength and sweetness, which he expresses by the different metals on which he recommends them to be engraven for the instruction of posterity. The speech of Agamemnon is such that it"]},"63":{"play":"Besides th’ applause and approbation,","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"The which, (to Agamemnon) most mighty for thy","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"place and sway,","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"(To Nestor) And thou most reverend for thy","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"stretched-out life,","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"I give to both your speeches, which were such","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"As Agamemnon and the hand of Greece","notes":["hand] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I once read for \"hand,\" the \"band\" of Greece, but I think the text is right. 69-71. As Agamemnon ... As venerable Ne[stor] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Many conjectures have been proposed in order to meet the difficulties of construction here. I have followed Orger. Ulysses is addressing Agamemnon and Nestor in turns. It is therefore impossible that, in apostrophising the former, he should say: \"As Agamemnon and the hand ... brass,\" and almost nonsense to talk of that chief holding up his own speech in brass; impossible that, in apostrophising Nestor, he should say: \"As venerable Nestor ... knit ... To his experienced tongue,\" etc. By treating \"Agamemnon\" and \"Nestor\" as vocatives, reading \"all the hands,\" in line 69, and \"thy\" for \"his\" in line 74, all will be clear as to construction and sense.—THISELTON (Notulæ Criticæ, 1907, 63-71, p. 23): With regard ... to the Orger-Deighton manipulation of the passage nothing could be more ridiculous than the picture it gives of all the hands of Greece holding up the words of Agamemnon engraved in brass, while old Nestor is bawling his speech into the ears of those whose hands are so occupied. ... What has led to this degradation of Ulysses’ somewhat hyperbolical eloquence is the inability to see that the expression \"Agamemnon and the hand of Greece\" does not signify two distinct things. Agamemnon is the \"hand of Greece\" similarly as he has already been called \"Nerve and Bone of Greece.\"—G. DUBISLAV (Anglia, XXXIX, 1915, 74) also takes this to be a case of \"and\" before the apposition; that is to say, Agamemnon is the hand of Greece. 71 ff.] MALONE (ed. 1790) calls attention to the portrait of Nestor in Lucrece,"]},"70":{"play":"Should hold up high in brass; and such again","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"As venerable Nestor, hatched in silver,","notes":["hatch’d in Siluer] HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 493): That is, adorned with silver, in allusion to his white locks of hair.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): To hatch, is a term of art for a particular method of engraving. Hacher, to cut, French.—TYRWHITT (Observations, 1766, p. 47): Hatching is used in the engraving of plates from which prints are to be taken, principally, I believe, to express the shadows: but it can be of no use in any other species of engraving, which could exhibit — either Nestor, or his speech, in silver. In short, I believe we ought to read,—“thatch’d in silver,” alluding to his silver hair.—TYRWHITT (Var. ’78): I once thought that we ought to read “thatch’d in silver.” ... But I know not whether the present reading may not be understood to convey the same allusion; as I find, that the species of engraving, called hatching, was particularly used in the hilts of swords.—STEEVENS (Var. ’78): Perhaps no alteration is necessary; “hatch’d in silver,” may mean, whose white hair and beard make him look like a figure engraved on silver. [He cites Shirley’s The Changes, II.ii (ed. Dyce, 1833, II, 301): “Thy hair is fine as gold, thy chin is hatch’d With silver.”]"]},"72":{"play":"Should with a bond of air, strong as the axletree","notes":["bond of ayre] TYRWHITT (Observations, 1766, pp. 47–48): Of the rest of this passage Mr. Johnson says nothing. If he has no more conception than I have of “—a bond of ayre, strong as the Axletree In which the Heauens ride;—”)—he will perhaps excuse me for hazarding a conjecture, that the true reading may possibly be, “—a bond of awe.”—STEEVENS (Var. ’73): The voice of Nestor, which on all occasions enforced attention, might be, I think, not unpoetically called, “a bond of air,” because its operations were visible, though his voice, like the air, was unseen. [See note to 73–74.—B.] Axletree] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): This word was anciently contracted into a dissyllable. Thus in Beaumont and Fletcher’s Bonduca [ed. Dyce, 1844, V, 58]: “When the mountain Melts under their hot wheels, and from their ax’trees Huge claps of thunder. ...” [The contraction was common. See axtree in N.E.D.]. 73–74. knit ... eares To ... tongue] This was a Renaissance commonplace. See, for instance, Alciat’s Emblem clxxx, where the “bonds” are made visible. For another instance, see 1 Henry IV, I.iii.238, “Tying thine ear to no tongue but thine own,” where Keightley would substitute “turning” for “tying” because he does not understand the allusion. The figure shades off in"]},"73":{"play":"On which heaven rides, knit all the Greekish ears","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"To his experienced tongue, yet let it please both,","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"Thou great, and wise, to hear Ulysses speak.","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Speak, Prince of Ithaca, and be ’t of less expect","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"That matter needless, of importless burden,","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"Divide thy lips than we are confident","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"When rank Thersites opes his mastic jaws","notes":["Masticke] KNIGHT (ed. 1841) thinks that the epithet alludes to the play Histriomastix. \"We attach little importance to the circumstance that the author of that satire has introduced a dialogue between Troilus and Cressida; for the subject had most probably possession of the stage before Shakspeare's play. But it appears to us by no means improbable that an epithet should be applied to the 'rank Thersites' which should pretty clearly point at one who had done enough to make himself obnoxious to the poet's fraternity.\"—WHITE (ed. 1865) notes that mastix \"was used to mean a whip or scourge.\" [It is so defined in Cooper's Thesaurus and all the old Latin dictionaries. Hence Zoilus was called \"Homeromastix.\" Hence also the titles Satiromastix and Histriomastix.] He cites Sidney's Arcadia (1605, p. 227): \"... an old acquaintance of his called Mastix, one of the repiningest fellowes in the world, and that beheld no body but with a mind of mislike, (saying still the world was amiss, but how it should be amended he knew not).\"—WHITE suggests that \"mastick\" was probably used to avoid the cacophony of \"his mastix jaws,\" or that \"masticke\" may be a misprint for \"masticks.\"—STOKES (Academy, Nov., 1883, p. 351): That \"mastick\" is the true reading will be obvious to everyone who remembers that, in Elizabeth's time, mastic was the substance used for stopping decayed teeth. Agamemnon implies that Thersites' jaws were so rotten that they might be said to be composed of mastic.—[The citation from Arcadia, and the common use of \"mastix\" by the satirists of 1598-1603 (see especially the satires of Marston), are sufficient to justify \"mastic\" against the popular emendation \"mastiff.\" This word has played an important part in linking T. and C. with the War of the Theaters.—Ed.] 81 ff. For an analysis of the speech of Ulysses, see SISTER MIRIAM JOSEPH (Sh.'s Use of the Arts of Language, 1947, pp. 237-240).—B."]},"80":{"play":"We shall hear music, wit, and oracle.","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"ULYSSES: Troy, yet upon his basis, had been down,","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"And the great Hector’s sword had lacked a master","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"But for these instances:","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"The specialty of rule hath been neglected,","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"And look how many Grecian tents do stand","notes":["looke how] MARK ECCLES (J.E.G.P., XLII, 1943, 386) points out that look how means \"even as,\" \"just as,\" introducing a comparison.—B."]},"86":{"play":"Hollow upon this plain, so many hollow factions.","notes":["Hollow vpon] MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 309): The word \"hollow,\" at the beginning of the line, injures the metre, without improving the sense, and should probably be struck out.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I would rather omit the word in the second instance. To \"stand empty\" (\"hollow\" as Shakespeare calls it) is a provincial phrase applied to houses which have no tenants. These \"factions,\" however, were \"avowed,\" not \"hollow,\" or insidious. Remove the word \"hollow,\" at the beginning of the verse, and every tent in sight would become chargeable as the quondam residence of a factious chief; for the plain sense must then be—there are as many 'hollow factions as there are tents."]},"87":{"play":"When that the general is not like the hive","notes":["Generall . . . Hiue] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): The image is taken from the government of bees. But what are we to understand by this line? either it has no meaning, or a meaning contrary to the drift of the speaker. For either it signifies, that \"the General and the hive are _-_ of the same degree or species,\" when as the speaker's complaint is, that the hive acts so perversely as to destroy all difference of degree between them and the General: or it must signify, \"that the General has private ends and interests distinct from that of the hive\"; which defeats the very end of the speaker; whose purpose is to justify the General, and expose the disobedience of the hive. We should certainly then read, \"When that the General not likes the hive\": i.e. when the soldiers like not, and refuse to pay due obedience to their General: This being the very case he would describe.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): No interpretation was ever more perverse than those of the commentator. The meaning is, \"When the General is not\" to the army \"like the hive\" to the bees, the repository of the stock of every individual, that to which each particular resorts with whatever he has collected for the good of the whole, \"what honey is expected?\" what hope of advantage? The sense is clear, the expression is confused.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, pp. 493–94): [Agrees with Warburton that the line is wrong.] But I apprehend the artful and insinuating Ulysses would scarce tell Agamemnon bluntly, and in so many words, that he was not liked by the army; nor indeed is this the thing he complains of, but a general dissolution of all discipline, an insensibility of due subordination. I should imagine therefore the poet might"]},"88":{"play":"To whom the foragers shall all repair,","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"What honey is expected? Degree being vizarded,","notes":["Maske] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) thinks that by “mask” is meant not the covering for the face “but the masquerade in which the several actors have a part.” But it is more probable that “mask” does mean “vizard,” the idea being that when the face is not seen all men look alike.—[When high degree (is concealed) it is not to be distinguished from those of lower degree.—A.—But in a masque all would be vizarded and so all alike.—B.]"]},"90":{"play":"Th’ unworthiest shows as fairly in the mask.","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"The heavens themselves, the planets, and this center","notes":["Center] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. the centre of the earth; which, according to the Ptolemaic System then in vogue, is the centre of the Solar System—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 390): By “this centre,” Ulysses means the earth itself, not, as Warburton supposes, the centre of the earth.—According to the system of Ptolemy, the earth is the centre round which the planets move."]},"92":{"play":"Observe degree, priority, and place,","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"Insisture, course, proportion, season, form,","notes":["Insisture] DELIUS (ed. 1856), on the basis of “in sisture” (Q1), suggests a misprint for “in fixture”: “The heavens etc. observe degree, priority and place in fixture, course etc.”—HUDSON (ed. 1881): “Insisture” is, I take it, about the same as “position” or “station”,—a sense congruent with its Latin original.—[It is a word apparently coined by Sh., of which this is the only instance. The meaning must therefore be deduced from contemporary uses of the verb “insist,” which (inter alia, see N.E.D.) could mean “to stand or rest upon,” and “to continue steadfastly or persist in a course of action.” Hence “insisture” has been taken to mean “constancy or regularity” (Johnson); “regularity, or perhaps station” (Nares, Glossary, 1822); “persistency, constancy” (Schmidt 1874); or, with a query, “ ‘steady continuance’ in their path” (N.E.D.).—ED.—Insisture is the apparent stopping when a planet appears to become stationary at either end of its course. See p. 402—B.]"]},"94":{"play":"Office, and custom, in all line of order.","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"And therefore is the glorious planet Sol","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"In noble eminence enthroned and sphered","notes":["other] SINGER (Sh. Vindicated, 1853, p. 192): “Amidst the other” is surely not what the poet wrote. [It should be “ether.”] The classical reader will be reminded of a passage in the Somnium Scipionis:—“Medium fere regionem Sol obtinet, dux et princeps, et moderator luminum reliquiorum, mens mundi, et temperator,” &c.—WHITE (Sh.'s Scholar, 1854, pp. 353-54): In spite of Mr. Singer and his quotations, the context shows that “amidst the other” is exactly what the poet did write. ... It is not Sol’s place in the “ether,” but his supremacy “amidst the other” heavenly bodies, which Ulysses wishes to impress upon his hearers. The tenor of his entire speech shows this, beyond a question."]},"97":{"play":"Amidst the other, whose med’cinable eye","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"Corrects the influence of evil planets,","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"And posts, like the commandment of a king,","notes":["postes] ORGER (Critical Notes, 1890, pp. 48-49) cannot understand how an eye can post. He suggests “parts ... the good and bad,” as having the virtue of rectifying the images and tying in with “evil mixture” in line 101.—[Of course the subject of “posts” is “Sol,” not “eye.”—A.]"]},"100":{"play":"Sans check, to good and bad. But when the planets","notes":["Planets] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): By “Planets” Shakespear here means “Comets,” which by some were supposed to be excentrical planets. The evil effects here recapitulated were those which superstition gave to the appearance of Comets.—EDWARDS (Canons, 1765, p. 160): If we can suppose any thing wanting to prove, that one means Planets, when he says so; not only the whole tenor of the passage, but the very line here quoted may serve for a proof. The words—“in evil mixture”—evidently alluding to the conjunctions of the Planets.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I believe the poet, according to astrological opinions, means, when the planets form malignant configurations, when their aspects are evil towards one another. This he terms “evil mixture.”"]},"101":{"play":"In evil mixture to disorder wander,","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"What plagues and what portents, what mutiny,","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"What raging of the sea, shaking of Earth,","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"Commotion in the winds, frights, changes, horrors","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"Divert and crack, rend and deracinate","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"The unity and married calm of states","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"Quite from their fixture! O, when degree is shaked,","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"Which is the ladder of all high designs,","notes":["The enterprize] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Perhaps we should read, “Then enterprize ...”"]},"109":{"play":"The enterprise is sick. How could communities,","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"Degrees in schools and brotherhoods in cities,","notes":["Brother-hoods] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Corporations; companies; “con-fraternities.”"]},"111":{"play":"Peaceful commerce from dividable shores,","notes":["diuidable] MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 309): “Dividable” is here used to express “divided.”—STEEVENS (ed. 1793) agrees, and cites Antony and Cleopatra, iv.xiv.73-74: “bending down His corrigible neck,” where “corrigible” has the passive sense.—[But in Othello, i.iii.325, “the power and corrigible authority of this,” the same word is used actively, for “corrective.”]—SCHMIDT (1874) also takes the passive sense—“divided, separated, different.” But N.E.D. defines as “having the function of dividing,” that is, shores that divide. And so FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §124), who includes “dividable” among those adjectives in -able for which the suffix has an active meaning, equivalent to “dividing.”—[Since this is the only instance of the word in Sh., the sense is subject to the interpretation of the context, which is not clear enough to be determinative.]"]},"112":{"play":"The primogeneity and due of birth,","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"Prerogative of age, crowns, scepters, laurels,","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"But by degree stand in authentic place?","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"Take but degree away, untune that string,","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"And hark what discord follows. Each thing meets","notes":["meere] From Latin merus, undiluted, pure. Hence the original meaning, as here, was “complete, absolute.” As ABBOTT says (Sh. Grammar, 1872, §15), from meaning “unmixed” and therefore “complete” the word has come to mean “unmixed” in the sense of “nothing but, bare, insignificant.”"]},"117":{"play":"In mere oppugnancy. The bounded waters","notes":["oppugnancie] Opposition. This is the first use recorded by N.E.D."]},"118":{"play":"Should lift their bosoms higher than the shores","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"And make a sop of all this solid globe;","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"Strength should be lord of imbecility,","notes":["Lord of imbecility] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): If the text is sound here, the only sense I can extract from it is that mere strength would necessarily be lord over weakness and that as a consequence the strong, rough, son would strike his feeble father dead. … Now, in the ordinary course of things, “strength” is “lord of imbecility,” and so nothing is upset by “degree” being “shaked.” I believe, therefore, that for “lord” we should read “dar’d,” i.e. defied, and that the latter of the two lines has no dependence upon the former.—THISSELTON (Notulae Criticae, 1907, 63–71, p. 25): If it were necessary to take “imbecility” as implying mental deficiency, I should regard “Lord of imbecility” as equivalent to “mad Lord,” but I think the next line “And the rude sonne …,” as well as the word “Strength” indicates physical weakness as the intended application of the word “imbecility.” The conjunction “and” prima facie imports close connection in meaning, and I do not doubt that the second line explains the first by way of a particular instance of the more general proposition. Mr. Deighton conjectures “dar’d” for “Lord,” but the resulting meaning is not easily reconcilable with the gist of the passage, which as he well states is that whe: “degree is shaked” everything is turned topsy-turvy; for it is surely no uncommon thing for imbecility, in whatever sense, to defy strength, while, on the other hand, it frequently happens that physical weakness combined with intelligence prevails over brute force, though it may not adopt the method of defiance.—[Imbecility means physical weakness. The current sense of mental weakness did not become established until the nineteenth century. See N.E.D. As to the relation of lines 120–121, nothing is commoner in Sh. than the sequence of abstract generalization followed by a particularizing instance. The two lines seem to be exactly of this kind. They are furthermore restated in a more compact generalization: “Force should be right.” With respect to “imbecility,” Sh. is thinking of that kind of weakness which in a well-ordered state should be in authority over strength, as the father over the son. Ambiguity is no rare thing in Sh.’s rapid and crowded thinking.—ED.] 122–23. right … recides] As Hanford has noted (see p. 392), this is the Aristotelian position of mediocrity, stated universally (Polyanthea, 1622, p. 1428) as Virtus est mediocritas duorum uitiourum, alterius secundum excessum, alterius secundum defectum. sec. Arist. l. 3. Ethic., and specifically (Polyanthea, 1622, p. 700) as In damni lucrique medio ac moderatione ius positum est. Eth. l. 5. c. 4. Rackham translates (Aristotle’s ethics for English readers, 1946, pp. 38, 93 f.): [Virtue] is a middle state between two vices, one"]},"121":{"play":"And the rude son should strike his father dead;","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"Force should be right, or, rather, right and wrong,","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"Between whose endless jar justice resides,","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"Should lose their names, and so should justice too.","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"Then everything includes itself in power,","notes":["includes] SCHMIDT (1874) defines: To terminate, to come to in the end. N.E.D. takes it to be a figurative use of the primary meaning of include, namely, to shut or close in; to enclose within material limits. By the first definition the passage would mean, that everything terminates in (or as Capell puts it, converts itself into) power, power converts into will, and will into appetite. By the second definition, everything is embraced in, or absorbed into, power, etc. The sense remains very much the same. 125–26. See Appendix, pp. 416–18.—B. 127–28. Appetite ... vniuersall] The sententia of this traces back to a commonplace from Cicero, placed in Polyanthea (1622, p. 119) under Appetitus. Rackham (Cicero, De finibus bonorum et malorum, 1914, Loeb Classical Library, p. 49): “For the desires are incapable of satisfaction; they ruin not individuals only but whole families (universas familias evertunt), nay often shake the very foundations of the state. It is they that are the source of hatred, quarreling and strife, of sedition and of war. Nor do they only flaunt themselves abroad, or turn their blind onslaughts solely against others; even when imprisoned within the heart they quarrel and fall out among themselves.”"]},"126":{"play":"Power into will, will into appetite,","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"And appetite, an universal wolf,","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"So doubly seconded with will and power,","notes":[]},"129":{"play":"Must make perforce an universal prey","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"And last eat up himself. Great Agamemnon,","notes":[]},"131":{"play":"This chaos, when degree is suffocate,","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"Follows the choking.","notes":[]},"133":{"play":"And this neglection of degree it is","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"That by a pace goes backward, with a purpose","notes":[]},"135":{"play":"It hath to climb. The General’s disdained","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"By him one step below, he by the next,","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"That next by him beneath; so every step,","notes":[]},"138":{"play":"Exampled by the first pace that is sick","notes":[]},"139":{"play":"Of his superior, grows to an envious fever","notes":["pale, and bloodlesse Emulation] Pallor is a conventional characteristic of Envy. Ovid (Metamorphoses, II, 775): Pallor in ore sedet, macies in corpore toto. Ovid here adapted, or was adapted by, supposed Virgil (De Livore,"]},"140":{"play":"Of pale and bloodless emulation.","notes":[]},"141":{"play":"And ’tis this fever that keeps Troy on foot,","notes":["Opinion] SCHMIDT (1875): Reputation, credit, public opinion. [So also in this scene, lines 193, 350, 387, 397; in IV.iv.108; v.iv.17.]"]},"142":{"play":"Not her own sinews. To end a tale of length,","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"Troy in our weakness stands, not in her strength.","notes":[]},"144":{"play":"NESTOR: Most wisely hath Ulysses here discovered","notes":[]},"145":{"play":"The fever whereof all our power is sick.","notes":[]},"146":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: The nature of the sickness found, Ulysses,","notes":[]},"147":{"play":"What is the remedy?","notes":[]},"148":{"play":"ULYSSES: The great Achilles, whom opinion crowns","notes":["Achilles] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Perhaps the authour wrote, “Alcides’ arm.”—KINNEAR (Cruces, 1883, p. 287) objects, as others have done, that Agamemnon would not swear by Achilles, and agrees with Johnson’s emendation."]},"149":{"play":"The sinew and the forehand of our host,","notes":[]},"150":{"play":"Having his ear full of his airy fame,","notes":[]},"151":{"play":"Grows dainty of his worth and in his tent","notes":[]},"152":{"play":"Lies mocking our designs. With him Patroclus,","notes":[]},"153":{"play":"Upon a lazy bed, the live-long day","notes":[]},"154":{"play":"Breaks scurril jests,","notes":[]},"155":{"play":"And with ridiculous and silly action,","notes":[]},"156":{"play":"Which, slanderer, he imitation calls,","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"He pageants us. Sometime, great Agamemnon,","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"Thy topless deputation he puts on,","notes":["topless] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I don’t know what can be meant by \"topless,\" but the contrary to what the speaker would insinuate. I suspect the poet wrote \"stopless,\" i.e. unlimited.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): \"Topless\" is that which has nothing topping or overtopping it; supreme; sovereign.—STEEVENS (Var. '78): So ... in [Chapman's] the Blind Beggar of Alexandria, [I.i.82, ed. Parrott, 1914, p. 5]: \"And topless honours be bestowed on thee.\""]},"159":{"play":"And, like a strutting player whose conceit","notes":[]},"160":{"play":"Lies in his hamstring and doth think it rich","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"To hear the wooden dialogue and sound","notes":[]},"162":{"play":"’Twixt his stretched footing and the scaffollage,","notes":["Scaffolage] MALONE (Var. '85): The galleries of the theatre, in the time of our author, were sometimes termed \"the scaffolds.\"—SINGER (ed. 1826):"]},"163":{"play":"Such to-be-pitied and o’erwrested seeming","notes":["ore-fretted] MALONE (Var. ’85): We should read, I think,—“o’er-wrested.” Wrested beyond the truth; overcharged. [This emendation had appeared in Pope’s edition and in most of those after his.]—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Over-wrested is=wound up too high. A wrest was an instrument for tuning a harp, by drawing up the strings.—[See note on II.iii.26.]"]},"164":{"play":"He acts thy greatness in; and when he speaks,","notes":[]},"165":{"play":"’Tis like a chime a-mending, with terms unsquared","notes":["Chime a mending] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): To this comparison the praise of originality must be allowed. He who, like myself, has been in the tower of a church while the chimes were repairing, will never wish a second time to be present at so dissonantly noisy an operation. vm[quar’d] SCHMIDT (1875): Not suitable, not shaped and adapted to the purpose."]},"166":{"play":"Which from the tongue of roaring Typhon dropped","notes":[]},"167":{"play":"Would seem hyperboles. At this fusty stuff,","notes":["fusty] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) would like to interpret as meaning “fustian, high-sounding”; but there is no justification for confusing the two words. “Fusty” means simply “stale,” as it does below in II.i.99."]},"168":{"play":"The large Achilles, on his pressed bed lolling,","notes":[]},"169":{"play":"From his deep chest laughs out a loud applause,","notes":[]},"170":{"play":"Cries “Excellent! ’Tis Agamemnon right.","notes":[]},"171":{"play":"Now play me Nestor; hem and stroke thy beard,","notes":["hum, and [stroke thy Beard] Compare Much Ado, v.i.15 f.: “If such a one will smile, and stroke his beard, Bid sorrow wag, cry ‘hem!’ when he should groan.”"]},"172":{"play":"As he being dressed to some oration.”","notes":["drest] Many editors have taken this to be the shortened form of “addressed.” But “dress” originally meant “to put in order, get ready” (see etymology in N. E. D.). It survives in the military command."]},"173":{"play":"That’s done, as near as the extremest ends","notes":[]},"174":{"play":"Of parallels, as like as Vulcan and his wife;","notes":[]},"175":{"play":"Yet god Achilles still cries “Excellent!","notes":[]},"176":{"play":"’Tis Nestor right. Now play him me, Patroclus,","notes":[]},"177":{"play":"Arming to answer in a night alarm.”","notes":[]},"178":{"play":"And then, forsooth, the faint defects of age","notes":[]},"179":{"play":"Must be the scene of mirth—to cough and spit,","notes":[]},"180":{"play":"And, with a palsy fumbling on his gorget,","notes":["palsie fumbling] TYRWHITT (Var. ’78): This should be written—“palsy-fumbling,” i.e. paralytic fumbling.—SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 420): The making thus a compound of palsy and fumbling, gives such a construction as I believe nobody can understand. What can be plainer than this?—Patroclus (says Ulysses) now proceeds to mimic the infirmities of Nestor ... “And, with a palsy, fumbling on his gorget, (i.e. Putting it on in a fumbling manner,) (To) shake in and out the rivet.” on] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): “On” seems to be used for—“at.” So [I.iii.345], “Pointing on him,” i.e. at him."]},"181":{"play":"Shake in and out the rivet. And at this sport","notes":[]},"182":{"play":"Sir Valor dies, cries “O, enough, Patroclus,","notes":[]},"183":{"play":"Or give me ribs of steel! I shall split all","notes":[]},"184":{"play":"In pleasure of my spleen.” And in this fashion,","notes":["Spleen] N.E.D.: [The bodily organ], regarded as the seat of laughter or mirth. Obs. (Frequent c. 1600.) [The spleen was also regarded as the seat of melancholy, and, more generally, as the seat of impulses and passions. Sh. uses it in all these senses.]"]},"185":{"play":"All our abilities, gifts, natures, shapes,","notes":[]},"186":{"play":"Severals and generals of grace exact,","notes":["of grace exact] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): The meaning is this, All our good qualities, “severals and generals of grace”: i.e. whether they be “several” and belonging to particular men ... or whether they be “general” and belonging to the Greek nations in general, ... all these good qualities, together with our “achievements, plots, order,” &c. are all turned into ridicule by the buffoonery of Achilles and Patroclus. This is the sense: but what then is the meaning of “grace exact”? no other can be made of it, than that Achilles and Patroclus “exactly mimic” all our qualities and actions. But the speaker thought very differently of their buffoonery: the imitation, he says, being as unlike the original as Vulcan to his wife. The fault lies here; “exact” should be “exacts”; and belongs to the second division, namely the enumeration of the “actions”; and should be read thus; ... Severals and generals of grace; exacts, Achievements, plots, &c. i.e. “exactments,” publick taxes, and contributions for carrying on the war.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I see no great need of emendation; the meaning is plain; of “grace exact,” of “excellence irreprehensible.”—RANN (ed. 1789): All our personal or national accomplishments, however decent and irreprehensible.—SINGER (ed. 1826): “Grace exact” seems to mean “decorous habits.”—DELIUS (ed. 1855): Our well-ordered gifts, individual and general.—SCHMIDT (1874): The minutest peculiar and general excellencies.—[No editor has given a very satisfactory interpretation of this baffling phrase; few have given it more than a passing glance. For emendations, see Textual Notes.]"]},"187":{"play":"Achievements, plots, orders, preventions,","notes":[]},"188":{"play":"Excitements to the field, or speech for truce,","notes":[]},"189":{"play":"Success or loss, what is or is not, serves","notes":[]},"190":{"play":"As stuff for these two to make paradoxes.","notes":["paradoxes] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): “Paradoxes” may have a meaning, but it is not clear and distinct. I wish the copies had given, “—to make parodies.”—[A paradox is a proposition that violates, or seems to violate, truth or received opinion, and hence sounds absurd. Schmidt defines paradoxes (for Sh.) simply as “absurdities.” The passage nearest in feeling to the present"]},"191":{"play":"NESTOR: And in the imitation of these twain,","notes":[]},"192":{"play":"Who, as Ulysses says, opinion crowns","notes":["Opinion] See note on I.iii.149. 195-96. beares ... reyne] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, holds up his head as haughtily. We still say of a girl, “she bridles.”","opinion] See note on I.iii.149.","opinion] See note on I.iii.149."]},"193":{"play":"With an imperial voice, many are infect:","notes":[]},"194":{"play":"Ajax is grown self-willed and bears his head","notes":[]},"195":{"play":"In such a rein, in full as proud a place","notes":[]},"196":{"play":"As broad Achilles; keeps his tent like him,","notes":[]},"197":{"play":"Makes factious feasts; rails on our state of war,","notes":[]},"198":{"play":"Bold as an oracle, and sets Thersites—","notes":[]},"199":{"play":"A slave whose gall coins slanders like a mint—","notes":[]},"200":{"play":"To match us in comparisons with dirt,","notes":[]},"201":{"play":"To weaken and discredit our exposure,","notes":["our expofure] Apparently, to weaken and discredit us, exposed as we are to dangers. A characteristically Sh.’n involution, with the abstract for the concrete."]},"202":{"play":"How rank soever rounded in with danger.","notes":[]},"203":{"play":"ULYSSES: They tax our policy and call it cowardice,","notes":[]},"204":{"play":"Count wisdom as no member of the war,","notes":[]},"205":{"play":"Forestall prescience, and esteem no act","notes":["Fore-ſtall] SCHMIDT (1874): To judge beforehand, to regard with prejudice.—[This definition is tailored to the present passage; unfortunately it has no support in usage. N.E.D. defines fore-stall (v. 4): “to hinder, obstruct, or"]},"206":{"play":"But that of hand. The still and mental parts","notes":[]},"207":{"play":"That do contrive how many hands shall strike","notes":[]},"208":{"play":"When fitness calls them on and know by measure","notes":[]},"209":{"play":"Of their observant toil the enemy’s weight—","notes":[]},"210":{"play":"Why, this hath not a fingers dignity.","notes":[]},"211":{"play":"They call this bed-work, mapp’ry, closet war;","notes":["Bed-worke, Mapp’ry] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): The Poet in my Opinion would say, This is planning out Action and War, as a Man might do on his Pillow and in his Closet. If so, “bed-work” must be the Epithet to “Mappery,” as “closet” is to “War”: and therefore I have expung’d the Comma, which separated the First from its Substantive. So Guiderius, in Cymbeline [III.iii.33], speaking of an unactive Life, says it is “A cell of ignorance; travelling a-bed.”—LEE (ed. 1910): “Mappery,” i.e., the making of maps or plans, is unknown elsewhere in the literature of the time. With this punctuation [omitting the comma] “bed-work” is an epithet, meaning either “ reposeful ” (i.e., of the character of work done at rest in bed), or “ground-work” (“bed” being used in the sense of “base” or “foundation” of a structure). If a comma be placed after “bed-work” (as is commonly done), that word would be a substantive, but might still be used seriously for “foundation” or “ground-work” to which “mappery” (with a scornful intention) and “closet-war” are in contemptuous apposition. This interpretation seems preferable to treating"]},"212":{"play":"So that the ram that batters down the wall,","notes":[]},"213":{"play":"For the great swinge and rudeness of his poise,","notes":[]},"214":{"play":"They place before his hand that made the engine","notes":[]},"215":{"play":"Or those that with the fineness of their souls","notes":[]},"216":{"play":"By reason guide his execution.","notes":[]},"217":{"play":"NESTOR: Let this be granted, and Achilles’ horse","notes":[]},"218":{"play":"Makes many Thetis’ sons.   Tucket.","notes":[]},"219":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: What trumpet? Look, Menelaus.","notes":["Menelaus] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Surely, the name of Menelaus only serves to destroy the metre, and should therefore be omitted."]},"220":{"play":"MENELAUS: From Troy.","notes":[]},"221":{"play":"[Enter Aeneas, with a Trumpeter.]","notes":[]},"222":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: What would you ’fore our tent?","notes":["god] WALKER (Critical Examination, 1860, I, 304-05) cites many instances of the typographical confusion of “god—good,” “godly—goodly.” Corruption cannot be proved here; it is a matter of opinion. DYCE is the last important editor to argue for “good.”"]},"223":{"play":"AENEAS: Is this great Agamemnon’s tent, I pray you?","notes":[]},"224":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Even this.","notes":[]},"225":{"play":"AENEAS: May one that is a herald and a prince","notes":[]},"226":{"play":"Do a fair message to his kingly eyes?","notes":[]},"227":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: With surety stronger than Achilles’ arm","notes":[]},"228":{"play":"’Fore all the Greekish host, which with one voice","notes":[]},"229":{"play":"Call Agamemnon head and general.","notes":["heads] KINNEAR (Cruces, 1883, p. 287) believes “heads” to be a printer’s error, caused by the eye catching “head” in the next line. The word should be “host.”","heads] KINNEAR (Cruces, 1883, p. 287) believes \"heads\" to be a printer's error, caused by the eye catching \"head\" in the next line. The word should be \"host.\""]},"230":{"play":"AENEAS: Fair leave and large security. How may","notes":[]},"231":{"play":"A stranger to those most imperial looks","notes":["[stranger] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): And yet this was the seventh year of the war. Shakespeare, who so wonderfully preserves character, usually confounds the customs of all nations, and probably supposed that the ancients (like the heroes of chivalry) fought with beavers to their helmets. So, in the fourth act of this play [IV.v.217-18], Nestor says to Hector: “But this thy countenance (still lockt in steel) I neuer saw till now.”","[stranger] STEEVENS (Var. '78): And yet this was the seventh year of the war. Shakespeare, who so wonderfully preserves character, usually confounds the customs of all nations, and probably supposed that the ancients (like the heroes of chivalry) fought with beavers to their helmets. So, in the fourth act of this play [iv.v.217-18], Nestor says to Hector: \"But this thy countenance (still lockt in steel) I neuer saw till now.\""]},"232":{"play":"Know them from eyes of other mortals?","notes":[]},"233":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: How?","notes":[]},"234":{"play":"AENEAS: Ay. I ask that I might waken reverence","notes":[]},"235":{"play":"And bid the cheek be ready with a blush","notes":[]},"236":{"play":"Modest as morning when she coldly eyes","notes":[]},"237":{"play":"The youthful Phoebus.","notes":[]},"238":{"play":"Which is that god in office, guiding men?","notes":[]},"239":{"play":"Which is the high and mighty Agamemnon?","notes":[]},"240":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: This Trojan scorns us, or the men of Troy","notes":[]},"241":{"play":"Are ceremonious courtiers.","notes":[]},"242":{"play":"AENEAS: Courtiers as free, as debonair, unarmed,","notes":["bending] SCHMIDT (1874): Bowing; courteous.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) interprets “with heads inclined to listen prayer”; but devotion has no pertinency. The courtesy of bending or bowing has, so that Schmidt’s interpretation is probably right. Compare Richard III, IV.iv.95: “Where be the bending peers that flattered thee?”"]},"243":{"play":"As bending angels—that’s their fame in peace.","notes":[]},"244":{"play":"But when they would seem soldiers, they have galls,","notes":[]},"245":{"play":"Good arms, strong joints, true swords, and—great","notes":[]},"246":{"play":"Jove’s accord—","notes":["Ioves accord] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): Can the Poet be suppos’d to mean, that the Trojans had Jove’s Accord whenever they would seem Soldiers? No; certainly, he would intimate that nothing was so full of Heart as they, when that God did but shew himself on their Side. This Circumstance, added, brings no Impeachment to their Courage: Valour would become Presumption and Impiety in them, if they had trusted to it when Jove manifestly declared himself on the other Side. My Regulation of the Pointing fixes the Poet’s Sense; and ’tis every where his Manner to mention the Concurrence of the Deity suppos’d.—MALONE (Second Appendix, 1783, p. 44): As this passage is printed, I cannot discover any meaning in it. If there be no corruption, the"]},"247":{"play":"Nothing so full of heart. But peace, Aeneas.","notes":[]},"248":{"play":"Peace, Trojan. Lay thy finger on thy lips.","notes":[]},"249":{"play":"The worthiness of praise distains his worth","notes":[]},"250":{"play":"If that the praised himself bring the praise forth.","notes":[]},"251":{"play":"But what the repining enemy commends,","notes":[]},"252":{"play":"That breath fame blows; that praise, sole pure,","notes":[]},"253":{"play":"transcends.","notes":[]},"254":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Sir, you of Troy, call you yourself Aeneas?","notes":[]},"255":{"play":"AENEAS: Ay, Greek, that is my name.","notes":[]},"256":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: What’s your affair, I pray you?","notes":["I pray you] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): [These words] are an apparent interpolation, and consequently destroy the metre. [Their omission permits a complete verse of the two hemistichs: “Ay, Greek, that is my name.—What’s your affair?”]"]},"257":{"play":"AENEAS: Sir, pardon. ’Tis for Agamemnon’s ears.","notes":[]},"258":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: He hears naught privately that comes from Troy.","notes":[]},"259":{"play":"AENEAS: Nor I from Troy come not to whisper with him.","notes":[]},"260":{"play":"I bring a trumpet to awake his ear,","notes":[]},"261":{"play":"To set his sense on the attentive bent,","notes":[]},"262":{"play":"And then to speak.","notes":[]},"263":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Speak frankly as the wind;","notes":["Speake ... winde] ROLFE (ed. 1884) cites Othello, V.ii.223: “I will speak as liberal as the north.”"]},"264":{"play":"It is not Agamemnon’s sleeping hour.","notes":[]},"265":{"play":"That thou shalt know, Trojan, he is awake,","notes":[]},"266":{"play":"He tells thee so himself.","notes":[]},"267":{"play":"AENEAS: Trumpet, blow loud!","notes":[]},"268":{"play":"Send thy brass voice through all these lazy tents;","notes":[]},"269":{"play":"And every Greek of mettle, let him know","notes":[]},"270":{"play":"What Troy means fairly shall be spoke aloud.","notes":[]},"271":{"play":"[Sound trumpet.]","notes":[]},"272":{"play":"We have, great Agamemnon, here in Troy","notes":[]},"273":{"play":"A prince called Hector—Priam is his father—","notes":[]},"274":{"play":"Who in this dull and long-continued truce","notes":["Truce] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Of this long truce there has been no notice taken; in this very act it is said [ii.ii.37] that Ajax “yesterday cop’d Hector in the battell.”—DANIEL (“Time-Analysis of T. and C.,” New Sh. Soc. Transactions, 1877–79, p. 181) supposes that an interval elapses between this and the preceding scenes.—SMALL (Stage Quarrel, 1899, p. 150): The contradiction is due simply to dramatic condensation. … In reducing the time of the play from several years to a few days, he [Sh.] has almost necessarily mingled the events of the truce with those of the time of war in a very confusing way."]},"275":{"play":"Is resty grown. He bade me take a trumpet","notes":[]},"276":{"play":"And to this purpose speak: “Kings, princes, lords,","notes":[]},"277":{"play":"If there be one among the fair’st of Greece","notes":["mould] DELIUS (ed. 1856) finds \"mould\" more \"significant\" than \"hoste\" of Q, and explains: \"If there be not, in the stuff from which we Grecians are made, one noble man,\" etc. He changed his mind in later editions."]},"278":{"play":"That holds his honor higher than his ease,","notes":[]},"279":{"play":"That seeks his praise more than he fears his peril,","notes":[]},"280":{"play":"That knows his valor and knows not his fear,","notes":[]},"281":{"play":"That loves his mistress more than in confession","notes":[]},"282":{"play":"With truant vows to her own lips he loves","notes":["confeſſion] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): Confession, for profession. 280–81. confeſſion … loues] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, confession made with idle vows to the lips of her whom he loves.—[The comma after “lips” in Theobald, Warburton, and White (ed. 1865) may have no significance. It is just possible, however, that it was intended to mark the supposed ellipsis of “that”—i.e. “with truant vows … [that] he loves”; which would add still an-"]},"283":{"play":"And dare avow her beauty and her worth","notes":[]},"284":{"play":"In other arms than hers—to him this challenge.","notes":["this Challenge] Hertzberg (ed. 1877): In Shakespeare’s sources the fight between Hector and Ajax results from a casual encounter of the heroes on the battlefield, not from a direct challenge. Here Shakespeare goes even a step farther in the spirit of romanticism than do his authorities. The truce, which in Shakespeare ends with the duel, in them begins when the two cousins recognize each other.—[But Hector’s challenge to single combat and the selec-"]},"285":{"play":"Hector, in view of Trojans and of Greeks,","notes":[]},"286":{"play":"Shall make it good, or do his best to do it,","notes":[]},"287":{"play":"He hath a lady wiser, fairer, truer","notes":[]},"288":{"play":"Than ever Greek did couple in his arms","notes":[]},"289":{"play":"And will tomorrow with his trumpet call,","notes":[]},"290":{"play":"Midway between your tents and walls of Troy,","notes":[]},"291":{"play":"To rouse a Grecian that is true in love.","notes":[]},"292":{"play":"If any come, Hector shall honor him;","notes":[]},"293":{"play":"If none, he’ll say in Troy when he retires","notes":[]},"294":{"play":"The Grecian dames are sunburnt and not worth","notes":["fun-burnt] PARTRIDGE (Sh.'s Bawdy, 1947, p. 198): There is a pun on 'son' (=man)-burnt' ...: i.e., infected with venereal disease.—B."]},"295":{"play":"The splinter of a lance.” Even so much.","notes":[]},"296":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: This shall be told our lovers, Lord Aeneas.","notes":[]},"297":{"play":"If none of them have soul in such a kind,","notes":[]},"298":{"play":"We left them all at home. But we are soldiers,","notes":[]},"299":{"play":"And may that soldier a mere recreant prove","notes":[]},"300":{"play":"That means not, hath not, or is not in love!","notes":[]},"301":{"play":"If then one is, or hath, or means to be,","notes":[]},"302":{"play":"That one meets Hector. If none else, I am he.","notes":[]},"303":{"play":"NESTOR, to Aeneas","notes":[]},"304":{"play":"Tell him of Nestor, one that was a man","notes":[]},"305":{"play":"When Hector’s grandsire sucked. He is old now,","notes":[]},"306":{"play":"But if there be not in our Grecian host","notes":[]},"307":{"play":"A noble man that hath one spark of fire","notes":[]},"308":{"play":"To answer for his love, tell him from me","notes":[]},"309":{"play":"I’ll hide my silver beard in a gold beaver","notes":[]},"310":{"play":"And in my vambrace put my withered brawns","notes":["Vambrace] POPE (ed. 1723): An armour for the arm, Avant-bras."]},"311":{"play":"And, meeting him, will tell him that my lady","notes":[]},"312":{"play":"Was fairer than his grandam and as chaste","notes":[]},"313":{"play":"As may be in the world. His youth in flood,","notes":["his youth in flood] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 3 March, 1729/30): Though he be in the prime, and flood of his youth.—[The reading first intended was perhaps \"his youth in blood,\" as in Love's Labor's Lost, IV.ii.3, \"The deer was, as you know, sanguis, in blood\" (see Baldwin, Small Latine, 1944, II, 349). The phrase \"in blood\" means in full vigor, in the flower of life, with a strong body. Then \"blood\" was probably changed to \"flood\" to avoid repetition, though such repetition was sometimes used as a rhetorical ornament.—B.]"]},"314":{"play":"I’ll prove this troth with my three drops of blood.","notes":[]},"315":{"play":"AENEAS: Now heavens forfend such scarcity of youth!","notes":[]},"316":{"play":"ULYSSES: Amen.","notes":[]},"317":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Fair Lord Aeneas, let me touch your hand.","notes":[]},"318":{"play":"To our pavilion shall I lead you, sir.","notes":[]},"319":{"play":"Achilles shall have word of this intent;","notes":[]},"320":{"play":"So shall each lord of Greece from tent to tent.","notes":[]},"321":{"play":"Yourself shall feast with us before you go,","notes":[]},"322":{"play":"And find the welcome of a noble foe.","notes":[]},"323":{"play":"[All but Ulysses and Nestor exit.]","notes":[]},"324":{"play":"ULYSSES: Nestor.","notes":[]},"325":{"play":"NESTOR: What says Ulysses?","notes":[]},"326":{"play":"ULYSSES: I have a young conception in my brain;","notes":[]},"327":{"play":"Be you my time to bring it to some shape.","notes":["time] STEEVENS (Var. ’73): I.e., be you to my present purpose what time is in respect of all other schemes, viz. a ripener and bringer of them to maturity.—T. C. (in Malone, ed. 1790): I believe Shakespeare was here thinking of the period of gestation, which is sometimes denominated a female’s “time,” or reckoning.—[This is certainly the meaning. I suspect “T. C.” of being Steevens, who hid under pseudonyms for notes on indelicate subjects, “Collins” being the name appended to his long note on aphrodisiacs at the end of T. and C. in his 1793 edition.]"]},"328":{"play":"NESTOR: What is ’t?","notes":[]},"329":{"play":"ULYSSES: This ’tis:","notes":[]},"330":{"play":"Blunt wedges rive hard knots; the seeded pride","notes":["Blunt wedges riue hard knots] ERASMUS (Adagia, 1574, p. 52): Malo nodo malus quaerendus cuneus. ... Ita diuus Hieron. ad Oceanum: Interim iuxta vulgare prouerbium, malo arboris nodo malus cuneus requirendus est. Eo licet ubi, quoties malum simili malitia retundimus. Sumptum a sectoribus roborum, qui si quando durior in ligno nodus incidit, nolunt in eo periclitari securim, uerùm cuneum quempiam durum magis quàm bonum inserunt.—SMITH (Oxford dictionary of English proverbs, 1936, p. 69) cites TAVERNER (Erasm. Prov., 1539, ed. 1552, 5), “Malo nodo malus quaerendus cuneus, To a crabbed knot must be sought a crabbed wedge. A strong disease requireth a strong medicine. A shrewd wife a shrewd husband to tame her.” WITHALS (Dictionary, 1634, p. 566) used the Erasmian form and paralleled with: A boysterous horse must have a boisterous snaffle. WALKER (Parœmiologia Anglo-Latina, 1672, p. 57) parallels with: A sharp disease, a sharp remedy. PARKHURST (Ludicra, 1573, sig. Av) uses the Latin proverb. See Hudson (The epigram in the English Renaissance, 1947, p. 143 n). Leosthenes (Sententiæ Prophanae Ex Diversis Scriptoribus in communem puerorum usum collectæ, per Leosthenem Coluandrum, included in Sententiæ et Proverbia Ex Poetis Latinis, 1547, p. 192) presents a slight variant: Malo nodo malus cuneus debetur.—B. feede[d] RANN (ed. 1789): Full blown and ready to seed."]},"331":{"play":"That hath to this maturity blown up","notes":["That ... blowne vp] KEATS (Spurgeon, Keats’s Sh., 1928, p. 157): One’s very breath while leaning over these Pages is held for fear of blowing this line away—as easily as the gentlest breeze Robs dandelions of their fleecy Crowns. blowne] HUDSON (ed. 1881, p. 341, supporting Collier’s “grown”): What can be the meaning of “blown” here? “Blown up,” in the sense of “blossomed” seems hardly English. Besides, the meaning of the passage clearly is, that pride has “gone to seed” in Achilles; and with what propriety can a thing be said to “blossom to seed?”—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): “Blown up”"]},"332":{"play":"In rank Achilles must or now be cropped","notes":["ranke] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): A rank weed is a high weed.—[It is also a rampant weed. Denseness rather than height is implied in the figure here. “Rank” is of course an adverb.]"]},"333":{"play":"Or, shedding, breed a nursery of like evil","notes":[]},"334":{"play":"To overbulk us all.","notes":[]},"335":{"play":"NESTOR: Well, and how?","notes":[]},"336":{"play":"ULYSSES: This challenge that the gallant Hector sends,","notes":[]},"337":{"play":"However it is spread in general name,","notes":[]},"338":{"play":"Relates in purpose only to Achilles.","notes":[]},"339":{"play":"NESTOR: True. The purpose is perspicuous as substance","notes":[]},"340":{"play":"Whose grossness little characters sum up;","notes":[]},"341":{"play":"And, in the publication, make no strain","notes":[]},"342":{"play":"But that Achilles, were his brain as barren","notes":[]},"343":{"play":"As banks of Libya—though, Apollo knows,","notes":[]},"344":{"play":"’Tis dry enough—will, with great speed of judgment,","notes":[]},"345":{"play":"Ay, with celerity, find Hector’s purpose","notes":[]},"346":{"play":"Pointing on him.","notes":[]},"347":{"play":"ULYSSES: And wake him to the answer, think you?","notes":[]},"348":{"play":"NESTOR: Why, ’tis most meet. Who may you else oppose","notes":[]},"349":{"play":"That can from Hector bring his honor off","notes":[]},"350":{"play":"If not Achilles? Though ’t be a sportful combat,","notes":[]},"351":{"play":"Yet in the trial much opinion dwells,","notes":[]},"352":{"play":"For here the Trojans taste our dear’st repute","notes":[]},"353":{"play":"With their fin’st palate. And, trust to me, Ulysses,","notes":[]},"354":{"play":"Our imputation shall be oddly poised","notes":["imputation] CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 121): “Imputation” ... is put for “reputation,” the repute of us, what is imputed to us. odde/y poiz’d] Unequally balanced (DEIGHTON, ed. 1906); placed at a disadvantage.","imputation] CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 121): “Imputation” ... is put for “reputation,” the repute of us, what is imputed to us. oddly poiz’d] Unequally balanced (DEIGHTON, ed. 1906); placed at a disadvantage."]},"355":{"play":"In this vile action. For the success,","notes":[]},"356":{"play":"Although particular, shall give a scantling","notes":["scantling] N.E.D., sb. 6: a sample, pattern, specimen.—[This is the proper meaning of the word according to its derivation from OF eschantillon (scantillon, hence scant-ling). The meaning “small measure or proportion,” usually given by the older editors, comes apparently from confusion of the word with “scant, scanty.” That may be the meaning intended here. The word occurs nowhere else in Sh.—Ed.]","scantling] N.E.D., sb. 6: a sample, pattern, specimen.—[This is the proper meaning of the word according to its derivation from OF eschantillon (scantillon, hence scant-ling). The meaning “small measure or proportion,” usually given by the older editors, comes apparently from confusion of the word with “scant, scanty.” That may be the meaning intended here. The word occurs nowhere else in Sh.—ED.]"]},"357":{"play":"Of good or bad unto the general;","notes":[]},"358":{"play":"And in such indexes, although small pricks","notes":["Indexes ... pricked] “Pricks” are small points or dots. WHITE (ed. 1883) suggests that Sh. may have meant the line of dots connecting the index word and the corresponding page number. In old books indexes frequently preceded the text.—[Sh. uses “prick” in the sense of “check”—as checking something in a list. Compare Julius Caesar, IV.ii.13, “These many then shall die; their names are prick’d,” and “Prick him down, Antony.” Thus the “prick” or “check” calls attention to certain things in a voluminous mass, serves, as it were, as a brief “index.” Might not the poet in this passage use “pricks” in the same general sense, i.e. although the “indexes” printed at the front of books serve as “small pricks” checking off to the reader’s eye the general form of the volumes to follow, etc.?—A.] 359-60. The baby ... at large] SAINTSBURY (“Sh. and the Grand Style,” Eng. Assoc. Essays, 1910, I, 134-35): [This is] no bad instance of what may be called the middle or average Shakespearian Grand Style—perhaps indeed it is a little below the average. It is all the better example. The poet takes, you see, the most ordinary words—the actual vocabulary of the phrase is not above even Wordsworthian proof. He takes for figure an equally ordinary antithesis—“baby” and “giant”—though a different writer would probably have spoilt his own farther chances by using “pygmy” or “dwarf” instead of “baby.” And here he gets his first hold on us; for the baby, unlike the dwarf, will grow—though whether it will grow to giant size or not, only the Future can tell. Then he thinks of something else—“figure” and “mass” being not, like “baby” and “giant,” contrasts of size merely, but indicating the form, the idea, that is to be impressed on the mass. And then he is not satisfied with the limited greatness of “giant mass” itself; but expands and flings it out into the obscure infinity of things to come, and of things to come at large. You"]},"359":{"play":"To their subsequent volumes, there is seen","notes":[]},"360":{"play":"The baby figure of the giant mass","notes":[]},"361":{"play":"Of things to come at large. It is supposed","notes":[]},"362":{"play":"He that meets Hector issues from our choice;","notes":[]},"363":{"play":"And choice, being mutual act of all our souls,","notes":[]},"364":{"play":"Makes merit her election and doth boil,","notes":[]},"365":{"play":"As ’twere from forth us all, a man distilled","notes":[]},"366":{"play":"Out of our virtues, who, miscarrying,","notes":[]},"367":{"play":"What heart receives from hence a conquering part","notes":[]},"368":{"play":"To steel a strong opinion to themselves?—","notes":[]},"369":{"play":"Which entertained, limbs are his instruments,","notes":[]},"370":{"play":"In no less working than are swords and bows","notes":[]},"371":{"play":"Directive by the limbs.","notes":[]},"372":{"play":"ULYSSES: Give pardon to my speech: therefore ’tis meet","notes":[]},"373":{"play":"Achilles meet not Hector. Let us like merchants","notes":[]},"374":{"play":"First show foul wares and think perchance they’ll sell;","notes":[]},"375":{"play":"If not, the luster of the better shall exceed","notes":[]},"376":{"play":"By showing the worse first. Do not consent","notes":[]},"377":{"play":"That ever Hector and Achilles meet,","notes":[]},"378":{"play":"For both our honor and our shame in this","notes":[]},"379":{"play":"Are dogged with two strange followers.","notes":[]},"380":{"play":"NESTOR: I see them not with my old eyes. What are they?","notes":[]},"381":{"play":"ULYSSES: What glory our Achilles shares from Hector,","notes":[]},"382":{"play":"Were he not proud, we all should share with him;","notes":[]},"383":{"play":"But he already is too insolent,","notes":[]},"384":{"play":"And it were better parch in Afric sun","notes":[]},"385":{"play":"Than in the pride and salt scorn of his eyes","notes":[]},"386":{"play":"Should he scape Hector fair. If he were foiled,","notes":[]},"387":{"play":"Why then we do our main opinion crush","notes":[]},"388":{"play":"In taint of our best man. No, make a lott’ry,","notes":["Lott’ry] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): The account of the casting of the lots will be found in Chapman’s Iliad, vii.153–179, but there is no mention of the “device.”"]},"389":{"play":"And, by device, let blockish Ajax draw","notes":["blockish Ajax] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): Shakespeare on this occasion has deserted Lidgate, who gives a very different character of Ajax. … Our author appears to have drawn his portrait of the Grecian chief from the invectives thrown out against him by Ulysses in the thirteenth book of Ovid’s Metamorphosis; or from the prologue to Harrington’s Metamorphosis of Ajax, 1596, in which he is represented as “strong, heady, boisterous, and a terrible fighting fellow, but neither wise, learned, staide, nor politicke.”—MALONE (ed. 1790) suggests that Sh. confused the two Ajaxes, knowing only that an Ajax was Hector’s nephew, but not knowing he was Ajax Telamonius. Lydgate’s description of Ajax Oileus, which precedes by a few lines the description of Ajax Telamonius, accords with Sh.’s character. [For these descriptions see Appendix, pp. 429–30.] The Recuyell may have contributed to the confusion, because Caxton, who gives Ajax Telamonius his full name, calls Ajax Oileus simply Ajax.—LEE (ed. 1910): Shakespeare followed Ovid, Metam., xiii, in making Ajax throughout this play a self-willed and stupid braggart. Golding, translating Ovid, calls Ajax “dolt and grosse head,” “having neither wit nor knowledge.” Neither Homer nor his English adapters make Ajax a mere fool.—[To the epithets drawn by Lee from Golding should be added “Ajax blockish wit,” line 397.]"]},"390":{"play":"The sort to fight with Hector. Among ourselves","notes":["fort] The only instance in Sh. of this noun in the sense of “lot.” He twice uses the verb in a related sense (to allot, ordain), as in Richard III, II.iii.36: “if God sort it so.”"]},"391":{"play":"Give him allowance for the better man,","notes":[]},"392":{"play":"For that will physic the great Myrmidon,","notes":[]},"393":{"play":"Who broils in loud applause, and make him fall","notes":[]},"394":{"play":"His crest that prouder than blue Iris bends.","notes":["Iris] SCHMIDT (1874): The goddess of the rainbow and messenger of"]},"395":{"play":"If the dull brainless Ajax come safe off,","notes":[]},"396":{"play":"We’ll dress him up in voices; if he fail,","notes":["opinion] See note on I.iii.149."]},"397":{"play":"Yet go we under our opinion still","notes":[]},"398":{"play":"That we have better men. But, hit or miss,","notes":["fell] ANNA G. HATCHER (M.L.N., LVIII, 1943, 10): The reference is hypothetical: not passive activity but the possibility of such activity is described.—B."]},"399":{"play":"Our project’s life this shape of sense assumes:","notes":[]},"400":{"play":"Ajax employed plucks down Achilles’ plumes.","notes":[]},"401":{"play":"NESTOR: Now, Ulysses, I begin to relish thy advice,","notes":[]},"402":{"play":"And I will give a taste thereof forthwith","notes":[]},"403":{"play":"To Agamemnon. Go we to him straight.","notes":[]},"404":{"play":"Two curs shall tame each other; pride alone","notes":[]},"405":{"play":"Must tar the mastiffs on, as ’twere a bone.","notes":["tarre] N.E.D.: To irritate, vex, provoke. Now only in “tar on” (Shakespeare “tarre on”), to incite, hound on.—[Sh. uses the word in two other instances: once with “on” (King John, IV.i.116-17: “And like a dog ... Snatch at his master that doth tarre him on”); once without (Hamlet, II.ii. 349-50: “... and the nation holds it no sin to tarre them to controversy”).]"]},"406":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 2, SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Ajax and Thersites.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"AJAX: Thersites!","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"THERSITES: Agamemnon—how if he had boils, full, all","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"over, generally?","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"AJAX: Thersites!","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"THERSITES: And those boils did run? Say so. Did not the","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"general run, then? Were not that a botchy core?","notes":["i. 7. core] WHITE (ed. 1865) finds the meaning of “botchy core” to be “past conjecture.” He reads “corps” (regarding “core” as a phonetic variant) and thinks that Thersites is punning on the word “general,” with reference to Agamemnon and to the general body or corps of soldiers.—MARSHALL (ed. 1889) admits the probability of a pun on “core” (center of a boil) and “corps” (body of men, or simply body), but thinks that the former is the primary meaning.—[“Botch” means a boil or sore, or an eruptive disease, as “the botch of Egypt” (N. E. D.). “Core” is the hard center of dead tissue in a boil, or perhaps (SCHMIDT, 1874) the boil itself. Most editors accept these meanings without finding an intended quibble.]"]},"8":{"play":"AJAX: Dog!","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"THERSITES: Then there would come some matter","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"from him. I see none now.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"AJAX: Thou bitchwolf’s son, canst thou not hear? Feel,","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"then.    Strikes him.","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"THERSITES: The plague of Greece upon thee, thou mongrel","notes":["plague of Greece] MALONE (ed. 1790) thinks that Sh. had in mind the plague which befell the Greeks as told by Lydgate (ed. Bergen, E. E. T. S., Bk. III, lines 4876 ff.)—STEEVENS (ed. 1793) thinks it quite as likely that he took it from the first book of the Iliad. Mongrel] MALONE (ed. 1790): He calls Ajax “mongrel” on account of his father's being a Grecian and his mother a Trojan. [See IV. v. 138.]"]},"14":{"play":"beef-witted lord!","notes":["beefe-witted] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): So in Twelfth Night [I. iii. 80–81]: “I"]},"15":{"play":"AJAX: Speak, then, thou unsalted leaven, speak. I will","notes":["whinid’st†] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): [The Folio reading] is corrupted and unintelligible; but the Emendation [see Textual Notes], which I have coin’d out of it, gives us a Sense apt and consonant to what Ajax would say.—“Thou Lump of sowr’ Dough, kneaded up out of a Flower unpurg’d and unsifted, with all the Dross and Bran in it.”—UPTON (Critical Observations, 1746, p. 210): ’Tis a common expression in the western counties to call an ill-natured, sour person, vinnid. For “vinewed,” “vinowed,” “vinny,” or “vinew” (the word is variously written) signifies mouldy. … Let this [word] be transplanted from the West into Kent, and they will pronounce it, “whinidst leaven.” So that it seems to me ’twas some Kentish person who occasioned this mistake, either player or transcriber, who could not bring his mouth to pronounce the V consonant; as ’tis remarkable the Kentish man cannot at this day.—WARBURTON (ed. 1747): It should be “windyest,” i.e. most windy; leaven being made by a great fermentation. This epithet agrees well with Thersites’s character.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Hanmer preserves “whinid’st,” the reading of the folio; but does not explain it, nor do I understand it. If the folio be followed, I read, “vinew’d,” that is “mouldy leven.” Thou composition of “mustiness” and “sourness”. … “Unsalted” leven is in the old quarto. It means, “sour” without “salt,” malignity without wit. Shakespeare wrote first “unsalted,” but recollecting that want of “salt” was no fault in leven, changed it to “vinew’d.”—MALONE (Var. ’85): In Dorsetshire they at this day call cheese that is become mouldy, “vinny” cheese. There can be no doubt therefore that Shakspere wrote—“vineid’st” leaven.—VERITY (ed. 1889): Why should the reading of Q have been changed? ... The fact, I imagine, is, that of the two epithets “vinewed’st” was far the more graphic, the more offensive and therefore the more appropriate.—[The verb “fnew” (to be mouldy) derives from OE “fynegian” (from “fynig,” mouldy, “fyne,” mildew). From “fyne” also comes “fen” (a mould that attacks hop plants) and “fenny” (mouldy). Variants of “finewed” are “vinewed” and “vinnied.” See N.E.D.] leauen] WILSON (Christian Dictionary, ed. 1612): Corrupt and vicious Liuers, which with their company (like Leauen) infect others. [1] Corin. 5, 6. [The Q reading “vnsalted” is also Biblical.] WILSON: Salt. ... The doctrine of the word, because it seasoneth, not onely the corrupt manners and conuersations of men, but the rotten heart within, euen corrupt reason and will, that all may become sauory to God, Mat. 5, 13.—[The description of Thersites in Q as"]},"16":{"play":"beat thee into handsomeness.","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"THERSITES: I shall sooner rail thee into wit and holiness,","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"but I think thy horse will sooner con an oration","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"than thou learn a prayer without book. Thou canst","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"strike, canst thou? A red murrain o’ thy jade’s tricks.","notes":["red Murrel] We find “red pestilence” in Coriolanus, iv.i.13, and “red plague” in Tempest, I.ii.364. Whether these all mean the same is hard to tell. SCHMIDT (1875) thinks they do, and explains that “three different kinds of plague-sore [are] mentioned by the physicians of the time: the red, the yellow, and the black.” N.E.D. (red, a. and sb., 16.b.) says merely that “red” is “applied to various diseases marked by evacuation of blood or cutaneous eruptions.”"]},"21":{"play":"AJAX: Toadstool, learn me the proclamation.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"THERSITES: Dost thou think I have no sense, thou strikest","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"me thus?","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"AJAX: The proclamation!","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"THERSITES: Thou art proclaimed a fool, I think.","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"AJAX: Do not, porpentine, do not. My fingers itch.","notes":["fence] Feeling.—B. 25–26. Porpentine ... thou didst itch] Batman vppon Bartholome (ed. 1582, f 369^rv): [The porcupine is] like vnto the Hedgehog, but more stronger armed with pricks, and bigger bodyed. … [The hedgehog] hath as Aristotle saith, li. 1. pikes in steed of haire: and piks heeleth him as the haire of other beasts, and be his weapon and armour: for with them he stingeth & pricketth and hurteth him that taketh or toucheth him. … [The common hedgehog] when he is hunted, he cloaseth him rounde as a ball, for nothing should him touch for his pikes and prickes, and when he trusteth not to scape, then hee casteth from him pissing most venimous, & that pisse grieueth himselfe first, if it cometh in any wise on his back, or on his pricks, for by such moisture of that"]},"27":{"play":"THERSITES: I would thou didst itch from head to foot,","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"and I had the scratching of thee; I would make","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"thee the loathsomest scab in Greece. When thou","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"art forth in the incursions, thou strikest as slow as","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"another.","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"AJAX: I say, the proclamation!","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"THERSITES: Thou grumblest and railest every hour on","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"Achilles, and thou art as full of envy at his greatness","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"as Cerberus is at Proserpina’s beauty, ay, that","notes":["I] STEEVENS (Var. '73): “Aye,” I believe, in this place means “ever.” Thou art, says Thersites, as envious of the greatness of Achilles as is Cerberus of Proserpine’s beauty, that thou art barking at him so perpetually."]},"36":{"play":"thou bark’st at him.","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"AJAX: Mistress Thersites!","notes":["Mistreffe Thersites] WHITE (ed. 1865): I do not see the purpose of this feminization of Thersites, or in fact the significance of the speech. We might read, “Master Thersites”; but what should we gain? [In ed. 1883 White simply says: “Very probably a misprint for ‘Master.’”]—VERITY (ed. 1889): Surely the application of the word to Thersites is not so inappropriate or strange. He is a scold, quick of tongue and coward of heart, and in Hamlet’s phrase “must fall a cursing, like a very drab.” He stings and buzzes about the unwieldy Ajax, and the latter expresses his contempt for mere cleverness, by retorting, You are not a man at all, you are only a shrill-tongued shrew.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) takes the phrase as a taunt at Thersites’ cowardice, noting that in Aeschylus’ Agamemnon, line 1625, the Chorus addresses Aegisthus as “Woman!” and that in Chapman’s Iliad, ii.204, Thersites calls the chiefs “Greekish girls.”"]},"38":{"play":"THERSITES: Thou shouldst strike him—","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"AJAX: Cobloaf!","notes":["Coblost] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): A crusty uneven loaf is in some counties called by this name.—MALONE (Var. ’21) cites Minsheu’s Guide into Tongues,","cobloafe or bunne.] 1617: \"[Cobloafe or bunne] is a litle loafe made with a round head, such as Cobirons which support the fire.\"—NARES (Glossary, 1822): A large loaf. \"Cob\" is used in composition to express large, as \"cob-nut,\" \"cob-swan,\" &c. Nares argues for the Q reading of lines 34-37 (see Textual Notes), on the grounds that it must be Ajax who is called a \"large, clumsy loaf,\" and that then \"the succeeding allusion to a biscuit is natural, and in its place.\"—Nares may have been following Gifford's comment on \"cob\" in Jonson's Every Man in his Humour. GIFFORD (ed. 1816, i, 28) wrote: \"Our old writers used the word as a distinctive mark of bulk; thus cob-loaf was the largest loaf of the batch, cob-apple, cob-nut, &c. were respectively the largest apples and nuts of the crop, &c.\" But he, like Nares, was only partly right. The introductory remarks in N.E.D. (cob, sb.¹) show how confusing the word can be: \"Used in a number of senses having but little apparent connexion with each other, and possibly of diverse origin. The notions may be roughly distinguished of 'something big or stout,' 'something rounded or forming a roundish lump,' 'a head or top,'; but these are intricately interwoven in individual senses. Thus cob = 'cob-nut,' can hardly be separated from the notion of 'stout or big nut' on the one hand, or from that of 'fruit-stone' on the other.\"—Minsheu's definition of \"cobloaf\" has not been overthrown, although it has been added to and emended, the better to fit Thersites. Thus FOSTER (Sh. Word-Book, 1908): \"A crusty uneven loaf with many knobs and a round top ..., hence, from appearance, a rough, loutish, misshapen fellow.\" WRIGHT (1898) notes that \"cop-loaf,\" a special kind of Christmas loaf, is in Wiltshire \"a square box of paste, with an apple in the middle, notched round the edges, and a cock's head made of paste on the top, with two currants for eyes.\" HALLIWELL (Dict. of Archaic and Provincial Words, 1847) says that \"Aubrey mentions an old Christmas game called cob-loaf-stealing.\" If, as Aubrey and Wright suggest, cob-loaves were a specialty of Christmas, and were made in odd shapes as in modern Wiltshire, the term may have suggested in Sh.'s time something more bizarre than Minsheu's \"bunne.\" At any rate, Nares has been voted down by editorial opinion; the cob-loaf is Thersites."]},"40":{"play":"THERSITES: He would pound thee into shivers with his","notes":["pun] JOHNSON (Var. '73): \"Pun\" is in the midland counties the vulgar and colloquial word for \"pound.\"—[According to N.E.D., early and dialectical variant of \"pound.\"]"]},"41":{"play":"fist as a sailor breaks a biscuit.","notes":["stopp’d] HALLIWELL (ed. 1864): Some writers imagine that there is here an allusion to the cucking-stool, but I cannot discover that that mode of punishment was ever used to witches. I find the passage thus explained in an anonymous note,—“alluding to the bow’d back of the deformed buffoon, to which his legs answered as the legs of a table or stool.” —[Could “stoole” here mean a witch’s privy stool? Noisome at best, but especially so as used by a witch?—A.]"]},"42":{"play":"AJAX: You whoreson cur!      Strikes him.","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"THERSITES: Do, do.","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"AJAX: Thou stool for a witch!","notes":["stoole for a Witch] GREY (Notes, 1754, II, 236): In one way of trying a witch, they used to place her upon a chair or a stool, with her legs tied cross, that all the weight of her body might rest upon her seat; and by that means, after some time, the circulation of the blood, in some hours, would be much"]},"45":{"play":"THERSITES: Ay, do, do, thou sodden-witted lord. Thou","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"hast no more brain than I have in mine elbows; an","notes":["Asinico] STEEVENS (Var. ’73): Asinico is Italian, says Hanmer, for an “ass-driver”; but in Mirza, a tragedy by Rob. Baron, act 3. the following passage occurs …: “the stout trusty blade, That at one blow has cut an asinego Asunder like a thread.” … I hope … that the experiment was rather made on an ass than an ass-driver. From the following passage I should suppose it to be merely a cant term for a foolish fellow, an ideot: “They apparell’d me as you see, made a fool, or an asinego of me.” See The Antiquary, a comedy, by S. Marmion, 1641. Again, in Beaumont and Fletcher’s Scornful Lady, “—all this would be forsworn, and I again an asinego, as your sister left me.”—MUSGRAVE (Var. ’78): “Asinego” is Portuguese for a little ass.—[Musgrave is wrong. The word is from Sp. “asnico,” dim. of “asno,” ass. The word “asinico” is closer to the original. According to Wright (1898), “asinego” (variant forms, “assneger,” “anegar,” “assegar”) used to be current in Devon and Cornwall for (1) ass and (2) fool, simpleton.—ED.]—[COOPER (Thesaurus, 1565) defines Asini homines from Plautus as “Blocke heads: dull heads: asses.” Compare also MINSHEU (Guide Into Tongues, 1617) “An Assehead or blockhead … l Asindccio. H. Asnejonázo. P. Asnidáo”; FLORIO (World of Wordes, 1598) “Asinaggine, as Asinario … follie, foolishnes, of an asses condition, assishnes … Asinesco, asselike, like an asse or a foole”; PERCYVALL (A Dictionarie in Spanish and English, 1599) “Asnico, vide Asnillo, a little asse”; N.E.D. “Asinego. Obs. or dial. Also 7 asinico [a. Sp. asnico, dim. of asno ass.] … 2. A ‘donkey’, fool, doit”, [quoting T. and C. Whatever the language, the meaning is clear enough, and wherever he got it, Plautus popularized the term.]—B.]"]},"47":{"play":"asinego may tutor thee, thou scurvy-valiant ass.","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"Thou art here but to thrash Trojans, and thou art","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"bought and sold among those of any wit, like a","notes":["bought and folde] Compare Richard III, v.iii.305: “Dickon thy master"]},"50":{"play":"barbarian slave. If thou use to beat me, I will begin","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"at thy heel and tell what thou art by inches, thou","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"thing of no bowels, thou.","notes":["bowels] Heath (Revisal, 1765, p. 495): That is, Thou thing of no feeling; a reflection certainly not improper from a man who had been just beaten, on the man who beat him.—[This gloss was aimed at Warburton's blundering proposal to read, \"'Thou thing of no vowels,' i.e. without sense; as a word without vowels is jargon and contains no idea.\"—Ed.—Bishop Warburton ought certainly to have recognized the Biblical \"bowels of compassion.\" See II.ii.11: \"There is no Lady of more softer bowels.\" This allusion is not used elsewhere in Sh.—B.] 53-54. Why ... man] These two lines are unmistakably printed as prose by"]},"53":{"play":"AJAX: You dog!","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"THERSITES: You scurvy lord!","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"AJAX: You cur!   Strikes him.","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"THERSITES: Mars his idiot! Do, rudeness, do, camel, do,","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"do.","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"[Enter Achilles and Patroclus.]","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"ACHILLES: Why, how now, Ajax? Wherefore do you","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"thus?—How now, Thersites? What’s the matter,","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"man?","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"THERSITES: You see him there, do you?","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"ACHILLES: Ay, what’s the matter?","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"THERSITES: Nay, look upon him.","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"ACHILLES: So I do. What’s the matter?","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"THERSITES: Nay, but regard him well.","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"ACHILLES: Well, why, so I do.","notes":["Well, why] Dyce (Remarks, 1844, p. 151): [This should be pointed “Well! why,”] Achilles echoes the “well” of Thersites. It is impossible that “well” when followed by “why” can be a term of admission."]},"68":{"play":"THERSITES: But yet you look not well upon him, for","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"whosomever you take him to be, he is Ajax.","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"ACHILLES: I know that, fool.","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"THERSITES: Ay, but that fool knows not himself.","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"AJAX: Therefore I beat thee.","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"THERSITES: Lo, lo, lo, lo, what modicums of wit he utters!","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"His evasions have ears thus long. I have","notes":["evasions] Rann (ed. 1789): Escapes, excursions of genius, flights of fancy. bobb’d] Knocked, beaten. Compare Richard III, v.iii.334: “beaten, bobb’d, and thump’d.” 68–69. nine Sparrows for a peny] Compare Matthew x, 29 (Geneva version, 1579), “Are not two sparowes sold for a farthing?” This would be eight for a penny. Luke xii, 6, “Are not fiue sparowes bought for two farthings?” This would be ten for a penny. Thersites splits the difference and gets nine. The individual sparrow was used as a symbol of lack of value, and Thersites further devaluates the brain of Ajax by fractionating. Ajax was a sparrow-wit of the sparrow-wits.—B."]},"75":{"play":"bobbed his brain more than he has beat my bones.","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"I will buy nine sparrows for a penny, and his pia","notes":["Piamater] The membrane which covers the brain; used for the brain itself. Compare Twelfth Night, I.v.107–08: “One of thy kin has a most weak pia mater.”"]},"77":{"play":"mater is not worth the ninth part of a sparrow.","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"This lord, Achilles—Ajax, who wears his wit in his","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"belly, and his guts in his head—I’ll tell you what I","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"say of him.","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"ACHILLES: What?","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"THERSITES: I say, this Ajax— Ajax menaces him.","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"ACHILLES: Nay, good Ajax.","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"THERSITES: Has not so much wit—","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"ACHILLES, to Ajax  Nay, I must hold you.","notes":["to Achilles, etc.] DYCE (Remarks, 1844, p. 152): The proper pointing is, \"to, Achilles! to, Ajax! to!\" Thersites is urging the supposed oxen to their tasks."]},"86":{"play":"THERSITES: As will stop the eye of Helen’s needle, for","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"whom he comes to fight.","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"ACHILLES: Peace, fool!","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"THERSITES: I would have peace and quietness, but the","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"fool will not—he there, that he. Look you there.","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"AJAX: O, thou damned cur, I shall—","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"ACHILLES: Will you set your wit to a fool’s?","notes":["fet ... wit to a Fooles] Compare Proverbs (Geneva version, 1579) xxvi,4: \"Answere not a foole according to his foolishness, least thou also be like him.\"—B. 84-85. Fooles ... fooles!] WALKER (Critical Examination, 1860, III, 193): Thersites, therefore, is the \"Fool\" of this play, understanding the term in a strictly official sense; otherwise it would be absurd. In this capacity he shifts his service from Ajax to Achilles. [See also ii.iii.41-62, a characteristic passage of \"fool's\" logic; ii.iii.91 (\"Achilles hath inueigled his Foole from him\"); iii.iii.246 (\"He send the foole to Aiax\").]"]},"93":{"play":"THERSITES: No, I warrant you. The fool’s will shame it.","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Good words, Thersites.","notes":["Good words] Terence's bona verba. See BALDWIN, Small Latine, 1944, I, 747-48.—B."]},"95":{"play":"ACHILLES, to Ajax  What’s the quarrel?","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"AJAX: I bade the vile owl go learn me the tenor of the","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"proclamation, and he rails upon me.","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"THERSITES: I serve thee not.","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"AJAX: Well, go to, go to.","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"THERSITES: I serve here voluntary.","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"ACHILLES: Your last service was suff’rance; ’twas not","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"voluntary. No man is beaten voluntary. Ajax was","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"here the voluntary, and you as under an impress.","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"THERSITES: E’en so. A great deal of your wit, too, lies in","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"your sinews, or else there be liars. Hector shall","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"have a great catch an he knock out either of","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"your brains; he were as good crack a fusty nut with","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"no kernel.","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"ACHILLES: What, with me too, Thersites?","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"THERSITES: There’s Ulysses and old Nestor—whose wit","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"was moldy ere your grandsires had nails on","notes":["their Grandfires] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): This is no Folly of Thersites’s venting. What! Was Nestor’s Wit mouldy, before his Grandsire’s Toes had any Nails? ... and yet so easy a Change, as one poor Derivative Pronoun for another, sets all right and clear.—MALONE (ed. 1790): In the Mss. of our authour’s time yr stood for “your” and “their.”—GREG (Principles of Emendation in Sh., 1928, p. 48): Strictly, “your” should be written as “yoʳ,” and"]},"112":{"play":"their toes—yoke you like draft-oxen and make","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"you plow up the wars.","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"ACHILLES: What? What?","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"THERSITES: Yes, good sooth. To, Achilles! To, Ajax! To—","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"AJAX: I shall cut out your tongue.","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"THERSITES: ’Tis no matter. I shall speak as much as","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"thou afterwards.","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"PATROCLUS: No more words, Thersites. Peace.","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"THERSITES: I will hold my peace when Achilles’ brach","notes":["Brooch] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): \"Brooch\" is an appendant ornament. The meaning may be, equivalent to one of Achilles's \"hangers on.\"—STEEVENS (Var. '73): \"Brach\" I believe to be the true reading. He calls Patroclus, in contempt, Achilles's dog.—MASON (Beaumont and Fletcher, 1798, Additional Comments, p. 55): I believe \"brache\" to be the true reading, it certainly means a bitch, not a dog, which renders the expression more abusive and offensive. Thersites calls Patroclus Achilles's brache, for the same reason that he afterwards calls him his male-harlot, and his masculine whore.—[\"Brooch,\" identical with \"broach,\" means a spit, bodkin, or (NARES, Glossary, 1822) an ornamental buckle, pin, or loop. The word was sometimes used in a more general sense, equivalent to \"precious ornament, or jewel,\" as in Hamlet, IV.vii.93-94: \"He is the brooch indeed And gem of all the nation.\" Johnson's definition, \"an appendant ornament,\" finds slight confirmation (although a necklace was occasionally called a brooch); a brooch was usually a pin of some kind. On the basis of the Hamlet passage, MALONE (Var. '85) suggested that Thersites means \"the person whom Achilles holds so dear; so highly estimates\"; but this does not express the scorn which Thersites clearly intends. SCHMIDT'S interpretation (1874) of the possible application of \"brooch\" is as good as any: \"Shall I hold my peace when any of Achilles' appurtenances bids me, for instance his brooch, which you resemble indeed in serving to set him off?\" But Thersites is habitually more direct than this. MALONE (ed. 1790) hazarded the conjecture \"brock\" (badger), a word which is used abusively by Sh. once, in Twelfth Night, II.v.95.—ED.]"]},"121":{"play":"bids me, shall I?","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"ACHILLES: There’s for you, Patroclus.","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"THERSITES: I will see you hanged like clodpolls ere I","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"come any more to your tents. I will keep where","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"there is wit stirring and leave the faction of fools.","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"PATROCLUS: A good riddance.","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"ACHILLES, to Ajax","notes":[]},"129":{"play":"Marry, this, sir, is proclaimed through all our host:","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"That Hector, by the fifth hour of the sun,","notes":["fift] KNIGHT (ed. 1841): The knights of chivalry did not encounter at the first (Q reading) hour of the sun; by the fifth of a summer’s morning the lists would be set, and the ladies in their seats. The usages of chivalry are those of this play.—[In III.iii.303 (as noted by HUDSON, ed. 1854) Thersites gives the time of the duel as eleven o’clock.]"]},"131":{"play":"Will with a trumpet ’twixt our tents and Troy","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"Tomorrow morning call some knight to arms","notes":[]},"133":{"play":"That hath a stomach, and such a one that dare","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"Maintain—I know not what; ’tis trash. Farewell.","notes":[]},"135":{"play":"AJAX: Farewell. Who shall answer him?","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"ACHILLES: I know not. ’Tis put to lott’ry. Otherwise,","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"He knew his man.     Achilles and Patroclus exit.","notes":[]},"138":{"play":"AJAX: O, meaning you? I will go learn more of it.","notes":["Exit] TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., VII, 1932, 73) thinks that the last speech of Ajax is undoubtedly spoken aside; “Exeunt” must therefore precede it. “Oh, meaning you!” is spoken scornfully, after Achilles and Patroclus have left the stage."]},"139":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 2, SCENE 2":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Priam, Hector, Troilus, Paris and Helenas.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"PRIAM: After so many hours, lives, speeches spent,","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"Thus once again says Nestor from the Greeks:","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"“Deliver Helen, and all damage else—","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"As honor, loss of time, travel, expense,","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"Wounds, friends, and what else dear that is consumed","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"In hot digestion of this cormorant war—","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"Shall be struck off.”—Hector, what say you to ’t?","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"HECTOR: Though no man lesser fears the Greeks than I","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"As far as toucheth my particular,","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"Yet, dread Priam,","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"There is no lady of more softer bowels,","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"More spongy to suck in the sense of fear,","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"More ready to cry out “Who knows what follows?”","notes":["who ... followes] MALONE (ed. 1790): Who knows what ill consequences may follow from pursuing this or that course?"]},"15":{"play":"Than Hector is. The wound of peace is surety,","notes":["wound ... surety] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): I.e. the great Danger of Peace is too much Security; the Opinion of our being least in Danger. Therefore, as our Author says in his Hamlet [i.iii.43]: “Be wary then; best safety lies in Fear.”"]},"16":{"play":"Surety secure; but modest doubt is called","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"The beacon of the wise, the tent that searches","notes":["tent] N.E.D. (sb.3. 1) cites Blancard’s Phys. Dict. (ed. 1693): “Tenta, a Chyrurgeons Instrument, called Specillum, the vulgar call it Tenta, a Tent, from trying.” In other words, a probe. It also means “a roll or pledget, usually of soft absorbent material, ... formerly much used to search and cleanse a wound ...” From F. tente, f. tenter (L. temptare, tentare)."]},"18":{"play":"To th’ bottom of the worst. Let Helen go.","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"Since the first sword was drawn about this question,","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"Every tithe soul, ’mongst many thousand dismes,","notes":["dismes] MINSHÉU (Guide into Tongues, 1617): Dismes (Decimae) is made of the French Decimes, and signifieth tithe, or the tenth part of all the fruits, either of the earth, or beasts, or our labour due unto God, and so consequently to him that is of the Lord’s lot, and hath his share: viz. our Pastour. It signifieth also the tenths of all spirituall liuings, yeerely giuen to the Prince ... which in ancient times were paid to the Pope. ... Lastly it signifieth a tribute leuied of the Temporaltie.—SINGER (ed. 1826): Disme is properly “tenths” or tythes, but “dismes” is here used for “tens.”—HUDSON (ed. 1881): [Repeats Singer’s gloss.] So that the meaning is, “Every tenth soul, among many thousand tens of souls.” “Every tithe soul” is every ten souls, apparently.—ROLFE (ed. 1884): Tenths; not necessarily=“tens,” as Hudson makes it, neither is “every tithe soul”=“every ten souls.” The meaning is that not only is every tenth soul taken, but there are many thousand of these souls.—HERTZBERG (ed. 1877) argues that “dismes” cannot mean “tenths,” otherwise a “thousand dismes” would come to a hundred times the number that exists. “I believe that Shakespeare had in mind the picture of tithe-sheaves in a field and called ‘dismes’ what are only units of the tithe; accordingly, by ‘thousand dismes’ he meant only ‘thousand Trojans,’ who are taken by death as tithes. Thus ‘one ten’ (line 23) becomes understandable, which I have translated simply as ‘ten of ours.’”—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Though “tithe” means “tenth” and “dismes” means “tenths,” it would, I think, be a mistake to understand these words in their literal sense. The meaning seems to be not that every tenth soul “only,” but every soul “that has been taken as a tithe by war” is as dear as Helen, and of such tithes there have been many thousands."]},"21":{"play":"Hath been as dear as Helen; I mean, of ours.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"If we have lost so many tenths of ours","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"To guard a thing not ours—nor worth to us,","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"Had it our name, the value of one ten—","notes":["Had it our name] HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 495): Were it really ours, with as certain evidence as if we had marked it with our name, whereas we ourselves know Helen is not a Trojan but a Greek."]},"25":{"play":"What merit’s in that reason which denies","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"The yielding of her up?","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"TROILUS: Fie, fie, my brother,","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"Weigh you the worth and honor of a king","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"So great as our dread father’s in a scale","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"Of common ounces? Will you with counters sum","notes":["Counters] N.E.D.: A round piece of metal, ivory, or other material, formerly used in performing arithmetical operations. Obs.—B."]},"31":{"play":"The past-proportion of his infinite,","notes":["past proportion] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): The meaning is, that greatness to which no measure bears any proportion."]},"32":{"play":"And buckle in a waist most fathomless","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"With spans and inches so diminutive","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"As fears and reasons? Fie, for godly shame!","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"HELENUS: No marvel though you bite so sharp at reasons,","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"You are so empty of them. Should not our father","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"Bear the great sway of his affairs with reason,","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"Because your speech hath none that tell him so?","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"TROILUS: You are for dreams and slumbers, brother priest.","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"You fur your gloves with reason. Here are your","notes":["reasons] MALONE (ed. 1790): Here is a wretched quibble between “reasons” and “raisins,” which in Shakspeare’s time were, I believe, pronounced alike. Dogberry in Much ado about Nothing plays upon the same words [vi.197-98]: “If justice cannot tame you, she shall ne’er weigh more reasons in her balance.”—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): The present suspicion of a quibble on the word—“reason,” is not, in my opinion, sufficiently warranted by the context.—","furre your gloues] CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 122): Equivalent to—you are for keeping yourself warm, i.e. out of harm’s way: the phrase is made more apposite, by conceiving—that Helenus is in his priestly habit, and that “gloves” were a part of it as they are of our bishops.—WHITER (Specimen of a Commentary, 1794, pp. 130–35) thinks that the reference is to the fur which ornamented the scholastic habit. “You fur ... the glove of the warrior with the scruples of the priest.” Compare Comus: “budge doctors of the Stoic fur.”—CRAIG (ed. 1905) thinks it only a proverbial expression, comparable to “feather one’s nest.”"]},"41":{"play":"reasons:","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"You know an enemy intends you harm;","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"You know a sword employed is perilous,","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"And reason flies the object of all harm.","notes":["obiect] N.E.D. (sb. II.9): The presentation (of something) to the eye or perception; [equivalent to objection 4. The word of this sense is derived from the -u-stem noun objectus (a casting before, a putting against or in the way). The word which means “purpose” or “material thing” has actually a different derivation, from obiectum, ppl. of obicere.]"]},"45":{"play":"Who marvels, then, when Helenus beholds","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"A Grecian and his sword, if he do set","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"The very wings of reason to his heels","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"And fly like chidden Mercury from Jove","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"Or like a star disorbed? Nay, if we talk of reason,","notes":["Or like a Starre diſorb’d] Swift as a shooting star.—B."]},"50":{"play":"Let’s shut our gates and sleep. Manhood and honor","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"Should have hare hearts, would they but fat their","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"thoughts","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"With this crammed reason. Reason and respect","notes":["respect] MALONE (ed. 1790): Caution, a regard to consequences.—SCHMIDT (1875): Deliberation, reflection, thought in reference to something."]},"54":{"play":"Make livers pale and lustihood deject.","notes":["Makes] TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., vii, 1932, 74) thinks that editors are wrong to desert the F in favor of the Q reading \"Make,\" since to Sh. \"reason and respect\" probably meant \"respective reason,\" reason which weighs and considers, and he therefore treated them as grammatically singular. Liuers] W. BLADES (Athenæum, 27 Jan., 1872, p. 124) thinks it possible that \"Lovers\" (F₂₋₄) may be the right reading, \"Liuers\" arising from the accident common to type-setters' cases of the i box spilling into the o box below it.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) cites II Henry IV, iv.iii.101 ff.: \"The second property of your excellent sherris is, the warming of the blood; which, before cold and settled, left the liver white and pale, which is the badge of pusillanimity and cowardice.\" 58-59. 'Tis made Idolatrie ... God] CARTER (Sh. and Holy Scripture, 1905, p. 385; see also NOBLE, Sh.'s Biblical Knowledge, 1935, p. 214) cites the Geneva version of Matthew xxiii, 19: \"Ye fooles and blinde, whether is greater, the offring, or the altar which sanctifieth the offring,\" where Noble adds that the Bishops' and Rheims versions substitute \"gift\" for \"offring.\" Rheims (1582) quotes Theophylactus: \"In the old law Christ permitteth not the gift to be greater then the altar, but with us, the altar is sanctified by the gift\"; and Fulke (1589) replies: \"Gifts bestowed upon ye Church, to the maintenance of true Religion, be sanctified by dedication vnto God: but gifts offered in superstition and Idolatrie, are accursed as Idols are. Popish altars that are set vp to ouerthrow the altar of the crosse, are not holy but cursed.\"—[That is, the Roman Catholics are guilty of idolatry in making the service greater than the God. The author of this passage in T. and C. agrees with the position of Fulke against that of Rheims.]—B."]},"55":{"play":"HECTOR: Brother, she is not worth what she doth cost","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"The keeping.","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"TROILUS: What’s aught but as ’tis valued?","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"HECTOR: But value dwells not in particular will;","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"It holds his estimate and dignity","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"As well wherein ’tis precious of itself","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"As in the prizer. ’Tis mad idolatry","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"To make the service greater than the god;","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"And the will dotes that is attributive","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"To what infectiously itself affects","notes":["in.. .fectiously] SCHMIDT (1875): Morbidly.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Sympathetically.—[“Infectious” has always a sinister meaning in Sh., but this is not always true of “infect.” Either interpretation is therefore possible. But the word is probably drawn in chiefly for the jingle with “affects,” secondarily to emphasize the affective corruption of the will, so that the exact shade of meaning is not important and may lie somewhere between the two.—ED.]"]},"65":{"play":"Without some image of th’ affected merit.","notes":["affected] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): We should read,—“th’ affected’s merit,” i.e. without some mark of merit in the thing affected.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): The present reading is right. The will “affects” an object for some supposed “merit,” which Hector says, is uncensurable, unless the “merit” so “affected” be really there.—HEATH (Revival, 1765, p. 496): [Agrees that no change is needed.] The sense is, Without some appearance of a merit on which to found the affection. 63-70. See Appendix, pp. 416-18; also the figure at i.i.106-09, which begets this one.—B."]},"66":{"play":"TROILUS: I take today a wife, and my election","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"Is led on in the conduct of my will—","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"My will enkindled by mine eyes and ears,","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"Two traded pilots ’twixt the dangerous shores","notes":["traded] SCHMIDT (Sh. Jbch., iii, 1868, 358-61) considers this an example of the participle in -ed with active meaning, equivalent to “trading, who trade.” See also FRANZ, Sh.-Gram., 1939, §661.—But it more probably means only “conversant, familiar,” a common meaning in Sh.’s time; compare N.E.D., and below, IV.v.200, “untraded,” unfamiliar."]},"70":{"play":"Of will and judgment. How may I avoid,","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"Although my will distaste what it elected,","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"The wife I choose? There can be no evasion","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"To blench from this and to stand firm by honor.","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"We turn not back the silks upon the merchant","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"When we have soiled them, nor the remainder","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"viands","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"We do not throw in unrespective sieve","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"Because we now are full. It was thought meet","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"Paris should do some vengeance on the Greeks.","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"Your breath with full consent bellied his sails;","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"The seas and winds, old wranglers, took a truce","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"And did him service. He touched the ports desired,","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"And for an old aunt whom the Greeks held captive,","notes":["an old Aunt] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): This old Aunt ... is Hesione, the Daughter of Laomedon and Sister of Priam. She was borne away Captive to Greece by Hercules, when he sack’d Troy; and was given to Telamon’s Bed, by whom she bore Teucer. ... The Particulars of her Story are to be found in Hyginus’s 89th Fable."]},"84":{"play":"He brought a Grecian queen, whose youth and","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"freshness","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"Wrinkles Apollo’s and makes pale the morning.","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"Why keep we her? The Grecians keep our aunt.","notes":["inclineable] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I think the first reading [\"attributive\"]"]},"88":{"play":"Is she worth keeping? Why, she is a pearl","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"Whose price hath launched above a thousand ships","notes":["Whose price ... Ships] Almost every commentator has remarked on the obvious parallel with Marlowe’s Faustus (Brooke, ed. 1910, line 1328): “Was this the face that lanch’d a thousand shippes?”—[See also II Tamburlaine, II.iv.87-8 (Marlowe, ed. Ellis-Fermor, 1930, p. 215): “Helen, whose beauty summoned Greece to arms, And drew a thousand ships to Tenedos.” W. H. WILLIAMS (M.L.R., X, 1915, 222) finds the ultimate source in Lucian (Dialogues of the Dead, 18): EPM. Τουτὶ τὸ κρανίον ἡ Ἑλένη ἐστίν. ΜΕΝ. Εἴτα διὰ τοῦτο αἱ χίλιαι νῆες ἐπληρώθησαν ἐξ ἀπάσης τῆς Ἑλλάδος.— Fowler (Lucian, 1905, I, 137-38): Her. This skull is Helen. Me. And for this a thousand ships carried warriors from every part of Greece. See BALDWIN, Small Latine, 1944, I, 169-70. The parallel between our dramatist and Marlowe does not necessarily mean direct connection, since both are using a well-worn statement.—B.]"]},"90":{"play":"And turned crowned kings to merchants.","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"If you’ll avouch ’twas wisdom Paris went—","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"As you must needs, for you all cried “Go, go”—","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"If you’ll confess he brought home worthy prize—","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"As you must needs, for you all clapped your hands","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"And cried “Inestimable”—why do you now","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"The issue of your proper wisdoms rate","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"And do a deed that never Fortune did,","notes":["deed that Fortune neuer did] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): If I understand this passage, the meaning is, “Why do you by censuring the determination of your own wisdoms, degrade Helen, whom fortune has not yet deprived of her value, or against whom, as the wife of Paris, fortune has not in this war so declared, as to make us value her less.” This is very harsh, and much strained.—MALONE (ed. 1790): Fortune was never so unjust and mutable as to rate a thing on one day above all price, and on the next to set no estimation whatsoever upon it. You are now going to do what fortune never did.—HENLEY (ed. 1793): The meaning, I believe, is: “Act with more inconstancy and caprice than ever did fortune.”"]},"98":{"play":"Beggar the estimation which you prized","notes":["estimation] Thing of value (SCHMIDT, 1874); i.e. the abstract for the concrete. 96 ff. But Theeues, etc.] CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 122): The disjunctive “But” can have no place, there is nothing to disjoin; the repetition [i.e. of “base” in Hanmer’s text] is natural: after calling the theft—base, “in that” (for so the word should be taken) “we have stoln what we do fear to keep”; the committers of the theft are call’d—base, too; and the other “That” [l. 97] ... is us’d loosely for—“Who”; “their” and “them” [l. 97] is meant of the Greek nation.—MALONE (ed. 1790): “That did” ... [l. 97] means—“that which did.”—SINGER (ed. 1856): It is a base theft to have stolen what we fear to keep."]},"99":{"play":"Richer than sea and land? O, theft most base,","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"That we have stol’n what we do fear to keep!","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"But thieves unworthy of a thing so stol’n,","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"That in their country did them that disgrace","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"We fear to warrant in our native place.","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"CASSANDRA, within","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"Cry, Trojans, cry!","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"PRIAM: What noise? What shriek is this?","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"TROILUS: ’Tis our mad sister. I do know her voice.","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"CASSANDRA, within  Cry, Trojans!","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"HECTOR: It is Cassandra.","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"[Enter Cassandra raving.]","notes":["Enter Cassandra] KNIGHT (ed. 1841, p. 143): One of the most extraordinary subtleties of Shakspere's Troilus and Cressida arises out of the circumstance that the real heroic tragedy is found side by side with the ironical heroic. Cassandra, short as the character is, may be classed among the finest creations of art. Dryden omits Cassandra altogether. Was this a want of real perception of “the grounds” of tragedy; or an instinct which avoided the higher heroic, when it would come into contrast with his own feebler conceptions? The Cassandra of Shakspere is introduced to heighten the effect of the petty passions, the worldliness, which are everywhere around her. The solemn and the earnest are in alliance with madness.—[The lament of Cassandra occurs in Lydgate and Caxton in connection with the debate which precedes the expedition of Paris to the court of Menelaus (see first note on this scene). But it is placed after the conclusion of the debate, when the news of the decision reaches her. Sh. has given a more dramatic turn by plunging her into the conference, at the same time strengthening the impression that the Trojans are stubbornly bent on their own destruction.—ED.]","old] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 3 March, 1729/30): As all the rest are substantives, I think, this should rather be, “eld,” i.e. elders, old folks. As, Merry Wives [iv.iv.35], “The superstitious idle-headed eld.”"]},"111":{"play":"CASSANDRA: Cry, Trojans, cry! Lend me ten thousand eyes,","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"And I will fill them with prophetic tears.","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"HECTOR: Peace, sister, peace!","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"CASSANDRA: Virgins and boys, mid-age and wrinkled elders,","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"Soft infancy, that nothing canst but cry,","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"Add to my clamors. Let us pay betimes","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"A moiety of that mass of moan to come.","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"Cry, Trojans, cry! Practice your eyes with tears.","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"Troy must not be, nor goodly Ilium stand.","notes":["Troy we stand] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): This line unavoidably reminds us of another in the second book of the Æneid [line 56]: Trojaque nunc stares, Priamique arx alta maneres."]},"120":{"play":"Our firebrand brother Paris burns us all.","notes":["fire-brand] RANN (ed. 1789): Alluding to Hecuba’s dream, when with child of Paris, that she was delivered of a fire brand, which was construed to forebode the destruction of Troy through his means. 120-23. See V.ii.167, and Appendix, pp. 416-18.—B."]},"121":{"play":"Cry, Trojans, cry! A Helen and a woe!","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"Cry, cry! Troy burns, or else let Helen go. She exits.","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"HECTOR: Now, youthful Troilus, do not these high strains","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"Of divination in our sister work","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"Some touches of remorse? Or is your blood","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"So madly hot that no discourse of reason","notes":["discourse of reason] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Reasoning faculty. Compare Hamlet, I.ii.150: “a beast that wants discourse of reason.”—N.E.D. quotes Wesley (1788): “Discourse, strictly speaking, is the motion or progress of the mind from one judgment to another.” Hence discourse is the act of reasoning, or ratiocination."]},"127":{"play":"Nor fear of bad success in a bad cause","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"Can qualify the same?","notes":[]},"129":{"play":"TROILUS: Why, brother Hector,","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"We may not think the justness of each act","notes":["We may] HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 496): Both the sense and construction evidently require that we should read, “May we.”—[Most certainly, the text is correct.—B.]"]},"131":{"play":"Such and no other than event doth form it,","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"Nor once deject the courage of our minds","notes":[]},"133":{"play":"Because Cassandra’s mad. Her brainsick raptures","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"Cannot distaste the goodness of a quarrel","notes":["distaste] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Corrupt; change to a worse taste.—SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 424): Dr. Johnson's explanation ... is too vague. ... To “distaste,” means here, to destroy or take away the relish of. 133-35. Jove forbid ... maintaine] SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 425) finds the passage obscure. He suggests that “perhaps Troilus only means to correct the vehemence of his argument, by deprecating any ill-will, among his brothers, about the question. ... ‘Jove forbid, that, in such a dispute between brothers, there should be any the least act committed that could provoke the most impatient of our tempers to violent contention.’ ”—[But this paraphrase would cohere neither with the argument of the speech nor with the next speech of Paris. What Troilus means seems to be this: “Jove forbid that we should behave so dishonorably, or so pusillanimously, that even those who are least inclined to the war would take offense.” By this interpretation “to fight for, and maintain” depends logically on “spleen,” not on “offend.”—ED.]"]},"135":{"play":"Which hath our several honors all engaged","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"To make it gracious. For my private part,","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"I am no more touched than all Priam’s sons;","notes":[]},"138":{"play":"And Jove forbid there should be done amongst us","notes":[]},"139":{"play":"Such things as might offend the weakest spleen","notes":[]},"140":{"play":"To fight for and maintain!","notes":[]},"141":{"play":"PARIS: Else might the world convince of levity","notes":["conuince] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): This word, which our author frequently employs in the obsolete sense of—to overpower, subdue, seems in the present instance to signify—“convict,” or subject to the charge of levity.—[Baret's Dictionarie (1580): “To Conuince, or conuict: to vanquish and ouercome.”]"]},"142":{"play":"As well my undertakings as your counsels.","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"But I attest the gods, your full consent","notes":[]},"144":{"play":"Gave wings to my propension and cut off","notes":[]},"145":{"play":"All fears attending on so dire a project.","notes":[]},"146":{"play":"For what, alas, can these my single arms?","notes":[]},"147":{"play":"What propugnation is in one man’s valor","notes":["propugnation] Defence; the only instance in Sh. of any form of the verb “propugna.”"]},"148":{"play":"To stand the push and enmity of those","notes":[]},"149":{"play":"This quarrel would excite? Yet, I protest,","notes":[]},"150":{"play":"Were I alone to pass the difficulties","notes":["passe] KINNEAR (Cruces, 1883, pp. 292–93) objects that “pass” is meaningless, and suggests “front” (oppose, challenge), as cohering with the ideas of fighting (“propugnation,” “stand the push and enmity of ”) and warlike steadfastness (“ne’er retract”).—SCHMIDT (1875) takes the sense “figuratively ... to experience, to suffer,” as in Othello, I.iii.167: “She loved me for the dangers I had pass’d.”—THISSELTON (Notulæ Criticæ, 1907, 63–71, p. 28) supports this meaning by a citation from a letter of Sir John Norreys to Anthony Bacon, 16 Sept., 1589 (Birch’s Memoirs of the Reign of Elizabeth, 1754, I, 57): “I assure you the king hath passed some difficulties, and is not yet at the end of them.”"]},"151":{"play":"And had as ample power as I have will,","notes":[]},"152":{"play":"Paris should ne’er retract what he hath done","notes":[]},"153":{"play":"Nor faint in the pursuit.","notes":[]},"154":{"play":"PRIAM: Paris, you speak","notes":[]},"155":{"play":"Like one besotted on your sweet delights.","notes":[]},"156":{"play":"You have the honey still, but these the gall.","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"So to be valiant is no praise at all.","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"PARIS: Sir, I propose not merely to myself","notes":["propose] SCHMIDT (1875): To call before the eye of the mind, to image; [as in II Henry IV, v.ii.92: “Be now the father and propose [suppose yourself to have] a son”]."]},"159":{"play":"The pleasures such a beauty brings with it,","notes":[]},"160":{"play":"But I would have the soil of her fair rape","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"Wiped off in honorable keeping her.","notes":[]},"162":{"play":"What treason were it to the ransacked queen,","notes":[]},"163":{"play":"Disgrace to your great worths, and shame to me,","notes":[]},"164":{"play":"Now to deliver her possession up","notes":[]},"165":{"play":"On terms of base compulsion? Can it be","notes":[]},"166":{"play":"That so degenerate a strain as this","notes":[]},"167":{"play":"Should once set footing in your generous bosoms?","notes":[]},"168":{"play":"There’s not the meanest spirit on our party","notes":["traine] SCHMIDT (1875): Motion of the mind, internal action, impulse, feeling."]},"169":{"play":"Without a heart to dare or sword to draw","notes":[]},"170":{"play":"When Helen is defended, nor none so noble","notes":[]},"171":{"play":"Whose life were ill bestowed or death unfamed","notes":[]},"172":{"play":"Where Helen is the subject. Then I say,","notes":[]},"173":{"play":"Well may we fight for her whom, we know well,","notes":[]},"174":{"play":"The world’s large spaces cannot parallel.","notes":[]},"175":{"play":"HECTOR: Paris and Troilus, you have both said well,","notes":["well] THELSTON (Notulæ Criticæ, 1907, 63-71, p. 28): I cannot but think that Shakespeare wrote or intended to write “ill” instead of “well”: for the whole tenour of the rest of Hector’s speech seems inconsistent with “said well.” It may help to account for the error that the last but one preceding line ends with the word “well.” 170-72. said well ... gloz’d] N.E.D. (Gloze v₁: 1 trans.): To make glozes or glosses upon; to discourse upon, expound, interpret. ... Shaks. Hen. V, I.ii.40 Which Salike land, the French vnhusity gloze To be the Realme of France.—[Hector says, you have spoken well as to rhetoric and delivery, and you have glossed upon, or expounded, the subject, but superficially, as to logic and philosophy.]—B.","And] W. W. LLOYD (N.Q. 16 Oct., 1886, p. 305) would read “Yet,” preferring it to Theobald’s “But” on account of the “but” in the following line. “Hector, as usual with courteous objections to preceding speakers, begins with a compliment and then proceeds to qualify it. To retain the old text would oblige us to accept the interpretation, ‘You have both said well and glozed well, only too superficially,’ which I hold to be utterly indefensible. How should one gloze otherwise than superficially?”"]},"176":{"play":"And on the cause and question now in hand","notes":[]},"177":{"play":"Have glozed—but superficially, not much","notes":["gloz’d] The meaning of this word in Sh. is somewhat slippery. STEEVENS (ed. 1793) and NARES (Glossary, 1822) define it, in the present instance, as “comment, interpret.” SCHMIDT’S (1875) definition for all occurrences in Sh. is “to make tirades, to make mere words,” which scarcely fits all cases. N.E.D. successively gives: “to interpret or comment; to veil with specious comments; to talk smoothly and speciously; to flatter.” It does not cite the present instance. Sh. seems always to use the word contemptuously. Probably in the present case it means “comment speciously or plausibly.”"]},"178":{"play":"Unlike young men, whom Aristotle thought","notes":["Aristotle] The earlier commentators were bothered by the anachronism of Hector’s citing Aristotle; later commentators by an apparent mistranslation of Aristotle, who in his Nicomachean Ethics (I.3) says that young men are not fitted to hear political philosophy. SPEDDING was probably the first to point out that the same “error” occurs in the Advancement of Learning, Bk. II"]},"179":{"play":"Unfit to hear moral philosophy.","notes":[]},"180":{"play":"The reasons you allege do more conduce","notes":[]},"181":{"play":"To the hot passion of distempered blood","notes":[]},"182":{"play":"Than to make up a free determination","notes":[]},"183":{"play":"’Twixt right and wrong, for pleasure and revenge","notes":[]},"184":{"play":"Have ears more deaf than adders to the voice","notes":["eares ... Adders] ANDERS (Sh.'s Books, 1904, p. 213) cites Psalm lviii, 4-5: \"They are as venemous as the poyson of a serpent: even like the deafe adder that stoppeth her eares. Which refuseth to hear the voyce of the charmer: charm he never so wisely,\" and II Henry VI, III.ii.76: \"What! art thou, like the adder, waxen deaf?\""]},"185":{"play":"Of any true decision. Nature craves","notes":[]},"186":{"play":"All dues be rendered to their owners. Now,","notes":[]},"187":{"play":"What nearer debt in all humanity","notes":[]},"188":{"play":"Than wife is to the husband? If this law","notes":[]},"189":{"play":"Of nature be corrupted through affection,","notes":[]},"190":{"play":"And that great minds, of partial indulgence","notes":["of] MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 311): \"Of\" partial indulgence, means \"through\" partial indulgence."]},"191":{"play":"To their benumbèd wills, resist the same,","notes":["benummed] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, inflexible, immoveable, no longer obedient to superiour direction. 191-92. Lawes ... of Nation] O. J. CAMPBELL (Comical Satyre, 1938, pp. 191-93): The phrase \"laws of nature and of nations,\" here used correctly in"]},"192":{"play":"There is a law in each well-ordered nation","notes":[]},"193":{"play":"To curb those raging appetites that are","notes":[]},"194":{"play":"Most disobedient and refractory.","notes":[]},"195":{"play":"If Helen, then, be wife to Sparta’s king,","notes":[]},"196":{"play":"As it is known she is, these moral laws","notes":[]},"197":{"play":"Of nature and of nations speak aloud","notes":[]},"198":{"play":"To have her back returned. Thus to persist","notes":[]},"199":{"play":"In doing wrong extenuates not wrong,","notes":[]},"200":{"play":"But makes it much more heavy. Hector’s opinion","notes":[]},"201":{"play":"Is this in way of truth; yet, ne’ertheless,","notes":["Is ... truth] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Though considering “truth” and “justice” in this question, this is my opinion; yet as a question of honour, I think on it as you."]},"202":{"play":"My sprightly brethren, I propend to you","notes":["propend] N.E.D.: To hang or lean forward or downward. ... To have a “leaning” or propensity: to incline, be disposed, tend.—[Sh. uses “propend” only in this instance; “propension” only in line 139 of this scene.]"]},"203":{"play":"In resolution to keep Helen still,","notes":[]},"204":{"play":"For ’tis a cause that hath no mean dependence","notes":[]},"205":{"play":"Upon our joint and several dignities.","notes":[]},"206":{"play":"TROILUS: Why, there you touched the life of our design!","notes":[]},"207":{"play":"Were it not glory that we more affected","notes":[]},"208":{"play":"Than the performance of our heaving spleens,","notes":["performance ... spleenes] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): The execution of spite and resentment."]},"209":{"play":"I would not wish a drop of Trojan blood","notes":[]},"210":{"play":"Spent more in her defense. But, worthy Hector,","notes":[]},"211":{"play":"She is a theme of honor and renown,","notes":[]},"212":{"play":"A spur to valiant and magnanimous deeds,","notes":["stale] THEOBALD (ed. 1733) remarks that “stale ... seems the Poet’s Antithesis to ‘Freshness.’ So in his Winter’s Tale [iv.i.12-14]:—‘so shall I do To the freshest things now reigning, and make stale The glistering of this present.’” 83-85. Pearle ... Merchants] CARTER (Sh. and Holy Scripture, 1905, p. 385) cites Matthew xiii, 45.—NOBLE (Sh.’s Biblical Knowledge, 1935, p. 214): The “pearl of great price” ... was a favourite metaphor of Shakespeare’s time. The Gospel text is, “Againe, the kingdome of heauen is like vnto a marchant man, seeking goodly pearles: Which when he had found one precious pearle, went and solde all that he had, and bought it.”—B."]},"213":{"play":"Whose present courage may beat down our foes,","notes":[]},"214":{"play":"And fame in time to come canonize us;","notes":["fame] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): [Read “sieve” with Q.] That is, into a common voider.—STEEVENS (Var. ’03): It is well known that sieves and half-sieves are baskets to be met with in every quarter of Covent Garden market; and that, in some families, baskets lined with tin are still employed as voiders. ... Dr. Farmer adds, that, in several counties of England, the baskets used for carrying out dirt, &c. are called sieves. The correction, therefore, in the second folio [“place”], appears to have been unnecessary.—KNIGHT (ed. 1841): That is true; but a “sieve” of fruit is a basket of “picked” fruit—of the finest fruit, sorted from the commoner, according to the original notion of “sieve,” which implies separation. “Same,” on the contrary, is used as a noun in the sense of a heap, or mass, collected in one place, in strict accordance with its Saxon derivation. Such use of the word is uncommon, but it is not the less correct.—[Knight does not explain this remarkable derivation. He probably took “same” to be related to “samnian,” or perhaps “samod.”]—DELIUS (ed. 1856) rejected “sieve” on the ground that it gives no satisfactory meaning, that it cannot, as Johnson says, mean a common voider. In Die Tieck'sche Shaksperkritik (1846, pp. 107–108) he proposed “safe,” “Speiseschrank” (written “saue” and easily corruptible to “same” and “siue”). In his first (1855) and subsequent editions of Sh. he proposed “sink” (based on “siue”), pointing out that in Coriolanus, I.i.120, the belly is called “the sink o' the body.”,—HERTZBERG (ed. 1877) suggests that “siue” is a variant spelling for “sew” (seugh, sheugh, sough, etc.), meaning ditch, drain, sewer. [Compare N.E.D. and WRIGHT (1904).]—THISELTON (N.Q., 14 Oct., 1899, p. 304) thinks that “same” and “siue” are both misprints. “Since non-final s for f or for the composite fi, and u (as v was printed) for r, are easy printers' blunders, it is not unlikely that the word in the original manuscript was ‘fire,’ which on a revision was changed to ‘flame,’ in order to avoid the awkward echo of the sound of ‘viands’ in the preceding line. On this theory, allowing for the misprints, we have a reconcilement between the Quarto and Folio readings, and an interesting trace of careful revision on the part of the poet.”—[Nevertheless, Steevens' note has sufficed to bolster “sieve” and make it the accepted reading. Confirmation, however, seems to be lacking for Farmer’s statement that “sieve” is, or was, a dialectical name for a voider. The case for “sieve” would be considerably","canonize] Glorify. N.E.D. cites Marlowe’s Faustus, I.iii8: “Faustus, these books, thy wit, and our experience, Shall make all nations to canonize us.”"]},"215":{"play":"For I presume brave Hector would not lose","notes":[]},"216":{"play":"So rich advantage of a promised glory","notes":[]},"217":{"play":"As smiles upon the forehead of this action","notes":[]},"218":{"play":"For the wide world’s revenue.","notes":[]},"219":{"play":"HECTOR: I am yours,","notes":[]},"220":{"play":"You valiant offspring of great Priamus.","notes":[]},"221":{"play":"I have a roisting challenge sent amongst","notes":[]},"222":{"play":"The dull and factious nobles of the Greeks","notes":[]},"223":{"play":"Will strike amazement to their drowsy spirits.","notes":[]},"224":{"play":"I was advertised their great general slept,","notes":[]},"225":{"play":"Whilst emulation in the army crept.","notes":["emulation] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, envy, factious contention.—[This is the usual meaning in Sh.]"]},"226":{"play":"This, I presume, will wake him.","notes":[]},"227":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 2, SCENE 3":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Thersites, alone.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"THERSITES: How now, Thersites? What, lost in the","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"labyrinth of thy fury? Shall the elephant Ajax carry","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"it thus? He beats me, and I rail at him. O, worthy","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"satisfaction! Would it were otherwise, that I could","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"beat him whilst he railed at me. ’Sfoot, I’ll learn to","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"conjure and raise devils but I’ll see some issue of","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"my spiteful execrations. Then there’s Achilles, a","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"rare enginer! If Troy be not taken till these two undermine","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"it, the walls will stand till they fall of","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"themselves. O thou great thunder-darter of Olympus,","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"forget that thou art Jove, the king of gods;","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"and, Mercury, lose all the serpentine craft of thy","notes":["plague] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I cannot help regarding the vulgar epi"]},"14":{"play":"caduceus, if you take not that little, little, less than","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"little wit from them that they have, which short-armed","notes":["short-arm’d] DYCE (Remarks, 1844, pp. 152-53): The right reading is undoubtedly “short-aimed” ignorance,—i.e. ignorance whose aim is short. In Coriolanus [I.ii.22-23] we find: “By the discovery We shall be shorten’d in our aim.” [He supports his argument by reference to Hamlet, IV.vii.24, where Q has rightly “aym’d,” but F “arm’d.”]—COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868): This has been changed to “short-aim’d”; but the original word expresses “incapable of reaching far,” “capable of achieving little”; while the word which is proposed as its substitution conveys but a superfluously-given meaning, since “ignorance” is, of course, “short-aim’d,” or comes short of its aim."]},"16":{"play":"ignorance itself knows is so abundant","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"scarce it will not in circumvention deliver a fly","notes":["in circumvention] Their wit is not equal to circumventing a spider. 16-17. without ... web] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, “without drawing their swords to cut the web.” They use no means but those of violence."]},"18":{"play":"from a spider without drawing their massy irons","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"and cutting the web. After this, the vengeance on","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"the whole camp! Or rather, the Neapolitan bone-ache!","notes":["bone-ach] PARTRIDGE (Sh.’s Bawdy, 1947, p. 158): Syphilis.—B."]},"21":{"play":"For that, methinks, is the curse depending","notes":["placket] LINTHICUM (Costume in the Drama of Sh., 1936, p. 192): A short opening or “vent” at the top of a woman’s petticoat or kirtle skirt, usually in front. ... In the drama placket is frequently used with indelicate suggestion."]},"22":{"play":"on those that war for a placket. I have said my","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"prayers, and devil Envy say “Amen.”—What ho,","notes":["diuell, enuie, fay Amen] RICHARD SIMPSON (Academy, IX, 1876, 402) first suggested that these words may echo the Epilogue to Mucedorus, 1610 (Brooke, ed. 1908, p. 126, line 79) where Envy is obliged to say “Amen” to Comedy’s prayer addressed to King James. As CHAMBERS points out (William Sh., 1930, I, 444), this passage first occurs in the edition of 1610, which presents a completely new writing of the Epilogue, evidently for a revival. The date of the revival is very uncertain. The words of Thersites have also, with less plausibility, been referred to Jonson’s Poetaster, where Envy opens the play, but does not say “Amen.”—[CARTER (Sh. and Holy Scripture, 1905, p. 385) quotes the explanatory note in Geneva-Tomson on 1 Corinthians xiv, 16, which is abbreviated from the Geneva (1579): “One onely made the praiers & the rest of the people followed in heart his words, & when he had prayed, they al said, Amen, signifying that they beleeued assuredly yt God would grant their requests.” The primary reference is thus certainly to church custom as given in the New Testament. Envy had been a devil from time immemorial and was evidently fundamental from the first in this play. Devil Envy—“speak of the devil”—appears in the person of Patroclus to say (in Q) “Amen,” and thus unwittingly to invoke a curse upon himself.—B.]"]},"24":{"play":"my lord Achilles!","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"PATROCLUS, within  Who’s there? Thersites? Good","notes":["Patr.] The anonymous suggestion, recorded by the CAMBRIDGE EDITORS (see Textual Notes), that Patroclus speaks “within” and does not enter until Thersites says “Wher’s Achilles?” in line 33, deserves more attention than it has had. It is certainly not decisive that Patroclus says “come in and raile”; but the arrangement proposed would get rid of a difficult wait for Patroclus while Thersites soliloquizes, and the speech, “What art thou deuout?” etc. would come more naturally if Patroclus entered just in time to see Thersites rise from his knees. 25-26. guilt counterfeit ... flipt] WHALLEY (Var. ’85): Here is a plain allusion to the counterfeit piece of money called a “slip,” which occurs again in Romeo"]},"26":{"play":"Thersites, come in and rail.","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"THERSITES: If I could ’a remembered a gilt counterfeit,","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"thou couldst not have slipped out of my contemplation.","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"But it is no matter. Thyself upon thyself! The","notes":["thy selfe vpon thy selfe] RANN (ed. 1789): My utmost severity towards thee is comprized in this short imprecation, “remain only the’doit thou art.”—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): I.e., I can invoke no worse curse than this."]},"30":{"play":"common curse of mankind, folly and ignorance,","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"be thine in great revenue! Heaven bless thee from","notes":["bleffe] Protect; usually said of evil things. Compare Milton’s Il Penseroso, lines 83-84: “Or the bellman’s drowsy charm To bless the doors from nightly harm” (N.E.D.)."]},"32":{"play":"a tutor, and discipline come not near thee! Let thy","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"blood be thy direction till thy death; then if she","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"that lays thee out says thou art a fair corse, I’ll be","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"sworn and sworn upon ’t she never shrouded any","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"but lazars. Amen.","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"[Enter Patroclus.]","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"Where’s Achilles?","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"PATROCLUS: What, art thou devout? Wast thou in","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"prayer?","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"THERSITES: Ay. The heavens hear me!","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Amen.","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"ACHILLES, within  Who’s there?","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Thersites, my lord.","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"ACHILLES, within  Where? Where? O, where?","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"[Enter Achilles.]","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"To Thersites. Art thou come? Why, my cheese, my","notes":["cheese] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) cites Middleton’s Your Five Gallants (ed. Bullen), II.iii.323: “It comes like cheese after a great feast, to digest the rest.”"]},"48":{"play":"digestion, why hast thou not served thyself in to my","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"table so many meals? Come, what’s Agamemnon?","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"THERSITES: Thy commander, Achilles.—Then, tell me,","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"Patroclus, what’s Achilles?","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Thy lord, Thersites. Then, tell me, I pray","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"thee, what’s Thersites?","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"THERSITES: Thy knower, Patroclus. Then, tell me, Patroclus,","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"what art thou?","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Thou must tell that knowest.","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"ACHILLES: O tell, tell.","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"THERSITES: I’ll decline the whole question. Agamemnon","notes":["declin] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Deduce the question from the first case to the last.—COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868): The word “decline” is here used in its grammatical sense; to state the question in all its [possible—B.] forms, as a noun is stated in all its cases and numbers."]},"59":{"play":"commands Achilles, Achilles is my lord, I am","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"Patroclus’ knower, and Patroclus is a fool.","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"PATROCLUS: You rascal!","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"THERSITES: Peace, fool. I have not done.","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"ACHILLES, to Patroclus  He is a privileged man.—Proceed,","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"Thersites.","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"THERSITES: Agamemnon is a fool, Achilles is a fool,","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"Thersites is a fool, and, as aforesaid, Patroclus is a","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"fool.","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"ACHILLES: Derive this. Come.","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"THERSITES: Agamemnon is a fool to offer to command","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"Achilles, Achilles is a fool to be commanded of","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"Agamemnon, Thersites is a fool to serve such a fool,","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"and this Patroclus is a fool positive.","notes":["positive] MALONE (ed. 1790): The poet is still thinking of his grammar; the first degree of comparison being here in his thoughts.—N.E.D.: Absolute, unconditional; opposed to “relative” and “comparative.”"]},"73":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Why am I a fool?","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"THERSITES: Make that demand of the creator. It suffices","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"me thou art.","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"[Enter at a distance Agamemnon, Ulysses, Nestor,","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"Diomedes, Ajax, and Calchas.]","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"Look you, who comes here?","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"ACHILLES: Patroclus, I’ll speak with nobody.—Come in","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"with me, Thersites. He exits.","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"THERSITES: Here is such patchery, such juggling, and","notes":["patcherie] Authorities differ as to derivation and meaning. N.E.D. derives from \"patch,\" a fool, and defines as meaning \"roguery,\" \"knavery\"; without, however, explaining how the word came to mean roguery and not folly. Most of the Sh. dictionaries give the same meaning. But Century Dictionary, SCHMIDT (1875), and FOSTER (Sh. Word-Book, 1908) derive from \"patch,\" a piece of cloth used to mend a tear, and explain as meaning botchery, clumsy workmanship, and hence \"gross and bungling hypocrisy\" (Schmidt), or roguery (Foster)."]},"82":{"play":"such knavery. All the argument is a whore and a","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"cuckold, a good quarrel to draw emulous factions","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"and bleed to death upon. Now the dry serpigo on","notes":["Suppaeago] Serpigo, a general term for creeping skin diseases [N.E.D.]. Med. L. serpigo, from serpere, to creep."]},"85":{"play":"the subject, and war and lechery confound all!","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"AGAMEMNON, to Patroclus  Where is Achilles?","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Within his tent, but ill-disposed, my lord.","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Let it be known to him that we are here.","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"He shent our messengers, and we lay by","notes":["He sent] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): Who sent, in the Name of Accuracy? ... I make no doubt, but the Poet wrote; \"He shent our Messengers\"; i.e. rebuked, ill-treated, rated out of his Presence. As, in Anthony, Augustus complains [II.ii.77-78] of the like Treatment from that Prince; \"Did pocket up my Letters, and with Taunts Did gibe my Missives out of Audience.\" The word \"shent\"... occurs more than once again in our Author. \"Clown. Alas, Sir, be patient. What say you, Sir? I am shent for speaking to you\" [Twelfth Night, IV.ii.99-100]. \"How in my Words soever she be shent, To give them Seals never did my Soul consent\" [Hamlet, III.ii.388-89].—[See also Merry Wives, I.iv.33, and Coriolanus, V.ii.94. Of the four instances of \"shent\" listed in Bartlett, all but the present one are in the passive voice. N.E.D. (vi: 2) defines \"to blame, reproach, reprove; to revile, scold.\" For the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries it lists no use, in this sense, in the active voice, and perhaps the active use was old-fashioned by 1600. Nevertheless Spenser employs it frequently. STEEVENS (Var. '78) cites Faerie Queene, VI.vi.33: \"He for such basenesse shamefully him shent,\" and also (Var. '03) found an exact parallel to the present instance in the old metrical romance The Sowdon of Babylonne: \"All messengers he doth shende.\")—To COLLIER's \"We sent\" (ed. 1842), and his opinion that \"He\" is \"a mere transcriber's error\" for \"We,\" DYCE (Remarks, 1844, p. 154) replies that \"a simple declaration that Agamemnon had sent messengers to Achilles ... by no means suits with what immediately follows in the sentence. Theobald's correction may not be the genuine reading; but it appears to me greatly preferable to that now adopted.\" To Collier's argument that Achilles \"had not rebuked any messengers,\" his answer is that that is true for the text of the play, but neither does it appear from any previous scene that messengers had been used; and yet they had, because Agamemnon says so; and it is not likely that Achilles treated them with respect.—THISELTON (Notulae Criticae, 1907, 63-71, p. 28) suggests \"scant\" (i.e. \"scanted\"), a word used several times by Sh., and occurring below in IV.iv.46: \"scants us with a single famisht kisse.\"—[But besides the questionable practice of assuming a preterite form which has no recorded existence, no meaning of \"scant,\" either in Sh. or in N.E.D., will fit with \"messengers.\" Theobald's emendation has never been seriously challenged.]"]},"91":{"play":"Our appertainments, visiting of him.","notes":["appertainments] Those formalities which appertain to the dignity of my place."]},"92":{"play":"Let him be told so, lest perchance he think","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"We dare not move the question of our place","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"Or know not what we are.","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"PATROCLUS: I shall say so to him. He exits.","notes":["I shall] TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., vii, 1932, 73) believes that in Elizabethan verse \"shall\" is frequently meant to be contracted to \"'se\" (\"I'se\" and \"you'se\"). \"The frequent occurrence of extra-metrical 'shall' warrants the assumption that writers intended it to be contracted.\""]},"96":{"play":"ULYSSES: We saw him at the opening of his tent.","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"He is not sick.","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"AJAX: Yes, lion-sick, sick of proud heart. You may call","notes":["Lyon ficke] Explained in the next phrase. The allusion is to the traditional pride of the lion. Compare Macbeth, iv.i.90: \"Be lion-mettled, proud.\" 96-97. argument Achilles] GREY (Notes, 1754, ii, 240) first called attention to Erasmus' Adagia (chii. i, cent. 7, prov. 41): \"Denique rationem aut argumentum Achilleum vocant, quod sit insuperabile & insolubile.\"—[Sh. must have had this proverb in mind; it gives a point of double meaning to Ulysses' comment, and accounts for the rather forced word-order of the clause.]"]},"99":{"play":"it melancholy if you will favor the man, but, by my","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"head, ’tis pride. But, why, why? Let him show us a","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"cause.—A word, my lord.","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"He and Agamemnon walk aside.","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"NESTOR: What moves Ajax thus to bay at him?","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"ULYSSES: Achilles hath inveigled his fool from him.","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"NESTOR: Who, Thersites?","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"ULYSSES: He.","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"NESTOR: Then will Ajax lack matter, if he have lost his","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"argument.","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"ULYSSES: No. You see, he is his argument that has his","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"argument: Achilles.","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"NESTOR: All the better. Their fraction is more our wish","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"than their faction. But it was a strong composure a","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"fool could disunite.","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"ULYSSES: The amity that wisdom knits not, folly may","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"easily untie.","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"[Enter Patroclus.]","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"Here comes Patroclus.","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"NESTOR: No Achilles with him.","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"ULYSSES: The elephant hath joints, but none for courtesy;","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"his legs are legs for necessity, not for flexure.","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"PATROCLUS, to Agamemnon","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"Achilles bids me say he is much sorry","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"If anything more than your sport and pleasure","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"Did move your greatness and this noble state","notes":["noble State] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Person of high dignity; spoken of Agamemnon.—STEEVENS (Var. ’73): “Noble state” rather means “the stately train of attending nobles whom you bring with you.”"]},"125":{"play":"To call upon him. He hopes it is no other","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"But for your health and your digestion sake,","notes":["digestion] For the suppression of the genitive ending (before the s-sound of “sake”) see FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §199.)"]},"127":{"play":"An after-dinner’s breath.","notes":["breath] SCHMIDT (1874): Gentle exercise. See IV.v.107-08."]},"128":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Hear you, Patroclus:","notes":[]},"129":{"play":"We are too well acquainted with these answers,","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"But his evasion, winged thus swift with scorn,","notes":[]},"131":{"play":"Cannot outfly our apprehensions.","notes":["lines] HANMER’s (ed. 1744) “lunes” (i.e. mad freaks) has been accepted by most editors. It is supported by the one indubitable occurrence in Sh., Winter’s Tale, ii.ii.30: “These dangerous unsafe lunes i’ the king.” But the word in this sense has not been found elsewhere before recent times (N.E.D. lists a few instances from 1778 on), and these modern uses probably all go back to Sh.—SCHMIDT (Sh. Jbch., III, 1868, 351-54) questions whether “lines” may not be right. In Merry Wives, iv.ii.177-18 (“Why, woman, your husband is in his old lunes again”), “lunes” is the modern reading for “lines” of F and “vaine” of Q1-2. It is a question whether the word in Winter’s Tale is not a mistake for “lines.” Schmidt would interpret “lines” as “behavior” (Verhalten, Benehmen).—N.E.D. (line, sb.2: 29) cites Merry Wives and T. and C., and defines as “‘goings on,’ caprices or fits of temper,” calling attention to the Warwickshire dialect phrase “on a line,” i.e. in a rage."]},"132":{"play":"Much attribute he hath, and much the reason","notes":["attribute] Reputation, honor. Compare Hamlet, I.iv.20–22: “Indeed it takes From our achievements ... The pith and marrow of our attribute.”"]},"133":{"play":"Why we ascribe it to him. Yet all his virtues,","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"Not virtuously on his own part beheld,","notes":[]},"135":{"play":"Do in our eyes begin to lose their gloss,","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"Yea, and like fair fruit in an unwholesome dish,","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"Are like to rot untasted. Go and tell him","notes":[]},"138":{"play":"We come to speak with him; and you shall not sin","notes":["you shall] Possibly contracted in speaking to “you’se.” See note on II.iii.83."]},"139":{"play":"If you do say we think him overproud","notes":[]},"140":{"play":"And underhonest, in self-assumption greater","notes":["Then ... judgement] This may be interpreted as meaning “than true judges know him to be” (SCHMIDT 1874), or “than in the distinctive mark of good judgment” (DEIGHTON, ed. 1906). The latter interpretation is to be preferred. in the] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Surely [these] two unnecessary words ..., which spoil the metre, should be omitted."]},"141":{"play":"Than in the note of judgment; and worthier than","notes":[]},"142":{"play":"himself","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"Here tend the savage strangeness he puts on,","notes":["tends] SCHMIDT (1875): To attend, to wait on, to serve. fauage ftrangenesfe] Uncivil, rude reserve."]},"144":{"play":"Disguise the holy strength of their command,","notes":[]},"145":{"play":"And underwrite in an observing kind","notes":["under write ... kinde] Submit respectfully to. For the particular sense of “observe” see SCHMIDT (1875)."]},"146":{"play":"His humorous predominance—yea, watch","notes":[]},"147":{"play":"His course and time, his ebbs and flows, as if","notes":[]},"148":{"play":"The passage and whole carriage of this action","notes":[]},"149":{"play":"Rode on his tide. Go tell him this, and add","notes":[]},"150":{"play":"That, if he overhold his price so much,","notes":[]},"151":{"play":"We’ll none of him. But let him, like an engine","notes":[]},"152":{"play":"Not portable, lie under this report:","notes":[]},"153":{"play":"“Bring action hither; this cannot go to war.”","notes":[]},"154":{"play":"A stirring dwarf we do allowance give","notes":["allowance] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): \"Allowance\" is \"approbation.\" So, in King Lear [II.iv.189-90]: \"If your sweet sway Allow obedience.\"—[See also above, I.iii.391: \"Giue him allowance as the worthier man.\"]"]},"155":{"play":"Before a sleeping giant. Tell him so.","notes":[]},"156":{"play":"PATROCLUS: I shall, and bring his answer presently.","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: In second voice we’ll not be satisfied;","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"We come to speak with him.—Ulysses, enter you.","notes":[]},"159":{"play":"Ulysses exits, with Patroclus.","notes":[]},"160":{"play":"AJAX: What is he more than another?","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: No more than what he thinks he is.","notes":[]},"162":{"play":"AJAX: Is he so much? Do you not think he thinks himself","notes":[]},"163":{"play":"a better man than I am?","notes":[]},"164":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: No question.","notes":[]},"165":{"play":"AJAX: Will you subscribe his thought and say he is?","notes":[]},"166":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: No, noble Ajax. You are as strong, as","notes":[]},"167":{"play":"valiant, as wise, no less noble, much more gentle,","notes":[]},"168":{"play":"and altogether more tractable.","notes":[]},"169":{"play":"AJAX: Why should a man be proud? How doth pride","notes":[]},"170":{"play":"grow? I know not what pride is.","notes":[]},"171":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Your mind is the clearer, Ajax, and your","notes":[]},"172":{"play":"virtues the fairer. He that is proud eats up himself.","notes":[]},"173":{"play":"Pride is his own glass, his own trumpet, his own","notes":[]},"174":{"play":"chronicle; and whatever praises itself but in the","notes":[]},"175":{"play":"deed devours the deed in the praise.","notes":[]},"176":{"play":"AJAX: I do hate a proud man as I hate the engendering","notes":[]},"177":{"play":"of toads.","notes":[]},"178":{"play":"NESTOR, aside","notes":[]},"179":{"play":"And yet he loves himself. Is ’t not strange?","notes":[]},"180":{"play":"[Enter Ulysses.]","notes":[]},"181":{"play":"ULYSSES: Achilles will not to the field tomorrow.","notes":["Achilles ... to morrow] DANIEL (“Time-Analysis of T. and C.,” New Sh. Soc. Transactions, 1877–79, p. 181) points out that this statement and another in lines 267–68 (“to morrow We must with all our maine of power stand fast”) “are somewhat ambiguous, for in fact only the single combat between Hector and Ajax is resolved on for the morrow.”—[The latter of the two statements is more than ambiguous; it is a flat contradiction to the truce and the single combat.]"]},"182":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: What’s his excuse?","notes":[]},"183":{"play":"ULYSSES: He doth rely on none,","notes":[]},"184":{"play":"But carries on the stream of his dispose,","notes":["streame of his commencement (Q)] MALONE (ed. 1790): “His” ... was probably misprinted for “this,” as it is in a subsequent passage in this scene in the quarto copy [line 204]: “And how his silence drinks up his [this, F1] applause.”"]},"185":{"play":"Without observance or respect of any,","notes":[]},"186":{"play":"In will peculiar and in self-admission.","notes":["will peculiar] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): “Will peculiar” should be read like “self-admission” with a hyphen. The meaning is, He does nothing but what his own will dictates, and approves of nothing but what his own fancy recommends."]},"187":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Why, will he not, upon our fair request,","notes":[]},"188":{"play":"Untent his person and share th’ air with us?","notes":[]},"189":{"play":"ULYSSES: Things small as nothing, for request’s sake only,","notes":["for requests sake onely] SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 427): Merely because they were requested."]},"190":{"play":"He makes important. Possessed he is with greatness","notes":["possest he is] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. greatness has got possession of him, as the devil of a witch. 174-75. [speakes ... selfe-breath] SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 427): He cannot, though his own flatterer, find terms of eulogy suited to the inordinate claims of his pride.—HUDSON (ed. 1881) explains, “speaks with a pride that makes him blame or scorn himself for speaking,” and finds a similarity in Julius Caesar, I.ii.205-08: “Seldom he smiles, and smiles in such a sort As if he mock’d himself, and scorn’d his spirit That could be moved to smile at any thing.” 175-79. See I.iii.204 ff., and Appendix, pp. 416-18.—B. 177-79. That twixt ... gainst it selfe] CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 124): The mental and active parts of Achilles are as members of this kingdom, which the swoln and hot discourse above-mention’d has put in commotion; and, in that state, the kingdom is said to rage and batter ’gainst itself.—[Compare Julius Caesar, II.i.67-69: “The state of man, Like to a little kingdom, suffers then The nature of an insurrection.”]"]},"191":{"play":"And speaks not to himself but with a pride","notes":[]},"192":{"play":"That quarrels at self-breath. Imagined worth","notes":[]},"193":{"play":"Holds in his blood such swoll’n and hot discourse","notes":[]},"194":{"play":"That ’twixt his mental and his active parts","notes":[]},"195":{"play":"Kingdomed Achilles in commotion rages","notes":[]},"196":{"play":"And batters down himself. What should I say?","notes":[]},"197":{"play":"He is so plaguy proud that the death-tokens of it","notes":[]},"198":{"play":"Cry “No recovery.”","notes":[]},"199":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Let Ajax go to him.—","notes":[]},"200":{"play":"Dear lord, go you and greet him in his tent.","notes":[]},"201":{"play":"’Tis said he holds you well and will be led","notes":[]},"202":{"play":"At your request a little from himself.","notes":[]},"203":{"play":"ULYSSES: O Agamemnon, let it not be so!","notes":["See Textual Note. This and subsequent speeches in the scene are enclosed by Capell in quotation marks, this being his way of marking an “aside.”"]},"204":{"play":"We’ll consecrate the steps that Ajax makes","notes":[]},"205":{"play":"When they go from Achilles. Shall the proud lord","notes":[]},"206":{"play":"That bastes his arrogance with his own seam","notes":["leame] N.E.D.: Fat, grease. ... OF. saim ..., mod. Fr. only in saindoux lard. ... [From] popular L. *sagimen, related to classical L. sagina, fattening, fatness."]},"207":{"play":"And never suffers matter of the world","notes":[]},"208":{"play":"[Enter his thoughts, save such as doth revolve]","notes":[]},"209":{"play":"And ruminate himself—shall he be worshipped","notes":[]},"210":{"play":"Of that we hold an idol more than he?","notes":[]},"211":{"play":"No. This thrice-worthy and right valiant lord","notes":[]},"212":{"play":"Shall not so stale his palm, nobly acquired,","notes":["ftaule his Palme] SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, 1, 428): Make his honours, his military trophies so cheap, common and familiar."]},"213":{"play":"Nor, by my will, assubjugate his merit,","notes":["affubiugate] SISTER MIRIAM JOSEPH (Sh.’s Use of the Arts of Language, 1947, p. 51): The addition of a syllable at the beginning of a word was called prosthesis.—B."]},"214":{"play":"As amply titled as Achilles is,","notes":[]},"215":{"play":"By going to Achilles.","notes":[]},"216":{"play":"That were to enlard his fat-already pride","notes":[]},"217":{"play":"And add more coals to Cancer when he burns","notes":["adde more Coles to Cancer] Ravisius Textor (Epitheta, 1549, p. 170): Cancer ... est ... signum coeleste, quod sol percurrit mense lunio, quam iam vehementissimus est calor. [Cancer thus becomes the symbol of heat, with various epithets applied. Consequently, to carry coals to Cancer is to add to what already has too much. Compare “carry coals to Newcastle.”]—B. Cancer] Singer (ed. 1826): The sign in the zodiac, into which the sun enters June 21."]},"218":{"play":"With entertaining great Hyperion.","notes":[]},"219":{"play":"This lord go to him? Jupiter forbid","notes":[]},"220":{"play":"And say in thunder “Achilles, go to him.”","notes":[]},"221":{"play":"NESTOR, aside to Diomedes","notes":[]},"222":{"play":"O, this is well; he rubs the vein of him.","notes":[]},"223":{"play":"DIOMEDES, aside to Nestor","notes":[]},"224":{"play":"And how his silence drinks up this applause!","notes":[]},"225":{"play":"AJAX: If I go to him, with my armèd fist","notes":[]},"226":{"play":"I’ll pash him o’er the face.","notes":["pas[h] N.E.D.: To strike ... violently, ... to ... smash. [Apparently, like many other verbs in -ash (e.g. bash, smash), of onomatopoeic origin. A much-used word from c. 1575 for some sixty years; but now chiefly dialectical. See below, v.v.12.]"]},"227":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: O, no, you shall not go.","notes":[]},"228":{"play":"AJAX: An he be proud with me, I’ll feeze his pride.","notes":["phefe] N.E.D.: [Obsolete form of feezel, to drive off or away; to ... put to flight. ... The threat \"I'll feeze you\" seems to have given rise to the following senses: a. vaguely, To \"do for,\" \"settle the business of\" (a person); b. To beat, flog."]},"229":{"play":"Let me go to him.","notes":[]},"230":{"play":"ULYSSES: Not for the worth that hangs upon our quarrel.","notes":[]},"231":{"play":"AJAX: A paltry, insolent fellow.","notes":[]},"232":{"play":"NESTOR, aside  How he describes himself!","notes":[]},"233":{"play":"AJAX: Can he not be sociable?","notes":[]},"234":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside  The raven chides blackness.","notes":[]},"235":{"play":"AJAX: I’ll let his humorous blood.","notes":[]},"236":{"play":"AGAMEMNON, aside  He will be the physician that","notes":[]},"237":{"play":"should be the patient.","notes":[]},"238":{"play":"AJAX: An all men were of my mind—","notes":[]},"239":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside  Wit would be out of fashion.","notes":[]},"240":{"play":"AJAX: —he should not bear it so; he should eat swords","notes":["eate Swords] GREY (Notes, 1754, II, 241-42): Qu. He should eat's words first? Though he [Sh.] has an expression somewhat like the former, in Much Ado [IV.i.272-73]: \"Bene. By my sword, Beatrix, thou lov'st me. Beat. Do"]},"241":{"play":"first. Shall pride carry it?","notes":[]},"242":{"play":"NESTOR, aside  An ’twould, you’d carry half.","notes":[]},"243":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside  He would have ten shares.","notes":["ten shares] Ulysses amends Nestor's \"half\" to \"ten shares,\" the implication being that ten shares would constitute the whole. SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 428) saw here \"an allusion to the distribution of theatrical profits which are still, in some country companies, divided into parts that are called shares.\"—C. W. WALLACE (Century Magazine, LXXX, 1910, 590) thought there was specific allusion to the ten shares into which the Globe property was divided when that theater was built in 1599. One \"moiety\" or half of the property was owned by Richard and Cuthbert Burbage, the other by Sh. and four fellow-actors, making a total of ten shares. Dating T. and C. in 1602, Wallace thought the jibe was directed at Kempe, owner of one-tenth, who had left the company in 1599 and struck out conceitedly on his own; but that sounds far-fetched. The allusion would have a closer pertinency if Richard Burbage were designed for the part of Ajax.—[Adams queries \"How?\" and adds that ten shares is used for \"all\"; i.e., \"all pride.\"—B.] 224-25. hee's ... warme] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): The latter Part of Ajax's Speech is certainly got out of Place, and ought to be assign'd to Nestor, as I have ventur'd to transpose it. Ajax is feeding on his Vanity, and boasting what he'll do to Achilles; he'll pash him o'er the Face, he'll make him eat Swords; he'll knead him, he'll supple him, &c. Nestor and Ulysses slily labour to keep him up in this Vein; and to this End Nestor craftily hints, that Ajax is not warm yet, but must be cram'd with more Flattery.—[But being through warm was both the cause and the consequence of the kneading and the suppling, and so certainly belongs with those items.—B.]"]},"244":{"play":"AJAX: I will knead him; I’ll make him supple.","notes":[]},"245":{"play":"NESTOR, aside  He’s not yet through warm. Force him","notes":[]},"246":{"play":"with praises. Pour in, pour in; his ambition is dry.","notes":["Force]: A variant form of \"farce,\" to stuff, to fill full of something"]},"247":{"play":"ULYSSES, to Agamemnon","notes":[]},"248":{"play":"My lord, you feed too much on this dislike.","notes":[]},"249":{"play":"NESTOR, to Agamemnon","notes":[]},"250":{"play":"Our noble general, do not do so.","notes":[]},"251":{"play":"DIOMEDES, to Agamemnon","notes":[]},"252":{"play":"You must prepare to fight without Achilles.","notes":[]},"253":{"play":"ULYSSES: Why, ’tis this naming of him does him harm.","notes":[]},"254":{"play":"Here is a man—but ’tis before his face;","notes":[]},"255":{"play":"I will be silent.","notes":[]},"256":{"play":"NESTOR: Wherefore should you so?","notes":[]},"257":{"play":"He is not emulous, as Achilles is.","notes":[]},"258":{"play":"ULYSSES: Know the whole world, he is as valiant—","notes":["emulous] See note on II.ii.220. 245 ff. Praise him that got thee] See the parallel passage in Taming of the Shrew, IV.v.38-40, \"Happy the parents of so fair a child; Happier the man,"]},"259":{"play":"AJAX: A whoreson dog, that shall palter with us thus!","notes":[]},"260":{"play":"Would he were a Trojan!","notes":[]},"261":{"play":"NESTOR: What a vice were it in Ajax now—","notes":[]},"262":{"play":"ULYSSES: If he were proud—","notes":[]},"263":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Or covetous of praise—","notes":[]},"264":{"play":"ULYSSES: Ay, or surly borne—","notes":[]},"265":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Or strange, or self-affected—","notes":[]},"266":{"play":"ULYSSES, to Ajax","notes":[]},"267":{"play":"Thank the heavens, lord, thou art of sweet","notes":[]},"268":{"play":"composure.","notes":[]},"269":{"play":"Praise him that gat thee, she that gave thee suck;","notes":[]},"270":{"play":"Famed be thy tutor, and thy parts of nature","notes":[]},"271":{"play":"Thrice famed beyond, beyond thy erudition;","notes":["beyond all erudition] BOSWELL (Var. ‘21): I think the quarto, if we correct the punctuation, affords the best reading: “—above all, thy erudition.” To praise Ajax for his learning corresponds with the rest of this speech, which is intended to feed the vanity of this “beef-witted lord.”"]},"272":{"play":"But he that disciplined thine arms to fight,","notes":[]},"273":{"play":"Let Mars divide eternity in twain","notes":[]},"274":{"play":"And give him half; and for thy vigor,","notes":[]},"275":{"play":"Bull-bearing Milo his addition yield","notes":["Milo] The celebrated athlete of Crotona, whose most notable exploit was to carry a four-year-old bull on his shoulders a distance of forty yards, kill it with one blow of his fist, and then eat it in one day. He is supposed to have lived in the sixth century B.C.; hence the present allusion is anachronistic. addition] WARNER (Letter to Garrick, 1768, pp. 37–38): The common meaning of the word “Addition” is very well known. But here, and in many other places of our author, it is us’d as a law term, and means, a title given to a man over and above his first or christian name and surname, shewing his estate, degree, trade, occupation, age, place or dwelling, or alluding to some exploit or atcheivement. [He cites North’s Plutarch, Life of Caius Martius Coriolanus (ed. 1579, p. 242): “And thereby it appeareth, that the first name the Romaines haue, as Caius: was our Christian name now. The second, as Martius: was the name of the house and familie they came of. The third, was some addition geuen, either for some acte or notable seruice, or for some marke on their face, or of some shape of their bodie, or els for some speciall vertue they had. Euen so dyd the Græcians in olde time giue additions to Princes, by reason of some notable acte worthie memorie.”—Ed.]"]},"276":{"play":"To sinewy Ajax. I will not praise thy wisdom,","notes":[]},"277":{"play":"Which like a bourn, a pale, a shore confines","notes":["bourne] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): A “bourn” is a boundary, and sometimes a rivulet dividing one place from another."]},"278":{"play":"Thy spacious and dilated parts. Here’s Nestor,","notes":[]},"279":{"play":"Instructed by the antiquary times;","notes":[]},"280":{"play":"He must, he is, he cannot but be wise.—","notes":[]},"281":{"play":"But pardon, father Nestor, were your days","notes":[]},"282":{"play":"As green as Ajax’ and your brain so tempered,","notes":[]},"283":{"play":"You should not have the eminence of him,","notes":[]},"284":{"play":"But be as Ajax.","notes":[]},"285":{"play":"AJAX: Shall I call you father?","notes":["my good Sonne] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): In the folio and in the modern editions Ajax desires to give the title of \"father\" to Ulysses; in the quarto, more naturally, to Nestor.—STEEVENS (Var. '03) notes that this kind of sentimental adoption, as a mark of esteem, was common in Sh.'s age, and cites Ashmole's Diary: \"April 3. Mr. William Backhouse, of Swallowfield, in com. Berks, caused me to call him father thenceforward.\"—PYE (Comments on the Commentators, 1807, pp. 226-27): I must dissent from the quarto. Surely it is most natural that Ajax should express his regard to the person who had just been flattering him in the grossest manner.—KNIGHT (ed. 1841) agrees. \"The flattery of Ulysses has won the heart of Ajax; Nestor has said nothing.\""]},"286":{"play":"NESTOR: Ay, my good son.","notes":[]},"287":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Be ruled by him, Lord Ajax.","notes":[]},"288":{"play":"ULYSSES: There is no tarrying here; the hart Achilles","notes":[]},"289":{"play":"Keeps thicket. Please it our great general","notes":[]},"290":{"play":"To call together all his state of war.","notes":[]},"291":{"play":"Fresh kings are come to Troy. Tomorrow","notes":["come to Troy] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): We might complete this imperfect verse by reading: Fresh kings are come to succour Troy: &c. So, Spenser [F.Q., II.iii.31]: \"To succour the weake state of sad afflicted Troy.\""]},"292":{"play":"We must with all our main of power stand fast.","notes":[]},"293":{"play":"And here’s a lord—come knights from east to west","notes":[]},"294":{"play":"And cull their flower, Ajax shall cope the best.","notes":["cope] Usually defined (e.g. N.E.D.) as meaning to meet, come in contact with (either in a hostile or friendly way). MORGAN (Warwickshire Dialect, 1900, pp. 21, 100) identifies the word with \"cop\" (to catch), which he says is sometimes spelled \"cope\" in plays; but this is doubtful. See I.ii.37."]},"295":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Go we to council. Let Achilles sleep.","notes":[]},"296":{"play":"Light boats sail swift, though greater hulks draw deep.","notes":[]},"297":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 3, SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Music sounds within. Enter Pandarus and Paris’s","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"Servingman.]","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"PANDARUS: Friend, you, pray you, a word. Do you not","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"follow the young Lord Paris?","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"MAN: Ay, sir, when he goes before me.","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"PANDARUS: You depend upon him, I mean.","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"MAN: Sir, I do depend upon the Lord.","notes":["Lord] DELIUS (ed. 1856) finds a quibble here, upon “lord” (master) and “Lord” (God). 13-15. I hope ... Grace] MALONE (ed. 1790): The servant means to quibble. He hopes that Pandarus will become a better man than he is at present. In his next speech he chooses to understand Pandarus as if he had said he wished to grow better, and hence the servant affirms that he is in the state of “grace.” The second of these speeches has been pointed in the late editions, as if he had asked, of what “rank” Pandarus was.—TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., VII, 1932, 75): The explanation usually given of this bit of dialogue seems to miss the entire point. ... When the Servant says he knows Pandarus only super-"]},"8":{"play":"PANDARUS: You depend upon a notable gentleman. I","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"must needs praise him.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"MAN: The Lord be praised!","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"PANDARUS: You know me, do you not?","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"MAN: Faith, sir, superficially.","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"PANDARUS: Friend, know me better. I am the Lord","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"Pandarus.","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"MAN: I hope I shall know your Honor better.","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"PANDARUS: I do desire it.","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"MAN: You are in the state of grace?","notes":["state of Grace] WILSON (Christian Dictionary, 1622 ed., defines “grace” as “The bountifull liberality of God, enabling vs to giue to the poore, 2 Cor. 9, 8.” Geneva (1579) reads, “And God is able to make all grace to abound toward you, that ye alwayes hauing al sufficiencie in all things, may abound in euerie good worke.” The annotation on “al sufficiencie” is, “Lest they should giue but litle, distrusting to impoverish them selues thereby, he sheweth that God wil so blesse their liberall heartes, that both they shal haue inough for themselues and also to helpe others withal.” On “good worke,” “That ye may do good & helpe others at all times.” The Servant asks if Pandarus is in this state of grace; i.e., if he is going to give a gratuity; but Pandarus replies as if “Grace” were the title of honor, saying he is only a lord; i.e., that he has no gratuity to give. NOBLE (Sh.’s Biblical Knowledge, 1935, pp. 214–15) comments, “This servant is, as anybody can understand, playing on the cant phrases of fervent devotees, and the point would lose nothing in gesture and tone of voice. ‘You are in the state of grace’ after ‘I do desire it’ (taken by the Servant to be a desire that his honour. might be better) addressed to the disreputable Pandarus would gain by the reply, ‘Grace! not so, friend: honour and lordship are my titles.’ The ridicule of the cant phrases of zealots in Twelfth Night, I.v.120–21, and Othello, II.iii.94 ff., should be compared with this passage here.” I am not certain that any ridicule of cant phrases is intended, only comical, punning parody.—B."]},"18":{"play":"PANDARUS: Grace? Not so, friend. “Honor” and “Lordship”","notes":["Grace, not fo] MASON (Comments, 1807, p. 573): Pandarus disclaims the title of “grace,” as he was a lord only, not a duke."]},"19":{"play":"are my titles. What music is this?","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"MAN: I do but partly know, sir. It is music in parts.","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"PANDARUS: Know you the musicians?","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"MAN: Wholly, sir.","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"PANDARUS: Who play they to?","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"MAN: To the hearers, sir.","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"PANDARUS: At whose pleasure, friend?","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"MAN: At mine, sir, and theirs that love music.","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"PANDARUS: Command, I mean, friend.","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"MAN: Who shall I command, sir?","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"PANDARUS: Friend, we understand not one another. I","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"am too courtly and thou art too cunning. At whose","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"request do these men play?","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"MAN: That’s to ’t indeed, sir. Marry, sir, at the request of","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"Paris my lord, who is there in person; with him the","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"mortal Venus, the heart blood of beauty, love’s visible","notes":["too't] Compare Hamlet (Q2) v.ii.125, and the setting.—B. 32–33. inuifible foule] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): [HANMER has “visible.”] The other editions have “invisible,” which perhaps may be right, and may mean the “soul of love” invisible every where else.—COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868): The original phrase means “love’s celestial essence as made manifest in her,” “the ethereal spirit of love as impersonated in her.”—TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., VII, 1932, 76) finds support for the conjectured reading “invincible” in II Henry IV, III.ii.304–05: “his dimensions to any thick sight were invisible.” Q, Ff read “iuinincible”; most modern editions, “invisible.”"]},"35":{"play":"soul.","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"PANDARUS: Who, my cousin Cressida?","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"MAN: No, sir, Helen. Could not you find out that by her","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"attributes?","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"PANDARUS: It should seem, fellow, that thou hast not","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"seen the Lady Cressid. I come to speak with Paris","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"from the Prince Troilus. I will make a complimental","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"assault upon him, for my business seethes.","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"MAN: Sodden business! There’s a stewed phrase indeed.","notes":["Sodden … ftewed] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): The quibbling speaker seems"]},"44":{"play":"[Enter Paris and Helen with Attendants.]","notes":["Enter Paris and Helena] ARTHUR SYMONS (Harper’s Mag., cxv, 1907, 662): The wonderful scene between Paris and Helen ... gives, with its touch of luxurious, almost lascivious satire, the Renaissance picture of the two most famous lovers of the world. There is a refrain of “love, love, love,” grossly, luxuriously, mockingly. “Let thy song be love,” murmurs Helen; “this love will undo us all. O Cupid, Cupid, Cupid!” And Pari- echoes: “Aye, ove now, love, love, nothing but love.” ... In the dispraise of Helen, from the mouth of Diomedes (Act IV., Scene I), Shakespeare forces the note, making even those who had least cause rail on the woman with all the contempt of hate. Yet the noblest praise that has ever been said of Helen comes to her in this play from the undistinguished mouth of a punning servant, who calls her “the mortal Venus, the heart-blood of beauty, love’s invisible soul.” Later on, in Cleopatra, Shakespeare is to give us the supreme enchantress, taking her wholly from her own point of view, or at least with sympathetic impartiality. Here he seems to ask with Pandarus, “Is love a generation of vipers?” His cruelty with Helen is but a part of his protest, his criticism, his valuation of love. Love in this cloying scene between Paris and Helen appears before us sickly, a thing of effeminate horror, which can be escaped only by turning it into laughter."]},"45":{"play":"PANDARUS: Fair be to you, my lord, and to all this fair","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"company! Fair desires in all fair measure fairly","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"guide them!—Especially to you, fair queen, fair","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"thoughts be your fair pillow!","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"HELEN: Dear lord, you are full of fair words.","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"PANDARUS: You speak your fair pleasure, sweet","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"queen.—Fair prince, here is good broken music.","notes":["broken Musicke] PULVER (Dict. of Old English Music, 1923): A term with many uses and meanings. ... [In T. and C. it] means music in parts. But it can also mean the sounding together of instruments belonging to different families. ... The term was also applied to such instruments as harps, guitars, lutes, etc., which could not sustain their notes, and on which the chords had to be “broken.”—Bacon (Sylva Sylvarum, Cent. iii, no. 278; Spedding, Bacon, 1859, ii, 433) speaks of “that music, which we call broken music, or"]},"52":{"play":"PARIS: You have broke it, cousin, and, by my life, you","notes":["cozen] COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868): There was a Pandarus, son to Lycaon, who was a son of Priam by his former wife Laothoe; and it is possible that Shakespeare may have blended the identity of this Pandarus with that of the Pandarus who figures in Chaucer as Troilus’s devoted friend; or, it may be that Paris uses the term “cousin” as a token of the easy familiarity which subsisted between himself and his brother’s associate."]},"53":{"play":"shall make it whole again; you shall piece it out","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"with a piece of your performance.","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"HELEN: He is full of harmony.","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"PANDARUS: Truly, lady, no.","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"HELEN: O, sir—","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"PANDARUS: Rude, in sooth; in good sooth, very rude.","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"PARIS: Well said, my lord; well, you say so in fits.","notes":["in fits] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): Now and then, by fits; or perhaps a quibble is intended. A “fit” was a part or division of a song, sometimes a strain in music, and sometimes a measure in dancing.—RANN (ed. 1789) interprets the"]},"60":{"play":"PANDARUS: I have business to my lord, dear queen.—","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"My lord, will you vouchsafe me a word?","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"HELEN: Nay, this shall not hedge us out. We’ll hear you","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"sing, certainly.","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"PANDARUS: Well, sweet queen, you are pleasant with","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"me.—But, marry, thus, my lord: my dear lord and","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"most esteemed friend, your brother Troilus—","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"HELEN: My Lord Pandarus, honey-sweet lord—","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"PANDARUS: Go to, sweet queen, go to—commends himself","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"most affectionately to you—","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"HELEN: You shall not bob us out of our melody. If you","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"do, our melancholy upon your head!","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"PANDARUS: Sweet queen, sweet queen, that’s a sweet","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"queen, i’ faith—","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"HELEN: And to make a sweet lady sad is a sour offence.","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"PANDARUS: Nay, that shall not serve your turn, that","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"shall it not, in truth, la. Nay, I care not for such","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"words, no, no.—And, my lord, he desires you that","notes":["And my Lord] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Here I think the speech of Pandarus should begin, and the rest of it should be added to that of Helen. 81–82] my cozen ... with you] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 3 March, 1729/30): Dr. Thirlby gives us this remark: “Pandarus must be supposed to have forgot himself, if he speaks this. ... I think the latter branch of the sentence should be spoken by Paris.” But Sh. has himself hinted, that Pandarus and Paris are cousins.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): What have these words to do here? Paris’s last question was: “Where sups he (sc. Troilus)"]},"78":{"play":"if the King call for him at supper, you will make his","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"excuse.","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"HELEN: My Lord Pandarus—","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"PANDARUS: What says my sweet queen, my very, very","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"sweet queen?","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"PARIS: What exploit’s in hand? Where sups he tonight?","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"HELEN: Nay, but, my lord—","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"PANDARUS: What says my sweet queen? My cousin will","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"fall out with you.","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"HELEN, to Paris  You must not know where he sups.","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"PARIS: I’ll lay my life, with my disposer Cressida.","notes":["disposer] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I think “disposer” should, in these places, be read “disposer”; she that would separate Helen from him.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I do not understand the word “disposer,” nor know what to substitute in its place.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 496): “Disposer,” is a word never before, that I have heard or known, used by any English writer, for one who would separate a man from his wife. Besides, there is not the least reason to imagine, from any thing said in the play, that Cressida desired to separate Paris from Helena. On the other hand, the common reading, “disposer,” is a compliment of great gallantry, to signify, that Paris was entirely at Cressida’s disposal and command.—STEEVENS (Var. ’73): That Cressida wanted to separate Paris from Helen, or that the beauty of Cressida"]},"89":{"play":"PANDARUS: No, no, no such matter; you are wide.","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"Come, your disposer is sick.","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"PARIS: Well, I’ll make ’s excuse.","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"PANDARUS: Ay, good my lord. Why should you say Cressida?","notes":["disposer.]—RITSON (Remarks, 1783, p. 162): [Helen] calls Cressida her “deposer,” not for either of the reasons assigned by mr. Steevens, but because she had “deposed” her in the affections of Troilus, whom Pandarus, in a preceding scene, is ready to swear “she lov’d more than Paris.”—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 312): Paris means to call Cressida his Governor or Director, as it appears from what Helen says afterwards, “that they had been good friends.”—MALONE (ed. 1790): In what sense ... Paris can call Cressida his “disposer,” I am altogether ignorant. ... Perhaps Shakspere wrote—“disperser.” What Pandarus says afterwards, that “Paris and Cressida are twain,” supports this conjecture. I do not believe that “deposer” ... was our author’s word; for Cressida had not deposed Helen in the affections of Troilus. A speech in a former scene in which Pandarus says, Helen loves Troilus more than Paris ... proves nothing. Had he said that Troilus once loved Helen better than Cressida, and afterwards preferred Cressida to her, the observation might deserve some attention.—STEEVENS (Var. ’03) reported that the word is used in Chapman’s Epistle Dedicatoire to his translation of the first twelve books of the Iliad: “Then let not this Diuinitie [Poesy] in earth, Deare Prince, be sleighted, as she were the birth of idle Fancie; since she workes so hie: Nor let her poore disposer, Learning, lye Still Bed-rid.” “Disposer” here would seem to be equivalent to “handmaid,” which would fit well in the context of T. and C. if we could be sure that the meaning was current.—SINGER (Sh. Vindicated, 1853, pp. 194–95 and ed. 1856) followed Steevens and defined “disposer” as “handmaid.” But in ed. 1856 he said that “disposer appears to have been an equivalent term anciently for steward, or manager.” In this he was evidently relying on Baret’s Dictionarie (1580), which under Disposition gives: “A steward, or officer laying out monie for the houshold: a dispenser: a disposer”; but anyone using Baret will know that these are not meant as synonyms, but as approximates.—[Cotgrave’s French Dictionarie (ed. 1611) defines disposeur as “A disposer, sorter, orderer, arranger of.” So far as we can tell from the old dictionaries, the word commonly meant then what it does today.]—COLLIER (ed. 1858): [“Disposer” is an easy and probable misprint for “disperser,” which is an emendation of the Perkins folio, 1632.] Cressida was the “disperser of Paris,” and did not allow his merits: consequently Pandarus tells Helen, just afterwards, “she’ll none of him; they two are twain”: they had had a disagreement, and she was the “disperser” of Paris.—[It is hardly necessary to say that the quarrel between Cressida and Paris is wholly in Collier’s imagi-"]},"93":{"play":"No, your poor disposer’s sick.","notes":["disposer.]—Another line of interpretation was started by DYCE. In explaining (Remarks, 1844, pp. 37–39) the meaning of the Princess' remark in Love's Labor's Lost (ii.i.249), \"Boyet is disposed,\" he adduces a number of illustrations from the Elizabethan dramatists to prove that \"to be disposed\" meant to be \"inclined to wanton mirth.\"—Proceeding from this basis, STAUNTON (ed. 1860) wonders whether \"disposer ... possibly in Shakespeare's day may have been a colloquial term for a wild, forward damsel.\"—DYCE (ed. 1865) glosses: \"She who 'disposes' or inclines me to mirth by her pleasant (and rather free) talk\"; but in the Glossary (1867) attached to the same edition he considers that \"perhaps the more proper explanation ... is, 'she who is disposed or inclined to pleasant (and rather free) talk,—my merry, free-spoken damsel'.\"—FOSTER (Sh. Word-Book, 1908) offers essentially the same definition.—DELIUS (ed. 1856) was the first to propose \"mistress\" as the equivalent of \"disposer\": \"meine Gebieterin, d. h. die über mich verfügt, von dem Verbum to dispose, nennt in affectirter Galanterie Paris die Cressida.\"—BRINSLEY NICHOLSON (N.Q., 1 June, 1867, p. 435) combines Delius with Dyce: \"Paris is the ladies-gallant of Troy, and speaks of Cressida in the exaggerated style of his counterparts of the Elizabethan day, and exaggerates the more in that he is aware of Pandarus's belief in the super-excellence of Cressid's beauty. Hence he is her captive knight taken by force of beauty, or a bondslave. ... Probably she called him her Obedience, or simply her servant. That he was Helen's quasi-husband was no bar to this. In Massinger we constantly find 'disposer' used in a similar sense. In The Bashful Lover [i.i, (ed. Gifford, 1813, iv, 366)], Matilda says—'I am not the disposer of myself, The duke my father challenges that power . ... At the same time it is pretty evident, from the unsuspecting manner in which Pandarus harps upon the term, that Shakespeare, more suo, intended to suggest an equivoque, and to imply that, as Ulysses afterwards tells us, Cressid's manner and style of beauty 'disposed' one in the merriest Elizabethan sense of the word. ... Paris the rake, and Ulysses the observant man of the world, both understood her at a glance, and so does Diomed.\"—The fullest discussion is by SCHÜCKING (Anglia Beiblatt, xliii, 1932, 189–92). He rejects all such interpretations as \"entertainer, merry-maker, flirt.\" To citations in N.E.D. and elsewhere he adds: \"And I as free as you, mine own disposer\" (Fletcher's Humorous Lieutenant, iv.i.145, Variorum, 1905, II, 536); \"We are ourselves, our owne disposers, masters; And those that you call husbands are our Servants\" (Barnevelt, ii.ii. ed. Bullen, 1883, II, 234); \"My Author and Disposer, what thou bidst Unargu'd I obey\" (Paradise Lost, IV, 635). There can hardly be a doubt that \"disposer\" means the same in T. and C., namely, \"mistress\" (Gebieterin, Herzenkaiserin); only it is here used ironically. Paris is amused by the courtly, precious tone of Pandarus' speech, and replies in kind. Pandarus is so delighted with the word that he uses it twice.—{And so the matter rests, not very satisfactorily. It is annoying that a fairly common word of fairly plain meaning should give so"]},"94":{"play":"PARIS: I spy.","notes":["I [spie] Steevens (Var. '78): This is the usual exclamation at a childish game called “Hie, spy, hie.” 94–95. My Neece, etc.] Theobald (letter to Warburton, 3 March, 1729/30): Is Pandarus throwing a wanton slur upon his niece; and hinting that she sadly wanted such a man bedfellow as Helen had in Paris?—[The question remains unanswered. The commentators have consistently ignored this cryptic remark of Pandarus.] 98–99. are twaine] I.e. are disjoined, are at variance, are enemies. H. Isaac (Sh. Jahr., xix, 1884, 207) cites Sonnet 36: “Let me confess that we two must be twain,” and Romeo and Juliet, III.v.241: “Thou and my bosom henceforth shall be twain.”—Schücking (Anglia Beiblatt, xliii, 1932, 191) insists that here, and in Sonnet 36, the meaning is not “they are enemies,” but simply “they are not one,” that is, “they have nothing in common.”"]},"95":{"play":"PANDARUS: You spy? What do you spy?—Come, give me","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"an instrument. An Attendant gives him an instrument.","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"Now, sweet queen.","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"HELEN: Why, this is kindly done.","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"PANDARUS: My niece is horribly in love with a thing you","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"have, sweet queen.","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"HELEN: She shall have it, my lord, if it be not my Lord","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"Paris.","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"PANDARUS: He? No, she’ll none of him. They two are","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"twain.","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"HELEN: Falling in after falling out may make them","notes":["Falling in, etc.] TOLLET (Var. '78): The reconciliation and wanton dalliance of two lovers after a quarrel, may produce a child, and so make three of two.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) indignantly rejects this interpretation as \"impossible.\" But it is not only possible but probable, for otherwise the remark of Helen has the largest of meanings."]},"106":{"play":"three.","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"PANDARUS: Come, come, I’ll hear no more of this. I’ll","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"sing you a song now.","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"HELEN: Ay, ay, prithee. Now, by my troth, sweet lord,","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"thou hast a fine forehead.","notes":["A fine fore-head] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Perhaps, considering the character of Pandarus, Helen means that he has a forehead illuminated by eruptions.—LEE (ed. 1910): A sign of manly beauty, here implying the possession of rare accomplishments."]},"111":{"play":"PANDARUS: Ay, you may, you may.","notes":["you may] STAUNTON (ed. 1860) explains this colloquialism as being equivalent to the modern slang \"go it, go it,\" and meaning \"You have full liberty to divert yourself.\" It occurs again in Coriolanus, II.iii.33-34: \"You are never without your tricks: you may, you may.\""]},"112":{"play":"HELEN: Let thy song be love. “This love will undo us all.”","notes":["this loue ... all] VERITY (ed. 1889): The editors have not remarked what is, I believe, the case, viz., that the expression is some catch from a song; compare Field's A Woman is a Weathercock, III.iii. [Dodsley-Hazlitt, Old English Plays, 1875, XI, 56. Pendant finds Sir Abraham Ninny composing a love sonnet, and exclaims: \"What, musing and writing? O, this love will undo us all.\"]"]},"113":{"play":"O Cupid, Cupid, Cupid!","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"PANDARUS: Love? Ay, that it shall, i’ faith.","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"PARIS: Ay, good now, “Love, love, nothing but love.”","notes":["loue ... but loue] DELIUS (ed. 1856): Perhaps \"loue, loue, no thing but loue\" should be written cursively, as though Paris were quoting the beginning of the song which Pandarus offers."]},"116":{"play":"PANDARUS: In good troth, it begins so.","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"Love, love, nothing but love, still love, still more!","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"For, O, love’s bow","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"Shoots buck and doe.","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"The shaft confounds","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"Not that it wounds","notes":["that it wounds] MUSGRAVE (Var. '78): That which it wounds.—MASON (Beaumont and Fletcher, 1798, Additional Comments, pp. 55-56): Both Malone and Musgrave have mistaken the sense of this passage.—Pandarus means to say, that the shaft confounds, not because the wounds it gives are severe, but because it tickles still the sore. To confound does not signify here to destroy, but to annoy or perplex; and \"that it wounds\" does not mean that \"which it wounds,\" but \"in\" that it wounds, or because it wounds."]},"122":{"play":"But tickles still the sore.","notes":["fore] RANN (ed. 1789) suggests that a pun is intended on \"sorel,\" a buck in the third year.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) agrees, and cites Love's Labor's Lost, iv.ii.54-55: \"The preyful princess pierced ... a ... pricket; Some say a sore; but not a sore, till now made sore with shooting.\"—[\"Sore\" and \"sorrel\" are both substantive uses of adjectives meaning reddish brown. \"Sorrel\" is a buck of the third year, \"sore\" one of the fourth. The terms are also applied to hawks.]"]},"123":{"play":"These lovers cry “O ho!” they die,","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"Yet that which seems the wound to kill","notes":["wound to kill] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): \"To kill the wound,\" is no very intelligible expression, nor is the measure preserved. We might read, ... \"But that which seems to kill.\" ... Yet as \"the wound to kill\" may mean \"the wound that seems mortal,\" I alter nothing.—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 312): The \"wound to kill\" is the \"killing wound.\"—ORGER (Critical Notes, 1890, p. 50) asserts that \"wound\" is the passive participle for \"wounded,\" like \"wed\" for \"wedded.\"—[This is much ado about nothing. Mason's explanation is obviously right.]"]},"125":{"play":"Doth turn “O ho!” to “Ha ha he!”","notes":["Doth turne, etc.] BOYLE (E.S., xxx, 1902, 35) cites Tourneur's Atheist's Tragedy (ed. Pearson, 1878, I, 57): \"Here's a sweete Comedie. 'T begins with O Dolentis and concludes with ha, ha, he!\"—[The Accidence of the authorized grammar says, \"An Interiection is a part of speach, which betokeneth a sudayne"]},"126":{"play":"So dying love lives still.","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"“O ho!” awhile, but “Ha ha ha!”","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"“O ho!”groans out for “ha ha ha!”—Hey ho!","notes":["hey ho] RITSON (Remarks, 1783, p. 162): The interjection is certainly no part of the song: and consequently should not appear in the same character: it is uttered by Pandarus after he has done singing. This is evident from Helen’s observation: \"In loue yfaith to the very tip of the nose.\""]},"129":{"play":"HELEN: In love, i’ faith, to the very tip of the nose.","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"PARIS: He eats nothing but doves, love, and that breeds","notes":["douses] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) cites Dekker’s II Honest Whore (ed. Pearson, 1873, ii, 182): \"Haue yee eaten Pigeons that y’are so kinde-hearted to your Mate?\" 126–29. Is this ... to day] RITSON (in Steevens, ed. 1793): However Pan. may have got shuffled to the head of this speech, no more of it, I am confident, than the last five or six words belongs to that character. The rest is clearly Helen’s. 126–40. FLATTER (Sh.’s Producing Hand, 1948, pp. 152–53): Pandarus tries to divide his flattery between Paris and Helen. At the same time, however, he has serious business with Paris which, in a silent understanding, they keep hidden from Helen. Within a dozen lines (prose lines) there are three interruptions, indicated by broken-off lines: the two men speak in private. Helen notices their having a secret, and remarks: ‘He hangs the lippe at something’, meaning Paris; she wishes Pandarus to tell her what is going on, but does not receive an answer. ... I submit that without the stage-business, indicated by the broken-off lines, the passage can scarcely be understood. The pauses as shown in the F text are a great help. In all the modern editions, however, they have been omitted.—B."]},"131":{"play":"hot blood, and hot blood begets hot thoughts, and","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"hot thoughts beget hot deeds, and hot deeds is love.","notes":[]},"133":{"play":"PANDARUS: Is this the generation of love? Hot blood,","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"hot thoughts, and hot deeds? Why, they are vipers.","notes":["generation of Vipers] Matthew iii, 7: “O generation of vipers, who hath warned you to flee from the wrath to come?”—[CARTER (Sh. and Holy Scripture, 1905, p. 385) cites four passages: Matthew iii, 7, xii, 34, xxiii, 33, Luke iii, 7. Upon the last of these, “O generation of vipers, who hath forewarned you to flee from the wrath to come?” NOBLE (Sh.’s Biblical Knowledge, 1935, p. 215) has this note, “‘B[ishops] has ‘generation’ in all except Matt. xii, 34; G[eneva], ‘generations’ in all except Matt. xxiii, 33; and R[heims], ‘brood’ or ‘broodes.’”—B.]"]},"135":{"play":"Is love a generation of vipers? Sweet lord, who’s","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"afield today?","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"PARIS: Hector, Deiphobus, Helenus, Antenor, and all the","notes":["whole a field] DANIEL (“Time-Analysis of T. and C.,” New Sh. Soc. Transactions, 1877–79, pp. 181–82): In this scene commences an extraordinary entanglement of the plot of the Play. It is quite clear that from its position it must represent a portion of the day on which Hector sent his challenge to the Greeks: a day on which there could be no encounters between the hostile forces, and which in fact is but one day of a long-continued truce; yet in this scene Pandarus asks Paris, “Sweete Lord, who’s a field today?” Paris replies, “Hector, Deiphobus, Helenus, Antenor, and all the gallantry of Troy.” ... Towards the end of the scene a retreat is sounded, and Paris says, “They’re come from fielde.”"]},"138":{"play":"gallantry of Troy. I would fain have armed today,","notes":[]},"139":{"play":"but my Nell would not have it so. How chance my","notes":[]},"140":{"play":"brother Troilus went not?","notes":[]},"141":{"play":"HELEN: He hangs the lip at something.—You know all,","notes":[]},"142":{"play":"Lord Pandarus.","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"PANDARUS: Not I, honey sweet queen. I long to hear how","notes":[]},"144":{"play":"they sped today.—You’ll remember your brother’s","notes":[]},"145":{"play":"excuse?","notes":[]},"146":{"play":"PARIS: To a hair.","notes":[]},"147":{"play":"PANDARUS: Farewell, sweet queen.","notes":[]},"148":{"play":"HELEN: Commend me to your niece.","notes":[]},"149":{"play":"PANDARUS: I will, sweet queen.    He exits.","notes":[]},"150":{"play":"[Sound a retreat.]","notes":[]},"151":{"play":"PARIS: They’re come from the field. Let us to Priam’s hall","notes":[]},"152":{"play":"To greet the warriors. Sweet Helen, I must woo you","notes":[]},"153":{"play":"To help unarm our Hector. His stubborn buckles,","notes":[]},"154":{"play":"With these your white enchanting fingers touched,","notes":[]},"155":{"play":"Shall more obey than to the edge of steel","notes":[]},"156":{"play":"Or force of Greekish sinews. You shall do more","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"Than all the island kings: disarm great Hector.","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"HELEN: ’Twill make us proud to be his servant, Paris.","notes":[]},"159":{"play":"Yea, what he shall receive of us in duty","notes":[]},"160":{"play":"Gives us more palm in beauty than we have,","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"Yea, overshines ourself.","notes":[]},"162":{"play":"PARIS: Sweet, above thought I love thee.","notes":[]},"163":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 3, SCENE 2":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus and Troilus’s Man, meeting.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"PANDARUS: How now? Where’s thy master? At my","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"cousin Cressida’s?","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"MAN: No, sir, he stays for you to conduct him thither.","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"[Enter Troilus.]","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"PANDARUS: O, here he comes.—How now, how now?","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"TROILUS, to his Man  Sirrah, walk off.  Man exits.","notes":["walke off] At a distance, out of ear-shot. As a matter of fact, the actor would walk off stage, and both instances of the phrase cited by N.E.D. under the definition, \"To depart suddenly or abruptly,\" are also subject to this interpretation. In the cases cited, the suddenness or abruptness inheres in the situation and not in the words.—B."]},"8":{"play":"PANDARUS: Have you seen my cousin?","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"TROILUS: No, Pandarus. I stalk about her door","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"Like a strange soul upon the Stygian banks","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"Staying for waftage. O, be thou my Charon,","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"And give me swift transportance to those fields","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"Where I may wallow in the lily beds","notes":["wallow in the Lilly beds] Root (Classical Mythology in Sh., 1903, p. 66): Elysium, the abode of the blest, is described in Aen. 6. 637-659. Most of Shakespeare's references are without significance, Elysium being equivalent to Paradise. Of more significance, however, are Troil. [iii.ii.13], Ant. [iv.iv.50-54], and Cymb. [iv.ii.97-98]. In Ant. we read: Stay for me: Where souls do couch on flowers, we'll hand in hand. ... again in Cymb.: Poor shadows of Elysium, hence, and rest Upon your never-withering banks of flowers. In each case, then, where Elysium is described the flowers are given chief prominence. Now Vergil, though mentioning 'the smiling lawns of happy groves' and 'the fragrant bay-trees,' and saying that the ghosts 'dwell in the shady woods, and haunt the couches that the river-banks afford, and the meadows that the fountains freshen,' does not mention any flowers; but in the Homeric Hades the spirits pass 'along the mead of asphodel,' Od. II. 539, and the asphodel is a species of lily. (In Aen. 6. 883 Anchises says 'give me handfuls of lilies,' which implies that they grew in Vergil's Elysian Fields also). [Sh.'s contemporaries knew of the asphodel, and their dictionaries identified it with the daffodil, a kind of lily. But it was Solomon, not Virgil, who for this Elysium furnished the lily-beds where Troilus hoped he was about to wallow. Song of Solomon vii, 2: \"thy belly is as an heape of wheat compassed about with lilies. 3 Thy two brests are as two yong roes that are twinnes\"; ii, 16, \"My welbeloued is mine, and I am his: he feedeth among the lilies\"; iv, 5, \"Thy two brestes are as two yong roes that are twinnes, feeding among the lilies\"; vi, 1, \"My welbeloued is gone downe into his garden to the beddes of spices, to feede in the gardens, and to gather lilies. 2 I am my welbeloueds, &"]},"14":{"play":"Proposed for the deserver! O, gentle Pandar,","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"From Cupid’s shoulder pluck his painted wings","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"And fly with me to Cressid!","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"PANDARUS: Walk here i’ th’ orchard. I’ll bring her","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"straight.","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"[Pandarus exits.]","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"TROILUS: I am giddy; expectation whirls me round.","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"Th’ imaginary relish is so sweet","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"That it enchants my sense. What will it be","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"When that the wat’ry palate taste indeed","notes":["watr[y] Watering, vehemently desiring (RANN, ed. 1789, and SCHMIDT 1875)."]},"24":{"play":"Love’s thrice-repurèd nectar? Death, I fear me,","notes":["reputed] From COLLIER (ed. 1842) on through several editors the statement is made that \"repured\" is a reading found in the Duke of Devonshire's Q and presumably unique. It is the reading of all Qq.","Sounding] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): The following forms are found in Shakespeare: \"sound, swound, swoun, swown, swoon, swoon.\"—[\"Sound,\" a common form of \"swoon\" until the middle seventeenth century, is now dialectical.]"]},"25":{"play":"Swooning destruction, or some joy too fine,","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"Too subtle-potent, tuned too sharp in sweetness","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"For the capacity of my ruder powers.","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"I fear it much; and I do fear besides","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"That I shall lose distinction in my joys,","notes":["loose distinction in my joyes] STEEVENS (Var. '03): Thus, in Sappho's Epistle to Phaon:—ubi jam amborum fuerat confusa voluptas.—B."]},"30":{"play":"As doth a battle when they charge on heaps","notes":["battaile] Army, as often in Sh. Compare Henry V, iv. Chor. 8–9: \"through their paly flames Each battle sees the other's umber'd face.\" In this sense it is equivalent to \"battalion.\""]},"31":{"play":"The enemy flying.","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus.]","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"PANDARUS: She’s making her ready; she’ll come straight.","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"You must be witty now. She does so blush and","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"fetches her wind so short as if she were frayed with","notes":["fraid] Aphetic form of \"affrayed,\" \"effrayed.\" 37–40. My heart ... Maieftie] BOYLE (E.S., XXX, 1902, 36) calls attention to the parallelism between this passage and Merchant of Venice, III.ii.177–82: \"Only my blood speaks to you in my veins; And there is such confusion in my"]},"36":{"play":"a spirit. I’ll fetch her. It is the prettiest villain. She","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"fetches her breath as short as a new-ta’en sparrow.","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"[Pandarus exits.]","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"TROILUS: Even such a passion doth embrace my bosom.","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"My heart beats thicker than a feverous pulse,","notes":["thicker] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) cites Cymbeline, III.ii.55: “say, and speak thick.”"]},"41":{"play":"And all my powers do their bestowing lose,","notes":["beftowing] Employment, use; a meaning not yet quite obsolete. Compare II.ii.165-66: “none so Noble, Whose life were ill bestow’d. ...”"]},"42":{"play":"Like vassalage at unawares encount’ring","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"The eye of majesty.","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus, and Cressida veiled.]","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"PANDARUS, to Cressida  Come, come, what need you","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"blush? Shame’s a baby.—Here she is now. Swear","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"the oaths now to her that you have sworn to me.","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"Cressida offers to leave. What, are you gone again?","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"You must be watched ere you be made tame, must","notes":["watcht] N.E.D.: Watch: to prevent (a hawk) from sleeping, in order to"]},"50":{"play":"you? Come your ways; come your ways. An you","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"draw backward, we’ll put you i’ th’ thills.—Why","notes":["fils] THEOBALD (ed. 1733, reading \"files\"): Pandarus here threatens her with military Discipline. It was a Custom, we find, as old as Homer’s Time, for them, in drawing up a Battle, to place such, as they suspected would misbehave ... in the mid Ranks; so that they might be watch’d on every hand. ... This is what we now call \"putting in the Files.\"—MALONE (ed. 1790): [’ the fills,] That is, in the shafts. \"Fill\" is a provincial word used in some counties for \"thills,\" the shafts of a cart or waggon. ... The words \"draw backward\" shew that the original is the true reading.—[“Fill-horse” (“fillhorse”) occurs in Merchant of Venice, ii.ii.87.]"]},"52":{"play":"do you not speak to her?—Come, draw this curtain","notes":["draw this curtaine] MALONES (ed. 1790): It should seem from these words that Cressida, like Olivia in Twelfth Night, was intended to come in veil’d.—[Compare Twelfth Night, I.v.218: \"We will draw the curtain and show you the picture.\"]"]},"53":{"play":"and let’s see your picture. He draws back her veil.","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"Alas the day, how loath you are to offend daylight!","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"An ’twere dark, you’d close sooner.—So, so, rub on,","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"and kiss the mistress. (They kiss.) How now? A","notes":["mitretfel] NARES (Glossary, 1822): The small ball at the game of bowls, now called the \"Jack,\" at which the players aim. ... \"Rub\" is still a term at the game, expressive of the movement of the bowls, and they are said to \"kiss,\" when they touch gently. kiffe in fee-farme] MALONE (ed. 1790): A kiss of a duration that has no bounds; a fee-farm being a grant of lands in fee, that is, for ever, reserving a certain rent."]},"57":{"play":"kiss in fee-farm? Build there, carpenter; the air is","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"sweet. Nay, you shall fight your hearts out ere I","notes":["fight] KELLNER (Restoring Sh., 1925, p. 61) thinks this a case of typesetting error,—f for ſ, and ght for gh. The word should be \"sigh.\"—TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., VII, 1932, 76) agrees. [But the following figure is one of fighting; and so the text is certainly correct. These are love’s wars, and the battle imagery continues.—B.]"]},"59":{"play":"part you. The falcon as the tercel, for all the ducks","notes":["Faulcon ... Tercell] N.E.D.: [The term \"falcon\" is] in Falconry, applied","as] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): This Reading [“has”] first got Place casually, as I presume, in Mr. Rowe’s Edition; and was implicitly follow’d by Mr. Pope. But they Both deprave the Text. Pandarus, seeing Troilus kiss with Fervour, and Cressida meet his Kisses with equal Zeal, means, that he’ll match his Neice against her Lover for any Bett.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 497): We should undoubtedly read, “The falcon at the tercel”; that is, I will fly my female hawk against the male, for all the ducks in the river.—STAUNTON (ed. 1860) cites Lingua, IX (Tudor Facsimile, sig. C3r): “Next after mee, I as your selfe at any time.”—[Theobald’s defense of the text is generally accepted.]"]},"60":{"play":"i’ th’ river. Go to, go to.","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"TROILUS: You have bereft me of all words, lady.","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"PANDARUS: Words pay no debts; give her deeds. But","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"she’ll bereave you o’ th’ deeds too, if she call your","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"activity in question. (They kiss.) What, billing","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"again? Here’s “In witness whereof the parties","notes":["interchangeably] CLARKSON and WARREN (Law of Property in Sh., 1942, pp. 125-26, n. 114): The word ‘interchangeably,’ i.e., by way of exchange or interchange, denoted a method of signing indentures executed in duplicate, where each party signs the copy which he delivers to the other. See Black’s Law Dictionary.—B."]},"66":{"play":"interchangeably—.” Come in, come in. I’ll go get a fire.","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"[Pandarus exits.]","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Will you walk in, my lord?","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"TROILUS: O Cressid, how often have I wished me thus!","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"CRESSIDA: “Wished,” my lord? The gods grant—O, my","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"lord!","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"TROILUS: What should they grant? What makes this","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"pretty abruption? What too-curious dreg espies","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"my sweet lady in the fountain of our love?","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"CRESSIDA: More dregs than water, if my fears have eyes.","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"TROILUS: Fears make devils of cherubins; they never","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"see truly.","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Blind fear, that seeing reason leads, finds","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"safer footing than blind reason, stumbling without","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"fear. To fear the worst oft cures the worse.","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"TROILUS: O, let my lady apprehend no fear. In all","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"Cupid’s pageant there is presented no monster.","notes":["monster] PARTRIDGE (Sh.'s Bawdy, 1947, p. 149): Cuckold. [Why?]—B."]},"83":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Nor nothing monstrous neither?","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"TROILUS: Nothing but our undertakings, when we vow","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"to weep seas, live in fire, eat rocks, tame tigers,","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"thinking it harder for our mistress to devise imposition","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"enough than for us to undergo any difficulty","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"imposed. This is the monstruosity in love, lady, that","notes":["monstrovtitie] The latest instance in N.E.D. of this once common alternative for “monstrosity” is from 1797."]},"89":{"play":"the will is infinite and the execution confined, that","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"the desire is boundless and the act a slave to limit.","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"CRESSIDA: They say all lovers swear more performance","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"than they are able and yet reserve an ability that","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"they never perform, vowing more than the perfection","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"of ten and discharging less than the tenth part","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"of one. They that have the voice of lions and the","notes":["voyce ... Hares] M. C. WAHL (Sh. Jahrb., xxii, 1887, 91) cites Coriolanus, I.i.169: \"Where he should find you lions, finds you hares\"; and the German proverb, \"Löwenmaul—Hasenherz.\""]},"96":{"play":"act of hares, are they not monsters?","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"TROILUS: Are there such? Such are not we. Praise us as","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"we are tasted, allow us as we prove; our head shall","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"go bare till merit crown it. No perfection in reversion","notes":["reuerfion] CLARKSON and WARREN (Law of Property in Sh., 1942, p. 72): If the estate granted away, which is called the particular estate, comes to an end the possession reverts to the grantor.—B."]},"100":{"play":"shall have a praise in present. We will not","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"name desert before his birth, and, being born, his","notes":["his addition fhall be humble] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): We will give him no high or pompous titles.—[See II.iii.251 and note.]"]},"102":{"play":"addition shall be humble. Few words to fair faith.","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"Troilus shall be such to Cressid as what envy can","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"say worst shall be a mock for his truth, and what","notes":["a mocke for his truth] RANN (ed. 1789): A mere mockery of his truth; shall not be able to impeach it.—MALONE (ed. 1790): I.e. shall be \"only\" a mock for his truth. Even malice (for such is the meaning of the word \"envy\") shall not be able to impeach his truth, or attack him in any other way except by ridiculing him for his constancy.—VERITY (ed. 1889): This may be right; I should have thought, however, that the meaning was rather, \"the worst that"]},"105":{"play":"truth can speak truest not truer than Troilus.","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Will you walk in, my lord?","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus.]","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"PANDARUS: What, blushing still? Have you not done","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"talking yet?","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Well, uncle, what folly I commit I dedicate","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"to you.","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"PANDARUS: I thank you for that. If my lord get a boy of","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"you, you’ll give him me. Be true to my lord. If he","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"flinch, chide me for it.","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"TROILUS, to Cressida  You know now your hostages:","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"your uncle’s word and my firm faith.","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"PANDARUS: Nay, I’ll give my word for her too. Our kindred,","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"though they be long ere they be wooed, they","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"are constant being won. They are burrs, I can tell","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"you; they’ll stick where they are thrown.","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Boldness comes to me now and brings me heart.","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"Prince Troilus, I have loved you night and day","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"For many weary months.","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"TROILUS: Why was my Cressid then so hard to win?","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Hard to seem won; but I was won, my lord,","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"With the first glance that ever—pardon me;","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"If I confess much, you will play the tyrant.","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"I love you now, but till now not so much","notes":[]},"129":{"play":"But I might master it. In faith, I lie;","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"My thoughts were like unbridled children grown","notes":[]},"131":{"play":"Too headstrong for their mother. See, we fools!","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"Why have I blabbed? Who shall be true to us","notes":["Comming] GREG (Principles of Emendation in Sh., 1928, p. 12) thinks “Coming” should be retained. The emendation “Cunning” gives a more perfect sense, but “coming” frequently means forward, apt, which makes good enough sense, and it rests upon the double authority of Q and F. On the other hand (p. 35), there is a case of “coming” being misprinted “cunning” in Massinger’s Bondman, ii.ii (1624 ed., sig. E1 v; ed. Gifford, 1813, II, 43–44), where the printed text reads: “your true Courtier knowes not His Neece, or Sister from another woman, If she be apt and cunning.” Massinger himself corrected “cunning” to “cominge” (see Library, Ser. 4, v, 1925, 65, 87).—[We need only to capitalize Silence as a personification and to put a comma after it to clear the text to modern style. “Comming” has only its usual meaning.—B.]"]},"133":{"play":"When we are so unsecret to ourselves?","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"But though I loved you well, I wooed you not;","notes":[]},"135":{"play":"And yet, good faith, I wished myself a man;","notes":["with my selfe a man] Compare Othello, I.iii.162–63; “Yet she wish’d That heaven had made her such a man.”–B."]},"136":{"play":"Or that we women had men’s privilege","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"Of speaking first. Sweet, bid me hold my tongue,","notes":[]},"138":{"play":"For in this rapture I shall surely speak","notes":[]},"139":{"play":"The thing I shall repent. See, see, your silence,","notes":[]},"140":{"play":"Cunning in dumbness, from my weakness draws","notes":[]},"141":{"play":"My very soul of counsel! Stop my mouth.","notes":[]},"142":{"play":"TROILUS: And shall, albeit sweet music issues thence.","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"They kiss.","notes":[]},"144":{"play":"PANDARUS: Pretty, i’ faith!","notes":[]},"145":{"play":"CRESSIDA, to Troilus","notes":[]},"146":{"play":"My lord, I do beseech you pardon me.","notes":[]},"147":{"play":"’Twas not my purpose thus to beg a kiss.","notes":[]},"148":{"play":"I am ashamed. O heavens, what have I done!","notes":[]},"149":{"play":"For this time will I take my leave, my lord.","notes":[]},"150":{"play":"TROILUS: Your leave, sweet Cressid?","notes":[]},"151":{"play":"PANDARUS: Leave? An you take leave till tomorrow","notes":[]},"152":{"play":"morning—","notes":[]},"153":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Pray you, content you.","notes":[]},"154":{"play":"TROILUS: What offends you, lady?","notes":[]},"155":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Sir, mine own company.","notes":[]},"156":{"play":"TROILUS: You cannot shun yourself.","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Let me go and try.","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"I have a kind of self resides with you,","notes":[]},"159":{"play":"But an unkind self that itself will leave","notes":[]},"160":{"play":"To be another’s fool. I would be gone.","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"Where is my wit? I know not what I speak.","notes":[]},"162":{"play":"TROILUS: Well know they what they speak that speak so wisely.","notes":[]},"163":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Perchance, my lord, I show more craft than love","notes":["shew] WHITE (ed. 1865) insisted that the tense is past, in conformity with \"fell\" in the next line, and that the form \"shew,\" being the old preterite, should be retained. The verb did, in fact, have a strong conjugation from early M.E., along with the weak; the preterite \"shew\" survives in dialect (see N.E.D. and Wright). But there is no necessity for taking the tense to be past in this instance, nor does Sh. elsewhere use what had become by his day a dialectical preterite."]},"164":{"play":"And fell so roundly to a large confession","notes":["roundly] A word of many shades of meaning. ABBOTT (Sh. Grammar, 1872, §60) explains that \"'round,' like 'square' with us, from its connection"]},"165":{"play":"To angle for your thoughts. But you are wise,","notes":["you] Is this not used as an indefinite personal pronoun?—N.E.D. (you, iii, 6): Denoting any hearer or reader; hence as an indef. pers. pron.: One, any one.—B. 156–57. but you are wife, etc.] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I read, \"—but we're not wise, Or else we love not. …\" Cressida, in return to the praise given by Troilus to her wisdom, replies, That \"lovers are never wise; that it is beyond the power of man to bring love and wisdom to a union.\"—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 313): I don't think that this passage requires any amendment; Cressida's meaning is this: \"Perchance I fell so roundly to confession in order to angle for your thoughts, but you are not so easily taken in; you are too wise, or too indifferent, for to be wise and love exceeds man's might.\"—MALONE (ed. 1790): Cressida's argument is certainly inconsequential: \"But you are wise, or else you are not in love; for no one who is in love can be wise.\" I do not, however, believe there is any corruption, as our authour sometimes entangles himself in inextricable difficulties of this kind. One of the commentators has endeavoured to extort sense from the words as they stand, and thinks there is no difficulty. In these cases the surest way to prove the inaccuracy, is, to omit the word that embarrasses the sentence. Thus, if, for a moment, we read—\"But you are wise; Or else you love; for to be wise and love Exceeds man's might\"; &c. the inference is clear, by the omission of the word \"not\": which is not a word of so little importance that a sentence shall have just the same meaning whether a negative is contained in it or taken from it. But for all inaccuracies of this kind our poet himself is undoubtedly answerable.—VERITY (ed. 1889): No doubt Cressida's reasoning is a trifle irregular. Such arguments would not pass muster in Mill's Logic; but the editors might have remembered that, in the first place, the speaker is a woman; and, in the second place, being in love, she cannot, according to her own showing, \"be wise.\" Really it is perfectly easy to trace the line of thought. \"I angled,\" she says, \"for your thoughts, but got nothing out of you, either because you are not in love, or because you are too wise\"; and then the words \"wise\" and \"love\" remind her of the proverb, and she whimsically rounds off her sentence with, \"for you know, you cannot both love and be wise.\" It is an admirable non sequitur, a triumph of feminine reasoning power, and ten times as true to life as the logical proprieties suggested by the commentators.—[Cressida presents the paradox of \"wise\" and \"love.\" The answering speech of Troilus is built"]},"166":{"play":"Or else you love not; for to be wise and love","notes":["Or else] STAUNTON (ed. 1860) paraphrases, “Or, in other words”; this being the “simple and obvious meaning” which the commentators have overlooked.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) agrees that that is the only possible meaning “if the text is sound.”—LEE (ed. 1910) finds that the phrase has “the unusual force here of ‘And if it be so.’ For ‘Or else you love not,’ Cressida means ‘That is to say you are not in love.’” 157-58. to be wise gods aboue] TYRWHITT (Var. ’73): This is from Spenser, Sh. Cal. March: “To be wise and eke to loue, Is graunted scarce to God aboue.”—[Almost every commentator from MALONE (Var. ’78) on has pointed to the line of Publius Syrus, Amare et sapere vix deo conceditur, which is certainly the original. But it was so frequently repeated in Sh.’s time that it would be useless to guess whether he got it directly from the source or from an intermediary.]"]},"167":{"play":"Exceeds man’s might. That dwells with gods above.","notes":[]},"168":{"play":"TROILUS: O, that I thought it could be in a woman—","notes":[]},"169":{"play":"As, if it can, I will presume in you—","notes":[]},"170":{"play":"To feed for aye her lamp and flames of love,","notes":["To feede ... lampe] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Troilus alludes to the perpetual lamps which were supposed to illuminate sepulchres."]},"171":{"play":"To keep her constancy in plight and youth,","notes":["constancie in plight and youth] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): To preserve in all its freshness the constancy she has plighted. Here, again, there is a slight confusion of ideas, the preposition “in” being used by a kind of zeugma in two different senses; her constancy in that which she has plighted (the matter) in all its freshness (the condition). So in Othello, II.i.77: “As when, by night and negligence, the fire Is spied,” i.e. As when the fire which has broken out by night owing to negligence, etc.—LEE (ed. 1910) takes “plight” in the sense (see N.E.D., sb^3, 5b) of “good condition,” health. The meaning then would be “Keeps her constancy young and healthy.”"]},"172":{"play":"Outliving beauty’s outward, with a mind","notes":["beauties outward] This phrase can be taken as “exterior beauties” or “beauty’s exterior” (the interpretation and reading generally accepted since Malone). Except for the inversion, “beauties outward” would parallel a large number of phrases in Sh.—“outward courtesies,” “outward behaviours,” “outward happiness,” “outward graces,” “outward shows,” “outward consciences,” etc., etc. (See Bartlett’s Concordance.) “Outward” is used as a noun once in the plays, thrice in the poems; on the other hand, the adjective “outward” occurs only once after its noun (“things outward,” Antony and Cleopatra, III.xiii.32). It is a nice question."]},"173":{"play":"That doth renew swifter than blood decays!","notes":["blood] MALONE (ed. 1790) thinks the word means desire or appetite, as it often does in Sh.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793) takes it in its common, physical sense, citing Much Ado, iv.i.193: “Time hath not yet so dried this blood of mine.” 167-68. affronted ... loue] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I wish my integrity might be met and matched with such equality and force of pure unmingled love.—[“Affront,” in Sh., always means to encounter, to meet face to face. The original meaning, to insult, has persisted. The meaning “to confront” and its related senses seem to have arisen in the sixteenth century, and are now mostly obsolete. We still may say “to affront death.” See N.E.D.]"]},"174":{"play":"Or that persuasion could but thus convince me","notes":[]},"175":{"play":"That my integrity and truth to you","notes":[]},"176":{"play":"Might be affronted with the match and weight","notes":[]},"177":{"play":"Of such a winnowed purity in love;","notes":[]},"178":{"play":"How were I then uplifted! But, alas,","notes":["vp-lifted] In the sense of “elated, proud” the word is still used in Scotland and the northern counties. See N.E.D. and also “Stylties” in N.Q., 14 April, 1855, pp. 278-79."]},"179":{"play":"I am as true as truth’s simplicity","notes":[]},"180":{"play":"And simpler than the infancy of truth.","notes":["timpler ... truth] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): This is fine: and means, “Ere truth, to defend itself against deceit in the commerce of the world, had, out of necessity, learn’d worldly policy.”"]},"181":{"play":"CRESSIDA: In that I’ll war with you.","notes":["I haue ... with you] MALONE (Second Appendix, 1783, p. 45) cites Sonnet 133: \"For I, being pent in thee, Perforce am thine, and all that is in me.\" —STEEVENS (ed. 1793) cites more appositely Antony and Cleopatra, I.iii.102–03: \"Our separation so abides and flies, That thou residing here go'st yet with me.\" —[This Platonic literary device is too frequent in Sh. and his age to require further citation.—B.]"]},"182":{"play":"TROILUS: O virtuous fight,","notes":[]},"183":{"play":"When right with right wars who shall be most right!","notes":[]},"184":{"play":"True swains in love shall in the world to come","notes":[]},"185":{"play":"Approve their truth by Troilus. When their rhymes,","notes":[]},"186":{"play":"Full of protest, of oath and big compare,","notes":[]},"187":{"play":"Wants similes, truth tired with iteration—","notes":["Wants similes, truth] TYRWHITT (Observations, 1766, p. 45): The metre,"]},"188":{"play":"“As true as steel, as plantage to the moon,","notes":["plantage] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): \"Plantage\" is certainly very justly thrown out, as a Reading of no Sense or Truth [in favor of Pope's \"planets\"].—HAMMER (ed. 1744): It was heretofore the prevailing opinion that the production and growth of Plants depended much upon the influences of the Moon: and the rules and directions given for sowing, planting, grafting, and pruning, had reference generally to the changes, the increase, or waning of the Moon.—WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I formerly made a silly conjecture, that the true reading was, \"Planets to their Moons.\" But I did not reflect that it was wrote before Galileo had discovered the Satellites of Jupiter. ... So that \"Plantage to the Moon\" is right, and alludes to the common opinion of the influence the Moon has over what is planted or sown, which was therefore done in the increase.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): \"Plantage\" is not, I believe, a general term, but the herb which we now call \"plantain,\" in Latin, plantago, which was, I suppose, imagined to be under the peculiar influence of the Moon.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 497): If \"Plantage\" cannot refer to whatever is planted or sown, because, however wide spread the belief in the moon's influence may be, yet that influence is not invariable, and therefore \"could not furnish a proper comparison for a truth of an invariable constancy.\"] I suppose therefore that \"plantage\" usurps the place of some other thing, which receives a certain and regular determination from the moon: and, as the regular influence of that planet on the tides is of all others the most generally acknowledged ... [he proposes \"floodage\"].—STEEVENS (Var. '73): [From Thos. Hill's Profitable Art of Gardening, 1579, pp. 23 ff.] I learn, that neither sowing, planting, nor grafting, were ever undertaken without a scrupulous attention to the encrease or waning of the moon.—FARMER (Var. '78): This may be fully illustrated by a quotation from Scott's Discoverie of Witchcraft (1584, p. 169): \"The poore husbandman perceiueth that the increase of the moone maketh plants and liuing creatures frutefull: so as in the full moone they are in best strength, decaieing in the wane, and in the conjunction doo vtterlie wither and vade.\"—U.O.N. (N.Q., 7 Dec., 1861, p. 451) [cites the authority of Walker's Critical Pronouncing Dictionary for defining \"plantage\" as an herb.] The great water-plantain (Alisma plantago) was esteemed by the old pharmacologists as a specific for the cure of the \"moon,\" or madness, in dogs, and persons bitten by them; and it seems more probable that Shakspeare had in mind this popular superstition, than that he alluded to the moon's supposed influence on vegetation, for which he must have coined the word.—ORGER (Critical Notes, 1890, pp. 51–54) believes"]},"189":{"play":"As sun to day, as turtle to her mate,","notes":[]},"190":{"play":"As iron to adamant, as Earth to th’ center”—","notes":[]},"191":{"play":"Yet, after all comparisons of truth,","notes":[]},"192":{"play":"As truth’s authentic author to be cited,","notes":["As ... cited] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): This line is absolute nonsense. We should read, \"As truth authentic, ever to be cited,\" i.e. when all comparisons of truth are exhausted, they shall be then all summed up in this great one, this authentic truth ever to be cited, \"as true as Troilus.\"—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Here again the commentator finds nonsense, where I cannot find it. Troilus, says he, shall \"crown the verse,\" as a man \"to be cited as the authentick author of truth\"; as one whose protestations were true to a proverb.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 498): The words, \"authentick author,\" and, \"cited,\" both refer to an author, whose text is universally received, and submitted to, as the test of truth in the matters he treats of. ... The sense therefore I apprehend to be this. In matters of love, after all comparisons of truth have been exhausted, to crown and sum up the whole, the truth of Troilus shall at last be cited, as the very authentick text itself of truth in love, according to which the truth of every man else will for the future be tried and determined upon the comparison."]},"193":{"play":"“As true as Troilus” shall crown up the verse","notes":[]},"194":{"play":"And sanctify the numbers.","notes":[]},"195":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Prophet may you be!","notes":[]},"196":{"play":"If I be false or swerve a hair from truth,","notes":[]},"197":{"play":"When time is old and hath forgot itself,","notes":[]},"198":{"play":"When water drops have worn the stones of Troy","notes":[]},"199":{"play":"And blind oblivion swallowed cities up,","notes":[]},"200":{"play":"And mighty states characterless are grated","notes":[]},"201":{"play":"To dusty nothing, yet let memory,","notes":[]},"202":{"play":"From false to false, among false maids in love,","notes":[]},"203":{"play":"Upbraid my falsehood! When they’ve said “as false","notes":[]},"204":{"play":"As air, as water, wind or sandy earth,","notes":[]},"205":{"play":"As fox to lamb, or wolf to heifer’s calf,","notes":[]},"206":{"play":"Pard to the hind, or stepdame to her son,”","notes":[]},"207":{"play":"Yea, let them say, to stick the heart of falsehood,","notes":[]},"208":{"play":"“As false as Cressid.”","notes":[]},"209":{"play":"PANDARUS: Go to, a bargain made. Seal it, seal it. I’ll be","notes":["seale it] H. ISAAC (Sh. Jahrb., xix, 1884, 215) finds parallels in Romeo and Juliet, v.iii.114-15: \"seal with a righteous kiss A dateless bargain to engrossing death\"; and Venus and Adonis, line 511: \"Pure lips, sweet seals in my soft lips imprinted, What bargains may I make, still to be sealing?\""]},"210":{"play":"the witness. Here I hold your hand, here my","notes":[]},"211":{"play":"cousin’s. If ever you prove false one to another, since","notes":[]},"212":{"play":"I have taken such pains to bring you together, let","notes":[]},"213":{"play":"all pitiful goers-between be called to the world’s","notes":[]},"214":{"play":"end after my name: call them all panders. Let all","notes":[]},"215":{"play":"constant men be Troiluses, all false women Cressids,","notes":["constant] HEATH (Revisal, 1765, pp. 498-99 re the current reading \"inconstant\"): The ancient reading ... is certainly the true one. It is clearly the intention of the poet, that this imprecation should be such a one as was verified by the event, as it is in part to this very day. But neither was Troilus ever a name used to denote an inconstant lover, nor, if we credit the story of this play, did he ever deserve that character, as both the others did in truth deserve that shame here imprecated upon them. Besides, Pandarus seems to adjust his imprecation to those of the other two preceding just as they dropped from their lips, \"as false as Cressid,\" and consequently, \"as true,\" or, \"as constant, as Troilus.\"—TYRWHITT (Var. '78): Though Hanmer's emendation be plausible, I believe Shakespeare wrote \"constant.\" He seems to have been less at-"]},"216":{"play":"and all brokers-between panders. Say “Amen.”","notes":[]},"217":{"play":"TROILUS: Amen.","notes":[]},"218":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Amen.","notes":[]},"219":{"play":"PANDARUS: Amen. Whereupon I will show you a chamber","notes":[]},"220":{"play":"with a bed, which bed, because it shall not","notes":[]},"221":{"play":"speak of your pretty encounters, press it to death.","notes":[]},"222":{"play":"Away.    Troilus and Cressida exit.","notes":[]},"223":{"play":"And Cupid grant all tongue-tied maidens here","notes":[]},"224":{"play":"[Bed, chamber, pander to provide this gear.]","notes":[]},"225":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 3, SCENE 3":{"1":{"play":"[Flourish. Enter Ulysses, Diomedes, Nestor,","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"Agamemnon, Calchas, Menelaus, and Ajax.]","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"CALCHAS: Now, princes, for the service I have done you,","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"Th’ advantage of the time prompts me aloud","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"To call for recompense. Appear it to your mind","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"That, through the sight I bear in things to come,","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"I have abandoned Troy, left my possessions,","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"Incurred a traitor’s name, exposed myself,","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"From certain and possessed conveniences,","notes":["possess’d conveniences, To doubtful fortunes.] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I am afraid, that after all the learned commentator’s efforts to clear the argument of Calchas, it will still appear liable to objection; nor do I discover more to be urged in his defence, than that though his skill in divination determined him to leave Troy, yet that he joined himself to Agamemnon and his army by unconstrain’d good-will; and though he came as a fugitive escaping from destruction, yet his services after his reception being voluntary and important, deserved reward. This argument is not regularly and distinctly deduced, but this is, I think, the best explication that it will yet admit.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 499): The words of Calchas will bear no other reasonable sense, than that he had abandoned Troy, from the foresight he had of the destruction that hung over it. and would inevitably overwhelm it. The following passage ... which Mr. Warburton adduces as inconsistent with this interpretation, is a strong confirmation of the truth of it. The sense is plainly, You may be sure I have the fullest persuasion of the certainty of my prediction, otherwise I should not have quitted certain and possessed conveniencies, to risque my fortunes with you, which, as they depend absolutely on your will and pleasure, I must still consider as doubtful.—MALONE (ed. 1790): Mr. Theobald thinks it strange that Calchas should claim any merit from having joined the Greeks, after he had said that he knew his country was undone; but there is no inconsistency: he had left, from whatever cause, what was dear to him, ... and, having joined and served the Greeks, was entitled to protection and reward.—BAYNES (Edinburgh Review, CXXX, 1869, 103–04): Taking “sight” in the sense of “foresight,” Calchas seems to say that through his certain knowledge the Greeks would prove victorious he had deserted the Trojans, and deserved special recompense for his timely retiring. Some shadow of this difficulty will probably attach to any explanation of the passage that may be given. But it is certainly softened by taking “sight” not in the usual and special sense of prescience, but in the general sense of acquaintance, skill, technical knowledge, professional conversation, a meaning by no means unusual in Shakspeare’s day. ... Taking “sight” in this sense, the speech of Calchas would mean, “through the general skill I have in things pertaining to Jove ... in my character as a priest.”—[All this argument is beside the point. Nothing could be plainer, in the Recuyell and the Troy Book, than the reasons for Calchas’"]},"10":{"play":"To doubtful fortunes, sequest’ring from me all","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"That time, acquaintance, custom, and condition","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"Made tame and most familiar to my nature,","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"And here, to do you service, am become","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"As new into the world, strange, unacquainted.","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"I do beseech you, as in way of taste,","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"To give me now a little benefit","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"Out of those many regist’red in promise,","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"Which you say live to come in my behalf.","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: What wouldst thou of us, Trojan, make demand?","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"CALCHAS: You have a Trojan prisoner called Antenor","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"Yesterday took. Troy holds him very dear.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"Oft have you—often have you thanks therefor—","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"Desired my Cressid in right great exchange,","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"Whom Troy hath still denied; but this Antenor,","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"I know, is such a wrest in their affairs","notes":["wrest] Douce (in Steevens, ed. 1793): [Wrest] means an instrument for tuning the harp by drawing up the strings. Laneham, in his Letter from Kenilworth [1871], p. 50, describing a minstrel, says, “his harp in good grace dependant before him; his wreast tyed to a green lace and hanging by.” ... To wrest, is to wind. [DOUCE cites other evidences, here and in his Illustrations (1807, II, 61–62), from which it appears that a wrest was used for tuning any stringed instrument.]"]},"26":{"play":"That their negotiations all must slack,","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"Wanting his manage; and they will almost","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"Give us a prince of blood, a son of Priam,","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"In change of him. Let him be sent, great princes,","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"And he shall buy my daughter; and her presence","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"Shall quite strike off all service I have done","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"In most accepted pain.","notes":["paine] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Sir T. Hanmer, and Dr. Warburton after him, read ... \"pay.\" They do not seem to understand the construction of the passage. \"Her presence,\" says Calchas, \"shall strike off,\" or recompence \"the service I have done, even in these labours which were most accepted.\"—DYCE (ed. 1865) argues for \"pay.\" \"The original compositor probably mistook 'paie' for 'paine': and 'pay' is supported by the preceding words of the sentence, 'buy my daughter'.\"—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) paraphrases \"in ... paine\" as \"in hardships to which I have most cheerfully submitted.\"—[If the text is right, one must almost toss a coin between Johnson and Deighton. But Johnson has a slight advantage, in that Calchas does not, in this speech, urge the losses he has sustained but rather the services he has rendered.—ED.—Calchas has served painfully but most acceptably (if he may judge by the attitude of the Princes).—B.]"]},"33":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Let Diomedes bear him,","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"And bring us Cressid hither. Calchas shall have","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"What he requests of us. Good Diomed,","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"Furnish you fairly for this interchange.","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"Withal, bring word if Hector will tomorrow","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"Be answered in his challenge. Ajax is ready.","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"DIOMEDES: This shall I undertake, and ’tis a burden","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"Which I am proud to bear.  He exits with Calchas.","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"Achilles and Patroclus stand in their tent.","notes":["Enter ... Tent] DELIUS (Sh. Jahr., VIII, 1873, 190): Act 3, Scene 3,"]},"42":{"play":"ULYSSES: Achilles stands i’ th’ entrance of his tent.","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"Please it our General pass strangely by him","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"As if he were forgot, and, princes all,","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"Lay negligent and loose regard upon him.","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"I will come last. ’Tis like he’ll question me","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"Why such unplausive eyes are bent, why turned on","notes":["Why ... turn’d on him] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): If the eyes were bent on him, they were turn’d on him. This tautology therefore, together with the redundancy of the line, plainly show that we ought to read, with SIR THOMAS HANMER: “Why such unplausive eyes are bent on him.”—LEE (ed. 1910) considers “why turn’d on him” to be “obviously a gloss which has accidentally crept into the text.”—GREG (Principles of Emendation in Sh., 1928, p. 36): Of course it is quite possible that “bent” and “turn’d” were originally alternatives, but the line is by no means impossible or even ineffective as it stands, and if it had no more than a single authority behind it I should still question whether it was right to extrude the words “why turn’d.”"]},"48":{"play":"him.","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"If so, I have derision medicinable","notes":["derision] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) remarks that in the ensuing dialogue with Achilles “nothing is less like derision in its ordinary sense than the line which Ulysses takes. ... The language there employed is seriously argumentative and skilfully persuasive, without a trace of irony, sarcasm or veiled mockery.” Accordingly he would understand by “derision” here “pretended seriousness of remonstrance,” a meaning which unfortunately is supported neither by Sh. nor by anyone else. It is plain fact that what Ulysses proposes here and what he later does are quite different; here he says that he will meet pride and arrogance with pride and derision. But as many commentators have noticed, the whole treatment of Achilles in the famous dialogue with Ulysses is at variance with the treatment of him elsewhere in the play. It would be an easy hypothesis to suppose that this dialogue is one of the later additions to the play, replacing an earlier scene of the satiric kind; to suppose further that the change was made because Sh. had discovered the parallel between Achilles and Essex, and wished to introduce an earnest admonition to his erring patron. (See Appendix, pp. 377–81.) There must be some reason for the apparent abandonment of a plan.—[The strangeness of the Princes is"]},"50":{"play":"To use between your strangeness and his pride,","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"Which his own will shall have desire to drink.","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"It may do good; pride hath no other glass","notes":["pride ... glasse] FAIRHOLT (in Halliwell, ed. 1864): The allusion seems borrowed from the emblematic pictures of Pride, common to the Shaksperian era; and which were often reproduced in the masques on state occasions.—[Thus Spenser's Pride (F.Q., I.iv.10): \"And in her hand she held a mirrhour bright, Wherein her face she often vewed fayne.\"]"]},"53":{"play":"To show itself but pride, for supple knees","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"Feed arrogance and are the proud man’s fees.","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: We’ll execute your purpose and put on","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"A form of strangeness as we pass along;","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"So do each lord, and either greet him not","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"Or else disdainfully, which shall shake him more","notes":["things to lore.] To support \"lore\" he goes to Chaucer's Troilus, 1.64 ff.: \"Now fil it so, that in the toun ther was ... A gret devyn, that cleped was Calkas, That in science so expert was, that he Knew wel that Troye sholde destroyed be. ... So whan this Calkas knew by calcullinge, And eke by answere of this Appollo, That Greekes sholden swiche a peple brynge,\" etc. \"Here the words 'That in science so expert was,' and 'So whan this ... Appollo,' correspond precisely with 'through the 'sight I bear in things of lore,' and scientia was of old the usual equivalent of 'lore'.—[All of which could be just as well said of 'things to come.' Deighton omits the best argument of his emendation, probably because it is too obvious to need comment—the literal closeness of \"lore\" and \"love.\" But on this point see Tannenbaum below.]—Thiselton (Nohulea Critique, 1907, 63–71, p. 29): [The original text] is perfectly intelligible, if due allowance is made for the old punctuation. \"In things to love\" (i.e. \"in things loveable\") is not to be taken in connection with \"the sight I beare,\" but with what follows, where many of such things are detailed.—Tannenbaum (Sh. Assoc. Bull., vii, 1932, 76) supports the reading \"come.\" \"From other errors in the Shakspere canon we know that his Roman c (a letter which many Elizabethans preferred to the secretary c) was sometimes mistaken for an l; also, that Shakspere's m, n, and v (u) were often indistinguishable (in this very play we have a number of such errors, e.g. 'same' for 'sieve').\"—[It must be agreed that \"come\" has no authority. But it fits the occasion as detailed in the sources, it is unmistakably clear, and indeed it falls almost inevitably after \"things.\" If \"love\" be a misreading of \"come,\" it is, as Tannenbaum shows, a quite plausible error.] 6–7. That ... Troy] Caxton, Recuyell, Bk. III, Chap. vi (ed. Sommer, n, 551; text from 1597 ed., p. 475): [Calchas is sent to the temple of Apollo at Delphos. After he makes oblations] Apollo answered to him: Calchas, Calchas, beware that thou returne not againe to Troy: but go thou with Achilles vnto the Greekes, and depart neuer from them, for the Greekes shall haue victorie of the Troyans, by the agreement of the Gods, and thou shalt be to them right necessarie in counsell, and in doctrine.—Lydgate (ed. Bergen, E.E.T.S., Bk. II, lines 5997 ff.; text from ed. 1555, sig. L2 v): [Apollo] sayd Calchas twies by his name. Be right wel ware thou ne tourne agayne, To Troye towne for that were but in vayne. For finally lerne this thinge of me, In shorte tyme it shall destroyed be. This is in sothe whych may not be denyed. Wherfore I wil that thou be alyed, With the Grekes and with Achilles go. ... And"]},"59":{"play":"Than if not looked on. I will lead the way.","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"They pass before Achilles and Patroclus. Ulysses","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"remains in place, reading.","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"ACHILLES: What, comes the General to speak with me?","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"You know my mind: I’ll fight no more ’gainst Troy.","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"AGAMEMNON, to Nestor","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"What says Achilles? Would he aught with us?","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"NESTOR, to Achilles","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"Would you, my lord, aught with the General?","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"ACHILLES: No.","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"NESTOR: Nothing, my lord.","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: The better. Agamemnon and Nestor exit.","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"ACHILLES, to Menelaus  Good day, good day.","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"MENELAUS: How do you? How do you? He exits.","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"ACHILLES: What, does the cuckold scorn me?","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"AJAX: How now, Patroclus?","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"ACHILLES: Good morrow, Ajax.","notes":["Good morrow] Steevens (ed. 1793): Perhaps in this repetition of the salute, we should read, as in the preceding instance,—“Good morrow, Ajax”; or, with more colloquial spirit,—“I say, good morrow.” Otherwise the metre is defective. 77–84. They passe by ... owne fall] Carter (Sh. and Holy Scripture, 1905, pp. 385–86) compares Ecclesiasticus xiii, 22—“If a rich man fal, his friends set him up againe, but when the poore falleth, his friends drive him away.”—B. 86–88. And not a man ... favour] Taylor (Sh.’s Debt to Montaigne, 1925, p. 17) compares Florio’s Montaigne (ed. 1603, pp. 139–40): “Why doe we not likewise esteeme a man for that which is his owne? He hath a goodly traine of men following him, a stately pallace to dwell-in, so great credit amongst men; and so much rent comming-in. Alas, all that is about him, and not in him. ... A man should be judged by himselfe, and not by his comple-"]},"76":{"play":"AJAX: Ha?","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"ACHILLES: Good morrow.","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"AJAX: Ay, and good next day too.  He exits.","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"ACHILLES: What mean these fellows? Know they not Achilles?","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"PATROCLUS: They pass by strangely. They were used to bend,","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"To send their smiles before them to Achilles,","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"To come as humbly as they use to creep","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"To holy altars.","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"ACHILLES: What, am I poor of late?","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"’Tis certain, greatness, once fall’n out with Fortune,","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"Must fall out with men too. What the declined is","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"He shall as soon read in the eyes of others","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"As feel in his own fall, for men, like butterflies,","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"Show not their mealy wings but to the summer,","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"And not a man, for being simply man,","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"Hath any honor, but honor for those honors","notes":["but honour (Q)] SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 431): The second \"honour\" in this line, which spoils the metre and perplexes the sense, was, I think, evidently, a slip of the transcribers, much more excusable than all the editors who have retained the mistake. 90-93. Which when ... fall] W. W. LLOYD (Athenaeum, 20 Jan., 1883, p. 86) finds the grammar insoluble. What is the construction of \"Which?\" of \"Doth one pluck?\" of \"together Dye?\" The emendations (see Textual Notes) \"Do one\" and \"Do 'th' one\" clear up the construction from there to the end of the sentence, but leave line 91 hanging. What has happened is that"]},"92":{"play":"That are without him—as place, riches, and favor,","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"Prizes of accident as oft as merit,","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"Which, when they fall, as being slippery slanders,","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"The love that leaned on them, as slippery too,","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"Doth one pluck down another and together","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"Die in the fall. But ’tis not so with me.","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"Fortune and I are friends. I do enjoy,","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"At ample point, all that I did possess,","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"Save these men’s looks, who do, methinks, find out","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"Something not worth in me such rich beholding","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"As they have often given. Here is Ulysses.","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"I’ll interrupt his reading.—How now, Ulysses?","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"ULYSSES: Now, great Thetis’ son—","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"ACHILLES: What are you reading?","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"ULYSSES: A strange fellow here","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"Writes me that man, how dearly ever parted,","notes":["how ... parted] HANMER (ed. 1744): That is, “how valuable soever his parts are.”—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): It means, “however excellently endowed,” with however dear or precious parts enriched or adorned."]},"108":{"play":"How much in having, or without or in,","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"Cannot make boast to have that which he hath,","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"Nor feels not what he owes, but by reflection;","notes":["owes] Owns, possesses. See SCHMIDT (1875). 111 ff. The beautie, etc.] STEEVENS (Var. ’78)-first called attention to the"]},"111":{"play":"As when his virtues, shining upon others,","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"Heat them, and they retort that heat again","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"To the first giver.","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"ACHILLES: This is not strange, Ulysses.","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"The beauty that is borne here in the face","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"The bearer knows not, but commends itself","notes":["but commends] But it commends; a type of common ellipsis. Compare Winter's Tale, iv.iv.168-69: \"They call him Doricles; and boasts himself To have a worthy feeding.\" See also ABBOTT (Sh. Grammar, 1872, §404), and FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §306). 112b. See note to l.162, and Appendix, pp. 416–18.—B.","married] SINGER (Sh. Vindicated, 1853, p. 198), speaking of the change in Collier’s folio to “mirror’d,” says that the same correction is made in his own copy of F2. “It is on all accounts a legitimate and desirable correction.”—[LETTSOM in Blackwood’s (LXXIV, 1853, 319) finds Collier’s mirror’d “a very excellent emendation,” but doubts whether the verb was used in Sh.’s time.—[As a matter of fact, N.E.D. lists no use of it before the nineteenth century.]—WHITE (Sh.’s Scholar, 1854, p. 356) approves “mirror’d.” Even if it was not a verb in Sh.’s England, “this is no ground for deciding that such a bold writer as Shakespeare did not use it; while it is the best reason for believing that a compositor who had never seen the word ‘mirrored’ should suppose it to be ‘married.’”—[In spite of F and Q, and of the fact that “married” can be made to yield some sense, “mirror’d” has effectually established itself in modern texts. Although Collier’s F is worthless as evidence, Singer’s F bears witness that “mirror’d” was thought to be the more sensible word as early as the seventeenth century. The Platonic passage which is thought to be the source strongly supports the relationship of eye and mirror.—ED.]"]},"117":{"play":"To others’ eyes; nor doth the eye itself,","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"That most pure spirit of sense, behold itself,","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"Not going from itself, but eye to eye opposed","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"Salutes each other with each other’s form.","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"For speculation turns not to itself","notes":["[speculation] SCHMIDT (1875): Vision, power of sight. Compare Macbeth, iii.iv.95-96: \"Thou hast no speculation in those eyes Which thou dost glare with.\" 115-17. turnes not, etc.] RANN (ed. 1789): For the sight conveys no knowledge of itself, till it meets with an object that reflects it."]},"122":{"play":"Till it hath traveled and is mirrored there","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"Where it may see itself. This is not strange at all.","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"ULYSSES: I do not strain at the position—","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"It is familiar—but at the author’s drift,","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"Who in his circumstance expressly proves","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"That no man is the lord of anything—","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"Though in and of him there be much consisting—","notes":[]},"129":{"play":"Till he communicate his parts to others;","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"Nor doth he of himself know them for aught","notes":[]},"131":{"play":"Till he behold them formed in the applause","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"Where they’re extended; who, like an arch, reverb’rate","notes":["who ... reuerb'rate] BOSWELL (Var. '21): I.e. They who applaud reverberate. This elliptic mode of expression is in our author's manner.—DYCE (ed. 1857): But, if we retain “reverberate,” we must also change “receives and renders back” to “receive and render back.”—I have merely (with the editor of the second folio) altered “reverb'rate” to “reverberates,”—understanding “who” as equivalent to “which.” Compare ... [below in this scene, line 210] “There is a mysterie, (with whom relation Durst neuer meddle).”—[For Sh.’s use of “who” for “which,” see FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §335).]"]},"133":{"play":"The voice again or, like a gate of steel","notes":["gate] HUDSON (ed. 1881, p. 349): I do not well understand what is meant by “A gate of steel.” Mr. P. A. Daniel [Notes and ... Emendations, 1870, p. 59] suggests “a glass of steel,” and so I suspect we ought to read. A steel mirror might well serve the purpose in question; but how a steel gate? Gate, however, may mean door; and a door plated with polished steel may have been what the Poet had in thought."]},"134":{"play":"Fronting the sun, receives and renders back","notes":[]},"135":{"play":"His figure and his heat. I was much rapt in this","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"And apprehended here immediately","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"Th’ unknown Ajax. Heavens, what a man is there!","notes":["The vnknowne Aiax] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Ajax, who has abilities which were never brought into view or use.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906), after noting [and quoting inaccurately—B.] the gloss of the COWDEN CLARKES (ed. 1868) (“unknown to himself, wanting in true self-knowledge,” which finds some support in “That has he knowes not what”), prefers SCHMIDT (1875), “hinted at unintentionally and unconsciously,” adding that this “seems best, since ‘here’ in the line above means ‘in this description.’” 131–33. The vnknowne ... there are] TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., IX, 1934, 133): The lines were evidently revised. In F line 131 is only a half-line and is metrical; in Q [it] is full and unmetrical. Considering that in Q line 133 ... consists of only three feet, whereas in F it consists of six feet, and that both in Q and in F we have a period after the word “are,” only one conclusion seems possible: these lines are a marginal substitution for matter which the poet marked for deletion from his original version of the speech. Ulysses’ speeches evidently concerned him a great deal and he worked on them with more than ordinary care."]},"138":{"play":"A very horse, that has he knows not what!","notes":[]},"139":{"play":"Nature, what things there are","notes":["what. Nature] THISELTON (Notulae Criticae, 1907, 63–71, p. 29): I have long suspected that the full stop after “what” was inserted by mistake, owing to the initial capital in “Nature,” and that the true reading is “That has he knowes not what Nature.”"]},"140":{"play":"Most abject in regard, and dear in use,","notes":[]},"141":{"play":"What things again most dear in the esteem","notes":[]},"142":{"play":"And poor in worth! Now shall we see tomorrow—","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"An act that very chance doth throw upon him—","notes":["feasting] MALONE (ed. 1790): I have preferred “fasting,” the reading of the quarto, ... not only because the quarto copies are in general preferable to the folio, but because the original reading furnishes that kind of antithesis of which our poet was so fond. One man eats, while another fasts. Achilles is he who fasts; who capriciously abstains from those active exertions which would furnish new food for his pride."]},"144":{"play":"Ajax renowned. O, heavens, what some men do","notes":["Ajax renown’d] MALONE (Var. ’85): I would read: “Ajax renown.” The passage as it stands in the folio is hardly sense. If “renown’d” be right, we ought to read: “By an act,” &c.—MALONE (ed. 1790): I once thought that we ought to read “renown.” But by considering the middle line as parenthetical, the passage is sufficiently clear.—HENLEY (ed. 1793): By placing a break after “him,” the construction will be: “Now we shall see to-morrow an act that very chance doth throw upon him—we shall see] Ajax renown’d.”"]},"145":{"play":"While some men leave to do!","notes":[]},"146":{"play":"How some men creep in skittish Fortune’s hall,","notes":["creepę] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): This is said with design that Achilles should apply it to himself and Ajax. But as “creep” is to be applied to Achilles, it conveys a wrong idea, as representing one who is timorous and afraid to achieve great acts: whereas it should represent one entirely negligent in achieving them. For this was then Achilles’s case. So that we should read, “How some men sleep in skittish Fortune’s hall.”—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): To “creep” is to “keep out of sight” from whatever motive. Some men “keep out of notice in the hall of Fortune, while others,” though they but “play the ideot,” are always “in her eye,” in the way of distinction.—MALONE (ed. 1790): I cannot think that “creep,” used without any explanatory word, can mean to “keep out of sight.” While some men, says Ulysses, remain “tamely inactive” in fortune’s hall, without any effort to excite her attention, others, &c.","Non videmus manticae quod in tergo est.] Babrius’ Aesop.—D. T. STARNES (N.Q., 14 Jan., 1939, p. 29) quotes from John Withals’ English-Latin Dictionarie for Children (ed. Wm. Clerk, 1602): “A trusse or packe. ... It is a double poake, bagged at both ends and hangeth behind and before on his shoulder that doth weare it, and thereof is our proverb, Non videmus manticae quod in tergo est. ... It is spoken of reprehension in other mens faults by such as can not see their owne, who be supposed to put other me[n]s faults in the wallet before them, and their owne in that behind them.”—[Erasmus begins his adage, “Catullus in Scazonte, Sed non videmus manticae quod in tergo est. Id est, non videmus nostra ipsorum vitia, quum aliena curiosis oculis perspicamus,” assigns the origin to Aesop, and quotes instances from Persius, Horace, and St. Jerome. Chapman (ed. Parrot, 1910, Byron’s Tragedy, iv.i.36) speaks of “the wallet of their faults.” In the Epistle Dedicatory, 1598, to his Homer, he writes: “And to cast this [poetry] with our vanities at our backs. ...” In Barna-velt (Bullen’s Old English Plays, 1883, II, 285) it is the “bag of his deserts.” Foxe (Acts, ed. 1570, II, 2042) writes: “And so the archbishop casting into the satchell behinde hym all those Syr Iohn Gostewickes ingratitudes. ...” It is apparent from these citations that the standard contents of the two bags are vices or faults, but that writers filled the bags according to their purposes. Apparently no one but Sh. joined the figures of the two bags and Time. In Coriolanus (II.i.35-37) he again refers to the adage: “You talk of pride: O that you could turn your eyes toward the napes of your necks, and make but an interior survey of your good selves!” In this case the implied contents of the rearward bag is the traditional vices of the owner.—Ed.—The use in Coriolanus is based on Persius (BALDWIN, Small Latine, 1944, II, 544-46). That in T. and C. is more general.—B.]"]},"147":{"play":"Whiles others play the idiots in her eyes!","notes":[]},"148":{"play":"How one man eats into another’s pride,","notes":[]},"149":{"play":"While pride is fasting in his wantonness!","notes":[]},"150":{"play":"To see these Grecian lords—why, even already","notes":[]},"151":{"play":"They clap the lubber Ajax on the shoulder","notes":[]},"152":{"play":"As if his foot were on brave Hector’s breast","notes":["[shrinking] MALONE (in Steevens, ed. 1793): The following passage in the subsequent scene [v.viii.99 ff.] supports the reading of the quarto [\"shrinking\"]: \"Harke how Troy roares; how Hecuba cries out; etc.—STEEVENS (the same): I prefer the reading of the folio. That the collective body of martial Trojans should “shrink” at sight of their hero’s danger, is surely more natural to be supposed, than that, like frighted women, they would unite in a general “shriek.”—[The military would shrink, but the citizens would shriek. And it is probable that the citizenry, not the military, is comprehended in the term “great Troy.” Malone’s citation from Act V is apposite.—Ed.—The picture is of Ajax with foot on Hector’s breast, sword upraised for the final blow, while the Greeks clap him on the shoulder in commendation, as Hector (“great Troy,” the city in its champion, a usual rhetorical figure) shrinks under the coming catastrophe. Hector (and Troy) would shrink under the blow of Ajax; they would not shriek. See v.viii.13 and the succession of figures leading up to it.—B.]"]},"153":{"play":"And great Troy shrieking.","notes":[]},"154":{"play":"ACHILLES: I do believe it, for they passed by me","notes":[]},"155":{"play":"As misers do by beggars, neither gave to me","notes":[]},"156":{"play":"Good word nor look. What, are my deeds forgot?","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"ULYSSES: Time hath, my lord, a wallet at his back","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"Wherein he puts alms for oblivion,","notes":["Time ... wallet] BOADEN (Var. '03): This image is literally from Spenser [F.Q., vi.viii.23-24]: “And eeke this wallet at your backe arreare ... And in this bag which I behinde me don, I put repentance for things past and gon.”—[Spenser tells us that the bag is torn, so that the contents fall out and are trampled by Scorn.]—ANDERS (Sh. Jbch., lxii, 1926, 158) thinks that Sh. had in mind Phaedrus’ Aesop (iv, 10), where we are told that Jupiter gave man two bags, one for his own faults (at his back) and one for his neighbor’s (at his breast).—“HIBERNICUS” (N.Q., 25 Sept., 1937, p. 227) agrees in thinking the source to be ultimately Phaedrus, and that for our own faults Sh. has substituted benefits received. “The notion was part of the common Elizabethan stock, known either from Erasmus’ Adages, I.vi.90, or from one of several collections cooked up out of his work.” In support he cites Chapman, The Tragedy of Sir John van Olden Barnavelt, and Foxe.—EDWARD BENSLY (N.Q., 9 Oct., 1937, p. 265) adds citations from Seneca, Plutarch’s Crassus, and"]},"159":{"play":"A great-sized monster of ingratitudes.","notes":["monster] The reference of “monster” has given trouble. SINGER (N.Q., 13 March, 1858, p. 202) quotes from a correspondent: “The ‘Monster’ should be the ‘alms,’ yet the next line calls these ‘scraps,’ and keeps to the plural number.” The same correspondent suggests “great portmanteau”; again, with a swing to Time, “great scythed monster.” Singer himself confidently emended “monster” to “muster.” J.W.M. (N.Q., 3 April, 1858, p. 270) pointed out that “monster” must refer to “oblivion” (as it is commonly taken to do), and that the old text is right."]},"160":{"play":"Those scraps are good deeds past, which are devoured","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"As fast as they are made, forgot as soon","notes":[]},"162":{"play":"As done. Perseverance, dear my lord,","notes":[]},"163":{"play":"Keeps honor bright. To have done is to hang","notes":[]},"164":{"play":"Quite out of fashion like a rusty mail","notes":["ruffie male] CRAIG (ed. 1905) quotes from North’s Plutarch (“Life of Caius Marius,” ed. 1595, p. 466): “and therefore in time of peace they made no more reckoning of him [Marius] then they did of an old rusty harnesse or implement that was good for nothing, but for the warres only.” 160–62. take ... a breatf] NOBLE (Sh.’s Biblical Knowledge, 1935, p. 215): Apparently in reminiscence of Matt. vii, 14: “Because straite is the gate, and narowe is the way which leadeth vnto life.” The Quarto and Folio reading “straight” is retained here instead of “strait” usually adopted by editors. The meaning in my opinion is governed by the word “instant” in the line before, which means quickest, and therefore I take our line to imply that honour travels in a straight path so narrow, etc.—B."]},"165":{"play":"In monumental mock’ry. Take the instant way,","notes":[]},"166":{"play":"For honor travels in a strait so narrow","notes":[]},"167":{"play":"Where one but goes abreast. Keep, then, the path,","notes":["one ... a breatf] “One” must of course be the indefinite pronoun—where there is room only for one man to walk abreast of another.—Ed.—But the figure is of single file, with the leader in front, while the others “one by one pursue.” The author has evidently overlooked the literal meaning of abreast.—B."]},"168":{"play":"For Emulation hath a thousand sons","notes":[]},"169":{"play":"That one by one pursue. If you give way","notes":[]},"170":{"play":"Or turn aside from the direct forthright,","notes":["forth right] STAUNTON (ed. 1860): A “forthright” means a straight path: thus in the Tempest, III.iii.3: “here’s a maze trod, indeed, Through forth-rights and meanders!”"]},"171":{"play":"Like to an entered tide they all rush by","notes":[]},"172":{"play":"And leave you hindmost;","notes":[]},"173":{"play":"Or, like a gallant horse fall’n in first rank,","notes":["Lye] MALONE (ed. 1790): The construction is, Or, like a gallant horse, &c. you lie there for pavement—; the personal pronoun of a preceding line being understood here. There are many other passages in these plays in which a similar ellipsis is found.—FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §306) explains the frequent omission of the personal pronoun as either an attempt at the casualness of colloquial speech or a concession to meter. See 112 above. abject.] PARADISE (ed. 1927): This meaning of \"abject\" ... is somewhat unusual. ... There is no implication that the rear was cowardly and in flight, but rather that it was despicable in being in the rear rather than in the front of battle. The application of the lines is that Achilles will be trampled on by less worthy and less courageous men than himself when they do come up.—SCHMIDT (1874): Mean, despicable [which is probably all that is intended]. abject, neere] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): We should read, \"abject Rear,\" i.e. the mean abject horses which, by reason of their unfitness for service, are put into the rear of the line; or at least become the rear in a vigorous charge.—PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910): All that is requisite for the sense is better supplied by the text as it stands. The \"abject\" are the mean, those not held in high repute, who are not in \"the first ranke,\" but who take advantage of the initiative of others. Being thrown upon the gallant pioneer who paves the way for them, he is nearly overrun and trampled on by those who, thus, are in the present, enabled to overtop one who was a leader, in the past. This figure, of course, implies that Achilles, the charger who was in the first rank, is now paving the way for one of the \"abject\" to overtop him. Ulysses does not mean to intimate that Ajax is the \"rear,\" but the \"abject.\"—[Reference to Textual Notes will show that Warburton's emendation has had universal acceptance.—ED.—Cooper (Thesaurus, 1565) defines \"Abiectus ... Base of courage ... prostrate.\" Since the best were put in front, the rear was necessarily abject.]"]},"174":{"play":"Lie there for pavement to the abject rear,","notes":[]},"175":{"play":"O’errun and trampled on. Then what they do in","notes":[]},"176":{"play":"present,","notes":[]},"177":{"play":"Though less than yours in past, must o’ertop yours;","notes":[]},"178":{"play":"For Time is like a fashionable host","notes":[]},"179":{"play":"That slightly shakes his parting guest by th’ hand","notes":[]},"180":{"play":"And, with his arms outstretched as he would fly,","notes":[]},"181":{"play":"Grasps in the comer. Welcome ever smiles,","notes":["the welcome] MALONE (ed. 1790): The compositor inadvertently repeated the word “the,” which has just occurred."]},"182":{"play":"And Farewell goes out sighing. Let not virtue seek","notes":[]},"183":{"play":"Remuneration for the thing it was,","notes":[]},"184":{"play":"For beauty, wit,","notes":[]},"185":{"play":"High birth, vigor of bone, desert in service,","notes":[]},"186":{"play":"Love, friendship, charity are subjects all","notes":[]},"187":{"play":"To envious and calumniating Time.","notes":[]},"188":{"play":"One touch of nature makes the whole world kin,","notes":["One touch of nature] TAYLOR (Sh.’s Debt to Montaigne, 1925, p. 17) cites Florio’s Montaigne (ed. 1603, p. 566): “Amongst humane conditions, this one is verie common, that wee are rather pleased with strange things then with our owne: we loue changes, affect alterations, and like innovations.”—Many protests have been made against the common misapplication of this “sentence.” For example, a correspondent who signs himself “KILLIGREW” (N.Q., 25 April, 1885, p. 325): “When are we to get rid of the palpable misapplication of these too familiar words? ... Popular opinion would seem to paraphrase the sentence to this effect: ‘Only touch the feelings and your world is with you.’ Whether the speaker was a ‘man of sentiment’ or not, he was speaking only as a man of sense when he expressed his opinion that ‘the love of novelty is common to all mankind’; for that, if paraphrase be needed, is the"]},"189":{"play":"That all, with one consent, praise newborn gauds,","notes":[]},"190":{"play":"Though they are made and molded of things past,","notes":[]},"191":{"play":"And give to dust that is a little gilt","notes":[]},"192":{"play":"More laud than gilt o’erdusted.","notes":[]},"193":{"play":"The present eye praises the present object.","notes":[]},"194":{"play":"Then marvel not, thou great and complete man,","notes":[]},"195":{"play":"That all the Greeks begin to worship Ajax,","notes":[]},"196":{"play":"Since things in motion sooner catch the eye","notes":[]},"197":{"play":"Than what stirs not. The cry went once on thee,","notes":[]},"198":{"play":"And still it might, and yet it may again,","notes":[]},"199":{"play":"If thou wouldst not entomb thyself alive","notes":[]},"200":{"play":"And case thy reputation in thy tent,","notes":[]},"201":{"play":"Whose glorious deeds but in these fields of late","notes":[]},"202":{"play":"Made emulous missions ’mongst the gods themselves","notes":["missions] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): “Missions,” for divisions, i.e. goings out, on one side and the other.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): The meaning ... seems to be “dispatches” of the gods “from heaven,” about mortal business, such as often happened at the siege of Troy.—STEEVENS (Var. ’78): It means the descent of deities to combat on either side; an idea which Shakespeare very probably adopted from Chapman’s translation of Homer. In the fifth book Diomed wounds Mars, who on his return to heaven is rated by Jupiter for having interfered in the battle. This disobedience is the “faction” which I suppose Ulysses would describe.—[If this instance was in Sh.’s mind, he could not have got it from Chapman, whose seven books of the Iliad did not include the fifth.]"]},"203":{"play":"And drave great Mars to faction.","notes":[]},"204":{"play":"ACHILLES: Of this my privacy,","notes":[]},"205":{"play":"I have strong reasons.","notes":[]},"206":{"play":"ULYSSES: But ’gainst your privacy","notes":[]},"207":{"play":"The reasons are more potent and heroical.","notes":[]},"208":{"play":"’Tis known, Achilles, that you are in love","notes":[]},"209":{"play":"With one of Priam’s daughters.","notes":["one of Priams daughters] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): Polyxena, in the act of marrying whom, [Achilles] was afterwards killed by Paris. daughters] WALKER (Sh.’s Versification, 1854, p. 207) and ABBOTT (Sh. Grammar, 1872, §478) read “daughter” as a trisyllable, here and elsewhere. Abbott’s explanation is that “er final seems to have been sometimes pronounced with a kind of ‘burr,’ which produced the effect of an additional syllable.”"]},"210":{"play":"ACHILLES: Ha? Known?","notes":[]},"211":{"play":"ULYSSES: Is that a wonder?","notes":[]},"212":{"play":"The providence that’s in a watchful state","notes":[]},"213":{"play":"Knows almost every grain of Pluto’s gold,","notes":["Plutus] STEEVENS (Var. ’73): I think we should read, “of Plutus’ gold.” So Beaumont and Fletcher’s Philaster, act 4 [ed. Dyce, 1843, i, 282]: “’Tis not the wealth of Plutus, nor the gold Lock’d in the heart of earth.”—[BECKET (Concordance, 1787, p. 165 n.): “Pluto” is right. Pluto is properly the god of riches. Plutus is rather the keeper or distributor of those riches.—B]—PERCY SIMPSON (N.Q., 30 Sept., 1899, p. 265): Even if Greek writers had not definitely connected Pluto with the idea of riches under the earth, Shakespeare, who had small Latin and less Greek, is not a nice authority on points of classical usage; and for his “Pluto” here he had the authority of Marlowe … in Hero and Leander [ed. Brooke, 1910, lines 325–26], at the close of the second sestiad: “Whence his admiring eyes more pleasure tooke, Than Dis, on heapes of gold fixing his looke. [And see Duchess of Malfi, III.iii.283 (ed. Lucas, 1927, II, 78): “Pluto the god of riches.”]—ROLLINS (P.M.L.A., xlvi, 1931, 792–93): There are several pieces of evidence to show that the ancients themselves … occasionally confused or identified Plutus and Pluto … as may be seen by reading the commentators on Aristophanes’ Plutus, 727, and Thesmophoriazusae, 298.—B.]—TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., vii, 1932, 77): The propriety of departing from the Folio admits of serious question. Shakspere has “Pluto” in Julius Caesar (IV.iii.101), “Plutus” in Timon of Athens (I.i.278) and “Platus” (a misprint) in All’s Well (V.iii.101). Elizabethans were not punctilious in distinguishing between Pluto, the god of the underworld, and Plutus, the personification of wealth.—[William Smith (Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology, 1849, III, 432) explains “Pluton (Πλούτων), the giver of wealth, at first a surname of Hades, the god of the lower world, and afterwards also used as the real name of the god.” Comes (Mythologiae, 1581, p. 179) says “Pluto siue elementum sit terrae, siue diuitiarum Deus, utroque nomine filius est Saturni.” Stephanus (Dictionarium historicum ac poeticum, 1570, f. 269r) has it “Dictus Pluton ἀπὸ τῶν πλούτων, hoc est a diuitiis, eò quòd opes omnes ab inferis, hoc est, ex intimis terrae visceribus eruantur. Eandem etiam ob causam Latini Ditem appellarunt. Cic. 2. de Nat. deo.” These are Pluto’s grains of gold in intimis terrae visceribus. Further, the following line shows that this is the correct interpretation. According to these authorities, Sh. is also correct about “Pluto’s mine” in Julius Caesar, IV.iii.101, where the text is usually tampered. In the other instances of use, Sh. refers to the god of"]},"214":{"play":"Finds bottom in the uncomprehensive deep,","notes":["incomprehensible] SCHMIDT (1875): Incomprehensible, mysterious.—This is one of a group of Sh.'n adjectives in -ive which have a passive meaning, instead of the usual active. See FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §130)."]},"215":{"play":"Keeps place with thought and almost, like the gods,","notes":["place] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. there is in the providence of a state, as in the providence of the universe, a kind of ubiquity. The expression is exquisitely fine. Yet the Oxford Editor [Hanmer] alters it to \"Keeps pace,\" and so destroys all its beauty.—KINNEAR (Cruces, 1883, p. 297) explains \"keeps place with\" as meaning consorts, lives with, and cites Merry Wives, II.i.53-55: \"but they do no more adhere and keep place together than the Hundredth Psalm to the tune of 'Green Sleeves.' \""]},"216":{"play":"Do thoughts unveil in their dumb cradles.","notes":["Doe ... dumbe cradles] MALONE (ed. 1790): It is clear from the defect of the metre that some word of two syllables was omitted by the carelessness of the transcriber or compositor. [For his conjectures see Textual Notes.]—HUDSON (ed. 1854): That is, in their infancy, and before they can give themselves utterance; as we know men often act out their thoughts before they express them, and even before they are fully conscious of having them; some pre-existing impulse being in fact the seed of the thought.—STAUNTON (ed. 1860): \"Dumb cradles,\" the silent \"incunabula\" of thoughts, may be right, but the doubtful expression and the limping measure of the line instruct us to suspect some error lurks under the word \"cradles,\" which, indeed, we once believed a misprint for \"oracles.\"—PERRING (N.Q., 22 June, 1907, p. 484) argues for \"dumb heraldry\"; pronounced and spelled \"eraldry,\" the word could be easily corrupted to \"cradles.\"—C.C.B. (N.Q., 31 Aug., 1907, p. 165) thinks that \"oracles\" is a better guess than \"heraldry,\" but questions whether a change is needed.—\"TOM JONES\" (N.Q., 31 Aug., 1907, p. 165) thinks no change is called for. \"The concluding idea is introduced to carry conviction, and the illustration is rounded off with a completeness which we find in Shakespeare and in no other author. The adjective 'dumb' is the proper attribute not to 'cradles,' but to 'thoughts'; and 'unveil' is also figuratively used from the familiar and homely object of a mother at the cradleside unveiling her infant. To vary the expression—providence not only keeps pace with thought, but unveils the new-born thoughts in their cradles.\"—BULLOCH (Studies, 1878, p. 177) suggests \"radicles,\" a term not elsewhere in Sh., but which is \"one of those Latinised expressions of a purely scientific cast, and likely to be used by Bacon. ... While the"]},"217":{"play":"There is a mystery—with whom relation","notes":[]},"218":{"play":"Durst never meddle—in the soul of state,","notes":["mysterie] This seems to be a fairly plain allusion to secret service, or service of information, such as was well established at the court of Elizabeth (and James) and well known, but never written about. relation] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): History. SCHMIDT (1875): Account, report."]},"219":{"play":"Which hath an operation more divine","notes":[]},"220":{"play":"Than breath or pen can give expressure to.","notes":[]},"221":{"play":"All the commerce that you have had with Troy","notes":[]},"222":{"play":"As perfectly is ours as yours, my lord;","notes":[]},"223":{"play":"And better would it fit Achilles much","notes":[]},"224":{"play":"To throw down Hector than Polyxena.","notes":[]},"225":{"play":"But it must grieve young Pyrrhus now at home","notes":[]},"226":{"play":"When Fame shall in our islands sound her trump,","notes":["Ilands (Q)! Both CAMBRIDGE editions make the mistake of giving the Q reading as “Iland.”"]},"227":{"play":"And all the Greekish girls shall tripping sing","notes":[]},"228":{"play":"“Great Hector’s sister did Achilles win,","notes":[]},"229":{"play":"But our great Ajax bravely beat down him.”","notes":[]},"230":{"play":"Farewell, my lord. I as your lover speak.","notes":[]},"231":{"play":"The fool slides o’er the ice that you should break.","notes":["The foole slides] COLLIER (ed. 1842) calls attention to an anecdote in Robert Armin’s Nest of Ninnies which may be alluded to in this remark. Jack Miller, a town fool, crossed forty yards of thin ice to join a band of strolling players. Armin testifies that he was a spectator; “My hart aked when my eares heard the ise crack all the way.” See Sh. Soc. reprint, 1842, p. 38. And see Appendix, p. 365.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): The inner meaning of this aphorism is not touched upon by any commentator known to me. Delius, indeed, says: “Under Achilles, a man of great weight, the ice would break, over which"]},"232":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]},"233":{"play":"PATROCLUS: To this effect, Achilles, have I moved you.","notes":[]},"234":{"play":"A woman impudent and mannish grown","notes":[]},"235":{"play":"Is not more loathed than an effeminate man","notes":[]},"236":{"play":"In time of action. I stand condemned for this.","notes":[]},"237":{"play":"They think my little stomach to the war,","notes":[]},"238":{"play":"And your great love to me, restrains you thus.","notes":[]},"239":{"play":"Sweet, rouse yourself, and the weak wanton Cupid","notes":["wanton Cupid] WALKER (Critical Examination, 1860, III, 196): “Wanton” is a substantive, and should have a comma after it."]},"240":{"play":"Shall from your neck unloose his amorous fold","notes":[]},"241":{"play":"And, like a dewdrop from the lion’s mane,","notes":["ayre ayre] STEWART (Some Textual Difficulties in Sh., 1914, pp. 14–19) argues for the F reading, because (1) it lends itself to dramatic gesture; (2) it contrasts better with “shook”; (3) the argument that a noun should not be modified by an adjective made from it does not hold—there are different kinds of air, and “airy” suggests air in motion; (4) it is not a compositor’s error—if so, we should have “ayre ayre”; the differentiation shows careful attention to the text."]},"242":{"play":"Be shook to air.","notes":[]},"243":{"play":"ACHILLES: Shall Ajax fight with Hector?","notes":[]},"244":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Ay, and perhaps receive much honor by him.","notes":[]},"245":{"play":"ACHILLES: I see my reputation is at stake;","notes":[]},"246":{"play":"My fame is shrewdly gored.","notes":["gored] COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868): This expressive word ... combines the meaning of bloodily torn and wounded as by the horn of an animal, and smirched, polluted, as derived from the Saxon word “gor,” dirt, mud, filth.—[N.E.D. gives no sense of the verb which relates to “gor” meaning filth."]},"247":{"play":"PATROCLUS: O, then, beware!","notes":[]},"248":{"play":"Those wounds heal ill that men do give themselves.","notes":[]},"249":{"play":"Omission to do what is necessary","notes":[]},"250":{"play":"Seals a commission to a blank of danger,","notes":[]},"251":{"play":"And danger, like an ague, subtly taints","notes":[]},"252":{"play":"Even then when they sit idly in the sun.","notes":[]},"253":{"play":"ACHILLES: Go call Thersites hither, sweet Patroclus.","notes":[]},"254":{"play":"I’ll send the fool to Ajax and desire him","notes":[]},"255":{"play":"T’ invite the Trojan lords after the combat","notes":[]},"256":{"play":"To see us here unarmed. I have a woman’s longing,","notes":[]},"257":{"play":"An appetite that I am sick withal,","notes":[]},"258":{"play":"To see great Hector in his weeds of peace,","notes":[]},"259":{"play":"To talk with him, and to behold his visage,","notes":[]},"260":{"play":"Even to my full of view.","notes":[]},"261":{"play":"[Enter Thersites.]","notes":[]},"262":{"play":"A labor saved.","notes":[]},"263":{"play":"THERSITES: A wonder!","notes":[]},"264":{"play":"ACHILLES: What?","notes":[]},"265":{"play":"THERSITES: Ajax goes up and down the field, asking for","notes":[]},"266":{"play":"himself.","notes":[]},"267":{"play":"ACHILLES: How so?","notes":[]},"268":{"play":"THERSITES: He must fight singly tomorrow with Hector","notes":[]},"269":{"play":"and is so prophetically proud of an heroical cudgeling","notes":[]},"270":{"play":"that he raves in saying nothing.","notes":[]},"271":{"play":"ACHILLES: How can that be?","notes":[]},"272":{"play":"THERSITES: Why, he stalks up and down like a peacock—","notes":[]},"273":{"play":"a stride and a stand; ruminates like an hostess","notes":[]},"274":{"play":"that hath no arithmetic but her brain to set","notes":[]},"275":{"play":"down her reckoning; bites his lip with a politic regard,","notes":["with ... regard] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): With a \"sly look.\"—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): [With] a look of profound wisdom."]},"276":{"play":"as who should say “There were wit in this","notes":[]},"277":{"play":"head an ’twould out”—and so there is, but it lies","notes":[]},"278":{"play":"as coldly in him as fire in a flint, which will not","notes":[]},"279":{"play":"show without knocking. The man’s undone forever,","notes":[]},"280":{"play":"for if Hector break not his neck i’ th’ combat,","notes":[]},"281":{"play":"he’ll break ’t himself in vainglory. He knows not","notes":[]},"282":{"play":"me. I said “Good morrow, Ajax,” and he replies","notes":[]},"283":{"play":"“Thanks, Agamemnon.” What think you of this","notes":[]},"284":{"play":"man that takes me for the General? He’s grown a","notes":[]},"285":{"play":"very land-fish, languageless, a monster. A plague of","notes":["land-fish] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) explains, \"as completely at his wits' end as a fish on shore\"; and SCHMIDT (1874), \"a fish on land, one dumb like a fish,\" although why a fish on land should be dumber than one in water is not clear. [N.E.D. gives, I think, the true explanation: \"a fish that lives on land; hence, an unnatural creature.\" Pliny has a chapter (ix.lvii) on land fishes. Among those which \"are about Babylon,\" as Philemon Holland translates (1601, I, 268), some \"are headed-like to the sea Frog, made in other parts as Gudgeons, and guilded in manner of other fishes.\" Batman vppon Bartholome (1582) seems to regard hippopotamuses and crocodiles as species of land fish.] 274-75. a plague of opinion] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): This is said in compliment to Achilles. Opinion went all for him before, as now for Ajax. But the observation is fine, and admirably expressed.—[SCHMIDT (1875) and others take \"opinion\" to mean conceit, arrogance, referring it to Ajax. But then what is meant by Ajax's wearing his conceit on both sides? If \"opinion\" means what it does elsewhere in this play, reputation, then the sense would seem to be that a man may wear his reputation with its good or ill side outward. Thersites has a way of darting from the particular to the general.—ED.—Cooper (The"]},"286":{"play":"opinion! A man may wear it on both sides, like a","notes":[]},"287":{"play":"leather jerkin.","notes":[]},"288":{"play":"ACHILLES: Thou must be my ambassador to him,","notes":[]},"289":{"play":"Thersites.","notes":[]},"290":{"play":"THERSITES: Who, I? Why, he’ll answer nobody. He professes","notes":[]},"291":{"play":"not answering; speaking is for beggars; he","notes":[]},"292":{"play":"wears his tongue in ’s arms. I will put on his presence.","notes":[]},"293":{"play":"Let Patroclus make his demands to me. You","notes":[]},"294":{"play":"shall see the pageant of Ajax.","notes":[]},"295":{"play":"ACHILLES: To him, Patroclus. Tell him I humbly desire","notes":[]},"296":{"play":"the valiant Ajax to invite the most valorous Hector","notes":[]},"297":{"play":"to come unarmed to my tent, and to procure safe-conduct","notes":[]},"298":{"play":"for his person of the magnanimous and","notes":[]},"299":{"play":"most illustrious, six-or-seven-times-honored captain","notes":[]},"300":{"play":"general of the Grecian army, Agamemnon,","notes":["&c.] DYCE (ed. 1857): [This symbol] is not unusual in old plays printed from the prompter's book: it seems to mean that the actor of the part might, if he chose, \"speak more than was set down for him.\""]},"301":{"play":"et cetera. Do this.","notes":[]},"302":{"play":"PATROCLUS, to Thersites, who is playing Ajax  Jove","notes":[]},"303":{"play":"bless great Ajax.","notes":[]},"304":{"play":"THERSITES: Hum!","notes":[]},"305":{"play":"PATROCLUS: I come from the worthy Achilles—","notes":[]},"306":{"play":"THERSITES: Ha?","notes":[]},"307":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Who most humbly desires you to invite","notes":[]},"308":{"play":"Hector to his tent—","notes":[]},"309":{"play":"THERSITES: Hum!","notes":[]},"310":{"play":"PATROCLUS: And to procure safe-conduct from","notes":[]},"311":{"play":"Agamemnon.","notes":[]},"312":{"play":"THERSITES: Agamemnon?","notes":[]},"313":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Ay, my lord.","notes":[]},"314":{"play":"THERSITES: Ha!","notes":[]},"315":{"play":"PATROCLUS: What say you to ’t?","notes":[]},"316":{"play":"THERSITES: God b’ wi’ you, with all my heart.","notes":[]},"317":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Your answer, sir.","notes":[]},"318":{"play":"THERSITES: If tomorrow be a fair day, by eleven of the","notes":[]},"319":{"play":"clock it will go one way or other. Howsoever, he","notes":[]},"320":{"play":"shall pay for me ere he has me.","notes":[]},"321":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Your answer, sir.","notes":[]},"322":{"play":"THERSITES: Fare you well with all my heart.","notes":[]},"323":{"play":"[He pretends to exit.]","notes":[]},"324":{"play":"ACHILLES: Why, but he is not in this tune, is he?","notes":[]},"325":{"play":"THERSITES: No, but he’s out of tune thus. What music","notes":[]},"326":{"play":"will be in him when Hector has knocked out his","notes":[]},"327":{"play":"brains I know not. But I am sure none, unless the","notes":[]},"328":{"play":"fiddler Apollo get his sinews to make catlings on.","notes":["catlings] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): A “catling” signifies a small lute-string made of catgut. One of the musicians in Romeo and Juliet is called Simon Catling."]},"329":{"play":"ACHILLES: Come, thou shalt bear a letter to him","notes":[]},"330":{"play":"straight.","notes":[]},"331":{"play":"THERSITES: Let me bear another to his horse, for that’s","notes":[]},"332":{"play":"the more capable creature.","notes":["capable] Having general capacity, intelligence, or ability (N.E.D.); more precisely, as MALONE suggests, “intelligent.”"]},"333":{"play":"ACHILLES: My mind is troubled, like a fountain stirred,","notes":[]},"334":{"play":"And I myself see not the bottom of it.","notes":[]},"335":{"play":"[Achilles and Patroclus exit.]","notes":[]},"336":{"play":"THERSITES: Would the fountain of your mind were clear","notes":[]},"337":{"play":"again, that I might water an ass at it. I had rather","notes":[]},"338":{"play":"be a tick in a sheep than such a valiant ignorance.","notes":[]},"339":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 4, SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Enter at one door Aeneas with a Torchbearer, at","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"another Paris, Deiphobus, Antenor, Diomedes and","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"Grecians with torches.]","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"PARIS: See, ho! Who is that there?","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"DEIPHOBUS: It is the Lord Aeneas.","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"AENEAS: Is the Prince there in person?—","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"Had I so good occasion to lie long","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"As you, Prince Paris, nothing but heavenly business","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"Should rob my bedmate of my company.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"DIOMEDES: That’s my mind too.—Good morrow, Lord Aeneas.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"PARIS: A valiant Greek, Aeneas; take his hand.","notes":["valiant] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): The epithet—“valiant” appears to have been caught by the compositor from the preceding speech, and is introduced here only to spoil the metre."]},"12":{"play":"Witness the process of your speech, wherein","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"You told how Diomed a whole week by days","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"Did haunt you in the field.","notes":["haunt] UPTON (Critic. Observations, 1746, pp. 242-43): Presently after Diomede says to Æneas, “By Jove I’ll play the hunter for thy life. Æn. And thou shalt haunt a lion. ...” How can we doubt then but Paris says, “Did haunt you in the field?”"]},"15":{"play":"AENEAS: Health to you, valiant sir,","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"During all question of the gentle truce;","notes":["question] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): “Question,” for force, virtue.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): How “question” should mean “force” or “virtue,” I cannot find. If such latitude of exposition be allowed, what can be difficult? I once thought to read, “During all quiet of the gentle truce”: But I think “question” means intercourse, interchange of conversation."]},"17":{"play":"But when I meet you armed, as black defiance","notes":["as blacke defiance, etc.] The enmity between Æneas and Diomed arose at the interview in Troy when Ulysses and Diomed came as ambassadors from Agamemnon to demand the return of Helen. Æneas taunted the Greeks, and Diomed lost his temper; each threatened the other with reprisals on the battle-field. See Appendix, p. 433. It is Sh. who changes mere hate into “the noblest hateful love” and gives a chivalrous coloring to their enmity which is found nowhere in his sources."]},"18":{"play":"As heart can think or courage execute.","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"DIOMEDES: The one and other Diomed embraces.","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"Our bloods are now in calm, and, so long, health;","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"But when contention and occasion meet,","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"By Jove, I’ll play the hunter for thy life","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"With all my force, pursuit, and policy.","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"AENEAS: And thou shalt hunt a lion that will fly","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"With his face backward. In human gentleness,","notes":["backward, in humaine gentlenesfe] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): What Con-"]},"26":{"play":"Welcome to Troy. Now, by Anchises’ life,","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"Welcome indeed. By Venus’ hand I swear","notes":["by Venus hand] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): This oath was used to insinuate his resentment for Diomedes wounding his mother in the hand.—STEEVENS (Var. '73): I believe Shakespeare had no such allusion in his thoughts. He would hardly have made Æneas civil and uncivil in the same breath.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Rather, as Blakeway says, \"he swears first by the life of his father and then by the hand of his mother.\""]},"28":{"play":"No man alive can love in such a sort","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"The thing he means to kill more excellently.","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"DIOMEDES: We sympathize. Jove, let Aeneas live,","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"If to my sword his fate be not the glory,","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"A thousand complete courses of the sun!","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"But in mine emulous honor let him die","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"With every joint a wound and that tomorrow.","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"AENEAS: We know each other well.","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"DIOMEDES: We do, and long to know each other worse.","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"PARIS: This is the most despiteful gentle greeting,","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"The noblest hateful love, that e’er I heard of.","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"To Aeneas. What business, lord, so early?","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"AENEAS: I was sent for to the King, but why I know not.","notes":["I was] TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., VII, 1932, 78) thinks this should be read \"I'se,\" just as one often reads \"you're\" for \"you were.\" See note on II.iii.83."]},"41":{"play":"PARIS: His purpose meets you. ’Twas to bring this Greek","notes":["His purpose meets you] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I bring you his meaning and his orders."]},"42":{"play":"To Calchas’ house, and there to render him,","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"For the enfreed Antenor, the fair Cressid.","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"Let’s have your company, or, if you please,","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"Haste there before us. (Aside to Aeneas.) I constantly","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"believe—","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"Or, rather, call my thought a certain knowledge—","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"My brother Troilus lodges there tonight.","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"Rouse him, and give him note of our approach,","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"With the whole quality whereof. I fear","notes":["quality whereof] RANN (ed. 1789): Substance of this business.—SCHMIDT (1875): Occasion, cause. Compare Timon, III.vi.107: “Know you the quality of Lord Timon’s fury?”—[Cooper (Thesaurus, 1565): Qualis ... Of what sorte or qualitie: of what facion.—B.]"]},"51":{"play":"We shall be much unwelcome.","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"AENEAS, aside to Paris  That I assure you.","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"Troilus had rather Troy were borne to Greece","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"Than Cressid borne from Troy.","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"PARIS, aside to Aeneas  There is no help.","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"The bitter disposition of the time","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"Will have it so.—On, lord, we’ll follow you.","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"AENEAS: Good morrow, all.","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"Aeneas exits with the Torchbearer.","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"PARIS: And tell me, noble Diomed, faith, tell me true,","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"Even in the soul of sound good-fellowship,","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"Who, in your thoughts, deserves fair Helen best,","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"Myself or Menelaus?","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Both alike.","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"He merits well to have her that doth seek her,","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"Not making any scruple of her soilure,","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"With such a hell of pain and world of charge;","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"And you as well to keep her that defend her,","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"Not palating the taste of her dishonor,","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"With such a costly loss of wealth and friends.","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"He, like a puling cuckold, would drink up","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"The lees and dregs of a flat tamèd piece;","notes":["flat tamed peece] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. a piece of wine out of which the spirit is all flown.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 501): A “tamed piece,” is a piece that hath been broached, and a part of it drawn out. In the western part of England we say, to “tame” a vessel, or a bottle, for, to draw, or pour out part of it.—[There is probably a play on “piece,” a cask of wine, and “piece,” a fairly common term for a woman. Compare Peele’s Tale of Troy, 1589, line 112 [ed. Bullen, 1888, II, 246]: “Fair Helena, that brave and peerless piece.”]"]},"73":{"play":"You, like a lecher, out of whorish loins","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"Are pleased to breed out your inheritors.","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"Both merits poised, each weighs nor less nor more;","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"But he as he, the heavier for a whore.","notes":["But ... whore] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I read, “But he as he, each heavier for a whore.” “Heavy” is taken both for “weighty,” and for “sad” or “miserable.” The quarto reads “... the heavier ...” I know not whether the thought is not that of a wager. It must then be read thus, “But he as he. Which heavier for a whore?” That is, “for a whore” staked down, “which is the heavier?”—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 501) would also read “each heavier.” “That is, each of you dragged down to ruin by your destructive connection with a whore.”—STEEVENS (Var. ’73): As the quarto reads, “—the heavier for a whore,” I think all new pointing or alteration unnecessary. The sense appears to be this: the merits of either are sunk in value, because the contest between them is only for a strumpet.—CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 131): The full sense intended is as follows;—“Both merits being poiz’d, each weighs nor less nor more than the other; but he is as he, and both are the heavier for a whore,” or for having a whore’s weight added to their own.—[VERITY (ed. 1889), thinks that Sh. changed “the” to “each,” and that the compositor misread “which.” But since the sense remains the same, whichever word is used, the matter is not very important. Of the two old readings Q is to be preferred.—ED.—Since a whore was “light,” the eventual point is, as the figure shows, that neither’s weight of merit would be increased by the whore Helen. I should prefer, therefore, the reading of F1. Since there was only one whore, it was a question of"]},"77":{"play":"PARIS: You are too bitter to your countrywoman.","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"DIOMEDES: She’s bitter to her country. Hear me, Paris:","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"For every false drop in her bawdy veins","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"A Grecian’s life hath sunk; for every scruple","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"Of her contaminated carrion weight","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"A Trojan hath been slain. Since she could speak,","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"She hath not given so many good words breath","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"As for her Greeks and Trojans suffered death.","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"PARIS: Fair Diomed, you do as chapmen do,","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"Dispraise the thing that they desire to buy.","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"But we in silence hold this virtue well:","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"We’ll not commend that not intend to sell.","notes":["Weele ... fell] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): But this is not talking like a chapman: for if it be the custom for the buyer to dispraise, it is the custom too for the seller to commend. Therefore, if Paris had an intention to sell Helen, he should, by this rule, have commended her. But the truth was he had no such intention, and therefore did prudently not to commend her: which shews Shakespear wrote, “We’ll not commend what we intend not sell,” i.e. what we intend not to sell.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I believe the meaning is only this: though you practise the buyer’s art, we will not practise the seller's. We intend to sell Helen dear, yet will not commend her.—TYRWHITT (Var. '73): The sense, I think, requires that we should read “condemn.”—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 314): The obvious objection to Johnson's explanation of this passage, which will also extend to Tyrwhitt’s amendment, is that the Greeks did not intend to sell Helen, but on the contrary had just determined not to part with her. I should therefore agree with Warburton in reading, “what we intend not sell.”—MALONE (ed. 1790): When Dr. Johnson says, they meant to sell Helen dear, he evidently does not mean that they really intended to sell her at all, (as he has been understood,) but that the Greeks should pay very dear for her. ... So Ajax (Thersites) says in a former scene [III.iii.304-305], “How-","commend what we intend not sell.] “Commend” is, I think, the true reading. — [Malone cites the 21st Sonnet: “I will not praise, that purpose not to sell,” as favoring Warburton’s emendation; but “intend not sell,” sounds very harsh. However, many very harsh combinations may be found in these plays, where rhymes are introduced.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Surely Dr. Warburton’s reading is the true one. “We’ll not commend what we intend not sell,” is evidently opposed to “Dispraise the thing that you desire to buy.”— BRINSLEY NICHOLSON (N. Q., 1 Sept., 1866, p. 164): Diomed’s words were too outspoken, and the subject dwelt upon overlong to please Paris; he therefore courteously closes it with the remark ending at “buy;” and turning off to the subject of their meeting, and pointing or looking to the house, says—We do differently; we’ll not commend our Cressida against Antenor—here lies our way. All the changes proposed on the supposition that the whole speech refers to Helen destroy the meaning and force of the third line [87].—MARSHALL (ed. 1889): It seems to me that the key to the meaning of the whole passage lies in line 86: “But we in silence hold this virtue well.” Paris here answers, with the courtesy and dignity of a gentleman, the vulgar abuse which Diomede, with such execrably bad taste, heaps upon Helen. ... He has already rebuked Diomede above in line 76: “You are too bitter to your countrywoman;” but Diomede, far from taking any notice of this rebuke, merely becomes more abusive. The reply of Paris may be awkwardly worded, but the meaning is quite clear; and the dignified sarcasm of it could hardly fail to have penetrated even Diomede’s panoply of self-conceit. “You,” Paris says, “practise the common trick of a petty dealer; ... you run down the article you want to buy, but we decline to compete with you on your own ground; we despise such tricks, and in silence hold fast to this virtue, not to ‘puff’ ... what we have to sell, but to let its value speak for itself.” Of course he means that they will part with Helen only as the prize of victory, and not for money; but the great point is that he excuses himself for not defending her from Diomede’s vulgar abuse by pointing out that, in such a case, a noble nature thinks silence the best answer.—THISELTON (Notulæ Criticæ, 1907, 63–71, p. 30) believes that “what we intend to sell” is “the lives of the Trojans to be lost for the purpose of retaining Helen,” which need no puffing.—LEE (ed. 1910): Paris deprecates Diomede’s vulgar depreciations of Helen with the assurance that the Trojans will not puff their wares like petty traders. Their value speaks for itself. Helen is not to be bartered in the petty ways of trade.—[The difficulty arises from the assumption that what Diomedes desires to buy, that is, Helen, is what the Trojans intend to sell, whereas that obviously is not the case. If we must specify the Trojans’ stock in trade, Thiselton’s statement is perhaps as good as any.—B.] iv. ii. See note at III. ii.—B. BAB (Shakespeare, 1925, p. 290): On the morning after the love-night ..."]},"89":{"play":"Here lies our way.","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 4, SCENE 2":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Troilus and Cressida.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"TROILUS: Dear, trouble not yourself. The morn is cold.","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Then, sweet my lord, I’ll call mine uncle down.","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"He shall unbolt the gates.","notes":["Who] HUDSON (ed. 1881, p. 351) \"cannot imagine\" what \"Who\" means here, and is sure it should be \"What!\"—TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., VII, 1932, 79) thinks that it \"probably represents Sh.'s 'ho!', an exclamation of impatience and disgust.\"—[N.E.D.: Stop! esp. as a call to a horse.—B.]"]},"5":{"play":"TROILUS: Trouble him not.","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"To bed, to bed! Sleep kill those pretty eyes","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"And give as soft attachment to thy senses","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"As infants’ empty of all thought!","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Good morrow, then.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"TROILUS: I prithee now, to bed.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Are you aweary of me?","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"TROILUS: O Cressida! But that the busy day,","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"Waked by the lark, hath roused the ribald crows,","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"And dreaming night will hide our joys no longer,","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"I would not from thee.","notes":["goe] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I believe the verb—“go” (which roughens this line) should be left out, in conformity to the ancient elliptical mode of writing, which, in like instances, omits it as unnecessary to sense. Thus [iv.ii.15] ... we find—“I would not from thee.”—SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 438): Mr. Steevens’s offered ellipsis, for reducing this line to metre, is not wanted; as the common contraction of “I will” to “I’ll” is sufficient for the purpose."]},"16":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Night hath been too brief.","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"TROILUS: Beshrew the witch! With venomous wights she stays","notes":["Venemous wights] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. with witches, who perform their venomous charms by night.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I.e. venefici; those who practise nocturnal sorcery.—ROLFE (ed. 1884) thinks that Steevens' interpretation is \"forced and improbable,\" and that \"venomous\" is used in a general sense, for \"malignant, as opposed to lovers.\"—SCHMIDT (1875), defining \"venemous\" as, metaphorically, \"pernicious, malignant,\" comments on Steevens' note: \"... which explication, strange to say, has been acquiesced in by the other commentators. Perhaps the words mean simply people thinking on evil.\""]},"18":{"play":"As tediously as hell, but flies the grasps of love","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"With wings more momentary-swift than thought.","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"You will catch cold and curse me.","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Prithee, tarry. You men will never tarry.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"O foolish Cressid! I might have still held off,","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"And then you would have tarried. Hark, there’s one up.","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"PANDARUS, within  What’s all the doors open here?","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"TROILUS: It is your uncle.","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"CRESSIDA: A pestilence on him! Now will he be mocking.","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"I shall have such a life!","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus.]","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"PANDARUS: How now, how now? How go maidenheads?","notes":["kill] JACKSON (Sh.'s Genius, 1819, p. 265): There is no great difficulty in accounting for the present error. The letter-case ... in which the k has its compartment, is next to that of the st: ... We should read ... \"still.\"—"]},"30":{"play":"Here, you maid! Where’s my Cousin Cressid?","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Go hang yourself, you naughty mocking uncle.","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"You bring me to do—and then you flout me too.","notes":["to doo] COLLINS [i.e. Steevens] (Var. ’78): To “do” is here used in a wanton sense.—BOSWELL (Var. ’21): The following speech of Pandarus shows clearly that there is not the least ground for ... (Mr. Steevens’s) observation. —[Whatever Cressida may have meant to “do,” there can be no question that Pandarus immediately turns it to a wanton sense. For instances, if needed, of use in this sense see SCHMIDT (1874).] 32-33. To doe ... you to doe] The intentions of the editors between HANMER and MALONE, as to whether these lines are verse or prose, are ambiguous."]},"33":{"play":"PANDARUS: To do what, to do what?—Let her say","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"what.—What have I brought you to do?","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Come, come, beshrew your heart! You’ll ne’er be good","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"Nor suffer others.","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"PANDARUS: Ha, ha! Alas, poor wretch! Ah, poor capocchia!","notes":["Chipochia] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): This ... is a Word in no living Language that I can find. Pandarus says it to his Neice, in a jeering Sort of Tenderness. ... He would say, I think, in English,—“Poor Innocent! Poor Fool! ha’st not slept to Night?” These Appellations are very well answer’d by the Italian Word Capocchia: for Capocchio signifies the thick Head of a Club; and thence metaphorically, a Head of not much Brain, a Sot, Dullard, heavy Gull.—DYCE (ed. 1857): Several editors print “capocchia,”—but wrongly, if the term is to be considered as Italian, and as meaning “simpleton” (though an ed. of Baretti’s Ital. Dict. is now before me, in which “capocchio” is given as an adjective.) The word “capocchia” signifies “the knob of a stick,” and—something else [i.e. foreskin].—[But since capocchio is an adjective, then capocchia is good Italian, whether or no it is good Sh. No one has bettered Theobald’s emendation, and it still stands.—ED.—MALONE (ed. 1790) refers to Florio (Worlde of Wordes, 1598): Capocchia, the foreskin or prepuce of a mans privie member.—B.]"]},"38":{"play":"Has ’t not slept tonight? Would he not—a","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"naughty man—let it sleep? A bugbear take him!","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"CRESSIDA, to Troilus","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"Did not I tell you? Would he were knocked i’ th’ head!","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"One knocks.","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"Who’s that at door?—Good uncle, go and see.—","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"My lord, come you again into my chamber.","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"You smile and mock me, as if I meant naughtily.","notes":["as if] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Here, I believe, a common ellipsis has been destroyed by a playhouse interpolation: “As,” in ancient language, has frequently the power of—“as if.” I would therefore omit the latter conjunction, which encumbers the line without enforcing the sense.—[It is true that Sh. frequently uses “as” for “as if.” See FRANZ, Sh.-Gram., 1939, §582. But the line is not encumbered beyond Sh.’s natural capacity.]"]},"46":{"play":"TROILUS: Ha, ha!","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Come, you are deceived. I think of no such thing.","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"Knock.","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"How earnestly they knock! Pray you, come in.","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"I would not for half Troy have you seen here.","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"[Troilus and Cressida exit.]","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"PANDARUS: Who’s there? What’s the matter? Will you","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"beat down the door?","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"[Enter Aeneas.]","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"How now? What’s the matter?","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"AENEAS: Good morrow, lord, good morrow.","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"PANDARUS: Who’s there? My Lord Aeneas? By my troth,","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"I knew you not. What news with you so early?","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"AENEAS: Is not Prince Troilus here?","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"PANDARUS: Here? What should he do here?","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"AENEAS: Come, he is here, my lord. Do not deny him.","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"It doth import him much to speak with me.","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"PANDARUS: Is he here, say you? It’s more than I know,","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"I’ll be sworn. For my own part, I came in late.","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"What should he do here?","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"AENEAS: Ho, nay, then! Come, come, you’ll do him","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"wrong ere you are ware. You’ll be so true to him to","notes":["ware] Not a shortening of \"aware.\" \"Ware\" is from OE wœr, \"aware\" from gewœr. Sh. uses the adjective \"ware\" five times, never \"aware.\" 61-62. Doe ... hither] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): You can affect, if you like, not to know anything about him, but, all the same, go, etc."]},"68":{"play":"be false to him. Do not you know of him, but yet go","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"fetch him hither. Go.","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"[Enter Troilus.]","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"TROILUS: How now? What’s the matter?","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"AENEAS: My lord, I scarce have leisure to salute you,","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"My matter is so rash. There is at hand","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"Paris your brother and Deiphobus,","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"The Grecian Diomed, and our Antenor","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"Delivered to us; and for him forthwith,","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"Ere the first sacrifice, within this hour,","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"We must give up to Diomedes’ hand","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"The Lady Cressida.","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"TROILUS: Is it so concluded?","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"AENEAS: By Priam and the general state of Troy.","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"They are at hand and ready to effect it.","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"TROILUS: How my achievements mock me!","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"I will go meet them. And, my Lord Aeneas,","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"We met by chance; you did not find me here.","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"AENEAS: Good, good, my lord; the secrets of nature","notes":["secrets of nature] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): I have ventur'd to make out the Verse thus; \"The Secret'st Things of Nature, &c.\" i.e. the Arcana Naturae, the Mysteries of Nature, of occult Philosophy, or of religious Ceremonies.—MALONE (Var. '85): \"The secrets of nature\" could hardly have been a corruption of \"the secrets of neighbour Pandar.\" Perhaps the alteration was made by the author, and that he wrote: ... \"the secrets of nature ... .\" So, in Macbeth [III.iv.126]: \"The secret'st man of blood.\"—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): There is no need of change. Secrets is here used as a trisyllable.—WALKER (Sh.'s Versification, 1854, pp. 10–11) proves by numerous citations that \"secrets\" was frequently a trisyllable with the Elizabethan poets. But he cites no instance from Sh.—ABBOTT (Sh. Grammar, 1872, §477), after abundantly illustrating the principle that \"r, and liquids in dissyllables, are frequently pronounced as though an extra vowel were introduced between them and the preceding consonant,\" adds, \"So also probably ‘sec(e)ret’,\" but gives no example. I fail to find any other instance in Sh. where \"secret\" is not clearly a dissyllable.—STAUNTON (ed. 1860): The error, we believe, ... is in the word \"secrets,\" which appears to have been a misprint for \"secretairs,\" or \"secretaries,\" meaning \"confidants.\"—N.E.D. cites Lodge's Rosalynde, 1592: \"Reueale it she durst not, as daring in such matters to make none her secretarie.\""]},"87":{"play":"Have not more gift in taciturnity.","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"[Troilus and Aeneas exit.]","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"PANDARUS: Is ’t possible? No sooner got but lost? The","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"devil take Antenor! The young prince will go mad.","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"A plague upon Antenor! I would they had broke ’s","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"neck!","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"[Enter Cressida.]","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"CRESSIDA: How now? What’s the matter? Who was here?","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"PANDARUS: Ah, ah!","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Why sigh you so profoundly? Where’s my lord?","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"Gone? Tell me, sweet uncle, what’s the matter?","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"PANDARUS: Would I were as deep under the earth as I","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"am above!","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O the gods! What’s the matter?","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"PANDARUS: Pray thee, get thee in. Would thou hadst","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"ne’er been born! I knew thou wouldst be his death.","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"O, poor gentleman! A plague upon Antenor!","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Good uncle, I beseech you, on my knees I","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"beseech you, what’s the matter?","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"PANDARUS: Thou must be gone, wench; thou must be","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"gone. Thou art changed for Antenor. Thou must to","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"thy father and be gone from Troilus. ’Twill be his","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"death; ’twill be his bane. He cannot bear it.","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O you immortal gods! I will not go.","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"PANDARUS: Thou must.","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"CRESSIDA: I will not, uncle. I have forgot my father.","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"I know no touch of consanguinity,","notes":["touch of consanguinitie] MALONE (ed. 1793): Sense or feeling of relationship."]},"114":{"play":"No kin, no love, no blood, no soul so near me","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"As the sweet Troilus. O you gods divine,","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"Make Cressid’s name the very crown of falsehood","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"If ever she leave Troilus! Time, force, and death","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"Do to this body what extremes you can,","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"But the strong base and building of my love","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"Is as the very center of the Earth,","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"Drawing all things to it. I’ll go in and weep—","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"PANDARUS: Do, do.","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Tear my bright hair, and scratch my praisèd cheeks,","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"Crack my clear voice with sobs, and break my heart","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"With sounding “Troilus.” I will not go from Troy.","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 4, SCENE 3":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Paris, Troilus, Aeneas, Deiphobus, Antenor,","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"and Diomedes.]","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"PARIS: It is great morning, and the hour prefixed","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"For her delivery to this valiant Greek","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"Comes fast upon. Good my brother Troilus,","notes":["fast upon] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Though “fast upon,” only signifies—“fast on,” I must suppose, with Sir Thomas Hanmer, we ought to read: “Comes fast upon us:—” The metre, as it stands at present, is obviously defective."]},"6":{"play":"Tell you the lady what she is to do","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"And haste her to the purpose.","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"TROILUS: Walk into her house.","notes":["Walke] STEEVENS (ed. 1793) proposes to eliminate “walk,” because it “destroys the measure.” He had the eighteenth century’s passion for “regularity,” and no understanding at all of Sh.’s metrical freedom—in this case of the free handling of last-line and first-line hemistichs. Walke into her house] PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910): This sets the scene as it was arranged for the Globe stage. ... As may be guessed from [iv.ii], “He shall unbolt the Gates,” the preceding scene was held in the upper stage, and Æneas knocked and called from below, then parleyed with Pandarus and Troylus, at the double door entrance into the rear stage on the ground floor of the stage, Æneas being outside “the gates,” throughout scene ii. Neither in Folio nor Quarto do we have ‘Enter Æneas’ at l. 49. It was there interpolated by Rowe. Now in this scene Paris with Troylus and the others appear on the fore stage and are invited to walk into her house, i.e. enter those gates, and at l. 15 they do “walke in”. ... They go off stage really through the main entrance into the rear stage, and the audience accepts this as walking into “her house.”"]},"9":{"play":"I’ll bring her to the Grecian presently;","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"And to his hand when I deliver her,","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"Think it an altar and thy brother Troilus","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"A priest there off’ring to it his own heart.      He exits.","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"PARIS: I know what ’tis to love,","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"And would, as I shall pity, I could help.—","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"Please you walk in, my lords?","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 4, SCENE 4":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus and Cressida, weeping.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"PANDARUS: Be moderate, be moderate.","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Why tell you me of moderation?","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"The grief is fine, full, perfect that I taste,","notes":["full perfect] CRAIG (ed. 1905) objects to the comma after “full” in all modern editions. “[It] spoils the metre. ‘Full perfect’ is ‘quite perfect’.”"]},"5":{"play":"And violenteth in a sense as strong","notes":["violenceth (Q)] According to N.E.D. the verb “to violent,” or “to violence,” was common in Sh.’s day in the transitive use, meaning “to constrain or force by violence.” In the intransitive sense, “to act or rage with violence,” only the present instance is cited. STEEVENS (Var. ’78) reported an instance in Jonson’s The Devil Is an Ass, 1616 [III.vi.59], “Nor nature violenceth in both"]},"6":{"play":"As that which causeth it. How can I moderate it?","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"If I could temporize with my affection","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"Or brew it to a weak and colder palate,","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"The like allayment could I give my grief.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"My love admits no qualifying dross;","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"No more my grief in such a precious loss.","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"[Enter Troilus.]","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"PANDARUS: Here, here, here he comes. Ah, sweet","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"ducks!","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"CRESSIDA, embracing Troilus  O Troilus, Troilus!","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"PANDARUS: What a pair of spectacles is here! Let me","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"embrace too. “O heart,” as the goodly saying is,","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"O heart, heavy heart,","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"Why sigh’st thou without breaking?","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"where he answers again,","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"Because thou canst not ease thy smart","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"By friendship nor by speaking.","notes":["friendship ... [speaking] DYCE (ed. 1857) remarks that this \"reads oddly,\" and mentions Collier's correction without comment.—HUDSON at first (ed. 1854) was strongly attracted to Collier's \"silence,\" but later (ed. 1881, p. 352) reversed his judgment. \"This ['silence'] is very plausible, but, I think, altogether wrong; for, besides that 'silence' could not easily have got misprinted 'friendship,' it quite misses the right sense. Doubtless a characteristic intimation lurks under the language; Pandarus meaning that relief must come from another sort of love than that of friendship.\"—This interpretation has come to be accepted; \"friendship\" (as ROLFE [ed. 1884] and DEIGHTON [ed. 1906] say) means \"mere friendship.\" rime] Where did Pandarus get this rhyme?—B."]},"23":{"play":"There was never a truer rhyme. Let us cast away","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"nothing, for we may live to have need of such a","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"verse. We see it, we see it. How now, lambs?","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"TROILUS: Cressid, I love thee in so strained a purity","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"That the blest gods, as angry with my fancy—","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"More bright in zeal than the devotion which","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"Cold lips blow to their deities—take thee from me.","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Have the gods envy?","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"PANDARUS: Ay, ay, ay, ay, ’tis too plain a case.","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"CRESSIDA: And is it true that I must go from Troy?","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"TROILUS: A hateful truth.","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"CRESSIDA: What, and from Troilus too?","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"TROILUS: From Troy and Troilus.","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Is ’t possible?","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"TROILUS: And suddenly, where injury of chance","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"Puts back leave-taking, jostles roughly by","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"All time of pause, rudely beguiles our lips","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"Of all rejoindure, forcibly prevents","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"Our locked embrasures, strangles our dear vows","notes":["deare] See note on v.iii.ii."]},"42":{"play":"Even in the birth of our own laboring breath.","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"We two, that with so many thousand sighs","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"Did buy each other, must poorly sell ourselves","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"With the rude brevity and discharge of one.","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"Injurious Time now with a robber’s haste","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"Crams his rich thiev’ry up, he knows not how.","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"As many farewells as be stars in heaven,","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"With distinct breath and consigned kisses to them,","notes":["With ... them] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): With the several utterances that should accompany those farewells, and with kisses that should ratify them.—SCHMIDT (1874) explains “kisses allotted to them”; but surely “consign’d” indicates the legal deliverance of a bond, “to them” meaning “in addition to them.” consign’d] HUDSON (ed. 1881): “Consign’d” for “consigning,” and with the sense of “sealing” or “confirming.”—N.E.D.: Committed, delivered, given"]},"50":{"play":"He fumbles up into a loose adieu","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"And scants us with a single famished kiss,","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"Distasted with the salt of broken tears.","notes":["broken] CAPELL (Notes, 1780, II, 132): Interrupted, broken-in upon.—MALONE (ed. 1790): Tears to which we are not permitted to give full vent, being interrupted and suddenly torn from each other. The poet was probably thinking of broken sobs, or broken slumbers.—WHITER (Specimen of a Commentary, 1794, p. 136): This word was certainly suggested to him by the “culinary” language, and the ideas annexed to it, into which he has fallen;—“Scants”—“famished”—“distasted”—“salt.\" He was certainly thinking of “broken meats”—“orts” or “fragments.”—MORGAN (Warwickshire Dialect, 1900, p. 318) says that in Warwickshire “broken tears” means “sobs.”—[How could one taste the salt of tears without their being broken?—B.]"]},"53":{"play":"AENEAS, within  My lord, is the lady ready?","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"TROILUS: Hark, you are called. Some say the genius","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"Cries so to him that instantly must die.—","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"Bid them have patience. She shall come anon.","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"PANDARUS: Where are my tears? Rain, to lay this wind,","notes":["raine ... winde] MALONE (ed. 1790) compares Lucrece, lines 1788-90: “This windy tempest, till it blow up rain, Held back his sorrow’s tide, to make it more; At last it rains, and busy winds give o’er.”—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Perhaps “rain, to lay this wind!” is an optative, and as if he had said—O for tears &c.! and so I have pointed it."]},"58":{"play":"or my heart will be blown up by the root.","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":["] PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910) think that Act IV ended here, \"the use of the rear-stage structure as Pandarus's house being concluded.\""]},"60":{"play":"CRESSIDA: I must, then, to the Grecians?","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"TROILUS: No remedy.","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"CRESSIDA: A woeful Cressid ’mongst the merry Greeks.","notes":["merry Greekes] See note on I.ii.110."]},"63":{"play":"When shall we see again?","notes":["When ... againe] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 6 March, 1729/30): [Without knowing Q, Theobald decides on logical grounds that the speech belongs to Cressida.] This is perfectly in character for Cressida; so Imogen, when her husband is on the point of going into his banishment: Cymbeline [I.i.123–24]: “O the gods! When shall we see again?”"]},"64":{"play":"TROILUS: Hear me, my love. Be thou but true of heart—","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"CRESSIDA: I true? How now, what wicked deem is this?","notes":["deeme] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Opinion, surmise. [This is Sh.’s only use of the word as substantive.]"]},"66":{"play":"TROILUS: Nay, we must use expostulation kindly,","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"For it is parting from us.","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"I speak not “Be thou true” as fearing thee,","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"For I will throw my glove to Death himself","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"That there is no maculation in thy heart;","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"But “Be thou true,” say I, to fashion in","notes":["fashion in] To “fashion,” in Sh., is frequently “to bring about, contrive.” As in Much Ado (II.ii.41–42): “I will so fashion the matter that Hero shall be absent.” To “fashion in,” not used elsewhere, would seem to mean “to shape or contrive so as to introduce,” or simply “to introduce.”"]},"72":{"play":"My sequent protestation: “Be thou true,","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"And I will see thee.”","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O, you shall be exposed, my lord, to dangers","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"As infinite as imminent! But I’ll be true.","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"TROILUS: And I’ll grow friend with danger. Wear this sleeve.","notes":["Weare this Sleeue] In Chaucer’s Troilus the lovers exchange no tokens at parting. On their first night together they “entrechaungeden hir ringes” and Criseyde gave Troilus “a broche, gold and asure” (III.1366 ff.). After"]},"77":{"play":"CRESSIDA: And you this glove. When shall I see you?","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"They exchange love-tokens.","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"TROILUS: I will corrupt the Grecian sentinels,","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"To give thee nightly visitation.","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"But yet, be true.","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O heavens! “Be true” again?","notes":["O heavens: be true againe] GARNETT (Contemporary Review, ciii, 1913, 185): The Cressida of Miss Edith Evans was an engaging study of a woman essentially light and fickle in soul. ... Nothing showed the justness and fineness of Mr. Poel’s conception better than his reading ... of the Lady Cressida’s leave-taking of her sorrowful lover. She is shown us as pinning on her hat, visibly intent on her looks and on her change of fortune, while Troilus is boring her with his repeated “But yet be true.” “Oh, heavens! be true again!” retorts the lady in her impatience to get his entreaties done with. Moral condemnation of Cressida is not merely out of place for the spectator, but is a misreading of this piece of subtle femininity.—[For other particulars of this production see Appendix, p. 505.]"]},"83":{"play":"TROILUS: Hear why I speak it, love.","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"The Grecian youths are full of quality,","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"Their loving well composed, with gift of nature","notes":["Their loving, etc.] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): The irregularity of metre in this speech, (unless the epithet—“loving” be considered as an interpolation,) together with the obscure phrase—“full of quality,” induce me to suspect the loss of some words which are now irretrievable.—[In Var. '03 he added: “ ‘Full of quality,’ however, may mean ‘highly accomplished.’ ” As indeed it does.]"]},"86":{"play":"flowing,","notes":["Flawing] CLARK and WRIGHT (ed. 1865): The word “Flowing” was in all probability a marginal correction for “swelling,” which the printer of the Folio by mistake added to the line.—[But see Appendix, p. 340.]"]},"87":{"play":"And swelling o’er with arts and exercise.","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"How novelty may move, and parts with person,","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"Alas, a kind of godly jealousy—","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"Which I beseech you call a virtuous sin—","notes":["godly iealoufie] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 6 March, 1729/30) cites Corinthians II, xi, 2: “For I am jealous over you with godly jealousy.” CARTER (Sh. and Holy Scripture, 1905, p. 386) also cites this passage, which"]},"91":{"play":"Makes me afeard.","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O heavens, you love me not!","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"TROILUS: Die I a villain then!","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"In this I do not call your faith in question","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"So mainly as my merit. I cannot sing,","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"Nor heel the high lavolt, nor sweeten talk,","notes":["lauiolt] NARES (Glossary, 1822): A kind of dance for two persons, consisting a good deal in high and active bounds.—[Compare Henry V, III.v.33: \"[They] teach lavoltas high and swift corantos.\"]"]},"97":{"play":"Nor play at subtle games—fair virtues all,","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"To which the Grecians are most prompt and pregnant.","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"But I can tell that in each grace of these","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"There lurks a still and dumb-discursive devil","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"That tempts most cunningly. But be not tempted.","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Do you think I will?","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"TROILUS: No.","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"But something may be done that we will not,","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"And sometimes we are devils to ourselves","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"When we will tempt the frailty of our powers,","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"Presuming on their changeful potency.","notes":["changefull potencie] DYCE (Strictures, 1859, p. 152): [Rejecting Collier’s emendation, “chainful.”] But why “must” the old reading “be wrong”? may not “their changeful potency” mean “their potency which is subject to variation, and therefore imperfect and not to be rashly relied on”?—HUDSON (ed. 1854): It would seem that this should read, “their changeless potency,” that is, their power of not changing; as this sense will best suit and cohere with the text. “Presuming on,” however, may very well carry the sense of men acting as if they were what they are not; for the way to “tempt the frailty of our powers” is by “presuming” that they are not frail; thus involving the common idea that the feeling of security makes men most insecure, or “best safety lies in"]},"108":{"play":"AENEAS, within","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"Nay, good my lord—","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"TROILUS: Come, kiss, and let us part.","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"They kiss.","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"PARIS, within","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"Brother Troilus!","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"TROILUS, calling  Good brother, come you hither,","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"And bring Aeneas and the Grecian with you.","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"CRESSIDA: My lord, will you be true?","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"TROILUS: Who, I? Alas, it is my vice, my fault.","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"Whiles others fish with craft for great opinion,","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"I with great truth catch mere simplicity.","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"Whilst some with cunning gild their copper crowns,","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"With truth and plainness I do wear mine bare.","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"Fear not my truth. The moral of my wit","notes":["morall] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, the “governing principle of my understanding,” but I rather think we should read ... “motto.”—[“Moral” here may mean “a doctrine, a maxim” (SCHMIDT, 1875), or “meaning, signification.” In the latter sense, “the moral of my wit” would mean “the gist of my analysis.”]"]},"123":{"play":"Is “plain and true”; there’s all the reach of it.","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"[Enter Aeneas, Paris, Antenor, Deiphobus, and","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"Diomedes.]","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"Welcome, Sir Diomed. Here is the lady","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"Which for Antenor we deliver you.","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"At the port, lord, I’ll give her to thy hand","notes":["port] N.E.D.: A gate or gateway: from the 14th c., usually that of a city or walled town. From F. porte; L. porta door, gate. Compare Coriolanus, V.vi.5-6: “Him I accuse The city ports by this hath enter’d.”"]},"129":{"play":"And by the way possess thee what she is.","notes":["possess’d] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I will “make thee fully understand.” This sense of the word “possess” is frequent in our author."]},"130":{"play":"Entreat her fair and, by my soul, fair Greek,","notes":[]},"131":{"play":"If e’er thou stand at mercy of my sword,","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"Name Cressid, and thy life shall be as safe","notes":[]},"133":{"play":"As Priam is in Ilium.","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Fair Lady Cressid,","notes":[]},"135":{"play":"So please you, save the thanks this prince expects.","notes":["save ... expects] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Here “save” is taken as a verb, with a colon after “expects.” I am not sure that it is not an adverb, with the sense “independently of the gratitude which this prince expects of me for his assurance of mercy, the lustre,” etc. If so, a comma will be the stop after “expects.”"]},"136":{"play":"The luster in your eye, heaven in your cheek,","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"Pleads your fair usage, and to Diomed","notes":[]},"138":{"play":"You shall be mistress and command him wholly.","notes":[]},"139":{"play":"TROILUS: Grecian, thou dost not use me courteously,","notes":[]},"140":{"play":"To shame the zeal of my petition to thee","notes":["seale] THEOBALD (ed. 1733, quoting Warburton): To “shame the Seal” of a Petition, carries no sensible Idea that I can find out. The Change of a single Letter makes Troilus’s Complaint apt and reasonable: “Grecian, you use me discourteously; you see, I am a passionate Lover, by my Petition to you; and therefore you should not shame the Zeal of it, by promising to do, what I require of you, for the Sake of her Beauty: when, if you had good Manners, or a Sense of a Lover’s Delicacy, you would have promised to do it in Compassion to his Pangs and Sufferings.”—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 502): [The text is right; Warburton has not taken pains to understand it.] But what is this seal of Troilus’s petition? It is, that if fortune ever subjected Diomede to the mercy of his sword, then the bare mention of Cressid’s name should be an effectual protection and security for his life and safety. The slight Diomede puts on this declaration ... is what Troilus calls “shaming” or affronting the “seal” of his petition, by treating it as a thing beneath his notice, and telling Cressida as much in very plain terms. This is a sense precise and determinate, very clearly and finely expressed; whereas Mr. Warburton’s conjecture is a general vague and cold expression, appealing only to Diomede’s politeness.—MALONE (ed. 1790): Troilus, I suppose, means to say, that Diomede does not use him courteously by addressing himself to Cressida, ... instead of making a direct answer to that warm request which Troilus had just made to him to “entreat her fair.”—[As the Textual Notes show, Warburton’s emendation has received an almost unanimous editorial approval.—ED.—But the text is clearly correct, since it sums up exactly, if obscurely, what has happened. Troilus has made a petition to Diomedes, who instead of sealing this petition which was “towards” (a word defined by N.E.D. [B I 1] as “in preparation, at hand, coming on, imminent,” therefore, in process), shames it (“shame the seale”; i.e., the sealing; i.e., prevents the seal from being affixed) by telling Cressida not to thank the Prince for it, that her own beauty is sufficient to win the desired effect.—B.]"]},"141":{"play":"In praising her. I tell thee, lord of Greece,","notes":[]},"142":{"play":"She is as far high-soaring o’er thy praises","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"As thou unworthy to be called her servant.","notes":[]},"144":{"play":"I charge thee use her well, even for my charge,","notes":["euen for my charge] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Merely because I so bid you."]},"145":{"play":"For, by the dreadful Pluto, if thou dost not,","notes":[]},"146":{"play":"Though the great bulk Achilles be thy guard,","notes":[]},"147":{"play":"I’ll cut thy throat.","notes":[]},"148":{"play":"DIOMEDES: O, be not moved, Prince Troilus.","notes":[]},"149":{"play":"Let me be privileged by my place and message","notes":[]},"150":{"play":"To be a speaker free. When I am hence,","notes":[]},"151":{"play":"I’ll answer to my lust, and know you, lord,","notes":[]},"152":{"play":"I’ll nothing do on charge. To her own worth","notes":[]},"153":{"play":"She shall be prized; but that you say “Be ’t so,”","notes":[]},"154":{"play":"I speak it in my spirit and honor: “no.”","notes":[]},"155":{"play":"TROILUS: Come, to the port. I’ll tell thee, Diomed,","notes":["Ile tell] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): This phraseology (instead of—“I tell thee”) occurs almost too frequently in our author, to need exemplification.—[E.g. King John, v.vi.39: “I’ll tell thee, Hubert, half my power this night,” etc.]"]},"156":{"play":"This brave shall oft make thee to hide thy head.—","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"Lady, give me your hand, and, as we walk,","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"To our own selves bend we our needful talk.","notes":[]},"159":{"play":"[Cressida, Diomedes, and Troilus exit.]","notes":[]},"160":{"play":"[Sound trumpet within.]","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"PARIS: Hark, Hector’s trumpet.","notes":[]},"162":{"play":"AENEAS: How have we spent this","notes":[]},"163":{"play":"morning!","notes":[]},"164":{"play":"The Prince must think me tardy and remiss","notes":[]},"165":{"play":"That swore to ride before him to the field.","notes":[]},"166":{"play":"PARIS: ’Tis Troilus’ fault. Come, come to field with him.","notes":[]},"167":{"play":"DEIPHOBUS: Let us make ready straight.","notes":[]},"168":{"play":"AENEAS: Yea, with a bridegroom’s fresh alacrity","notes":[]},"169":{"play":"Let us address to tend on Hector’s heels.","notes":[]},"170":{"play":"The glory of our Troy doth this day lie","notes":[]},"171":{"play":"On his fair worth and single chivalry.","notes":["Dio.] RITSON (Remarks, 1783, p. 163) and MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 315) both point out that Diomed cannot reasonably have made this speech. Mason thought it a continuation of Paris' speech. Ritson suggested that it might be assigned to Deiphobus, who is present, and this has been universally done. 155-59. Dio. Let vs ... Chivalrie] MALONE (ed. 1790): I suspect these five lines were an injudicious addition by the actors for the sake of concluding the scene with a couplet; to which (if there be no corruption) they were more attentive than to the country of Diomed, or the particular commission he was entrusted with by the Greeks. ... It was undoubtedly intended by Shakespeare that Diomed should make his exit with Troilus and Cressida.—TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., IX, 1934, 138 n.) agrees, and as proof that the lines were not in the original copy points to the \"Exeunt\" in F after line 153 and the absence of any exit direction after line 159."]},"172":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 4, SCENE 5":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Ajax, armed, Achilles, Patroclus, Agamemnon,","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"Menelaus, Ulysses, Nestor, etc. and Trumpeter.]","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"AGAMEMNON, to Ajax","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"Here art thou in appointment fresh and fair,","notes":["appointment;] C. A. PELL (Notes, i, 150, ii, 133): Ajax’s dress, the “fittings-out” he appears in."]},"5":{"play":"Anticipating time with starting courage.","notes":["Anticipating ... courage] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): I have alter’d the Pointing of this Passage for this Reason: The Poet seems to mean, that Ajax shew’d his starting Courage in coming into the Field before the Challenger.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Modern editors, almost without exception, here follow Theobald’s punctuation in removing the full stop after “time” and placing it at the end of the line. Knight and Schmidt (Lexicon) retain the punctuation of all the old copies, and with this I interpret “starting courage” as “bold defiance”; “the appalled air” seems to bear out this sense. ... Shakespeare more than once uses “start” transitively for “startle.” With Theobald’s punctuation I can see no satisfactory explanation of “starting courage.”—[Where the two basic copies agree in pointing, and where the old pointing makes sense, it should be against sound editorial policy to change. There is no compelling reason for repunctuating these lines. “With starting courage” may mean what Deighton suggests; I think it more probable that the phrase means “With courage to get things started, to get in ahead of the challenger.”—ED.]"]},"6":{"play":"Give with thy trumpet a loud note to Troy,","notes":["Æne.] This speech had an odd adventure. In Var. ’78 “Ene” was silently changed to “Men.” RITSON (Remarks, 1783) observed that “this is rather a blunt way for a man to announce himself,” and declared that “the speech belongs to Æneas.” The error was repeated in Var. ’85, REED adding a note that “the author of The Remarks supposes this speech to belong to Æneas.” And it was repeated (with the honorable exception of RANN [ed. 1789]) until KNIGHT (ed. 1841), gathering more speculative notes from MASON and SINGER. Knight restored the text for good."]},"7":{"play":"Thou dreadful Ajax, that the appallèd air","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"May pierce the head of the great combatant","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"And hale him hither.","notes":["hale] COLLIER (ed. 1858) suggests “hail”; “for how was sound, by piercing the head of the combatant, to ‘hale’ or drag Hector to the field? It may mean to ‘hail,’ or call him to it.” But Benedick could have told him (Much Ado,"]},"10":{"play":"AJAX: Thou, trumpet, there’s my purse.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"He gives money to Trumpeter.","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"Now crack thy lungs and split thy brazen pipe.","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"Blow, villain, till thy spherèd bias cheek","notes":["Bias cheeke] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Swelling out like the bias of a bowl.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, pp. 502-503): “Bias cheek,” appears to me to be nonsense. Possibly the poet might have written, “Boreas cheek,” alluding to the common pictures of Boreas, in which he is always drawn with cheeks puffed out almost to bursting.—STEEVENS (Var. ’78) cites appositely Webster’s White Devil [I.ii.66-67, ed. Lucas, 1927, I, 114]: “Faith, his cheeke Hath a most excellent Bias”; and (ed. 1793) comments that “the idea is taken from the puffy cheeks of the winds, as represented in ancient prints, maps, &c.”"]},"14":{"play":"Outswell the colic of puffed Aquilon.","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"Come, stretch thy chest, and let thy eyes spout blood.","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"Thou blowest for Hector.   Sound trumpet.","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"ULYSSES: No trumpet answers.","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"ACHILLES: ’Tis but early days.","notes":["early dayes] An adverbial phrase, still occasionally used in England, of which “days” is in the genitive. See “nowadays,” “earlier o’ nights” (Twelfth Night, I.iii.3-4), and FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §237)."]},"19":{"play":"[Enter Cressida and Diomedes.]","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Is not yond Diomed with Calchas’ daughter?","notes":["yong (yond)] “Yond” is the demonstrative pronoun, as it is usually in Sh., not the adverb. “Is not that fellow yonder Diomed?” The construction is similar to All’s Well, III.v.79: “yond’s that same knave That leads him to these places.” See FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §319)."]},"21":{"play":"ULYSSES: ’Tis he. I ken the manner of his gait.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"He rises on the toe; that spirit of his","notes":["He rifes on the toe] This has been taken to be a touch drawn from the"]},"23":{"play":"In aspiration lifts him from the earth.","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Is this the Lady Cressid?","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Even she.","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Most dearly welcome to the Greeks, sweet lady.","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"He kisses her.","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"NESTOR: Our general doth salute you with a kiss.","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"ULYSSES: Yet is the kindness but particular.","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"’Twere better she were kissed in general.","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"NESTOR: And very courtly counsel. I’ll begin. He kisses her.","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"So much for Nestor.","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"ACHILLES: I’ll take that winter from your lips, fair lady.","notes":["He take that winter] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Probably with allusion to the belief that disease was thus transferred to the kisser. Compare Timon, IV.iii.63-64: “I will not kiss thee; then the rot returns To thine own lips again.”—[Aged Nestor, who has just kissed, is by virtue of his great age “cold” winter.—B.]"]},"34":{"play":"Achilles bids you welcome. He kisses her.","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"MENELAUS: I had good argument for kissing once.","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"PATROCLUS, stepping between Menelaus and Cressida","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"But that’s no argument for kissing now,","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"For thus popped Paris in his hardiment","notes":["hardiment] Sh. uses this word three times. In the other two cases it means “bold action” such as a fighter performs in battle. Compare Cymbeline, v.iv.75-76: “Like hardiment Posthumus hath To Cymbeline perform’d,” and I Henry IV, i.iii.101. Here it apparently means “boldness.”"]},"39":{"play":"And parted thus you and your argument.","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"He kisses her.","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"ULYSSES: O deadly gall and theme of all our scorns,","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"For which we lose our heads to gild his horns!","notes":["loose our heads] HUDSON (ed. 1881) takes this to mean “lose our judgment or reason”; but it might just as well mean “lose our lives.”"]},"43":{"play":"PATROCLUS: The first was Menelaus’ kiss; this mine.","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"Patroclus kisses you.      He kisses her again.","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"MENELAUS: O, this is trim!","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Paris and I kiss evermore for him.","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"MENELAUS: I’ll have my kiss, sir.—Lady, by your leave.","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"CRESSIDA: In kissing, do you render or receive?","notes":["render, or receive] STEEVENS (ed. 1793) cites Merchant of Venice, III.ii.139–40 (Bassanio kissing Portia): “Fair lady, by your leave; I come by note, to give and to receive.” The parallelism of rhyme and phrase is striking. See note on III.ii.37–40."]},"49":{"play":"MENELAUS: Both take and give.","notes":["Both take and give] TYRWHITT (Var. ’73): This speech should rather be given to Menelaus."]},"50":{"play":"CRESSIDA: I’ll make my match to live,","notes":["Ile make my match to liue] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I will make such bargains as I may live by, such as may bring me profit, therefore will not take a worse kiss than I give.—TYRWHITT (Var. ’78): I believe this only means—“I’ll lay my life.”"]},"51":{"play":"The kiss you take is better than you give.","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"Therefore no kiss.","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"MENELAUS: I’ll give you boot: I’ll give you three for one.","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"CRESSIDA: You are an odd man. Give even, or give none.","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"MENELAUS: An odd man, lady? Every man is odd.","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"CRESSIDA: No, Paris is not, for you know ’tis true","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"That you are odd, and he is even with you.","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"MENELAUS: You fillip me o’ th’ head.","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"CRESSIDA: No, I’ll be sworn.","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"ULYSSES: It were no match, your nail against his horn.","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"May I, sweet lady, beg a kiss of you?","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"CRESSIDA: You may.","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"ULYSSES: I do desire it.","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Why, beg two.","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"ULYSSES: Why, then, for Venus’ sake, give me a kiss","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"When Helen is a maid again and his.","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"CRESSIDA: I am your debtor; claim it when ’tis due.","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"ULYSSES: Never’s my day, and then a kiss of you.","notes":["Neuer's ... of you] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I once gave both these lines to Cressida. She bids Ulysses beg a kiss; he asks that he may have it, \"When Helen is a maid again.\" She tells him that then he shall have it. ... \"I am"]},"69":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Lady, a word. I’ll bring you to your father.","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"Diomedes and Cressida talk aside.","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"NESTOR: A woman of quick sense.","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"ULYSSES: Fie, fie upon her!","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"There’s language in her eye, her cheek, her lip;","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"Nay, her foot speaks. Her wanton spirits look out","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"At every joint and motive of her body.","notes":["motiue] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): “Motive,” for motion.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): “Motive,” for “part that contributes to motion.”—SCHMIDT (1875): “Instrument,” as, in Richard II (ii.i.193), the tongue is called “The slavish motive of recanting fear.”"]},"76":{"play":"O, these encounterers, so glib of tongue,","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"That give accosting welcome ere it comes","notes":["coasting] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 6 Dec., 1729): What is intended here by “coasting?” I know that it is spoken of a vessel either saluting a coast, or being saluted from a shore; but this allusion seems too remote, and the metaphor too obscure, as there is no single syllable of a ship in the context. I have substituted, if you like it, “They give accosting welcome ere it comes,” i.e. they are ready to caress every man, even before he makes the address.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): An amorous address; courtship.—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 315): Ere what come? As this passage stands the pronoun “it” has no antecedent. Johnson says a coasting means an amorous address, but he has given us no example to prove it, or shewn how the word can possibly bear that meaning. I have no doubt that we should read: “And give accosting,” etc.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Mr. M. Mason’s conjecture is plausible and ingenious;","a coasting welcome, ere it comes.] MASON (Steevens’s 1778 ed.): To coast is to approach side-ways, to move along the coast. A “coasting welcome” may, therefore, mean a side-long glance of invitation—and yet, without some hesitation, it cannot be admitted into the text. A “coasting welcome” may mean a “side-long glance of invitation.” Ere “it” comes, may signify, “before such an overture has reached her.” Perhaps, therefore, the plain sense of the passage may be, that Cressida is one of those females who throw out their lure, before any like signal has been made to them by our sex. [He remembers from an old book of voyages that] the phrase, a “coasting salute,” was used to express a salute of guns from a ship passing by a fortified place at which the navigator did not design to stop, though the salute was instantly returned. ... Cressida may therefore resemble a fortress which salutes before it has been saluted.—HUDSON (ed. 1854) remarks that in the original reading “it would seem that ‘coasting’ must be an adjective, thus leaving ‘it’ without an antecedent.”—[This was evidently Mason's opinion, and indeed the general opinion of the editors. They seem not to have thought that “coasting” could as easily be a substantive.]—WHITE (ed. 1865): Steevens’ explanation that “a coasting welcome” is “a sidelong glance of invitation,” even if accepted, will not help us to a sense; for to read, “that give a sidelong glance of invitation ere it (i.e., the sidelong glance, &c.) comes,” is nonsense. We have Sir Toby Belch’s authority (Twelfth Night, I.iii.52) that “‘accost’ is, front her, board her, woo her, assail her”; and thus the line means, That give bold wooing welcome ere it comes.—J. ADDIS (N.Q., 17 Aug., 1867, pp. 122-23) cites Cotgrave’s French Dictionarie (ed. 1611): “Costoyer: To accost, side, abbord; to be, or ly, by the side of; also, to coast along by, or goe by the coast of.” He adds that “accoasting,” or “coasting,” and “accosting” mean the same thing, so that nothing is gained by emendation.—The COWDEN CLARKES (ed. 1868) take “a coasting welcome” in the sense “a sidling welcome.” “The ‘it’ in this line, which seems to have no antecedent, is probably used as Shakespeare sometimes employs this word in reference to an implied particular; the implied particular being ‘encounter,’ or ‘amorous advance,’ involved in the previous expression, ‘encounters.’”—COLLINS (Studies in Sh., 1904, pp. 301-02): But the original word is perfectly right, being a term from coursing, a well known source of many of Shakespeare’s metaphors. Turberville in his Noble Art of Venerie or Hunting [1575, not written by Turberville—ROLLINS] has: “In coursing at the hare it is not materiall which dog kylleth her ... but he that giveth most Cotes, or most turnes winneth the wager. A Cote is when a greyhound goeth endwayes by his fellow and giveth the hare a turn, ... but if he coast, and so come by his fellow, that is no Cote.” So that to give a “coasting welcome, ere it comes,” is to move alongside of a welcome, or meet it, before it comes.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906), referring to Collins’ explanation, says: “Had the words been ‘to give welcome a coasting,’ I could have understood this explanation, but, as they stand, it seems impossible.”—[Collins has simply bungled his own explanation. He should have said that the words mean “to welcome a movement alongside.” “A coasting” may be a misprint for the more common word “accosting.” Or, as ADDIS (N.Q., 17 Aug., 1867, pp."]},"78":{"play":"And wide unclasp the tables of their thoughts","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"To every tickling reader! Set them down","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"For sluttish spoils of opportunity","notes":["sluttish spoyles of opportunitie] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Corrupt wenches, of whose chastity every opportunity may make prey."]},"81":{"play":"And daughters of the game.","notes":["daughters of the game] DOUCE (Illustrations, 1807, ii, 62): This expression seems borrowed from the “maister of the game,” the ancient title of the king’s game-keeper. There was also a treatise on hunting, so called, which Shakespeare had often read of, or might perhaps have seen.—[Compare cock of the game.—B.] game] Amorous sport, a common meaning. Thus Othello, II.iii.19: “I’ll warrant her, full of game”; and All’s Well, v.iii.186: “[She] was a common gamester to the camp.”—HARRIS (Women of Sh., 1912, p. 213 n.): The phrase of the prostitute to-day on the streets of London is: “I’m on the game.”"]},"82":{"play":"[Diomedes and Cressida exit.]","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"[Flourish.]","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"ALL: The Trojan’s trumpet.","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"[Enter all of Troy: Hector, armed, Paris, Aeneas,","notes":["Troians] DELIUS (ed. 1856) suggests “Trojan’s” (instead of the usual “Trojans'”), linking it with iv.iv.149: “Harke, Hector’s Trumpet.”"]},"86":{"play":"Helenus, Troilus, and Attendants.]","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Yonder comes the troop.","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"AENEAS: Hail, all the state of Greece! What shall be done","notes":["you ftate] DYCE (ed. 1865): I strongly suspect that Shakespeare wrote here “you (or “ye”) states”; the plural being formerly very common in the sense of “nobility.” 79-80. what fhallbe done To him] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): This phrase is scriptural, and signifies—“what honour shall he receive?” So, in Samuel I.xvii.26: “What shall be done to the man that killeth this Philistine?”"]},"89":{"play":"To him that victory commands? Or do you purpose","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"A victor shall be known? Will you the knights","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"Shall to the edge of all extremity","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"Pursue each other, or shall they be divided","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"By any voice or order of the field?","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"Hector bade ask.","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Which way would Hector have it?","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"AENEAS: He cares not; he’ll obey conditions.","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: ’Tis done like Hector.","notes":["Aga. 'Tis done, etc.] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): It seems absurd to me, that Agamemnon should make a Remark to the Disparagement of Hector for Pride, and that Æneas should immediately say, \"If not Achilles, Sir, what is your Name?\" and then desire him to take Notice, that Hector was as void of Pride as he was full of Valour. ... I was fully satisfied, that this Reproach on Hector ought to be placed to Achilles, as I have ventur'd to place it.—In a letter to Warburton of 6 March, 1729/30, Theobald had suggested two other arrangements: Achil. 'Tis done like Hector. Agam. But securely done. Achil. A little proudly, &c. or, Agam. 'Tis done like Hector: not securely done. Achil. A little proudly. \"I.e. when Agamemnon has gallantly confessed, it is done like Hector, and without any regard to the hazard: it is natural for Achilles to reply; 'What though it is not securely done? yet it is proudly done, and with contempt to his opponent.' \" securely] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): In the sense of the latin, securus—securus admodum de bello, animi securi homo. A negligent security arising from a contempt of the object opposed."]},"98":{"play":"ACHILLES: But securely done,","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"A little proudly, and great deal misprizing","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"The knight opposed.","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"AENEAS: If not Achilles, sir,","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"What is your name?","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"ACHILLES: If not Achilles, nothing.","notes":["If ... nothing] GREY (Notes, 1754, II, 244) relates, from Cresacre More, the story of the first meeting of Sir Thomas More and Erasmus, at which, un-","If ... nothing] GREY (Notes, 1754, II, 244) relates, from Cresacre More, the story of the first meeting of Sir Thomas More and Erasmus, at which, un"]},"104":{"play":"AENEAS: Therefore Achilles. But whate’er, know this:","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"In the extremity of great and little,","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"Valor and pride excel themselves in Hector,","notes":["excell!] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): It is an high absurdity to say, that any thing can “excell!” in the extremity of little; which little, too, is as blank as nothing. Without doubt Shakespear wrote, “Valour and pride parcell themselves in Hector”; i.e. divide themselves in Hector in such a manner, that the one is almost infinite; the other almost nothing.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I would not petulantly object, that excellence may as well be little as absurdity be high, but to direct the reader’s attention rather to sense than words. Shakespeare’s thought is not exactly deduced. Nicety of expression is not his character. The meaning is plain, “Valour,” says Æneas, “is in Hector greater, than valour in other men, and pride in Hector is less than pride in other men. So that Hector is distinguished by the excellence of having pride less than other pride, and valour more than other valour.”"]},"107":{"play":"The one almost as infinite as all,","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"The other blank as nothing. Weigh him well,","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"And that which looks like pride is courtesy.","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"This Ajax is half made of Hector’s blood,","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"In love whereof half Hector stays at home;","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"Half heart, half hand, half Hector comes to seek","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"This blended knight, half Trojan and half Greek.","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"ACHILLES: A maiden battle, then? O, I perceive you.","notes":["maiden battail] ROLFE (ed. 1884): Bloodless contest, like that of novices; not “a gorie emulation” [line 141].—N.E.D., maiden (sb. and a.), B.4: That has yielded no results. a. Of an assize, circuit, session: Formerly, one at which no prisoner was condemned to death; now, one at which there are no cases for trial. b. Of a game, esp. Cricket of an over: One in which no runs are scored.—[This latter meaning would accord very well with the context. Unfortunately there are no instances cited before 1700, except one from Florio"]},"115":{"play":"[Enter Diomedes.]","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Here is Sir Diomed.—Go, gentle knight;","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"Stand by our Ajax. As you and Lord Aeneas","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"Consent upon the order of their fight,","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"So be it, either to the uttermost","notes":["breach (breath)] CRAIG (ed. 1905): A bout of tilting done for the sake of putting the tilters in breath (in wind).—[If this is a technical term of tilting, I have not found it elsewhere. SCHMIDT (1875), for the present instance, gives “a gentle exercise,” and so also N.E.D. See II.iii.112.]"]},"120":{"play":"Or else a breath. The combatants being kin","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"Half stints their strife before their strokes begin.","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"Hector and Ajax enter the lists.","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"ULYSSES: They are opposed already.","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: What Trojan is that same that looks so heavy?","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"ULYSSES: The youngest son of Priam, a true knight,","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"Not yet mature, yet matchless firm of word,","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"Speaking in deeds, and deedless in his tongue,","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"Not soon provoked, nor being provoked soon calmed,","notes":[]},"129":{"play":"His heart and hand both open and both free.","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"For what he has, he gives; what thinks, he shows;","notes":[]},"131":{"play":"Yet gives he not till judgment guide his bounty,","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"Nor dignifies an impair thought with breath;","notes":["impairèd] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): A thought unsuitable to the dignity of his character. This word I should have changed to “impure,” were I not over-powered by the unanimity of the editors, and concurrence of the old copies.—STEEVENS (Var. ’78) thought he had fixed the meaning and substantiated Johnson’s definition, by discovering the word in Chapman’s address “To the Vnderstander,” prefixed to Achilles’ Shield (1598): “nor is it more emparie to an honest and absolute mans sufficiencie to haue few friendes. . . .” Later scholarship, however, has insisted that “impair” here is not an adjective but a noun, equivalent to “impairment.” DYCE (Strictures, 1859, pp. 152–53) found three other uses of “impair” by Chapman, all unquestionably substantives. (E.g. near the end of the same address cited by Steevens, “in the empairie of our Poets sweetnes.”)—HUDSON (ed. 1854) insisted that “impair” must be an error for “impure,” because “no instance [has] been found of ‘impair’ used in any sense that will make sense in this place.”—DYCE (ed. 1857), supporting “impure,” cites Stirling’s Tragedy of Darius (ed. Kastner and Charlton, line 1278, text of 1603): “Nor suffer impure thoughts to staine his mind.”—CLARK and WRIGHT (ed. 1865): Although we have not been able to find any other instance of “impair” as an adjective, we have retained it; for editors should be careful not to obliterate ἅπαξ λεγόμενα, and etymologically “impair” may have the sense of “unsuitable, unequal to the theme.” Johnson’s conjecture of “impure,” though plausible, is not entirely satisfactory, as it is Troilus’s ripeness of judgement and not his modesty which is the subject of praise.—COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868): There are three senses in which he may have used “impair” adjectively here, each and all of them consisting well with the drift of the present passage: “impair” signifying unequal, unsuitable, unbefitting, unworthy, as derived from the Latin impar; “impair” signifying unprepared, unready, or perplexed, entangled, as derived from the Latin imparatus; and “impair” signifying injurious, impairing, deteriorating, “detractive.” It is in this latter sense that the word “impair,” as a noun, is used","imbarre thought.] HERFORD (ed. 1899): \"Impare,\" imperfect, immature, \"unproportioned.\" ... The word appears to be Shakespeare’s coinage. It is probably suggested by Lat. impar, not by the verb \"impair\"; but the emendator of the Folio text, after his wont, assimilated it to the familiar word. The best commentary is Polonius’s charge to Laertes [Hamlet, I.iii.59-60]: \"Give thy thoughts no tongue, Nor any unproportion’d thought his act.\"—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Though no instance has been found of \"impare,\" or of \"impair,\" as an adjective, the former may, I think, be taken as an equivalent of the Lat. impar. For it is not the modesty of Troilus that is here in question, as the advocates of \"impure\" assume, nor his \"ripeness of judgment,\" as the Cambridge editors say, but his \"sincerity,\" his \"evening\" of his words to his thoughts. The line \"Yet gives he not till judgment guide his bounty\" qualifies and expands the words \"For what he has he gives,\" and the line \"Nor dignifies an impure thought with breath\" qualifies and expands the words \"he thinks he shows.\"—THISELTON (Notulae Criticae, 1907, 63-71, p. 31): Having regard to the easy confusion of \"e\" and \"d\" as written, I suspect Shakespeare wrote \"impaired,\" i.e. \"impaired.\"—[The dictionaries are not very helpful. SCHMIDT (1874) defines as \"unsuitable, impertinent\"; N.E.D. as \"unfit, inferior.\" But in each case the meaning is adapted to this passage, which supplies the only instance of \"impair\" (if indeed that is the word Sh. intended) as an adjective. \"Impair\" as a noun, meaning \"impairment, injury,\" was fairly common in Elizabethan England. Webster and Century Dictionary derive \"impair\" from the French impar; N.E.D. more cautiously says \"cf. F. impar unequal,\" and refers to an instance of the French word dating 1484. The word \"impar\" (\"impare\") was an adjective used in the sixteenth century, but apparently only in mathematics, to mean \"uneven, unequal.\" Sh. may have given a figurative turn to this word and meaning. But on the whole Deighton’s commentary seems to me to be the best. Certainly \"impure\" is to be rejected as impertinent to the context.—ED.—COOPER (Thesaurus, 1565) gives \"Imparatus = Adiectivum. Cic. Vnready: vnprouided: vnprepared.\" An \"impaire thought\" is thus an unprepared or unconsidered thought.—B.]"]},"133":{"play":"Manly as Hector, but more dangerous,","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"For Hector in his blaze of wrath subscribes","notes":["subscribes] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is; \"yields, gives\" way.","objects] N.E.D.: Something which on being seen excites a particular"]},"135":{"play":"To tender objects, but he in heat of action","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"Is more vindicative than jealous love.","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"They call him Troilus, and on him erect","notes":["they call him Troylus] KNIGHT (ed. 1841): These words ... are found below; and their introduction here is probably a clerical or typographical error. [Hence the Q reading is to be preferred.]—CLARK and WRIGHT (ed. 1865) also believe the Q reading to be the right one. If, however, the F reading is retained, it should be arranged: “They call him Troilus: The youngest son of Priam, a true knight.” But probably “they call him Troilus” was the insertion of a hasty corrector.—CHAMBERS (William Sh., 1930, I, 440): These [words] recur at 124, where they are metrical, and Q has them. I can only suppose"]},"138":{"play":"A second hope, as fairly built as Hector.","notes":[]},"139":{"play":"Thus says Aeneas, one that knows the youth","notes":["Even to his inches] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): From top to toe. The phrase was also used in the sense of \"as far as one's capacities go,\" as in Jonson, The Magnetic Lady [I.vi.30-31]: \"all men are Philosophers, to their inches.\""]},"140":{"play":"Even to his inches, and with private soul","notes":[]},"141":{"play":"Did in great Ilium thus translate him to me.","notes":["tranflate him] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Thus explain his character.—N.E.D.: II.3. To interpret, explain; to expound the significance of (conduct, gestures, etc.). 138 ff. Thou art, etc.] This appeal of Hector to kinship occurs in Lydgate and in the Recuyell, but there the encounter between Hector and Ajax takes place in general battle. Ajax's reply is to beg Hector and the Trojans, who have the"]},"142":{"play":"[Alarum. The fight begins.]","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: They are in action.","notes":[]},"144":{"play":"NESTOR: Now, Ajax, hold thine own!","notes":[]},"145":{"play":"TROILUS: Hector, thou sleep’st. Awake thee!","notes":[]},"146":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: His blows are well disposed.—There, Ajax!","notes":[]},"147":{"play":"[Trumpets cease.]","notes":[]},"148":{"play":"DIOMEDES: You must no more.","notes":[]},"149":{"play":"AENEAS: Princes, enough, so please you.","notes":[]},"150":{"play":"AJAX: I am not warm yet. Let us fight again.","notes":[]},"151":{"play":"DIOMEDES: As Hector pleases.","notes":[]},"152":{"play":"HECTOR: Why, then, will I no more.—","notes":[]},"153":{"play":"Thou art, great lord, my father’s sister’s son,","notes":["my Fathers (sisters Sonne] “HARMAIOTAEOGOS” (N.Q., 25 Aug., 1928, p. 134): When Hector ... called the mother of Ajax by this appellation [\"aunt,\" line 152], he was apparently under the impression that she was Hesione, who was indeed married to Telamon, but, so far as I know, is not credited by any ancient author with having given birth to Ajax. His mother is called Periboea or Eriboea. But as Telamon appears to have had three wives Shakespeare may be forgiven this indifference to classical orthodoxy.—[Sh. found the parentage in his sources; e.g. Lydgate (ed. Bergen, E.E.T.S., Bk. III, lines 2046-48; text from ed. 1555, sig. P₄ v): \"Whose father ... hym begat, the storye telleth vs, Of Exyon, syster to Pryamus.\" Hesione is also stated to be the mother of Ajax in Cooper’s Thesaurus (1565), thus showing that the error was current in the sixteenth century.] 142 ff. Were thy commiion, etc.] BOYLE (E.S., XXX, 1902, 54) cites Marston's Antonio’s Revenge, III.ii.161 ff. (ed. Bullen, 1887, I, 149): \"O that I knew which joint, which side, which limb, Were father all, and had no mother in’t, That I might rip it vein by vein, and carve revenge In bleeding races! but since tis mix’d together, Have at adventure, pell mell, no reverse.\""]},"154":{"play":"A cousin-german to great Priam’s seed.","notes":[]},"155":{"play":"The obligation of our blood forbids","notes":[]},"156":{"play":"A gory emulation ’twixt us twain.","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"Were thy commixtion Greek and Trojan so","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"That thou couldst say “This hand is Grecian all,","notes":[]},"159":{"play":"And this is Trojan; the sinews of this leg","notes":[]},"160":{"play":"All Greek, and this all Troy; my mother’s blood","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"Runs on the dexter cheek, and this sinister","notes":[]},"162":{"play":"Bounds in my father’s,” by Jove multipotent,","notes":[]},"163":{"play":"Thou shouldst not bear from me a Greekish member","notes":[]},"164":{"play":"Wherein my sword had not impressure made","notes":[]},"165":{"play":"Of our rank feud. But the just gods gainsay","notes":[]},"166":{"play":"That any drop thou borrowd’st from thy mother,","notes":[]},"167":{"play":"My sacred aunt, should by my mortal sword","notes":["My sacred Aunt] HUDSON (ed. 1854): It is remarkable that the Greeks give to the aunt, the father's sister, the title of \"sacred,\" ἢ πρὸς πατρὸς θεία, sometimes expressed by θεὶα alone."]},"168":{"play":"Be drained. Let me embrace thee, Ajax.","notes":[]},"169":{"play":"By him that thunders, thou hast lusty arms!","notes":[]},"170":{"play":"Hector would have them fall upon him thus.","notes":[]},"171":{"play":"Cousin, all honor to thee! They embrace.","notes":[]},"172":{"play":"AJAX: I thank thee, Hector.","notes":[]},"173":{"play":"Thou art too gentle and too free a man.","notes":[]},"174":{"play":"I came to kill thee, cousin, and bear hence","notes":[]},"175":{"play":"A great addition earnèd in thy death.","notes":[]},"176":{"play":"HECTOR: Not Neoptolemus so mirable—","notes":["Neoptolemus] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 6 Dec., 1729): Does not our good Poet forget himself here in the truth of story? He cannot by this Neoptolemus mean Pyrrhus the son of Achilles; for he, from our own Poet's words, was not yet come to the Trojan wars; consequently had no eclat in arms to make him so mirable. ... \"But it must grieve young Pyrrhus now at home,\" &c. [III.iii.278]. And was there any other Neoptolemus?—THE SAME (letter to Warburton, 6 March, 1729/30): But looking into an old Treatise, (printed by Wynkyn de Worde, anno 1503, called the Recyles and Sieges of Troy) I find there that among the list of the warriors, that came with Agamemnon before Troy, Neoptolemus is mentioned; without any notice of his being the son of Achilles, or of his not coming to the war till after his father's death. (And the spurious Dares Phrygius has committed the very same fault.) And to this old Treatise it is, (and not to Lollius, or Chaucer, as the Editors imagine,) that our Author owes his subject; for hence only could he derive the name of Hector's horse, Galathe; Troilus's horse being taken by Diomede; and several other circumstances that I could particularize.—THE SAME (letter to Warburton, 15 Sept., 1730), re Warburton's proposed emendation [see Textual Notes]: As much as I am pleased with this emendation, give me leave to say, dear Sir, that there are several reasons for contesting it. In the first place, why should Hector here decypher Achilles by such an obscure periphrasis as calling him the sire of Neoptolemus, no where else mentioned by that name in this Play? for, where he mentions him before, ... he calls him \"young Pyrrhus.\" And to have given him both appelations might, perhaps, have raised an ambiguity to an English audience. ... In the next place, as intimately acquainted as Shakespeare might be with the circumstances of this famous siege, it does not appear","Not Neoptolemus' sire irascible.] “Irascible” is an old school term, and is an epithet suiting his character, and the circumstances he was then in. ... But our editor Mr. Theobald, by his obscure diligence, had found out that Wynken de Werde ... introduces one Neoptolemus into the ten years quarrel, a person distinct from the son of Achilles, and therefore will have it, that Shakespear here means no other than the Neoptolemus of this worthy chronicler. He was told, to no purpose, that his fancy was absurd. For first, Wynken’s Neoptolemus is a common rate warrior, and so described as not to fit the character here given. Secondly, it is not to be imagined that the poet should on this occasion make Hector refer to a character not in the play, and never so much as mentioned on any other occasion. Thirdly, Wynken’s Neoptolemus is a warrior on the Trojan side, and slain by Achilles. But Hector must needs mean by one “who could promise a thought of added honour torn from him,” a warrior amongst his enemies on the Grecian side.—[Warburton does not consider whether the courteous Hector would insult Ajax by referring to the superior prowess of Achilles.]—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): After all this contention it is difficult to imagine that the critick believes “mirable” to have been changed to “irascible.” I should sooner read, “Not Neoptolemus th’ admirable”; as I know not whether “mirable” can be found in any other place? ... But nothing is more remote from justness of sentiment, than for Hector to characterise Achilles as the father of Neoptolemus, a youth that had not yet appeared in arms, and whose name was therefore much less known than his father’s. My opinion is, that by Neoptolemus the authour meant Achilles himself, and remembering that the son was Pyrrhus Neoptolemus, considered Neoptolemus as the nomen gentilium, and thought the father was likewise Achilles Neoptolemus.—STEEVENS (Var. ’73): Shakespeare certainly uses Neoptolemus for Achilles.—[And Wilfride Holme, in The Fall and evil Success of Rebellion (1537),","Neoptolemus, etc.] MALONE (adopting Johnson's conjecture that Sh. supposed Neoptolemus to be a bastard son of Achilles, and not Pyrrhus under another name): Johnson's interpretation is found in Steevens's note, which, though full and accurate, makes the same confusion.]—In Var. '78 STEEVENS rediscovers the Neoptolemus of Caxton and Lydgate, who is in fact and contrary to Warburton a Grecian prince. But the descriptions of him in Caxton and Lydgate would scarcely give Sh. grounds for singling him out as an heroic model; we are told that he has black hair, prominent eyes, a big frame, a stammer in his speech, and a passion for law and legal pleading. He is merely one of the Grecian princes, and by no means distinguished from the rest.—MALONE (Second Appendix, 1783, p. 45): In the margin of Phaer's translation of Virgil, ... a book that Shakspeare had certainly read, Neoptolemus and Pyrrhus are called brothers.—[Aen. ii, 547–49: Cui Pyrrhus: Referes ergo haec et nuntius ibis Pelidae genitori: illi mea tristia facta Degeneremque Neoptolemum narrare memento. Phaer translates (1558, sig. [E3r]): “Than Pyrrhus said, thou shalt go now therfore & tidings bryng Onto my father Achilles soule, my dolefull dedes to tell. Neoptolemus his bastard is, not I, say this in hell.” The marginal note is: “Neoptolemus and Pyrrhus wer brethren.” Stanyhurst (1583, sig. D1r & v) likewise misunderstands the lines: “My father aduertise, that I was ful truely begotten, Basely Neoptolemus was borne, that carie for errand.” Both translators were apparently quite unable to cope with Pyrrhus’ irony. But even if Sh. also thought Neoptolemus to be a bastard son of Achilles, it hardly explains why he chose him as an exemplar of heroic virtue. As a matter of fact, the editors have generally agreed to accept Johnson's theory, that Neoptolemus means Achilles. DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) wonders whether the learned Jonson did not make the same mistake in Poetaster [iv.iii.22–24] when Tucca says: “Giue me thy hand, Agamemnon; we heare abroad, thou art the Hector of citizens: what sayest thou? are we welcome to thee, noble Neoptolemus?”—ED.—Compare Elucidarius (Hagenau. 1510), “Filius Achillis ex Deidamia, alio nomine Pyrrhus. Neoptolemus interpretatur novus miles.” This is the basic interpretation (from Servius) of the century, appearing in Cooper (Thesaurus, 1565) as “A yong, or new souldiour.” See also (Dictionarium Historicum in the same volume): “Pyrrhus, The sonne of Achillis by Deidamia, so named of his yalowe heare. He was also called Neoptolemus, because he was a yong souldiour, and came with his father to the warre of Troy, when he was but a childe.” Hector means to say that even though the “new souldiour” Neoptolemus was cried up by Fame as destined to win the height of glory (it had been prophesied that Troy could not be taken without him), yet not even Neoptolemus, unprovided as he is, can expect to make any addition toward that honor through Hector.—B.]"]},"177":{"play":"On whose bright crest Fame with her loud’st “Oyez”","notes":["O yes] N.E.D.: Of oiez, oyez, hear ye! imperative pl. of oir to hear ...; orig. pronounced oye'z, but subseq. reduced to oye's, and so identified in sound with the two words O yes! and hence often so written.—[The word is so written in Q and F, and in each case the e of “loudest” is elided. Yet DELIUS (ed. 1856), noting that in Merry Wives, v.v.39–40 (“Crier Hobgoblin, make the fairy oyes. ... Elves, list your names; silence, you airy toys”) “oyes” rhymes with “toys,” assumes that to be the case here and reads “loudest.”—ED.]"]},"178":{"play":"Cries “This is he”—could promise to himself","notes":[]},"179":{"play":"A thought of added honor torn from Hector.","notes":[]},"180":{"play":"AENEAS: There is expectance here from both the sides","notes":[]},"181":{"play":"What further you will do.","notes":[]},"182":{"play":"HECTOR: We’ll answer it;","notes":["anſwere it] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, answer the expectance."]},"183":{"play":"The issue is embracement.—Ajax, farewell.","notes":[]},"184":{"play":"They embrace again.","notes":[]},"185":{"play":"AJAX: If I might in entreaties find success,","notes":[]},"186":{"play":"As seld I have the chance, I would desire","notes":["As ... chance] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): An elliptical expression = “which I might hope for now, for I so rarely,” etc.—[For the elliptical senses of “as” see Abbott (1872), §§110–111. It should not need to be pointed out that “As ... chance” refers to meeting Hector, not to success in entreaties. Yet CRAIG (ed. 1905) says: “This may mean ‘I seldom entreat.’ ”]"]},"187":{"play":"My famous cousin to our Grecian tents.","notes":[]},"188":{"play":"DIOMEDES: ’Tis Agamemnon’s wish; and great Achilles","notes":[]},"189":{"play":"Doth long to see unarmed the valiant Hector.","notes":[]},"190":{"play":"HECTOR: Aeneas, call my brother Troilus to me,","notes":[]},"191":{"play":"And signify this loving interview","notes":[]},"192":{"play":"To the expecters of our Trojan part;","notes":[]},"193":{"play":"Desire them home.","notes":[]},"194":{"play":"Aeneas speaks to Trojans, who exit; he then","notes":[]},"195":{"play":"returns with Troilus.","notes":[]},"196":{"play":"To Ajax. Give me thy hand, my cousin.","notes":[]},"197":{"play":"I will go eat with thee and see your knights.","notes":[]},"198":{"play":"Agamemnon and the rest come forward.","notes":[]},"199":{"play":"AJAX: Great Agamemnon comes to meet us here.","notes":["Enter ... ref[ſ] WHITE (ed. 1865): In Shakespeare’s time they ... [Agamemnon, etc.] probably remained in the inner or second apartment of the stage, which was sometimes shut off by a curtain. The front of the stage was probably used to set out the lists; and at this speech by Ajax, Agamemnon and the other Greeks came forward into the arena of the fight."]},"200":{"play":"HECTOR, to Aeneas","notes":[]},"201":{"play":"The worthiest of them tell me name by name;","notes":[]},"202":{"play":"But for Achilles, my own searching eyes","notes":[]},"203":{"play":"Shall find him by his large and portly size.","notes":[]},"204":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Worthy all arms! As welcome as to one","notes":[]},"205":{"play":"That would be rid of such an enemy—","notes":[]},"206":{"play":"But that’s no welcome. Understand more clear:","notes":[]},"207":{"play":"What’s past and what’s to come is strewed with husks","notes":[]},"208":{"play":"And formless ruin of oblivion;","notes":[]},"209":{"play":"But in this extant moment, faith and troth,","notes":[]},"210":{"play":"Strained purely from all hollow bias-drawing,","notes":[]},"211":{"play":"Bids thee, with most divine integrity,","notes":[]},"212":{"play":"From heart of very heart, great Hector, welcome.","notes":[]},"213":{"play":"HECTOR: I thank thee, most imperious Agamemnon.","notes":["imperious] Imperial; a sense frequent in Sh. See SCHMIDT (1874)."]},"214":{"play":"AGAMEMNON, to Troilus","notes":[]},"215":{"play":"My well-famed lord of Troy, no less to you.","notes":[]},"216":{"play":"MENELAUS: Let me confirm my princely brother’s greeting:","notes":[]},"217":{"play":"You brace of warlike brothers, welcome hither.","notes":[]},"218":{"play":"HECTOR, to Aeneas","notes":[]},"219":{"play":"Who must we answer?","notes":[]},"220":{"play":"AENEAS: The noble Menelaus.","notes":[]},"221":{"play":"HECTOR: O, you, my lord? By Mars his gauntlet, thanks!","notes":[]},"222":{"play":"Mock not that I affect th’ untraded oath;","notes":["untraded] SCHMIDT (1875): Not used in common practice, unhackneyed.—N.E.D.: Unskilled, inexperienced, unfamiliar (as “untraded in philosophie,” in Udall’s translation of Erasmus’ Apophthegmes, 1542, p. 172); hence, figuratively, not customary, unhackneyed.—[The present instance is the only one cited for this meaning. In II.ii.66 occurs the term “traded Pylots,” meaning experienced or skilful pilots.]"]},"223":{"play":"Your quondam wife swears still by Venus’ glove.","notes":["Venus Gloue] MALONE (ed. 1790): Under the lady's oath perhaps more is meant than meets the ear; unless the poet caught his idea from Grange's Golden Aphroditis, 4to. 1577, Sign. M iijr: \"... Nexte vnto hyr [Juno] satte Venus the Goddesse of loue, with a gloue made of floures stickyng in hyr bosome.\"—STEEVENS (ed. 1793) is skeptical of the glove made of flowers. \"How could any form resembling a glove, be produced out of such materials?\" He indulges in the wild surmise that \"glove\" (in the Grange passage) \"must be a corruption of some other word, perhaps of—‘Globe.’ A flowery globe might have been worn by Venus as an emblem of the influence of Love.\""]},"224":{"play":"She’s well, but bade me not commend her to you.","notes":[]},"225":{"play":"MENELAUS: Name her not now, sir; she’s a deadly theme.","notes":["deadly] WRIGHT (1900) tells us that \"deadly\" has a wide dialectical use as an intensive, in both good and bad sense, and cites from south Warwickshire, \"He's a deadly man for going to church.\""]},"226":{"play":"HECTOR: O, pardon! I offend.","notes":[]},"227":{"play":"NESTOR: I have, thou gallant Trojan, seen thee oft,","notes":[]},"228":{"play":"Laboring for destiny, make cruel way","notes":[]},"229":{"play":"Through ranks of Greekish youth; and I have seen","notes":[]},"230":{"play":"thee,","notes":[]},"231":{"play":"As hot as Perseus, spur thy Phrygian steed,","notes":["Perseus] See note on I.iii.45."]},"232":{"play":"Despising many forfeits and subduments,","notes":[]},"233":{"play":"When thou hast hung thy advanced sword i’ th’ air,","notes":[]},"234":{"play":"Not letting it decline on the declined,","notes":[]},"235":{"play":"That I have said to some my standers-by","notes":[]},"236":{"play":"“Lo, Jupiter is yonder, dealing life!”","notes":[]},"237":{"play":"And I have seen thee pause and take thy breath","notes":[]},"238":{"play":"When that a ring of Greeks have hemmed thee in,","notes":[]},"239":{"play":"Like an Olympian wrestling. This have I seen.","notes":[]},"240":{"play":"But this thy countenance, still locked in steel,","notes":[]},"241":{"play":"I never saw till now. I knew thy grandsire","notes":["I knew thy Grandfire] When Jason was on his way to the Golden Fleece he was inhospitably treated by King Laomedon of Troy. After his return he raised an army, attacked, and conquered Troy. Nestor was one of his allies, and engaged in personal combat with Laomedon. In the looting of Troy the princess Hesione was given to Telamon. The story is told at length by Lydgate in Book L, briefly by Caxton but without mention of any fight between Laomedon and Nestor."]},"242":{"play":"And once fought with him; he was a soldier good,","notes":[]},"243":{"play":"But, by great Mars, the captain of us all,","notes":[]},"244":{"play":"Never like thee! O, let an old man embrace thee;","notes":[]},"245":{"play":"And, worthy warrior, welcome to our tents.","notes":[]},"246":{"play":"AENEAS, to Hector  ’Tis the old Nestor.","notes":["'Tis the old Nestor] MALONE (ed. 1790): So, in Julius Caesar [v.i.63]: \"Old Cassius still.\" If the poet had the same idea in both passages, Æneas means, \"Nestor is still the same talkative old man, we have long known him to be.\" He may, however, only mean to inform Hector that Nestor is the person who has addressed him.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I believe, that Æneas, who acts as master of the ceremonies, is now merely announcing Nestor to Hector, as he had before announced Menelaus to him."]},"247":{"play":"HECTOR: Let me embrace thee, good old chronicle","notes":[]},"248":{"play":"That hast so long walked hand in hand with time.","notes":[]},"249":{"play":"Most reverend Nestor, I am glad to clasp thee.","notes":[]},"250":{"play":"They embrace.","notes":[]},"251":{"play":"NESTOR: I would my arms could match thee in contention","notes":[]},"252":{"play":"As they contend with thee in courtesy.","notes":[]},"253":{"play":"HECTOR: I would they could.","notes":[]},"254":{"play":"NESTOR: Ha! By this white beard, I’d fight with thee tomorrow.","notes":[]},"255":{"play":"Well, welcome, welcome. I have seen the time!","notes":[]},"256":{"play":"ULYSSES: I wonder now how yonder city stands","notes":[]},"257":{"play":"When we have here her base and pillar by us.","notes":[]},"258":{"play":"HECTOR: I know your favor, Lord Ulysses, well.","notes":[]},"259":{"play":"Ah, sir, there’s many a Greek and Trojan dead","notes":[]},"260":{"play":"Since first I saw yourself and Diomed","notes":[]},"261":{"play":"In Ilium, on your Greekish embassy.","notes":[]},"262":{"play":"ULYSSES: Sir, I foretold you then what would ensue.","notes":[]},"263":{"play":"My prophecy is but half his journey yet,","notes":["propheſie] See note on iv.i.18, regarding this embassy of Ulysses and Diomed. Lydgate has Ulysses say (ed. Bergen, E.E.T.S., Bk. II, lines 6872 ff.; text from ed. 1555, sig. M1 r): \"this riche stronge Cyte, Shall downe be bete & ylayde ful lowe, Walle and Toures also ouerthrowe.\""]},"264":{"play":"For yonder walls, that pertly front your town,","notes":[]},"265":{"play":"Yon towers, whose wanton tops do buss the clouds,","notes":["Yond Towers] MALONE (ed. 1790) cites Caxton's Recuyell [ed. Sommer, II, 508; text from 1597 ed., p. 438] as to the great height of the towers of Ilion, \"that it seemed to them that sawe them from ferre, yt they raught vnto the heauen.\" But Lydgate says the same. Sh. had referred to \"cloud-kissing Ilion\" in Lucrece, line 1370."]},"266":{"play":"Must kiss their own feet.","notes":[]},"267":{"play":"HECTOR: I must not believe you.","notes":[]},"268":{"play":"There they stand yet, and modestly I think","notes":[]},"269":{"play":"The fall of every Phrygian stone will cost","notes":[]},"270":{"play":"A drop of Grecian blood. The end crowns all,","notes":["the end crownes all] Finis coronat opus. See SMITH (Oxford dictionary of English proverbs, 1936, p. 433).—B."]},"271":{"play":"And that old common arbitrator, Time,","notes":[]},"272":{"play":"Will one day end it.","notes":[]},"273":{"play":"ULYSSES: So to him we leave it.","notes":[]},"274":{"play":"Most gentle and most valiant Hector, welcome.","notes":[]},"275":{"play":"After the General, I beseech you next","notes":[]},"276":{"play":"To feast with me and see me at my tent.","notes":[]},"277":{"play":"ACHILLES: I shall forestall thee, Lord Ulysses, thou!—","notes":["thou] TYRWHITT (Var. '73): Should we not read—\"though\"? Notwithstanding you have invited Hector to your tent, I shall draw him first into mine.—STEEVENS (Var. '78): The repetition of \"thou!\" was anciently used by one who meant to insult another. So ... [vi.i.30] of T. and C.: \"thou tassell of a Prodigals purse thou.\"—CAPELL (Notes, 1780, ii, 134–35): Insolence cannot be stronger painted than by that \"Thou!\" ... nor any sense express'd clearer than his is by it, if what preceeds be remember'd;—\"shalt thou be second in feasting Hector! and before me!\"—RITSON (Remarks, 1783, p. 164): Yes;—but"]},"278":{"play":"Now, Hector, I have fed mine eyes on thee;","notes":[]},"279":{"play":"I have with exact view perused thee, Hector,","notes":[]},"280":{"play":"And quoted joint by joint.","notes":["quoted] N. E. D.: Quote: to take mental note of ... scrutinize.—[Compare Hamlet, II.i.111-12: \"I am sorry that with better heed and judgement I had not quoted him.\"]"]},"281":{"play":"HECTOR: Is this Achilles?","notes":[]},"282":{"play":"ACHILLES: I am Achilles.","notes":[]},"283":{"play":"HECTOR: Stand fair, I pray thee. Let me look on thee.","notes":[]},"284":{"play":"ACHILLES: Behold thy fill.","notes":[]},"285":{"play":"HECTOR: Nay, I have done already.","notes":[]},"286":{"play":"ACHILLES: Thou art too brief. I will the second time,","notes":[]},"287":{"play":"As I would buy thee, view thee limb by limb.","notes":["buy thee] BOSWELL (Var. '21) states that the F1 reading is \"pry thee.\" This is a curious and apparently quite unfounded error. 267 ff. Tell me, etc.] KNIGHT (ed. 1841): It was a fine stroke of art in Shakspere to borrow the Homeric incident of Achilles surveying Hector before he slew him, not using it in the actual scene of the conflict, but more characteristically in the place which he has given it.—[This occurs in the 22d book of the"]},"288":{"play":"HECTOR: O, like a book of sport thou ’lt read me o’er;","notes":[]},"289":{"play":"But there’s more in me than thou understand’st.","notes":[]},"290":{"play":"Why dost thou so oppress me with thine eye?","notes":[]},"291":{"play":"ACHILLES: Tell me, you heavens, in which part of his body","notes":[]},"292":{"play":"Shall I destroy him—whether there, or there, or","notes":["Whether] DYCE (ed. 1865): Here “whether” is to be read (as it is frequently written in Shakespeare) “wher.”"]},"293":{"play":"there—","notes":[]},"294":{"play":"That I may give the local wound a name","notes":[]},"295":{"play":"And make distinct the very breach whereout","notes":[]},"296":{"play":"Hector’s great spirit flew. Answer me, heavens!","notes":[]},"297":{"play":"HECTOR: It would discredit the blest gods, proud man,","notes":[]},"298":{"play":"To answer such a question. Stand again.","notes":[]},"299":{"play":"Think’st thou to catch my life so pleasantly","notes":[]},"300":{"play":"As to prenominate in nice conjecture","notes":[]},"301":{"play":"Where thou wilt hit me dead?","notes":[]},"302":{"play":"ACHILLES: I tell thee, yea.","notes":[]},"303":{"play":"HECTOR: Wert thou an oracle to tell me so,","notes":[]},"304":{"play":"I’d not believe thee. Henceforth guard thee well,","notes":[]},"305":{"play":"For I’ll not kill thee there, nor there, nor there,","notes":[]},"306":{"play":"But, by the forge that stithied Mars his helm,","notes":["stythied] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): So, again, in Hamlet [III.ii.81-82]; “And my imaginations are as foul As Vulcan’s stithy.” A “Stithy,” or “Sith,” signifies an Anvil. ... But, I own, I suspect this not to have been our Author’s Word either in Hamlet or here. For, in the first Place, an Anvil is far from being the dirtiest thing in a Smith’s Shop: and then the Forge, or Furnace, cannot be said to “anvil” the Helmet. I have corrected; “But by the Forge that smithied Mars's Helm.”—[Theobald’s emendation is unnecessary. N.E.D. gives as a late meaning of “stithy” (“stith, stiddy”) “a forge, smithy,” citing Hamlet as the earliest occurrence.]"]},"307":{"play":"I’ll kill thee everywhere, yea, o’er and o’er.—","notes":[]},"308":{"play":"You wisest Grecians, pardon me this brag;","notes":[]},"309":{"play":"His insolence draws folly from my lips.","notes":[]},"310":{"play":"But I’ll endeavor deeds to match these words,","notes":[]},"311":{"play":"Or may I never—","notes":[]},"312":{"play":"AJAX: Do not chafe thee, cousin.—","notes":[]},"313":{"play":"And you, Achilles, let these threats alone","notes":[]},"314":{"play":"Till accident or purpose bring you to ’t.","notes":[]},"315":{"play":"You may have every day enough of Hector","notes":[]},"316":{"play":"If you have stomach. The general state, I fear,","notes":[]},"317":{"play":"Can scarce entreat you to be odd with him.","notes":["to be odde with him] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): This is obscurely express’d, but the Meaning must be this. Notwithstanding this Blustering which you have made, I fear, the whole Grecian Confederacy with their united Prayers could scarce prevail with you to make Hector your Adversary in good Earnest, to oppose your self to him. This will be farther explain’d by a Passage in King Henry V [ii.iv.128–29]: “for I desire Nothing but odds with England.”—[In a letter to Warburton, 6 March, 1729/30, Theobald had queried the text and suggested “not be odd with him”; “i.e. the general posture of our affairs is so bad, that they can scarce persuade you not to engage against Hector. Sed minus placet.”]—STEEVENS (Var. ’78): I.e. I am aware that the Greeks will not wish you to meet him singly; insinuating that it would be bad policy in them to desire the man who had the greatest reputation for valour, to run such a hazard of being foiled.—MASON (Comments, 1785, pp. 316–17): Steevens has totally mistaken the meaning of this passage, Ajax had no such refined political notions in his head as the editor ascribes to him, nor had he that high opinion of Achilles, having been just wrought up by Ulysses, and the other leaders, to consider himself as the better man; he therefore treats Achilles with contempt, and means to insinuate that he was afraid of fighting with Hector:—“You may every day, says he, have enough of Hector, if you chuse it, but I believe the whole state of Greece will scarcely prevail on you to engage with him.”—[In his edition of 1793 Steevens withdrew his own note, accepting and printing that of Mason.]—SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 442): Suspend (says Ajax) your threats, until accident or agreement bring you together in the field. ... But upon your caprice only, not any regard to the general good, must such a meeting depend."]},"318":{"play":"HECTOR, to Achilles","notes":[]},"319":{"play":"I pray you, let us see you in the field.","notes":[]},"320":{"play":"We have had pelting wars since you refused","notes":["pelting] N.E.D.: Paltry, petty ... insignificant.—[Compare Midsummer-Night's Dream, II.i.88–91: “Therefore the winds ... Have every pelting river made so proud,” etc.]"]},"321":{"play":"The Grecians’ cause.","notes":[]},"322":{"play":"ACHILLES: Dost thou entreat me, Hector?","notes":[]},"323":{"play":"Tomorrow do I meet thee, fell as death;","notes":[]},"324":{"play":"Tonight all friends.","notes":[]},"325":{"play":"HECTOR: Thy hand upon that match.","notes":[]},"326":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: First, all you peers of Greece, go to my tent;","notes":[]},"327":{"play":"There in the full convive we. Afterwards,","notes":["coniue] To feast together. The present example is the only one cited in N.E.D. Steevens (Var. ’78), however, says that the word is used several times in The History of Helyas Knight of the Swanne."]},"328":{"play":"As Hector’s leisure and your bounties shall","notes":[]},"329":{"play":"Concur together, severally entreat him.","notes":[]},"330":{"play":"Beat loud the taborins; let the trumpets blow,","notes":["Taborins] N.E.D.: A kind of drum, less wide and longer than the tabor, and struck with one drumstick only, to accompany the sound of a flute which is played with the other hand.—[But in this instance it probably means drums of no specific kind, for the taborin would scarcely be the proper accompaniment for a fanfare of trumpets.]"]},"331":{"play":"That this great soldier may his welcome know.","notes":[]},"332":{"play":"[Flourish.]","notes":[]},"333":{"play":"[All but Troilus and Ulysses exit.]","notes":[]},"334":{"play":"TROILUS: My Lord Ulysses, tell me, I beseech you,","notes":[]},"335":{"play":"In what place of the field doth Calchas keep?","notes":[]},"336":{"play":"ULYSSES: At Menelaus’ tent, most princely Troilus.","notes":[]},"337":{"play":"There Diomed doth feast with him tonight,","notes":[]},"338":{"play":"Who neither looks upon the heaven nor Earth,","notes":[]},"339":{"play":"But gives all gaze and bent of amorous view","notes":[]},"340":{"play":"On the fair Cressid.","notes":[]},"341":{"play":"TROILUS: Shall I, sweet lord, be bound to you so much,","notes":[]},"342":{"play":"After we part from Agamemnon’s tent,","notes":[]},"343":{"play":"To bring me thither?","notes":[]},"344":{"play":"ULYSSES: You shall command me, sir.","notes":[]},"345":{"play":"As gentle tell me, of what honor was","notes":[]},"346":{"play":"This Cressida in Troy? Had she no lover there","notes":[]},"347":{"play":"That wails her absence?","notes":[]},"348":{"play":"TROILUS: O sir, to such as boasting show their scars","notes":[]},"349":{"play":"A mock is due. Will you walk on, my lord?","notes":[]},"350":{"play":"She was beloved, she loved; she is, and doth;","notes":[]},"351":{"play":"But still sweet love is food for Fortune’s tooth.","notes":[]},"352":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Achilles and Patroclus.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"ACHILLES: I’ll heat his blood with Greekish wine tonight,","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"Which with my scimitar I’ll cool tomorrow.","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"Patroclus, let us feast him to the height.","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Here comes Thersites.","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"[Enter Thersites.]","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"ACHILLES: How now, thou core of envy?","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"Thou crusty botch of nature, what’s the news?","notes":["batch] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): What is a crusty batch of Nature? We must certainly read, “Botch”; i.e. Scab, Sore, &c. So, before in the Beginning of the 2d Act [iii.7], “were not that a botchy core?”—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): “Batch” is any thing “baked.”—STEEVENS (Var. ’73): “Batch” does not signify anything baked, but all that is baked at one time, without heating the oven afresh."]},"9":{"play":"THERSITES: Why, thou picture of what thou seemest and","notes":["thou picture] DELIUS (ed. 1856): There is nothing more to him than one sees at first glance, just as a picture has nothing more to it [hinter sich]."]},"10":{"play":"idol of idiot-worshippers, here’s a letter for thee.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"ACHILLES: From whence, fragment?","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"THERSITES: Why, thou full dish of fool, from Troy.","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"Achilles takes the letter and moves aside to read it.","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Who keeps the tent now?","notes":["Who ... now] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): A question of appeal, equivalent to “You see that Achilles can no longer be taunted with keeping his tent.”—[Deighton is one of the few editors who attempt to explain this speech. His interpretation agrees with that of the Cowden Clarkes and of Porter and Clarke, and, although labored, is no more so than the witticism itself.]"]},"15":{"play":"THERSITES: The surgeon’s box or the patient’s wound.","notes":["The Surgeons ... wound] HAMNER (ed. 1742): In this answer Thersites only quibbles upon the word “Tent” [i.e. a surgeon’s probe].—[Since Achilles was “instructed of Chiron in deedes of armes and surgery” (Cooper, Thesaurus, 1565), as the conventional reference works made known, that fact is doubtless the occasion of the surgical pun, and the further progress of the wit combat.—B.]"]},"16":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Well said, adversity. And what need these","notes":["aduerfity] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 6 March, 1729/30): If the text be right here, as I am afraid it is, this is a very singular use of the word. The meaning should be, “well said, cross-purposes”: but that “adversity” ever before signified this, I hardly can imagine.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): “Adversity,” I believe, in this instance, signifies “contrariety.” The reply of Thersites has been studiously “adverse” to the drift of the question urged by Patroclus. So, in Love’s Labour’s Lost [v.ii.298], the Princess, addressing Boyet, (who had been capriciously employing himself to perplex the dialogue,) says—“Avaunt, perplexity!”"]},"17":{"play":"tricks?","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"THERSITES: Prithee, be silent, boy. I profit not by thy","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"talk. Thou art said to be Achilles’ male varlet.","notes":["male Varlot] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): Dr. Thirlby [letter of 7 May, 1729; Nichols, Illustrations, 1817, II, 229] very reasonably conjectures, “harlot”; and this seems confirm’d by what Thersites immediately subjoins;—“Why, his masculine Whore.”—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Hanmer reads “male-harlot,” plausibly enough, except that it seems too plain to require the explanation","male varlet.]—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 317): A male varlet is merely a footman, not as Thersites afterwards explains the phrase, a masculine whore. ... The sense therefore requires that we should adopt Hanmer's amendment ... which precisely answers that description, and is what Thersites afterwards calls a preposterous discovery. There is nothing either criminal or extraordinary in a male-varlet.—Johnson's objection that \"Male-harlot\" is \"too plain to require the explanation which Patroclus demands,\" is sound. Mason's point about the meaning of \"male varlet\" is not well taken. Of course the term, in itself, does not mean what Thersites later says it does. But the tone with which he pronounces the words tells Patroclus that he has a hidden meaning. As to the accusation itself, ECKHARDT (E. S., LXIV, 1929, 377) has this to say: \"Inasmuch as neither of the two [Achilles and Patroclus] denies [the charge], it is probable that Thersites here expresses Shakespeare's own opinion. Neither the Troy legend of antiquity nor that of the middle ages offers the least ground for such a conception; this trait therefore seems to be the invention of the poet.\" On this point I may quote my colleague, the late Professor W. A. OLDFATHER, who has made a study of Patroclus: \"That there had been an erotic relation between Achilles and Patroclus was widely believed in antiquity and often discussed, the chief point of disagreement being over the relatively unimportant question as to which was the 'Lover' and which the 'Beloved.' I cite briefly the mere names of those who are known to have made positive statements on the score, or else used expressions, when speaking of this relation, that are characteristic of the sermo amatorius: Aeschylus and Sophocles (5th cent.), Plato and Aeschines (4th cent.), Zenodotus and Aristarchus, the great Homeric scholars (3d and 2nd cents.), Theocritus (3d cent.), Bion (2nd cent.), Martial (1st cent. after Christ), Lucian, Maximus of Tyre, and Pseudo-Apollodorus (2nd cent.), Athenaeus and Philostratus (3d cent.), Cyrus the epigrammatist (5th cent.), etc., and of course Scholiasts, Eustathius, et id genus omne.\"—[The reference works of the sixteenth century merely say that these two were the most intimate of friends; in fact, they were a \"common-place\" pair. The allegation, however, would be available to scholars in the fundamental sources, or such a charge might under the circumstances arise at any time by \"spontaneous combustion.\" Nevertheless, the author of this"]},"20":{"play":"PATROCLUS: “Male varlet,” you rogue! What’s that?","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"THERSITES: Why, his masculine whore. Now the rotten","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"diseases of the south, the guts-griping, ruptures,","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"catarrhs, loads o’ gravel in the back, lethargies,","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"cold palsies, raw eyes, dirt-rotten livers, whissing","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"lungs, bladders full of impostume, sciaticas,","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"limekilns i’ th’ palm, incurable bone-ache, and the","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"rivelled fee-simple of the tetter, take and take","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"again such preposterous discoveries.","notes":["discoveries] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 6 March, 1729–30): Does Thersites allude to the invention of unnatural lewdness?—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 317): “Discoveries” mean, here, “inventions” [and refers to the male-harlotry of Patroclus].—DELIUS (ed. 1856) thinks that Thersites refers to the condition of general moral chaos in the Grecian army, which is the subject of his monologue later in the scene.—SINGER (Sh. Vindicated, 1853, p. 204): It is possible that we should read “discoverers” instead of “discoveries,” which would give the required personification. But, as Iago says in Othello [I.iii. 327–291, “the blood and baseness of our natures would conduct us to most preposterous conclusions,” discoveries here may have the same meaning, and Thersites imprecates the curses ironically on those who had made such discoveries, or come to such conclusions.—SINGER (ed. 1856): We should surely read “discoverers”; that is, those who had raised the calumny. The “discoveries” could not be the subject of the imprecation of Thersites, and it is evident from what follows that Patroclus is not meant.—COLLIER (ed. 1858) explains his emendation “discourers” (taken from the Perkins folio) as referring “to the discolouration of the face by paint, worn by such persons as Thersites has described Patroclus to be.—DYCE (ed. 1865) quotes Lettsom: “Singer, I think, is right in reading ‘discoverers’; but surely ‘discoverers’ with the epithet ‘preposterous’ can mean nothing but ‘masculine whores.’ Compare Isaiah lvii, 8; ‘Thou hast discovered thyself to another than me.’” Dyce himself queries, “Is ‘discoveries’ the abstract for the concrete?”—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Whether this is the abstract for the concrete or not, the meaning is too plain for doubt.—[I wish it were!]"]},"29":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Why, thou damnable box of envy, thou,","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"what means thou to curse thus?","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"THERSITES: Do I curse thee?","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Why, no, you ruinous butt, you whoreson","notes":["ruinous] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Patroclus reproaches Thersites with deformity, with having one part crowded into another. indistinguishable] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I.e. thou cur of an undeterminate shape."]},"33":{"play":"indistinguishable cur, no.","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"THERSITES: No? Why art thou then exasperate, thou idle","notes":["thou idle, etc.] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): All the terms used by Thersites of"]},"35":{"play":"immaterial skein of sleave-silk, thou green sarsenet","notes":["Sley’d [silke] SCHMIDT (1875): Raw, untwisted silk. “Sleave” (“sleuie Q) or “sleave silk” is soft floss silk used for weaving.—[Sh. uses both terms in other places.] Sarcenet] LINTHICUM (Costume in the Drama of Sh., 1936, pp. 121-22): Sarcenet, a fine, thin, soft silk of taffeta weave ... was made in both “single and double” quality, that is, thin, and heavy. ... [In T. and C.] sarcenet is used metaphorically to suggest contemptuous slightness."]},"36":{"play":"flap for a sore eye, thou tassel of a prodigal’s purse,","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"thou? Ah, how the poor world is pestered with such","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"waterflies, diminutives of nature!","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"PATROCLUS: Out, gall!","notes":["Out gall] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Hanmer reads “Nut-gall,” which answers well enough to “finch-egg”; it has already appeared [qv., where?] that our Authour thought the nut-gall the bitter gall. He is called “nut,” from the conjugation of his form; but both the copies read, “Out, gall!”—[If Sh. did write “nut-gall,” it would seem to be as a term equivalent to “wart, excrescence,” and reflecting on the deformity of Thersites; not with reference to the bitterness of gall.]"]},"40":{"play":"THERSITES: Finch egg!","notes":["Finch Egge] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Of this reproach I do not know the exact meaning. I suppose he means to call him “singing bird,” as implying an useless favourite, and yet more, something more worthless, a singing bird in the egg, or generally, a slight thing easily crushed.—STEEVENS (Var. ’73): A finch’s egg is remarkably gaudy; but of terms of reproach it is difficult always to pronounce the exact meaning.—HALLIWELL (ed. 1864): Perhaps the opposition in form is what Shakespeare here intended, and not the bitter of the gall in the first instance. The nut gall is rough, a companion term to cob-loaf and crusty batch, and this is well opposed by the smooth but gaudy spotting of the finch-egg. Patroclus was characterised by his love of fine armour.—ROLFE (ed. 1884) cites Love’s Labor’s Lost, v.i.63: “thou pigeon egg of discretion,” and Macbeth, IV.ii.82: “What, you egg!”"]},"41":{"play":"ACHILLES, coming forward","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"My sweet Patroclus, I am thwarted quite","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"From my great purpose in tomorrow’s battle.","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"Here is a letter from Queen Hecuba,","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"A token from her daughter, my fair love,","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"Both taxing me and gaging me to keep","notes":["gaging] Not a contraction for “engaging,” but an independent verb, originating either from the French gager, or as an aphetic form of “engage.” See N.E.D."]},"47":{"play":"An oath that I have sworn. I will not break it.","notes":["Oath] The oath was to fight no more against Troy, and to do all that he could to bring awe war to an end. On this basis Priam agreed to the marriage of Polyxena to Achilles; Hecuba was the intermediary in the arrangement. See Appendix, pp. 441 ff, 445-46. All this occurred after the death of Hector. Because of his oath, Achilles refused all solicitations to fight, thus throwing the Greeks into despair and bringing them near to defeat. He was finally aroused by the beatings his Myrmidons received from Troilus and the reproaches of an unnamed man."]},"48":{"play":"Fall, Greeks; fail, fame; honor, or go or stay;","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"My major vow lies here; this I’ll obey.","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"Come, come, Thersites, help to trim my tent.","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"This night in banqueting must all be spent.","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"Away, Patroclus.     He exits with Patroclus.","notes":["Exit] TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., IX, 1934, 130 n.): This may have resulted from the dramatist’s habit of writing “Ex” or “Ext” both for “Exit” and “Exeunt.” 46-47. See note to II.3.175-79, and Appendix, pp. 416-18—B."]},"53":{"play":"THERSITES: With too much blood and too little brain,","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"these two may run mad; but if with too much brain","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"and too little blood they do, I’ll be a curer of madmen.","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"Here’s Agamemnon, an honest fellow enough","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"and one that loves quails, but he has not so much","notes":["Quailes] NARES (Glossary, 1822): A prostitute; borrowed from the French, where caille, and caille quoffée, had the same meaning. … The quail was thought to be a very amorous bird; thence the metaphor. [Nares cites Motteux’s Rabelais, 1694, Prol. to Bk. IV: “With several coated Quails, and lac’d Mutton, wag­gishly singing.”]—COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868): We think … that the sentence may bear reference to the antique custom of matching quails gainst one another, as cocks are more modernly matched. Shake­speare elsewhere has alluded to this ancient practice ... [Antony and Cleopatra,"]},"58":{"play":"brain as earwax. And the goodly transformation","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"of Jupiter there, his brother, the bull—the primitive","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"statue and oblique memorial of cuckolds, a","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"thrifty shoeing-horn in a chain, hanging at his","notes":["shoeing-horn:] NARES (Gloss.,y, 1822): The name of this implement, from its convenient use in drawing on a tight shoe, was applied, in a jocular metaphor, to other subservient and tractable assistants. Thus Thersites. ... Whether it was ever the practice of thrifty persons so to carry their shoeing-horns, as seems to be implied, I cannot undertake to say. The \"horn\" was clearly suggested by his cuckoldom, just before mentioned; and he was a \"shoeing-horn\" to Agamemnon, in the other sense, because he was made the pretext for invading Troy; and he was said to hang at his brother's leg, as being entirely dependent on him.—[According to N.E.D. the term was used in the sense of \"tool\" from the sixteenth to the nineteenth centuries; e.g. Wood (Athenae Oxon., 1692, ii, 494): \"Oliver had made him ... his shooing horn, merely to serve his turn.\" But it was also an accepted symbol of cuckoldry.]"]},"62":{"play":"brother’s leg—to what form but that he is should","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"wit larded with malice and malice forced with","notes":["forced] Stuffed, \"farced.\""]},"64":{"play":"wit turn him to? To an ass were nothing; he is both","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"ass and ox. To an ox were nothing; he is both ox","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"and ass. To be a dog, a mule, a cat, a fitchew, a","notes":["Fitchew] Polecat. Compare Othello, IV.i.144: \"'Tis such another fitchew! marry, a perfumed one.\""]},"67":{"play":"toad, a lizard, an owl, a puttock, or a herring without","notes":["Puttocke] FOSTER (Sh. Word-Book, 1908): For \"pout-hawk\" or \"poot-"]},"68":{"play":"a roe, I would not care; but to be Menelaus! I","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"would conspire against destiny. Ask me not what I","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"would be, if I were not Thersites, for I care not to be","notes":["to bee] RANN (ed. 1789): If I were to be.—For the indefinite use of “to” (in this case equivalent to “about” [being]), and the confusion of infinitive and gerund, see ABBOTT (Sh. Grammar, 1872, §356)."]},"71":{"play":"the louse of a lazar so I were not Menelaus.","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"[Enter Hector, Troilus, Ajax, Agamemnon, Ulysses,","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"Nestor, Menelaus, and Diomedes, with lights.]","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"Heyday! Sprites and fires!","notes":["[spirits and fires] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): This Thersites speaks upon the first sight of the distant lights."]},"75":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: We go wrong, we go wrong.","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"AJAX: No, yonder—’tis there, where we see the lights.","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"HECTOR: I trouble you.","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"AJAX: No, not a whit.","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"[Enter Achilles.]","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"ULYSSES, to Hector  Here comes himself to guide you.","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"ACHILLES: Welcome, brave Hector. Welcome, princes all.","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"AGAMEMNON, to Hector","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"So now, fair prince of Troy, I bid good night.","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"Ajax commands the guard to tend on you.","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"HECTOR: Thanks, and good night to the Greeks’ general.","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"MENELAUS: Good night, my lord.","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"HECTOR: Good night, sweet lord","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"Menelaus.","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"THERSITES, aside  Sweet draught. “Sweet,” quoth he?","notes":["draught] Privy; or perhaps (?) cesspool, sink (N.E.D.)."]},"90":{"play":"Sweet sink, sweet sewer.","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"ACHILLES: Good night and welcome, both at once, to those","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"That go or tarry.","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Good night.","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"[Agamemnon and Menelaus exit.]","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"ACHILLES: Old Nestor tarries, and you too, Diomed.","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"Keep Hector company an hour or two.","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"DIOMEDES: I cannot, lord. I have important business,","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"The tide whereof is now.—Good night, great Hector.","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"HECTOR: Give me your hand.","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"Follow his torch; he goes to Calchas’ tent.","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"I’ll keep you company.","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"TROILUS: Sweet sir, you honor me.","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"HECTOR: And so, good night.","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"Diomedes exits, followed by Troilus and Ulysses.","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"ACHILLES: Come, come, enter my tent.","notes":["him too] For the not uncommon repetition of a preposition at the end of a clause or question, see ABBOTT (Sh. Grammar 1872, §407), and FRANZ (Sh.-Gram. 1939, §543)."]},"107":{"play":"[Achilles, Ajax, Nestor, and Hector exit.]","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"THERSITES: That same Diomed’s a false-hearted rogue,","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"a most unjust knave. I will no more trust him when","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"he leers than I will a serpent when he hisses. He","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"will spend his mouth and promise like Brabbler","notes":["Brabler the Hound] ANON. (Var. ’73): If a hound “gives his mouth,” and is not upon the scent of the game, he is by sportsmen called a “babbler” or “brabler.” The proverb says, “Brabling curs never want sore ears.”—[N.E.D. supports this definition for “babbler,” not for “brabbler.” WRIGHT (1896) cites the proverb in illustration of the meaning quarrelsome, wrangling, for “brabbling.”—ED.—The description in T. and C., “he will spend his mouth & promise,” indicates that Babbler is the dog in question; he probably draws his pedigree from one of Ovid’s dogs.—B.]"]},"112":{"play":"the hound, but when he performs, astronomers","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"foretell it; it is prodigious, there will come some","notes":["prodigious] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Portentous, ominous.—[The only sense in which the word is used by Sh.]"]},"114":{"play":"change. The sun borrows of the moon when","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"Diomed keeps his word. I will rather leave to see","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"Hector than not to dog him. They say he keeps a","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"Trojan drab and uses the traitor Calchas his tent.","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"I’ll after. Nothing but lechery! All incontinent varlets!","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 2":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Diomedes.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"DIOMEDES: What, are you up here, ho? Speak.","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"CALCHAS, within  Who calls?","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Diomed. Calchas, I think? Where’s your","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"daughter?","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"CALCHAS, within  She comes to you.","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"[Enter Troilus and Ulysses, at a distance, and then,","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"apart from them, Thersites.]","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"Stand where the torch may not discover us.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"[Enter Cressida.]","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"TROILUS, aside to Ulysses","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"Cressid comes forth to him.","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"DIOMEDES: How now, my charge?","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Now, my sweet guardian. Hark, a word with you.","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"She whispers to him.","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"TROILUS, aside  Yea, so familiar?","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus  She will sing any man at","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"first sight.","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"THERSITES, aside  And any man may sing her, if he","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"can take her clef. She’s noted.","notes":["Cliff (Q!) JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, her “key.” Clef, French.—[In Sh.’s time both “clef” and “cleft” were variously spelled, as “cliff, cliffe, clift.” One meaning of cleft was the fork of the legs. Thersites is, of course, punning obscenely.—ED.—PARTRIDGE (Sh.’s Bawdy, 1947, pp. 87–88): Pudend.—B.] noted] DELIUS (ed. 1856) calls attention to a similar play on the verb “note” in Romeo and Juliet, IV.v.115–16, “I’ll re you, I’ll fa you; do you note me?”"]},"22":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Will you remember?","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Remember? Yes.","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Nay, but do, then, and let your mind be","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"coupled with your words.","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"TROILUS, aside  What should she remember?","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus  List!","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Sweet honey Greek, tempt me no more to folly.","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"THERSITES, aside  Roguery!","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Nay, then—","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"CRESSIDA: I’ll tell you what—","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Foh, foh, come, tell a pin! You are forsworn.","notes":["tell a pin] I find no history of this idiom. But the meaning is clear enough: \"tell me nothing, tell me no tales.\""]},"33":{"play":"CRESSIDA: In faith, I cannot. What would you have me do?","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"THERSITES, aside  A juggling trick: to be secretly open!","notes":["juggling] PARTRIDGE (Sh.'s Bawdy, 1947, p. 135): To copulate, there being a word-play on 'jugglers' balls' and 'testicles'; pertaining to copulation.—B. secretly open] PARTRIDGE (Sh.'s Bawdy, 1947, p. 184): Sexually open, in a secret part and in private, to his phallic ingression.—B."]},"35":{"play":"DIOMEDES: What did you swear you would bestow on me?","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"CRESSIDA: I prithee, do not hold me to mine oath.","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"Bid me do anything but that, sweet Greek.","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Good night.","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"TROILUS, aside  Hold, patience!","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus  How now, Trojan?","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Diomed—","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"DIOMEDES: No, no, good night. I’ll be your fool no more.","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"TROILUS, aside  Thy better must.","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Hark, a word in your ear.","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"She whispers to him.","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"TROILUS, aside  O plague and madness!","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"You are moved, prince. Let us depart, I pray you,","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"Lest your displeasure should enlarge itself","notes":["Fanne] ORGER (Critical Notes, 1890, p. 56) suggests \"fan,\" i.e. wind, as being more suitable to the formation of waterspouts than the sun, and cites \"Euen in the fanne and winde of your faire Sword\" (V.iii.47)."]},"50":{"play":"To wrathful terms. This place is dangerous;","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"The time right deadly. I beseech you, go.","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"TROILUS, aside to Ulysses","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"Behold, I pray you.","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus  Nay, good my lord, go off.","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"You flow to great distraction. Come, my lord.","notes":["flow to great diffraction] Steevens (Var. '73): [Johnson would read \"You show too great distraction.\"] I would adhere to the old reading. \"You flow to great distruction,\" or \"distraction,\" means, the tide of your imagination will hurry you either to noble death from the hand of Diomed, or to the height of madness from the predominance of your own passions.—Mason (Comments, 1785, p. 317): Possibly we ought to read \"destruction,\" as Ulysses had told Troilus just before, that \"this place is dangerous; The time right deadly.\""]},"56":{"play":"TROILUS, aside to Ulysses","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"I prithee, stay.","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus  You have not patience. Come.","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"TROILUS, aside to Ulysses","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"I pray you, stay. By hell and all hell’s torments,","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"I will not speak a word.","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"DIOMEDES: And so good night.   He starts to leave.","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Nay, but you part in anger.","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"TROILUS, aside  Doth that grieve thee? O withered","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"truth!","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus","notes":[]},"67":{"play":"How now, my lord?","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"TROILUS, aside to Ulysses  By Jove, I will be patient.","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Guardian! Why, Greek!","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Foh foh! Adieu. You palter.","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"CRESSIDA: In faith, I do not. Come hither once again.","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"You shake, my lord, at something. Will you go?","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"You will break out.","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"TROILUS, aside  She strokes his cheek!","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus  Come, come.","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"TROILUS, aside to Ulysses","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"Nay, stay. By Jove, I will not speak a word.","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"There is between my will and all offenses","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"A guard of patience. Stay a little while.","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"THERSITES, aside  How the devil Luxury, with his fat","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"rump and potato finger, tickles these together.","notes":["potato] STEEVENS (Var. '78): Potatoes were anciently regarded as provocatives. [Under the pseudonym of Collins, Steevens appended to the play a quantity of references, mostly from the Elizabethan dramatists, relating to the venereal properties of potatoes. But the subject is too well known to need elaboration.]"]},"83":{"play":"Fry, lechery, fry!","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"DIOMEDES: But will you, then?","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"CRESSIDA: In faith, I will, la. Never trust me else.","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Give me some token for the surety of it.","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"CRESSIDA: I’ll fetch you one.     She exits.","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"You have sworn patience.","notes":[]},"90":{"play":"TROILUS, aside to Ulysses  Fear me not, my lord.","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"I will not be myself nor have cognition","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"Of what I feel. I am all patience.","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"[Enter Cressida with Troilus’s sleeve.]","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"THERSITES, aside  Now the pledge, now, now, now!","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"CRESSIDA, giving the sleeve  Here, Diomed. Keep this","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"sleeve.","notes":["this Sleeue] STEEVENS (Var. '78) comments at length on the knightly custom of wearing a lady's sleeve as a favor.—MALONE (ed. 1790) objects that here we have to do with a man's sleeve given to a lady, i.e. the sleeve that Troilus gave Cressida in IV.iv.71. \"It may,\" he thinks, \"be supposed to be an ornamented cuffe, such perhaps as was worn by some of our young nobility at a tilt, in Shakspeare's age.\"—ED.—See LINTHICUM (Costume in the Drama of Sh., 1936, pp. 171 ff.) on sleeves.—B."]},"97":{"play":"TROILUS, aside  O beauty, where is thy faith?","notes":["where is thy Faith?] NOBLE (Sh.'s Biblical Knowledge, 1935, p. 216): Compare Luke viii, 25: \"And he sayde vnto them, Where is your faith'\"—B."]},"98":{"play":"ULYSSES, aside to Troilus  My lord—","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"TROILUS, aside to Ulysses","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"I will be patient; outwardly I will.","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"CRESSIDA: You look upon that sleeve? Behold it well.","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"He loved me—O false wench!—Give ’t me again.","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"She snatches the sleeve from Diomedes.","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Whose was ’t?","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"CRESSIDA: It is no matter, now I ha ’t again.","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"I will not meet with you tomorrow night.","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"I prithee, Diomed, visit me no more.","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"THERSITES, aside  Now she sharpens. Well said,","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"whetstone.","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"DIOMEDES: I shall have it.","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"CRESSIDA: What, this?","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Ay, that.","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"CRESSIDA: O all you gods!—O pretty, pretty pledge!","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"Thy master now lies thinking on his bed","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"Of thee and me, and sighs, and takes my glove,","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"And gives memorial dainty kisses to it","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"As I kiss thee.","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"He grabs the sleeve, and she tries to retrieve it.","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Nay, do not snatch it from me.","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"CRESSIDA: He that takes that doth take my heart withal.","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"DIOMEDES: I had your heart before. This follows it.","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"TROILUS, aside  I did swear patience.","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"CRESSIDA: You shall not have it, Diomed, faith, you shall not.","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"I’ll give you something else.","notes":[]},"125":{"play":"DIOMEDES: I will have this. Whose was it?","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"CRESSIDA: It is no matter.","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Come, tell me whose it was.","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"CRESSIDA: ’Twas one’s that loved me better than you will.","notes":[]},"129":{"play":"But now you have it, take it.","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Whose was it?","notes":[]},"131":{"play":"CRESSIDA: By all Diana’s waiting-women yond,","notes":["Dianas waiting women] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. the stars which she points to."]},"132":{"play":"And by herself, I will not tell you whose.","notes":[]},"133":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Tomorrow will I wear it on my helm","notes":[]},"134":{"play":"And grieve his spirit that dares not challenge it.","notes":[]},"135":{"play":"TROILUS, aside","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"Wert thou the devil and wor’st it on thy horn,","notes":[]},"137":{"play":"It should be challenged.","notes":[]},"138":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Well, well, ’tis done, ’tis past. And yet it is not.","notes":[]},"139":{"play":"I will not keep my word.","notes":[]},"140":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Why, then, farewell.","notes":[]},"141":{"play":"Thou never shalt mock Diomed again.","notes":[]},"142":{"play":"He starts to leave.","notes":[]},"143":{"play":"CRESSIDA: You shall not go. One cannot speak a word","notes":[]},"144":{"play":"But it straight starts you.","notes":[]},"145":{"play":"DIOMEDES: I do not like this fooling.","notes":[]},"146":{"play":"TROILUS, aside","notes":[]},"147":{"play":"Nor I, by Pluto! But that that likes not you","notes":[]},"148":{"play":"Pleases me best.","notes":["likes not me] HUDSON (ed. 1854): So in the folio; in the quarto, “... likes not you ...” To choose between the two, is not so easy as might be; but the folio seems to give some ground of preference, in that it indicates the snarling, spiteful humour of Thersites, which is most pleased with what irks and riles him.—DELIUS (ed. 1856) takes “likes me” in a double sense: resembles me, and pleases me.—[Q must be right, in order to obtain any reasonable progression of sense. Diomed has said, “I do not like this fooling.” Thersites responds, “Nor I, by Pluto,” but immediately qualifies by adding, “except that whatever you don’t like pleases me.” The speech is scarcely worth much effort at exegesis.]"]},"149":{"play":"DIOMEDES: What, shall I come? The hour?","notes":[]},"150":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Ay, come.—O Jove!—Do, come.—I shall be plagued.","notes":["plagu’d] Punished. The primary meaning, from late L. plagae (to strike, wound), was to harass, chasten, especially with reference to divine punishment. See N.E.D. Often used in this sense by Sh."]},"151":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Farewell, till then.","notes":[]},"152":{"play":"CRESSIDA: Good night. I prithee, come.—","notes":[]},"153":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]},"154":{"play":"Troilus, farewell. One eye yet looks on thee,","notes":[]},"155":{"play":"But with my heart the other eye doth see.","notes":["But ... fee] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I think it should be read thus, “But my heart with the other eye doth see.”—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 318):"]},"156":{"play":"Ah, poor our sex! This fault in us I find:","notes":[]},"157":{"play":"The error of our eye directs our mind.","notes":[]},"158":{"play":"What error leads must err. O, then conclude:","notes":[]},"159":{"play":"Minds swayed by eyes are full of turpitude. She exits.","notes":[]},"160":{"play":"THERSITES, aside","notes":[]},"161":{"play":"A proof of strength she could not publish more,","notes":["A proofe ... more] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): She could not publish a stronger proof.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Rather, I think, \"a strong proof that she could not publish more.\""]},"162":{"play":"Unless she said “My mind is now turned whore.”","notes":[]},"163":{"play":"ULYSSES: All’s done, my lord.","notes":[]},"164":{"play":"TROILUS: It is.","notes":[]},"165":{"play":"ULYSSES: Why stay we then?","notes":[]},"166":{"play":"TROILUS: To make a recordation to my soul","notes":["recordation] N.E.D.: An act of commemorating or making mention; a commemorative account. Obs.—B."]},"167":{"play":"Of every syllable that here was spoke.","notes":[]},"168":{"play":"But if I tell how these two did co-act,","notes":[]},"169":{"play":"Shall I not lie in publishing a truth?","notes":[]},"170":{"play":"Sith yet there is a credence in my heart,","notes":[]},"171":{"play":"An esperance so obstinately strong.","notes":[]},"172":{"play":"That doth invert th’ attest of eyes and ears,","notes":[]},"173":{"play":"As if those organs had deceptious functions,","notes":[]},"174":{"play":"Created only to calumniate.","notes":[]},"175":{"play":"Was Cressid here?","notes":[]},"176":{"play":"ULYSSES: I cannot conjure, Trojan.","notes":["conjure] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, I cannot raise spirits in the form of Cressida."]},"177":{"play":"TROILUS: She was not, sure.","notes":[]},"178":{"play":"ULYSSES: Most sure she was.","notes":["Most sure she was] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): The present deficiency in the measure induces me to suppose our author wrote: “It is most sure she was.”"]},"179":{"play":"TROILUS: Why, my negation hath no taste of madness.","notes":[]},"180":{"play":"ULYSSES: Nor mine, my lord. Cressid was here but now.","notes":[]},"181":{"play":"TROILUS: Let it not be believed for womanhood!","notes":[]},"182":{"play":"Think, we had mothers. Do not give advantage","notes":[]},"183":{"play":"To stubborn critics, apt, without a theme","notes":["Criticks] Critic, in Sh., always has the sense of carping, censorious. See SCHMIDT (1874)."]},"184":{"play":"For depravation, to square the general sex","notes":[]},"185":{"play":"By Cressid’s rule. Rather, think this not Cressid.","notes":[]},"186":{"play":"ULYSSES: What hath she done, prince, that can soil our","notes":[]},"187":{"play":"mothers?","notes":[]},"188":{"play":"TROILUS: Nothing at all, unless that this were she.","notes":["Nothing ... the] WILLIAMS (English Poetic Mind, 1932, pp. 60–62): Troilus sways between two worlds. His reason, without ceasing to be reason, tells him that this appearance of Cressida is not true; yet his loss is reasonable and cannot protest because this is the nature of things. Entire union and absolute division are experienced at once: heaven and the bonds of heaven are at odds. All this is in his speech [i.e. lines 162–183], but it is also in one line. There is a world where our mothers are unsoiled and Cressida is his; there is a world where our mothers are soiled and Cressida is given to Diomed. What connexion have those two worlds? “Nothing at all, unless that this were she.” ... It might be too much to say that the line is the first place in which [a] special kind of greatness occurs in Shakespeare; but it is, I think, true to say that never before in his work had such complexity of experience been fashioned into such a full and final line. It is his power entering into a new freedom. ... His genius itself changed; it began to create lines so profound and intense that they cannot be analysed. ... “She should have died hereafter.” “It is the cause, it is the cause, my soul.” On those lines there is perhaps no better comment"]},"189":{"play":"THERSITES, aside  Will he swagger himself out on ’s","notes":[]},"190":{"play":"own eyes?","notes":[]},"191":{"play":"TROILUS: This she? No, this is Diomed’s Cressida.","notes":[]},"192":{"play":"If beauty have a soul, this is not she;","notes":[]},"193":{"play":"If souls guide vows, if vows be sanctimonies,","notes":[]},"194":{"play":"If sanctimony be the gods’ delight,","notes":[]},"195":{"play":"If there be rule in unity itself,","notes":["rule in unitie] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I do not well understand what is meant by “rule in unity.” By “rule” our authour, in this place as in others, intends “virtuous restraint, regularity of manners, command of passions and appetites” ... But I know not how to apply the word in this sense to “unity.” I read, “... rule in purity ...,” or, “... rule in verity ...” Such alterations would not offend the reader, who saw the state of the old editions, in which, for instance, a few lines lower, “the Almighty Sun” is called “the Almighty Fenne.” Yet the words may at last mean, “If there be certainty in unity, if it be a rule that one is one.”—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 318): That is, “if it be true that one individual cannot be two distinct persons.”—[I strongly suspect a reference to Aristotelian metaphysics, to such a rule or law as is implied in the following definition from Bailey’s Dictionarium Britannicum (1736): “Unity (in Metaphysicks) is the Indivision of any being, i.e. the division of its essence implying such a contradiction, that, except a thing can be divided from itself, it is impossible to divide it,” which is an excellent gloss on lines 173–77. In the Metaphysics (ed. Smith and Ross, 1908, viii), Bk. X, 1054^20, Aristotle says: “The one and the many are opposed in several ways, of which one is the opposition of the one and plurality as indivisible and divisible; for that which is either divided or divisible is called a plurality, and that which is indivisible or not divided is called one.” And again (Bk. V, 1016^b): “In general those things the thought of whose essence is indivisible, and cannot separate them either in time or place or in definition, are most of all one. ... For in general those things that do not admit of division are called one in so far as they do not admit of it.” The rule of unity, then, seems to be (in Cressid’s case) indivisibility. Sh. may have got the thought from Aristotle, or from some intermediary of his own time, perhaps from Armandus Bellovisius (de Bello Visu), whose Explicationes terminorum theologicorum, philosophicorum, & logicorum was popular through the Renaissance. Ch. lviii (“De nominibus, quae conueniunt rebus de genere quantitatis”) has two sections (“De unitate numeri” and “De discretione”) which would give a good deal of logical armament for this speech of Troilus.—ED.—"]},"196":{"play":"This is not she. O madness of discourse,","notes":[]},"197":{"play":"That cause sets up with and against itself!","notes":[]},"198":{"play":"Bifold authority, where reason can revolt","notes":["By-fould authority (Q)] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): There is madness in that disquisition in which a man reasons at once “for” and “against himself upon authority” which he knows not to be valid. The quarto is right.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, pp. 505–506): [“Bi-fold” is meaningless; the true reading must be “By foul”;] and then the passage should be thus pointed, “O madness of discourse, That cause sets up with and against thyself, By foul authority!” That is, O madness of reasoning, which would at the same time persuade thee that thy mistress is true, and yet that she is false too, and in both those respects relying on a testimony which is all stained with pollution, to wit, her own.—PORTER and CLARKE (ed. 1910): Does Troylus mean double or two-fold authority? If so, half of the two-foldness of the evidence would be in his favour. It is the altogether “foule” authority, showing him what Diomed’s Cressida is against his own Cressida (that which she seemed to be to him before) which makes him doubt her as his and believe in her as his against foul evidence.—[Most editors have silently preferred the Q reading without comment. It has the better argument, in that “Bi-fold” suggests the dominating idea of dichotomy, the idea which is repeated and emphasized through these lines in the strongest possible manner.] 169–71. where reason ... Without reuolt] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): A miserable expression of a quaint thought, “That to be unreasonable in love is reasonable; and to be reasonable, unreasonable.” “Perdition” and “loss” are both used in the very same sense, and that an odd one, to signify “unreasonableness.”—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): The words “loss” and “perdition” are used in their common sense, but they mean the loss or perdition of reason.—HEATH (Revisal, 1765, p. 506): If I may venture to guess at the meaning of so dark a riddle, I should imagine it might be this; Where reason founded on past assurances can determine in contradiction to the clearest evidence, that I have not lost Cressida’s affection, and where the loss of that affection is so manifest, that all my reason ranges itself on this side, in concurrence with the fullest evidence.—HUDSON (ed. 1881): “Perdition” and “loss” have the same sense, and refer to one and the same thing, namely, loss of reason. Thus: Where reason can rebel against evident truth without losing itself, and where reason so lost can, without breach of its own laws, assume to be altogether reasonable. To argue thus in self-contradictions is to talk madly indeed.—ROLFE (ed."]},"199":{"play":"Without perdition, and loss assume all reason","notes":[]},"200":{"play":"Without revolt. This is and is not Cressid.","notes":[]},"201":{"play":"Within my soul there doth conduce a fight","notes":["conduce] THE COWDEN CLARKES (ed. 1868) take “conduce” in “its classical sense of ‘lead together,’ ‘assemble,’” and “fight” as meaning “the contending forces, the tumultuous feelings, the battling emotions that surge and meet tumultuously within the speaker’s soul.”—HUDSON (ed. 1881) thinks, if the text be right, that “conduce” must be used in the primitive sense of “collect, assemble, ... draw together,” as if Troilus were thinking of troops mustering for a fight. He does not explain how this sense could be applied to “conducing” a fight.—CRAIG (ed. 1905) thinks the word “very doubtful. ... If ‘conduce’ is not corrupt, it must mean ‘a fight of this strange nature brings me there,’ i.e., to that state or extremity.”—N.E.D. marks this, apparently unique, use as being “of uncertain meaning,” and suggests that it may be the intransitive form for the reflexive, signifying “conducts itself, carries itself on, goes on.” {Cooper (Thesaurus, 1565) defines conduco as “to gather or assemble in one place,” instancing from Tacitus, “Exercitus in unum conducere ... To gather together.” Cooper thus justifies the Cowden Clarkes and Hudson—a fight, or battle, doth gather together.—B.]"]},"202":{"play":"Of this strange nature, that a thing inseparate","notes":["thing inseperate] MALONE (ed. 1790): I.e. the plighted troth of lovers. Troilus considers it inseparable, or at least that it ought never to be broken, though he has unfortunately found that it sometimes is.—[This is altogether"]},"203":{"play":"Divides more wider than the sky and Earth,","notes":["more wider] For the double comparative, frequent in Sh., see FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §217a). 175-77. And yet ... enter] KEIGHTLEY (N.Q., 12 May, 1860, p. 358): A point as subtle as a broken woof! and Ariadne written by one so well read in Golding’s Ovid! Let us apply the talisman of transposition: “And yet the spacious breadth of this division, As subtle as Arachne’s broken woof, Admits no orifice for a point to enter.” “Subtle” is the Latin subtilis, “fine-spun”; and he says “broken woof” probably because Minerva tore Arachne’s web to pieces. The printer introduced Ariadne to complete the metre."]},"204":{"play":"And yet the spacious breadth of this division","notes":[]},"205":{"play":"Admits no orifex for a point as subtle","notes":[]},"206":{"play":"As Ariachne’s broken woof to enter.","notes":["Ariadne] STEEVENS (Var. ’73): [Notices that some Q’s read “Ariachna’s” and some “Ariathna’s.”] It is not impossible that Shakspere might have written “Ariadne’s” broken woof, having confounded the two names of the stories, in his imagination; or alluding to the clue of thread, by the assistance of which Theseus escaped from the Cretan labyrinth.—MALONE (ed. 1790): Mr. Steevens hopes the mistake was not originally the author’s, but I think it extremely probable that he pronounced the word as a word of four syllables.—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Shakespeare ... might have written—“Arachnea”; great liberties being taken in spelling proper names ... by ancient English writers. Thus we have both “Alcmene” and “Alcumene,” “Alcimena” and “Alcumena.”—INGLEBY (Sh. Hermeneutics, 1875, pp. 65-66): The point [of how Sh. came to write “Ariachne”] is of no moment. What is of moment for us to see is that by Ariachne Shakespeare meant the spider into which Arachne was transformed, and which in Greek bears the same name; and that the “woof” he meant was finer than was ever produced by human hand, viz., the woof of the spider’s web—those delicate transverse filaments which cross the main radial threads or “warps,” and which are perhaps the nearest material approach to mathematical lines! Thus has Shakespeare in one beautiful allusion wrapped up in two or three little words the whole story of Arachne’s metamorphosis, the physical fact of the fineness of the woof-"]},"207":{"play":"Instance, O instance, strong as Pluto’s gates,","notes":[]},"208":{"play":"Cressid is mine, tied with the bonds of heaven;","notes":[]},"209":{"play":"Instance, O instance, strong as heaven itself,","notes":[]},"210":{"play":"The bonds of heaven are slipped, dissolved, and","notes":[]},"211":{"play":"loosed,","notes":[]},"212":{"play":"And with another knot, five-finger-tied,","notes":["fine finger tied] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): A knot tied by giving her hand to Diomede."]},"213":{"play":"The fractions of her faith, orts of her love,","notes":[]},"214":{"play":"The fragments, scraps, the bits and greasy relics","notes":[]},"215":{"play":"Of her o’er-eaten faith are given to Diomed.","notes":["ore-eaten faith] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Vows which she has already swallowed “once over.” We still say of a faithless man, that he has “eaten his words.”—MALONE (Second Appendix, 1783, pp. 45–46): I believe our author had a less delicate idea in his mind. “Her o’er-eaten faith” means, I think, her troth plighted to Troilus, of which she was surfeited, and, like one who has over-eaten himself, had thrown off. All the preceding words, the “fragments, scraps,” &c. show that this was Shakspere’s meaning.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Possibly “which she has mouthed over and over again in her fulsome protestations of loyalty to Troilus.”—[The banquet of Cressida’s faith has been eaten over (as a dog or a hog first eats over what is set before him to get the best), and now only the filthy scraps are left for Diomedes.—B.]"]},"216":{"play":"ULYSSES: May worthy Troilus be half attached","notes":[]},"217":{"play":"With that which here his passion doth express?","notes":[]},"218":{"play":"TROILUS: Ay, Greek, and that shall be divulgèd well","notes":["Troylus] The one apparent exception to the rule that “Troilus” is a dissyllable in Sh. Hence the addition of “but” before “half,” recommended by WALKER (Sh.'s Versification, 1854, p. 165) and followed by DYCE (ed. 1865) and others, in order to avoid the exception. 186-87. May worthy Troylus, etc.] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Can Troilus really feel on this occasion half of what he utters? A question suitable to the calm Ulysses.—[For “attached with,” meaning “possessed by, overcome,” compare Tempest, III.iii.4-5: “I cannot blame thee, Who am myself attach’d with weariness.”] 188-93. and that ... hate I her Diomed] The early editors, from Rowe through Warburton, misconstrued these clauses. They put a strong stop after “divulged well,” and treated the rest, from “In Characters” through “Diomed,” as a continuous statement. Necessarily the clause “never did ... soul” had to be treated as a parenthetical interjection. And this in spite of the fact that the pointing of both Q and F indicates clearly the constructions."]},"219":{"play":"In characters as red as Mars his heart","notes":[]},"220":{"play":"Inflamed with Venus. Never did young man fancy","notes":[]},"221":{"play":"With so eternal and so fixed a soul.","notes":[]},"222":{"play":"Hark, Greek: as much as I do Cressid love,","notes":[]},"223":{"play":"So much by weight hate I her Diomed.","notes":[]},"224":{"play":"That sleeve is mine that he’ll bear on his helm.","notes":[]},"225":{"play":"Were it a casque composed by Vulcan’s skill,","notes":[]},"226":{"play":"My sword should bite it. Not the dreadful spout","notes":["[spout] N.E.D. (waterspout, 3b) gives “sudden and violent fall of rain; a cloudburst” as an established meaning, but lists no instance before 1779. But Sh. understood it in that sense in Lear, and almost certainly in the present instance. It is possible that Psalm xlii, 7 influenced the meaning. The Vulgate reads: “Abyssus abyssum advocat, ad vocem cataractarum tuarum.” This is translated in the Geneva Bible (1579): “One deepe calleth another deepe by the noyse of thy water spoutes.” STEEVENS (ed. 1793) quotes from John Smith’s Sea Grammar, 1627: “A spout is, as it were a small river falling entirely"]},"227":{"play":"Which shipmen do the hurricano call,","notes":["Hurricane] See Lear, III.ii.2-3: \"You cataracts and hurricanoes, spout Till you have drench’d our steeples.\" Also Drayton, xiœon-calf, lines 667-68 (ed. Hebel, 1932, III, 183): \"And downe the shower impetuously doth fall, Like that which men the Hurricano call.\" N.E.D. notes that the use of \"hurricano\" for \"water-spout\" is peculiar to Sh. and Drayton."]},"228":{"play":"Constringed in mass by the almighty sun,","notes":[]},"229":{"play":"Shall dizzy with more clamor Neptune’s ear","notes":[]},"230":{"play":"In his descent than shall my prompted sword","notes":["prompted [word] N.E.D.: In sense ‘to make prompt or ready to do something’.—B."]},"231":{"play":"Falling on Diomed.","notes":[]},"232":{"play":"THERSITES, aside  He’ll tickle it for his concupy.","notes":["Heele ... concupie] MINTO (Characteristics of English Poets, 1891, p. 300): [This speech is] one of the best examples of Shakespeare's extraordinary swiftness in changing his point of view. ... The comment of the impish mocker upon the passionate apostrophe of the indignant betrayed lover is incomparably fine: it takes us by surprise, and the more we dwell upon it, the more exquisite its edge seems to be. tickle it] This is usually taken as an instance of the indefinite \"it\" combined with a verb to express an action, as in the phrase \"fight it out.\" Now mostly in slang, as \"beat it.\" In that case \"He\" must be Diomed. But a few editors take \"He\" to be Troilus, DELIUS (ed. 1856) conjecturing \"him\""]},"233":{"play":"TROILUS: O Cressid! O false Cressid! False, false, false!","notes":[]},"234":{"play":"Let all untruths stand by thy stainèd name,","notes":[]},"235":{"play":"And they’ll seem glorious.","notes":[]},"236":{"play":"ULYSSES: O, contain yourself.","notes":[]},"237":{"play":"Your passion draws ears hither.","notes":[]},"238":{"play":"[Enter Aeneas.]","notes":[]},"239":{"play":"AENEAS, to Troilus","notes":[]},"240":{"play":"I have been seeking you this hour, my lord.","notes":[]},"241":{"play":"Hector, by this, is arming him in Troy.","notes":[]},"242":{"play":"Ajax, your guard, stays to conduct you home.","notes":[]},"243":{"play":"TROILUS: Have with you, prince.—My courteous lord, adieu.—","notes":[]},"244":{"play":"Farewell, revolted fair!—And, Diomed,","notes":[]},"245":{"play":"Stand fast, and wear a castle on thy head!","notes":["weare a Castle] STEEVENS (Var. ’73): Defend thy head with armour of more than common proof.—STEEVENS (Var. ’78) defines “castle” as “a close helmet,” and this definition NARES (Glossary, 1822) repeats, as does N.E.D., adding “but perhaps only a figurative use.” A similar use occurs in Titus Andronicus, iii.i.168-70: “Which of your hands hath not defended Rome, And rear’d aloft the bloody battle-axe, Writing destruction on the enemy’s castle?” And in Holinshed’s Chronicle (1587), II, 815: “Then ... entred sir Thomas Kneuet in a castell of cole blacke, and ouer the castell was written, The dolorous castell.”"]},"246":{"play":"ULYSSES: I’ll bring you to the gates.","notes":[]},"247":{"play":"TROILUS: Accept distracted thanks.","notes":[]},"248":{"play":"[Troilus, Aeneas, and Ulysses exit.]","notes":[]},"249":{"play":"THERSITES: Would I could meet that rogue Diomed! I","notes":[]},"250":{"play":"would croak like a raven; I would bode, I would","notes":[]},"251":{"play":"bode. Patroclus will give me anything for the intelligence","notes":[]},"252":{"play":"of this whore. The parrot will not do more","notes":[]},"253":{"play":"for an almond than he for a commodious drab.","notes":[]},"254":{"play":"Lechery, lechery, still wars and lechery! Nothing","notes":[]},"255":{"play":"else holds fashion. A burning devil take them!","notes":[]},"256":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 3":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Hector, armed, and Andromache.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"ANDROMACHE: When was my lord so much ungently tempered","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"To stop his ears against admonishment?","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"Unarm, unarm, and do not fight today.","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"HECTOR: You train me to offend you. Get you in.","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"By all the everlasting gods, I’ll go!","notes":["By ... goe] SNIDER (System of Sh.'s Dramas, 1877, II, 221-22): Also, there is a change in Hector; the most noble, generous, and humane of all the chieftains ... perishes, though there is an attempt to justify his fate through his disregard of the entreaties of parents, sister, and wife, and of the omens of Heaven. But the deeper ethical retribution was prepared long before in the Trojan council, when he surrendered conviction mainly to desire for personal glory. ... ·But the parting scene at Priam's palace is clearly the motive intended here, and thus produces a new discrepancy."]},"7":{"play":"ANDROMACHE: My dreams will sure prove ominous to the day.","notes":["to the day] MALONE (ed. 1793), noting that all editions from Pope through Var. ’85 read “to-day,” approves the restoration of the article and glosses: “[My dreams] forbode ill to it, and shew that it will be a fatal day to Troy.”—STEEVENS (ibid.) inquires: “Do we gain any thing more than rough versification by restoring the article—‘the?’ The meaning of Andromache (without it) is—‘My dreams will to-day be fatally verified.’”"]},"8":{"play":"HECTOR: No more, I say.","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"[Enter Cassandra.]","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"CASSANDRA: Where is my brother Hector?","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"ANDROMACHE: Here, sister, armed and bloody in intent.","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"Consort with me in loud and dear petition;","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"Pursue we him on knees. For I have dreamt","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"Of bloody turbulence, and this whole night","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"Hath nothing been but shapes and forms of slaughter.","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"CASSANDRA: O, ’tis true!","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"HECTOR, calling out  Ho! Bid my trumpet sound!","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"CASSANDRA: No notes of sally, for the heavens, sweet brother!","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"HECTOR: Begone, I say. The gods have heard me swear.","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"CASSANDRA: The gods are deaf to hot and peevish vows.","notes":["peeuiſh] N.E.D. gives, as the first meaning, “silly, senseless, foolish.” This word, of which the derivation is unknown, seems to have been used, in earlier times, with various senses adapted to the feeling of the moment, but always condemnatory. N.E.D. remarks: “The exact sense of the adjective in many of the early quotations is difficult to fix.”"]},"21":{"play":"They are polluted off’rings more abhorred","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"Than spotted livers in the sacrifice.","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"ANDROMACHE, to Hector","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"O, be persuaded! Do not count it holy","notes":["iuft] SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 444): Faithful to a vow. 23-24. as lawfull ... thefts] This difficult, and perhaps insoluble, passage has been subjected to various desperate remedies. TYRWHITT's emendation (see Tevtr'^'t. Notes) still stands, faute de mieux. He comments (Var., '78): \"I.e. to use violent thefts, 'because' we would give much. The word 'count' had crept in from the last line but one.\"—KNIGHT (ed. 1841) objects to \"use thefts\" as being \"clearly not Shakespearian. Perhaps 'count,' or 'give,' might be omitted, supposing that one word had been substituted for another in the manuscript, without the erasure of that first written; but this omission will not give us a meaning. We have ventured to transpose 'count,' and omit 'as:'—'For we would give much, to count violent thefts.' We have now a clear meaning:—it is as lawful, because we desire to give much, to count violent thefts as holy.\"—VERPLANCK (ed. 1847): The reading now first proposed, in this edition, makes no verbal change but of \"as\" into \"so,\" and transposes \"count,\" which is evidently out of place in the original. The whole then means—\"Do not count it holy to inflict injury in the pursuit of right; we might as well so count (i.e. count holy) violent thefts committed to enable us to give liberally.—\"PERIERGUS BIBLIOPHILUS\" (N.Q., 9 Nov., 1850, p. 386) was the first to suggest that \"count\" is an error for \"commit,\" written \"comit.\" \"We must, I think, be convinced that in copying an interlineated MS., the printer misplaced and misprinted that word, and transposed 'as'; if the repetition of it be not also an error.\"—TAYLOR (N.Q., 25 Jan., 1851, p. 63—see"]},"25":{"play":"To hurt by being just. It is as lawful,","notes":["is] were Rowe-Johns., Var. '73. 23-24. as lawfull: For ... thefts] Ff. as lawful For us to count we give what's gain'd by Thefts Rowe-Var. '85. as lawful, For we would give much, to use violent thefts Rann (Tyrwhitt conj.), Mal.-Sing. i, Huds. i, Dyce, Sta., Wh., Cam., Rolfe, Herf., Ard., Tud., Yale, Kit. as lawful, For us to give much count to violent thefts Coll. i (Amyot conj.). as lawful, For we would give much, to count violent thefts Knt. as lawful (For we would give much) to commit violent thefts Sing. ii [based on \"Periergus Bibliophilus\" conj., NQ, 1850 as lawful as (For, etc.)]. as lawful, (line lost) For we would give as much to violent thefts Del. (See Taylor conj.). as lawful, For we would give much, to so count violent thefts Verplanck. unlawful: For we'd give much count so to violent thefts Ktly. as lawful For us to give much laud to violent","count it holy to hurt by being just. as much to theefts, &c.] Textual Notes) glosses his emendation: “The meaning being, it is as unlawful to do hurt by being just, as it would be to give to a robbery, or to rob for a charity. ... The word ‘count,’ in its second occurrence, was inserted by the printer in the wrong line.”—Delius (ed. 1856): If one supposes that “count” has inadvertently been transposed from a previous line, and that “as” belongs not before “violent” but before “much,” then one has the above text [see Textual Notes] and the meaning: “Do not count it holy to hurt by being just (that is, to injure us by holding to your oath in spite of our pleas and going to the field); it is just as lawful (after ‘lawful’ a line must be lost, somewhat of this meaning: as if we should wish to do evil for a good purpose), for we would give as much (as much justice) to violent thefts, and rob in the behalf of charity.”—Singer (ed. 1856): The passage was evidently printed from an interlined copy, and two words jumbled into wrong places, one of them being also misprinted. To “count” violent thefts is sheer nonsense; and we should recollect how easily “comit” is mistaken for “count.” ... “For” stands for “because.”—Hudson (ed. 1854): As to the objection made by Knight, and repeated by Verplanck, that “to use thefts” is clearly not Shakespearian, we confess it has little weight with us, as, in our judgment, it will not hold.—Dyce (ed. 1857) finds the phrase “use adulterous thefts” in Middleton’s Women Beware Women, iv.iii.36 (ed. Bullen, 1885, vi, 356).—Bulloch’s labored emendation (Studies, 1878, pp. 179–80) accepts “use” for “as,” but changes “count” to “counsel” and “thefts” to “shifts.” “For we would counsel give” is parenthetical. “Much” is “in a peculiarly interjectional sense, of which we have only one other instance in Shakespeare,” namely, in II Henry IV, II.iv.124–25: “God’s light, with two points on your shoulder? much!” “It is as lawful ... much,” would mean “it is equally lawful (or unlawful).”—[This at least can be said for most of the emendations, that they amount to much the same thing, and that the meaning of the lines is generally agreed on. It is probable that Andromache’s speech was an afterthought, inserted into the middle of Cassandra’s speech, and was almost illegible. See Appendix, p. 000.—Ed.]"]},"26":{"play":"For we would give much, to use violent thefts","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"And rob in the behalf of charity.","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"CASSANDRA: It is the purpose that makes strong the vow,","notes":["It is the purpose, etc.] Johnson (ed. 1765): The mad Prophetess speaks here with all the coolness and judgment of a skilful casuist. “The essence of a lawful vow, is a lawful purpose, and the vow of which the end is wrong must not be regarded as cogent.”—Malone (ed. 1790): [Cassandra] alludes to a doctrine which Shakspeare has often enforced. “Do not think you are acting virtuously by adhering to an oath, if you have sworn to do amiss.” So, in King John. [III.i.265 ff The passage is too long to quote]."]},"29":{"play":"But vows to every purpose must not hold.","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"Unarm, sweet Hector.","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"HECTOR: Hold you still, I say.","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"Mine honor keeps the weather of my fate.","notes":["keepes the weather of] STEEVENS (ed. 1793), not understanding this idiom, supposed that the text might be wrong, and tentatively offered \"keeps the weather off,\" i.e. averts the storms of fate.—BOSWELL (Var. '21) was the first to interpret correctly. \"To 'keep the weather,' I apprehend, is the same as to 'take the wind,' to have the superiority.\""]},"33":{"play":"Life every man holds dear, but the dear man","notes":["deere] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): “‘Dear,’ on this occasion, seems to mean ‘important, consequential.’ So, in King Lear [IV.iii.51-52]: ‘Some dear cause Will in concealment wrap me up awhile.’—[A meaning frequent in Sh. See SCHMIDT (1874). We have had “deare vowes” in IV.iv.36 of this play.]"]},"34":{"play":"Holds honor far more precious-dear than life.","notes":["deere man] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Valuable man. ... The repetition of the word is in our author's manner.—N.E.D. gives as the original meaning (when applied to persons), \"glorious, noble, honourable, worthy.\" The earliest citation is from about the year 1000, the latest is the present instance. Here the sense that applies best is \"honorable,\" or \"noble\" (in the sense of a man of noble nature). In 1 Henry IV, iv.iv.31, the sense is \"worthy\": \"Corrivals and dear men Of estimation and command.\"—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): It is not impossible, I think, that we should read \"clear,\"=of spotless honour. [Deighton was evidently not aware that Collier had so printed in his 1878 edition.] Compare Macbeth, I.vii.16-18: \"Duncan ... hath been So clear in his great office\"; Merchant of Venice, II.ix.42-43: \"that clear honour Were purchased by the merit of the wearer\"; King Lear, IV.vi.73: \"the clearest gods.\""]},"35":{"play":"[Enter Troilus, armed.]","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"How now, young man? Meanest thou to fight today?","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"ANDROMACHE: Cassandra, call my father to persuade.","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"[Cassandra exits.]","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"HECTOR: No, faith, young Troilus, doff thy harness, youth.","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"I am today i’ th’ vein of chivalry.","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"Let grow thy sinews till their knots be strong,","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"And tempt not yet the brushes of the war.","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"Unarm thee, go, and doubt thou not, brave boy,","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"I’ll stand today for thee and me and Troy.","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"TROILUS: Brother, you have a vice of mercy in you","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"Which better fits a lion than a man.","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"HECTOR: What vice is that? Good Troilus, chide me for it.","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"TROILUS: When many times the captive Grecian falls,","notes":["captive] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): This reading supposes Hector insulting over his “captives,” which is not Troilus’s meaning: who is here speaking of Hector’s actions in the field. Without doubt Shakespeare wrote, “... caitiff Grecians ...”, i.e. dastardly Grecians; a character natural for the speaker to give them, and justified by his account of them. [This reading was suggested to Warburton by Theobald in a letter of 6 March, 1729/30, but Theobald rejected it for his own text.]—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I see no hint of insult in the present reading.—WHITE (ed. 1865) also inclines to “caitiff.” “For, was Hector in the habit of slaughtering captives? and besides, does not the next line show that they were slain in furious battle?”—[“Captive” means here, as SCHMIDT says, vanquished, subdued. Sh. occasionally uses it in antithesis to “victorious,” as in Lucrece, line 730: “A captive victor that hath lost his gain.”]","Grecian falls] ROLFE (ed. 1884): The majority of the editors follow Rowe in reading “Grecians fall”; but the old text may be what Sh. wrote, the antecedent of “them” being implied in “many times.”"]},"49":{"play":"Even in the fan and wind of your fair sword,","notes":["fanne ... Sword] SEYMOUR (Remarks, 1805, I, 444) notes the resemblance to Hamlet, II.ii.467: “But with the whiff and wind of his fell sword.” faire] TANNENBAUM (Sh. Assoc. Bull., vii, 1932, 81): “Fierce” and “fell” do not fit Hector’s character; “fear’d” is not likely to have been mistaken for “fair.” I would, therefore, suggest “sure,” meaning “strong,” “steady,” “trusty.” “Sure,” written (as often in Elizabethan manuscripts) “suer;” with the secretary long s, could easily be misread “fair,” the s being mistaken for f, the u for open a, and the e for i."]},"50":{"play":"You bid them rise and live.","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"HECTOR: O, ’tis fair play.","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"TROILUS: Fool’s play, by heaven. Hector.","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"HECTOR: How now? How now?","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"TROILUS: For th’ love of all the gods,","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"Let’s leave the hermit Pity with our mother,","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"And when we have our armors buckled on,","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"The venomed Vengeance ride upon our swords,","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"Spur them to ruthful work, rein them from ruth.","notes":["ruthfull ... ruth] SINGER (ed. 1826): \"Ruthful\" is rueful, woeful; and \"ruth\" is mercy. The words are opposed to each other.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): It would be a pity to alter this to \"deathful,\" Walker's conjecture, or \"ruthless,\" Hudson's. It is quite in Shakespeare's way to use in one and the same line a word that has two cognate senses, as here of a feeling that is caused in others and one that is felt by the actor."]},"59":{"play":"HECTOR: Fie, savage, fie!","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"TROILUS: Hector, then ’tis wars.","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"HECTOR: Troilus, I would not have you fight today.","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"TROILUS: Who should withhold me?","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"Not fate, obedience, nor the hand of Mars,","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"Beck’ning with fiery truncheon my retire;","notes":["Beckning ... retire] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): In combats between two champions, the arbiter of the proceedings directed their course by a truncheon, or \"warder,\" which was thrown down when the combat was to cease. Compare Richard II, I.iii.118-20: \"Marshal. ... Stay, the king hath thrown his warder down. K. Rich. Let them lay by their helmets and their spears, And both return back to their chairs again.\""]},"65":{"play":"Not Priamus and Hecuba on knees,","notes":[]},"66":{"play":"Their eyes o’er-gallèd with recourse of tears;","notes":["recourse of teares] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. tears that continue to course one another down the face."]},"67":{"play":"Nor you, my brother, with your true sword drawn","notes":[]},"68":{"play":"Opposed to hinder me, should stop my way,","notes":[]},"69":{"play":"But by my ruin.","notes":[]},"70":{"play":"[Enter Priam and Cassandra.]","notes":[]},"71":{"play":"CASSANDRA, indicating Hector","notes":[]},"72":{"play":"Lay hold upon him, Priam; hold him fast.","notes":[]},"73":{"play":"He is thy crutch. Now if thou loose thy stay,","notes":[]},"74":{"play":"Thou on him leaning, and all Troy on thee,","notes":[]},"75":{"play":"Fall all together.","notes":[]},"76":{"play":"PRIAM: Come, Hector, come. Go back.","notes":[]},"77":{"play":"Thy wife hath dreamt, thy mother hath had visions,","notes":[]},"78":{"play":"Cassandra doth foresee, and I myself","notes":[]},"79":{"play":"Am like a prophet suddenly enrapt","notes":[]},"80":{"play":"To tell thee that this day is ominous.","notes":[]},"81":{"play":"Therefore, come back.","notes":[]},"82":{"play":"HECTOR: Aeneas is afield,","notes":[]},"83":{"play":"And I do stand engaged to many Greeks,","notes":[]},"84":{"play":"Even in the faith of valor, to appear","notes":[]},"85":{"play":"This morning to them.","notes":[]},"86":{"play":"PRIAM: Ay, but thou shalt not go.","notes":[]},"87":{"play":"HECTOR: I must not break my faith.","notes":[]},"88":{"play":"You know me dutiful; therefore, dear sir,","notes":[]},"89":{"play":"Let me not shame respect, but give me leave","notes":["shame respect] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I.e. disgrace the respect I owe you, by acting in opposition to your commands."]},"90":{"play":"To take that course by your consent and voice","notes":[]},"91":{"play":"Which you do here forbid me, royal Priam.","notes":[]},"92":{"play":"CASSANDRA: O Priam, yield not to him!","notes":[]},"93":{"play":"ANDROMACHE: Do not, dear father.","notes":[]},"94":{"play":"HECTOR: Andromache, I am offended with you.","notes":[]},"95":{"play":"Upon the love you bear me, get you in.","notes":[]},"96":{"play":"[Andromache exits.]","notes":[]},"97":{"play":"TROILUS: This foolish, dreaming, superstitious girl","notes":[]},"98":{"play":"Makes all these bodements.","notes":[]},"99":{"play":"CASSANDRA: O farewell, dear Hector.","notes":[]},"100":{"play":"Look how thou diest! Look how thy eye turns pale!","notes":[]},"101":{"play":"Look how thy wounds do bleed at many vents!","notes":[]},"102":{"play":"Hark, how Troy roars, how Hecuba cries out,","notes":[]},"103":{"play":"How poor Andromache shrills her dolor forth!","notes":[]},"104":{"play":"Behold, distraction, frenzy, and amazement,","notes":[]},"105":{"play":"Like witless antics, one another meet,","notes":[]},"106":{"play":"And all cry “Hector! Hector’s dead! O, Hector!”","notes":[]},"107":{"play":"TROILUS: Away, away!","notes":[]},"108":{"play":"CASSANDRA: Farewell.—Yet soft! Hector, I take my leave.","notes":[]},"109":{"play":"Thou dost thyself and all our Troy deceive. She exits.","notes":[]},"110":{"play":"HECTOR: You are amazed, my liege, at her exclaim.","notes":[]},"111":{"play":"Go in and cheer the town. We’ll forth and fight,","notes":[]},"112":{"play":"Do deeds worth praise, and tell you them at night.","notes":[]},"113":{"play":"PRIAM: Farewell. The gods with safety stand about thee!","notes":[]},"114":{"play":"Hector and Priam exit at separate doors.","notes":[]},"115":{"play":"[Alarum.]","notes":[]},"116":{"play":"TROILUS: They are at it, hark! Proud Diomed, believe,","notes":[]},"117":{"play":"I come to lose my arm or win my sleeve.","notes":[]},"118":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus, with a paper.]","notes":[]},"119":{"play":"PANDARUS: Do you hear, my lord? Do you hear?","notes":[]},"120":{"play":"TROILUS: What now?","notes":[]},"121":{"play":"PANDARUS: Here’s a letter come from yond poor girl.","notes":[]},"122":{"play":"TROILUS: Let me read.  He reads.","notes":[]},"123":{"play":"PANDARUS: A whoreson phthisic, a whoreson rascally","notes":[]},"124":{"play":"phthisic so troubles me, and the foolish fortune of","notes":["tisicke] SIGISMUND (Sh. Jahrb., XVI, 1881, 73): Pandarus suffers from syphilis, of which he makes special mention in “aching bones.”—[“Tisick” was a common variant of “phthisic.” Properly, it meant then as now pulmonary consumption, but it was loosely applied to various lung or throat disorders, such as a severe cough. SCHMIDT (1875) suggests that Pandarus may be referring to the hectic fever which accompanies consumption. Compare N.E.D. The suggestion of syphilis is stronger in Pandarus’ “epilogue,” scene 10 of this act.—ED.]"]},"125":{"play":"this girl, and what one thing, what another, that I","notes":[]},"126":{"play":"shall leave you one o’ these days. And I have a","notes":[]},"127":{"play":"rheum in mine eyes too, and such an ache in my","notes":[]},"128":{"play":"bones that, unless a man were cursed, I cannot tell","notes":["curft] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I.e. under the influence of a malediction, such as mischievous beings have been supposed to pronounce upon those who had offended them. 132-34. Why ... name] KNIGHT (ed. 1841) notes that these lines are omitted from \"all modern editions.\" But, replying to Steevens (see note above on line 114), he asks why Sh. would not have dismissed Pandarus twice in the same manner. \"Is not the loathing which Troilus feels towards Pandarus more strongly marked by this repetition? We have no doubt about the restoration of the lines.\"—COLLIER (ed. 1842): The two last lines (with a similar introduction by Pandarus) are also found just before the close o‘ .‘le play. They cannot be rightly inserted in both places, and as they seem to come in with at least equal propriety, and with the correction of a misprint, subsequently, we have given them in that place, and omitted them here.—WALKER (Critical Examination, 1860, III, 203–204): This is the proper place for these two speeches; for without them the ... [scene] ends abruptly. ... Besides, after what had passed, is it conceivable that Pandarus's disgrace should have been put off to the end of the play? Pandarus’s epilogue must, therefore, be an interpolation. ... Perhaps the words from \"A goodly medicine\" to \"painted cloathes\" [V.x.39–49] ought to be added to the end of V.iii.—HUDSON (ed. 1881, p. 358) has \"scarce any doubt\" that Walker is right.—THISELTON (Notulæ Criticæ, 1907, 63–71, p. 33): These lines do not appear in the Quarto, and from their similarity to V.x.36–38 it may be inferred that, when or after the Quarto version came eventually to be acted, it was found convenient to end the play at V.x.34, and to dismiss Pandarus here. It should be noticed that between this scene and V.x.35 Pandarus makes no appearance, and probably his reappearance at the latter point was felt to have a jarring effect by reason of its palpable artificiality. As one of the main subjects of the Quarto, to judge by its later title page, was \"the conceited wooing of Pandarus Prince of Licia\" Shakespeare in writing thought it in keeping to bring him in at the end of the"]},"129":{"play":"what to think on ’t.—What says she there?","notes":[]},"130":{"play":"TROILUS: Words, words, mere words, no matter from the heart.","notes":[]},"131":{"play":"Th’ effect doth operate another way.","notes":[]},"132":{"play":"Go, wind, to wind! There turn and change together.","notes":[]},"133":{"play":"He tears up the paper and throws the pieces in the air.","notes":["brother lackie] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): In this [Pope’s “Brothel, Lacky”], and the Repetition of it, towards the Close of the Play, Troilus is made absurdly to call Pandarus—“bawdy-house”; ... but he meant to call him an Attendant on a Bawdy-house, a Messenger of obscene Errands: a Sense which I have retriev’d, only by clapping an Hyphen betwixt the two Words.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): I ... believe the emendation wholly unnecessary. For “brothel,” the folio reads “brother,” erroneously for “broker,” as it stands at the end of the play where the lines are repeated. Of “brother” the following editors made “brothel.” ignomìie] N.E.D. shows a range of use of this shortened form of “ignominy” extending from 1534 to 1805.—[SISTER MIRIAM JOSEPH (Sh.’s Use of the Arts of Language, 1947, p. 52): Syncope ... the removal of a letter or syllable from the middle of a word.—B.] v.iv.4. that same] FRANZ (Sh.-Gram., 1939, §317) notes how frequently the phrase is used to express scorn or contempt: “this same fat rogue ... that same knave.”"]},"134":{"play":"My love with words and errors still she feeds,","notes":[]},"135":{"play":"But edifies another with her deeds.","notes":[]},"136":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 4":{"1":{"play":"[Alarum. Excursions. Enter Thersites.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"THERSITES: Now they are clapper-clawing one another.","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"I’ll go look on. That dissembling abominable varlet,","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"Diomed, has got that same scurvy doting foolish","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"young knave’s sleeve of Troy there in his helm.","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"I would fain see them meet, that that same young","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"Trojan ass that loves the whore there might send","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"that Greekish whoremasterly villain with the sleeve","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"back to the dissembling luxurious drab, of a sleeveless","notes":["sleueeleffe] Useless, futile. Very common from c. 1580 to c. 1700 in the expression \"a sleeveless errand,\" and persisting to the present in dialect. See N.E.D. and Wright.","Margarelou] He appears in Caxton and in Lydgate. But Caxton calls him “Margareton,” and Lydgate “Margariton.” Sh.’s spelling has not been found elsewhere."]},"10":{"play":"errand. O’ th’ t’other side, the policy of those","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"crafty swearing rascals—that stale old mouse-eaten","notes":["fwearing] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): But in what Sense are Nestor and Ulysses accus'd of being \"swearing\" Rascals? ... I am positive, I have restor'd the true Reading. They had collogued with Ajax, and trim'd him up with insincere Praises, only in Order to have stir'd Achilles's Emulation. In this, they were true Sneerers; betraying the first, to gain their Ends on the latter by that Artifice.—DELIUS (ed. 1856) explains \"swearing\" as meaning not cursing, but bolstering their protestations with oaths.—HALLIWELL (ed. 1864): If any alteration be required, it might be \"steering,\" trimming between two points of management, the choler of Achilles and the pride and excitable temper of Ajax.—The COWDEN CLARKES (ed. 1868) take \"crafty\" as an adjective used adverbially. \"Crafty swearing rascals\" are rascals \"that will pledge themselves to anything for their own crafty purposes.\"—Accepting this interpretation, DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) prints \"crafty-swearing.\""]},"12":{"play":"dry cheese, Nestor, and that same dog-fox,","notes":["beame] Lance; a figurative application of the common meaning, i.e. a long piece of timber, such as a weaver’s beam (N.E.D.)."]},"13":{"play":"Ulysses—is proved not worth a blackberry. They","notes":["pashed] See note on II.iii.205."]},"14":{"play":"set me up, in policy, that mongrel cur, Ajax, against","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"that dog of as bad a kind, Achilles. And now is the","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"cur Ajax prouder than the cur Achilles, and will","notes":["Sagittary] Caxton, Recuyell, Bk. III, Chap. ix (ed. Sommer, II, 567; text from 1597 ed., p 489): From the raigne of Eliane, that is beyond the realme of Amazon, came an auncient king right wise and discreete, named Epistro pus, and brought a thousand knightes, and a marueillous beast that was called Sagit tary, that behinde the middest was an horse, and before a man, this beast was harie, like an horse, and had his eyes red as a coale, and shot right well with a bowe: and this beast made the Greekes sore afraid, and slewe many of them with his bowe.—[And see Appendix, p. 435. Lydgate refers to the monster only as an “archer.”]"]},"17":{"play":"not arm today, whereupon the Grecians begin to","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"proclaim barbarism, and policy grows into an ill","notes":["barbarisme] DELIUS (ed. 1856) suggests that a double antithesis is intended: between “barbarism” and “policy,” and between “barbarism” and “Grecians.” policie] HUDSON (ed. 1881): “Policy” here means “polity,” one of its old senses; that is, a frame or state of civil order, as opposed to a barbarous state. opinion] See note on i.iii.149."]},"19":{"play":"opinion.","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"[Enter Diomedes, and Troilus pursuing him.]","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"Soft! Here comes sleeve and t’ other.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"Thersites moves aside.","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"TROILUS, to Diomedes","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"Fly not, for shouldst thou take the river Styx","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"I would swim after.","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Thou dost miscall retire.","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"I do not fly, but advantageous care","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"Withdrew me from the odds of multitude.","notes":["scaled] MALONE (ed. 1790): \"Scaled\" means here, dispersed, put to flight. ... This is proved decisively by the original reading of the quarto, \"scaling,\" which was either changed by the poet himself to \"scaled\" (with the same sense) or by the editor of the folio. If the latter was the case, it is probable that not being sufficiently acquainted with our author's manner, who frequently uses the active for the passive participle, he supposed that the epithet was merely descriptive of some quality in the thing described.—[For evidence of the meaning assigned Malone refers to notes in his edition: Vol. II, p. 72, note 4 (Measure for Measure), and Vol. VII, p. 148, note 6 (Coriolanus). But the curious will find all his learning, and much more, gathered in the Furness variorum note on Coriolanus, I.i.94 (Menenius' famous \"To scale't a little more\"). There is no doubt that \"to scale\" meant to spread, dislodge, scatter, and it is curious that N.E.D. omits these meanings, although they occur in Holinshed and other examples of non-dialect literature. Most editors take \"scaled\" in the present instance to be a descriptive epithet.—ED.] fculls] STEEVENS (Var. '73): \"Sculls\" are great numbers of fishes swimming together. The modern editors not being acquainted with the term, changed it into \"shoals.\"—RITSON (Remarks, 1783, p. 165): \"Sculls\" and \"shoals\" have not only one and the same meaning, but are, actually, or at least originally, one and the same word. A \"scull of herrings\" (and it is to these fish that the speaker alludes), so termed on the coast of Norfolk and Suffolk, is elsewhere called a \"shoal.\"","forcelesffe care] TATLOCK (ed. 1912) suggests that “‘forceless’ may have the sense of ‘reckless’ (‘No force!’ meant ‘No matter!’ ‘Never mind!’); ‘reckless care’ amounting to ‘recklessness.’”"]},"29":{"play":"Have at thee!   They fight.","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"THERSITES: Hold thy whore, Grecian! Now for thy","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"whore, Trojan! Now the sleeve, now the sleeve!","notes":["swath] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): \"Swath\" is the quantity of grass cut down by a single stroke of the mower's scythe."]},"32":{"play":"Diomedes and Troilus exit fighting.","notes":["takes] Destroys, according to SCHMIDT (1875), citing Coriolanus, II.ii. 105-06: \"his sword, death's stamp, Where it did mark, it took.\"—STAUNTON (ed. 1860) proposes \"cleaves and takes,\" thereby missing the point supported by the following lines, that Hector is so much the master of the battle that he kills at will, can pick and choose.—[But the COWDEN CLARKES (ed. 1868) interpret \"leaves\" as meaning \"leaves them dead.\"—ED.—In perfect rhythm, the"]},"33":{"play":"[Enter Hector.]","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"HECTOR: What art thou, Greek? Art thou for Hector’s match?","notes":["Art thou, etc.] REED (Var. ’85): It appears from [Sir William] Segar on"]},"35":{"play":"Art thou of blood and honor?","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"THERSITES: No, no, I am a rascal, a scurvy railing","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"knave, a very filthy rogue.","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"HECTOR: I do believe thee. Live.  He exits.","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"THERSITES: God-a-mercy, that thou wilt believe me!","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"But a plague break thy neck for frighting me!","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"What’s become of the wenching rogues? I think","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"they have swallowed one another. I would laugh at","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"that miracle—yet, in a sort, lechery eats itself. I’ll","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"seek them.","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]},"54":{"notes":["we draw together] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): This remark seems to be made by Nestor in consequence of the return of Ajax to the field, he having lately refused to co-operate or “draw together” with the Greeks, though at present he is roused from his sullen fit by the loss of a friend."]},"57":{"notes":["boy-queller] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I.e. murderer of a boy. So, in II Henry IV [II.i.50-51]: \"... a man-queller, and a woman-queller.\""]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 5":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Diomedes and Servingman.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Go, go, my servant, take thou Troilus’ horse;","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"Present the fair steed to my Lady Cressid.","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"Fellow, commend my service to her beauty.","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"Tell her I have chastised the amorous Trojan","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"And am her knight by proof.","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"MAN: I go, my lord.    He exits.","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"[Enter Agamemnon.]","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Renew, renew! The fierce Polydamas","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"Hath beat down Menon; bastard Margareton","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"Hath Doreus prisoner,","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"And stands colossus-wise, waving his beam","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"Upon the pashèd corses of the kings","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"Epistrophus and Cedius. Polyxenes is slain,","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"Amphimachus and Thoas deadly hurt,","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"Patroclus ta’en or slain, and Palamedes","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"Sore hurt and bruised. The dreadful Sagittary","notes":["cogging] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): This epithe[t] has no particular propriety in this place, but the authour had heard of Grœcia Mendax.—STEEVENS (Var. '73): Surely the epithet had propriety in respect of Diomed at least, who had defrauded him of his mistress. Troilus bestows it on both, unius ob culpam. 22-23. Now ... thou wilt] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 6 March, 1729/30): I cannot understand what our Poet means here: Achilles is upon the point of attacking Hector; Hector bids him take breath; Achilles will not accept of the courtesy; yet pretends to be restive, and leaves Hector with a threat that he will be up with him anon.—[The poet means that a fight takes place between lines 22 and 23. Why the necessary stage direction has dropped out of editions since RANN (ed. 1789) is something of a mystery.]"]},"18":{"play":"Appals our numbers. Haste we, Diomed,","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"To reinforcement, or we perish all.","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"[Enter Nestor, with Soldiers bearing the body of","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"Patroclus.]","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"NESTOR: Go, bear Patroclus’ body to Achilles,","notes":["carry him] Steevens (ed. 1793): Prevail over him.—Schmidt (1874): Conquer him.—See Coriolanus, iv.vii.27: “Think you he’ll carry Rome?” “Carry it” (or “carry it away”) means to prevail, have the victory, as above, ii.iii.3 (“Shall the Elephant Ajax carry it thus?”) and ii.iii.221 (“Shall pride carry it?”)."]},"23":{"play":"And bid the snail-paced Ajax arm for shame.","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"Soldiers exit with Patroclus’s body.","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"There is a thousand Hectors in the field.","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"Now here he fights on Galathe his horse,","notes":["My reft ... befriends thee now] H. ISAAC (Sh. Jbch., xix, 1884, 253) cites Sonnet 120: “That you were once unkind befriends me now.”"]},"27":{"play":"And here lacks work; anon he’s there afoot","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"And there they fly or die, like scalèd schools","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"Before the belching whale; then is he yonder,","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"And there the strawy Greeks, ripe for his edge,","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"Fall down before him like a mower’s swath.","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"Here, there, and everywhere he leaves and takes,","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"Dexterity so obeying appetite","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"That what he will he does, and does so much","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"That proof is called impossibility.","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"[Enter Ulysses.]","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"ULYSSES: O, courage, courage, princes! Great Achilles","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"Is arming, weeping, cursing, vowing vengeance.","notes":["Enter one in Armour] The episode is more fully and circumstantially treated by Lydgate than by Caxton. See Appendix, pp. 425, 440-41."]},"39":{"play":"Patroclus’ wounds have roused his drowsy blood,","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"Together with his mangled Myrmidons,","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"That noseless, handless, hacked and chipped, come","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"to him,","notes":["frush] N.E.D.: To strike violently so as to crush, bruise, or smash. (OF fruissier, froissier; mod. F. froisser.)—See Heywood’s Troia Britannica (1609, xi, lxv): “With fury each invades His opposite, their mutuall Armors frush"]},"43":{"play":"Crying on Hector. Ajax hath lost a friend","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"And foams at mouth, and he is armed and at it,","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"Roaring for Troilus, who hath done today","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"Mad and fantastic execution,","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"Engaging and redeeming of himself","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"With such a careless force and forceless care","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"As if that luck, in very spite of cunning,","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"Bade him win all.","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"[Enter Ajax.]","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"AJAX: Troilus, thou coward Troilus!     He exits.","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Ay, there, there!  He exits.","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"NESTOR: So, so, we draw together.","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"[Enter Achilles.]","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"ACHILLES: Where is this Hector?—","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"Come, come, thou boy-queller, show thy face!","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"Know what it is to meet Achilles angry.","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"Hector! Where’s Hector? I will none but Hector.","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"He exits, with the others.","notes":[]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 6":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Ajax.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"AJAX: Troilus, thou coward Troilus, show thy head!","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"[Enter Diomedes.]","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Troilus, I say! Where’s Troilus?","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"AJAX: What wouldst thou?","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"DIOMEDES: I would correct him.","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"AJAX: Were I the General, thou shouldst have my office","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"Ere that correction.—Troilus, I say! What, Troilus!","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"[Enter Troilus.]","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"TROILUS: O traitor Diomed! Turn thy false face, thou traitor,","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"And pay the life thou owest me for my horse!","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"DIOMEDES: Ha! Art thou there?","notes":["double hen’d] Why “double-henned”? It would seem to be the other way round. SCHMIDT (1874) suggests “perhaps=sparrow with a double-hen, i.e. with a female married to two cocks, and hence false to both.” DYCE-LITTLEDALE (Sh. Glossary, 1902) also suggests that meaning, “or else double-wived, Helen and Oenone?”—[Qy: should we read “double hened sparrows,” i.e. sparrows that are doubled to one hen? But I have not much faith in it.]","Strike fellowes] Sh. here combines the accounts of Lydgate and Caxton of the deaths of Hector and Troilus. According to both sources, Hector was occupied with disarming the captured knight, and had slung his shield behind his back, when Achilles found him thus unprepared and killed him with a spear thrust. It was Troilus who was surrounded by Myrmidons and so killed; it was likewise his body that Achilles dragged with his horse. See Appendix, pp. 440–41, 445–47.—STEEVENS (Var. ’73) notes that Heywood, in The Rape of"]},"13":{"play":"AJAX: I’ll fight with him alone. Stand, Diomed.","notes":["[sparrow] Batman vppon Bartholome (1582, Bk. XII, Ch. xxxii): [The"]},"14":{"play":"DIOMEDES: He is my prize. I will not look upon.","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"TROILUS: Come, both you cogging Greeks. Have at you both!","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"[Enter Hector.]","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"Troilus exits, fighting Diomedes and Ajax.","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"HECTOR: Yea, Troilus? O, well fought, my youngest brother!","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"[Enter Achilles.]","notes":["dragon wing of night] ANDERS (Sh.'s Books, 1904, p. 101) cites Midsummer-Night's Dream, iii.ii.379: \"For night's swift dragons cut the clouds full fast\"; and Cymbeline, ii.ii.48: \"Swift, swift, you dragons of the night.\""]},"20":{"play":"ACHILLES: Now do I see thee. Ha! Have at thee, Hector!","notes":["a Bastard] It is curious that only Capell and Kittredge among our list of editors follow the better reading of Q, which omits \"a.\" 22–23. one Beare, etc.] Anders (Sh.'s Books, 1904, p. 284; following Theobald, ed. 1733) cites Juvenal, Satire XV: \"Saevís inter se convenit ursis\" and","stickler-like ... feperates] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): [Pope's \"separate\" is wrong; we must restore \"separates,\"] and then the Sense will be this: \"Night, Stickler-like, puts an End to the Engagement, and separates the Armies.\" I am apt to think, Mr. Pope did not know the Word, or the Office of the Person intended by it. ... In this very Play, Diomede and Æneas are Sticklers to Ajax and Hector in their Combat: Seconds, to see fair Play, and arbitrate the Duel.—[\"Stickler\" is from the verb \"stickle,\" identical with \"stightle,\" to set in order; not, as most commentators have said, so called because the stickler carried a stick or wand.]"]},"21":{"play":"[They fight.]","notes":["frankly] COLLIER (ed. 1858) maintained that the word means hoggishly (from \"frank,\" a fattening-pen, sty); but it means only \"freely, abundantly.\" 21-24. My halfe ... traile] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): These four despicable verses ... could scarce have fallen from the pen of our author, in his most unlucky moments of composition. [He suggests that Sh. may have hastily altered T. and C. of Dekker and Chettle, the present passage being a relic of the older play.]"]},"22":{"play":"HECTOR: Pause if thou wilt.","notes":["bed (Q bait, F2 bitt)] DELIUS (ed. 1872) points out that the noun \"bait\" is used elsewhere in Sh. only in the sense of food to allure fish, whereas \"bit\" is used more than once as equivalent generally to food. Thus in Love's Labor's Lost, I.i.26-27: \"dainty bits Make rich the ribs\"; Coriolanus, IV.v.33: \"batten on cold bits\"; and Timon, II.ii.166: \"How many prodigal bits have slaves and peasants This night englutted!\" v.x. 4. Enter Troylus] To the present editor Q's treatment of this entrance seems preferable. See Appendix, pp. 342-43."]},"23":{"play":"ACHILLES: I do disdain thy courtesy, proud Trojan.","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"Be happy that my arms are out of use.","notes":["execute your arme|STEEVENS (Var. '78): Thus all the copies [i.e. \"arms\"];"]},"25":{"play":"My rest and negligence befriends thee now,","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"But thou anon shalt hear of me again;","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"Till when, go seek thy fortune.  He exits.","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"HECTOR: Fare thee well.","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"I would have been much more a fresher man","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"Had I expected thee.","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"[Enter Troilus.]","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"How now, my brother?","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"TROILUS: Ajax hath ta’en Aeneas. Shall it be?","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"No, by the flame of yonder glorious heaven,","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"He shall not carry him. I’ll be ta’en too","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"Or bring him off. Fate, hear me what I say!","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"I reck not though I end my life today.","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"[Enter one in Greek armor.]","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"HECTOR: Stand, stand, thou Greek! Thou art a goodly mark.","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"No? Wilt thou not? I like thy armor well.","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"I’ll frush it and unlock the rivets all,","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"But I’ll be master of it.  The Greek exits.","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"Wilt thou not, beast, abide?","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"Why then, fly on. I’ll hunt thee for thy hide.","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 7":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Achilles, with Myrmidons.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"ACHILLES: Come here about me, you my Myrmidons.","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"Mark what I say. Attend me where I wheel.","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"Strike not a stroke, but keep yourselves in breath,","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"And, when I have the bloody Hector found,","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"Empale him with your weapons round about.","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"In fellest manner execute your arms.","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"Follow me, sirs, and my proceedings eye.","notes":["smile at Troy] THEOBALD (Nichols, ii, 276): ‘Smile at Troy!’ A miserable image: the image is in the thought, not in the expression: ‘to smile at’ in our author's manner signifies to insult over, to treat with contempt, or to exult in the fate of. So in Hamlet: “That from her working all his visage wann’d, Tears in his eyes, distraction in his aspect, A broken voice, and his whole function suiting With forms to his conceit? And all for nothing!” Again in Macb.: “Who could refrain, That had a heart to love, and in that heart Courage, to make his love known?” —and so also in many passages. HANMER: To smile upon, may be good sense in this place; but I think “at Troy” should be “at Troy’s,” i.e., at the destruction of Troy. UPTON (Obs., p. 283): The true reading is “smite at Troy”: it is a metaphor taken from archery. In this sense we have it very often in our author; as, “O, let me gall him! for by him I’ll smite,” &c. In the Psalms, cxxxii, 18, “Upon himself shall his crown flourish,” but in the margin, “There shall the horn of David bud; I have ordained a lamp for mine anointed. His enemies will I clothe with shame: but upon himself shall his crown flourish.” Mr Upton's whole note is founded on a mistaken reading. In the true reading there is nothing harsh or obscure. MALONE: Shakespeare had in his thoughts the following passage in the Psalms, “He that dwelleth in heaven shall laugh them to scorn: the Lord shall have them in derision.” Ps. ii, 4. “The Lord shall laugh him to scorn; for he hath seen that his day is coming.” Ps. xxxvii, 13 ... In the above cited passage the Heavens are the Ministers of the Gods to execute their vengeance, and they are bid “to frown on”; but the Gods themselves “smile at Troy”; they hold Troy “in derision, for they see it’s day is coming.”—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 319): There can be no doubt but we should read, “smite” at, instead of “smile”:—The following words, “I say at once,” make that unquestionable; to call upon the heavens to “frown,” and on the Gods to “smile” at the self-same moment, would be too absurd, even for that violent agitation of mind, with which Troilus is supposed to be actuated.—WHITE (ed. 1865) would consider “smite” very plausible “did it complete a sentence which as a whole we could receive as Shakesperian. But ‘smite at’ is hardly a phrase that Shakespeare would use to express the action of the gods when sitting upon their thrones.”—DYCE (ed. 1865, reading “smite all”) thinks that “at” is a printer's error for “al” (“all”), and that “smile” is an easy mistake for “smite.”—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) likewise approves Lettsom’s “smite all.” “It seems impossible, even if ‘smile at Troy’ were used derisively, that it should be followed by two lines invoking speedy destruction.” 16-17. dare ... dangers in] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): But dare whatever imminent dangers either gods or men may be preparing for me: “Address,” prepare, make ready."]},"9":{"play":"It is decreed Hector the great must die.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":["fmlie] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): Here Troilus is made to invoke the Gods to “frown” in one line, and to “smile” in the other: And, as if he had not talked nonsense enough, after having made them do and undo, and protract the fate of Troy, in the next line he begs them to be speedy and “brief,” and dispatch them at once. We should read ... “smite.”—UPTON (Critical Ob-"]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 8":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Thersites; then Menelaus fighting Paris.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"THERSITES: The cuckold and the cuckold-maker are at","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"it. Now, bull! Now, dog! Loo, Paris, loo! Now, my","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"double-horned Spartan! Loo, Paris, loo! The bull","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"has the game. Ware horns, ho!","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"Paris and Menelaus exit, fighting.","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"[Enter Bastard.]","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"BASTARD: Turn, slave, and fight.","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"THERSITES: What art thou?","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"BASTARD: A bastard son of Priam’s.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"THERSITES: I am a bastard too. I love bastards. I am","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"bastard begot, bastard instructed, bastard in mind,","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"bastard in valor, in everything illegitimate. One","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"bear will not bite another, and wherefore should","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"one bastard? Take heed: the quarrel’s most ominous","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"to us. If the son of a whore fight for a whore,","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"he tempts judgment. Farewell, bastard.     He exits.","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"BASTARD: The devil take thee, coward!","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 9":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Hector, with the body of the Greek in armor.]","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"HECTOR: Most putrefied core, so fair without,","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"Thy goodly armor thus hath cost thy life.","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"Now is my day’s work done. I’ll take my breath.","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"Rest, sword; thou hast thy fill of blood and death.","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"He begins to disarm.","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"[Enter Achilles and his Myrmidons.]","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"ACHILLES: Look, Hector, how the sun begins to set,","notes":["smile at Troy] THEOBALD (Nichols, ii, 276): ‘Smile at Troy!’ A miserable image: the image is in the thought, not in the expression: ‘to smile at’ in our author's manner signifies to insult over, to treat with contempt, or to exult in the fate of. So in Hamlet: “That from her working all his visage wann’d, Tears in his eyes, distraction in his aspect, A broken voice, and his whole function suiting With forms to his conceit? And all for nothing!” Again in Macb.: “Who could refrain, That had a heart to love, and in that heart Courage, to make his love known?” —and so also in many passages. HANMER: To smile upon, may be good sense in this place; but I think “at Troy” should be “at Troy’s,” i.e., at the destruction of Troy. UPTON (Obs., p. 283): The true reading is “smite at Troy”: it is a metaphor taken from archery. In this sense we have it very often in our author; as, “O, let me gall him! for by him I’ll smite,” &c. In the Psalms, cxxxii, 18, “Upon himself shall his crown flourish,” but in the margin, “There shall the horn of David bud; I have ordained a lamp for mine anointed. His enemies will I clothe with shame: but upon himself shall his crown flourish.” Mr Upton's whole note is founded on a mistaken reading. In the true reading there is nothing harsh or obscure. MALONE: Shakespeare had in his thoughts the following passage in the Psalms, “He that dwelleth in heaven shall laugh them to scorn: the Lord shall have them in derision.” Ps. ii, 4. “The Lord shall laugh him to scorn; for he hath seen that his day is coming.” Ps. xxxvii, 13 ... In the above cited passage the Heavens are the Ministers of the Gods to execute their vengeance, and they are bid “to frown on”; but the Gods themselves “smile at Troy”; they hold Troy “in derision, for they see it’s day is coming.”—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 319): There can be no doubt but we should read, “smite” at, instead of “smile”:—The following words, “I say at once,” make that unquestionable; to call upon the heavens to “frown,” and on the Gods to “smile” at the self-same moment, would be too absurd, even for that violent agitation of mind, with which Troilus is supposed to be actuated.—WHITE (ed. 1865) would consider “smite” very plausible “did it complete a sentence which as a whole we could receive as Shakesperian. But ‘smite at’ is hardly a phrase that Shakespeare would use to express the action of the gods when sitting upon their thrones.”—DYCE (ed. 1865, reading “smite all”) thinks that “at” is a printer's error for “al” (“all”), and that “smile” is an easy mistake for “smite.”—DEIGHTON (ed. 1906) likewise approves Lettsom’s “smite all.” “It seems impossible, even if ‘smile at Troy’ were used derisively, that it should be followed by two lines invoking speedy destruction.” 16-17. dare ... dangers in] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): But dare whatever imminent dangers either gods or men may be preparing for me: “Address,” prepare, make ready."]},"9":{"play":"How ugly night comes breathing at his heels.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"Even with the vail and dark’ning of the sun","notes":["fmlie] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): Here Troilus is made to invoke the Gods to “frown” in one line, and to “smile” in the other: And, as if he had not talked nonsense enough, after having made them do and undo, and protract the fate of Troy, in the next line he begs them to be speedy and “brief,” and dispatch them at once. We should read ... “smite.”—UPTON (Critical Ob-"]},"11":{"play":"To close the day up, Hector’s life is done.","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"HECTOR: I am unarmed. Forgo this vantage, Greek.","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"ACHILLES: Strike, fellows, strike! This is the man I seek.","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"The Myrmidons kill Hector.","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"So, Ilium, fall thou next! Come, Troy, sink down!","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"Here lies thy heart, thy sinews, and thy bone.","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"On, Myrmidons, and cry you all amain","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"“Achilles hath the mighty Hector slain.”","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"[Retreat sounded from both armies.]","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"Hark! A retire upon our Grecian part.","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"A MYRMIDON: The Trojan trumpets sound the like, my lord.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"ACHILLES: The dragon wing of night o’erspreads the Earth","notes":["weis, and Niobes] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): We should certainly read,"]},"23":{"play":"And, stickler-like, the armies separates.","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"My half-supped sword, that frankly would have fed,","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"Pleased with this dainty bait, thus goes to bed.","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"He sheathes his sword.","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"Come, tie his body to my horse’s tail;","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"Along the field I will the Trojan trail.","notes":["pight] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I.e. pitched, fixed. The obsolete preterite and participle passive of to \"pitch.\"","pight] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I.e. pitched, fixed. The obsolete preterite and participle passive of to “pitch.”"]},"29":{"play":"[They exit with the bodies.]","notes":[]},"39":{"notes":["ignomy] See note on v.iii.133. 37-38. Hence ... name] WHITE (ed. 1865) considers this and the preceding speech to be in their right places here, but erroneously printed at the end of v.iii. His explanation, if it may be called such, is that “they came there [v.iii], doubtless, by some one of those many inexplicable accidents to which manuscript and ‘standing matter’ (i.e., standing in type) are subject in the printing office.”—COWDEN CLARKE (ed. 1868): [The repetition of this couplet from v.iii is] a circumstance which confirms our belief that the closing scenes and existing end are not Shakespeare’s own. It may be that he concluded the play there. It is possible that the final arrangement which he made may not have been considered to form an effective stage catastrophe, and he may have permitted the brief scenes descriptive of the various engagements on the battle-"]},"52":{"notes":["coward] DELIUS (ed. 1856) takes this to mean Diomed. That is surely wrong. Troilus’ personal grievances have been wiped out of his mind by the death of Hector; he talks of nothing else. “Coward” refers to “murderer” of line 7. 33–34. Strike ... woe] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): This couplet affords a full and natural close to the play; and though I once thought differently, I must now declare my firm belief that Shakspeare designed it should end here, and that what follows is either a subsequent and injudicious restoration from the elder"]},"53":{"notes":["painted cloathes] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): I.e. the painted canvas with which your rooms are hung.—ROLFE (ed. 1884) notes that such painted hangings had mottoes connected with the figures on them, and instances As You Like It, III.ii.358–59: “I answer you right painted cloth, from whence you have studied your questions.”"]},"59":{"notes":["hold-dore trade] PARTRIDGE (Sh.’s Bawdy, 1947, p. 127): Prostitution.—prostitutes lounging at brothel-doors to attract customers.—[B]."]},"60":{"notes":["my will] This has been taken as a promise of a sequent play. HERTZBERG (ed. 1877) is one of the most vigorous proponents of this interpretation. “Pandarus says that within two months he will make his will here; under no circumstances can that mean anything else than here on the stage. He will then come back, healed ... but in any case in a new play. ... But that can only happen in his Trojan and Greek setting, that is, in a play which will provide the continuation and presumably the conclusion of the action, which is here broken off in the middle."]},"62":{"notes":["Goose of Wincheſter] POPE (ed. 1723): The publick stews were anciently under the jurisdiction of the Bishop of Winchester.—MASON (Comments, 1785, p. 319): A strumpet was called a Winchester goose, and a “galled Winchester goose” may mean, either a strumpet that had the venereal disease, or one that felt herself hurt by what Pandarus had said: It is probable that the word was purposefully used to express both these senses.—HERTZBERG (ed. 1877) insists vigorously that the term here refers to a syphilitic ulcer, not to a prostitute. To take the latter sense leads to absurdity. “For the whole distasteful joke turns on the supposition that Pandarus cannot bequeath his illness until he"]},"108":{"notes":["coward] DELIUS (ed. 1856) takes this to mean Diomed. That is surely wrong. Troilus' personal grievances have been wiped out of his mind by the death of Hector; he talks of nothing else. \"Coward\" refers to \"murderer\" of line 7. 33-34. Strike ... woe] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): This couplet affords a full and natural close to the play; and though I once thought differently, I must now declare my firm belief that Shakspeare designed it should end here, and that what follows is either a subsequent and injudicious restoration from the elder"]},"117":{"notes":["traitours] DEIGHTON (ed. 1906): Mr. Craig’s conjecture, “traders,” seems certain. Compare line 49 below, “Good traders in the flesh.”"]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 10":{"1":{"play":"[Sound retreat. Enter Agamemnon, Ajax, Menelaus,","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"Nestor, Diomedes, and the rest, marching to the beat of","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"[drums. Shout within.]]","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: Hark, hark, what shout is this?","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"NESTOR: Peace, drums!  The drums cease.","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"SOLDIERS, within","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"Achilles! Achilles! Hector’s slain! Achilles!","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"DIOMEDES: The bruit is Hector’s slain, and by Achilles.","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"AJAX: If it be so, yet bragless let it be.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"Great Hector was as good a man as he.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"AGAMEMNON: March patiently along. Let one be sent","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"To pray Achilles see us at our tent.","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"If in his death the gods have us befriended,","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"Great Troy is ours, and our sharp wars are ended.","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"[They exit, marching.]","notes":[]}},"ACT 5, SCENE 11":{"1":{"play":"[Enter Aeneas, Paris, Antenor, Deiphobus, and Trojan","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"soldiers.]","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"AENEAS: Stand, ho! Yet are we masters of the field.","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"Never go home; here starve we out the night.","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"[Enter Troilus.]","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"TROILUS: Hector is slain.","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"ALL: Hector! The gods forbid!","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"TROILUS: He’s dead, and at the murderer’s horse’s tail,","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"In beastly sort, dragged through the shameful field.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"Frown on, you heavens; effect your rage with speed.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"Sit, gods, upon your thrones, and smite at Troy!","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"I say at once: let your brief plagues be mercy,","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"And linger not our sure destructions on!","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"AENEAS: My lord, you do discomfort all the host.","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"TROILUS: You understand me not that tell me so.","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"I do not speak of flight, of fear, of death,","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"But dare all imminence that gods and men","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"Address their dangers in. Hector is gone.","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"Who shall tell Priam so, or Hecuba?","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"Let him that will a screech-owl aye be called","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"Go into Troy and say their Hector’s dead.","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"There is a word will Priam turn to stone,","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"Make wells and Niobes of the maids and wives,","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"Cold statues of the youth and, in a word,","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"Scare Troy out of itself. But march away.","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"Hector is dead. There is no more to say.","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"Stay yet. You vile abominable tents,","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"Thus proudly pitched upon our Phrygian plains,","notes":[]},"29":{"play":"Let Titan rise as early as he dare,","notes":[]},"30":{"play":"I’ll through and through you! And, thou great-sized","notes":[]},"31":{"play":"coward,","notes":[]},"32":{"play":"No space of earth shall sunder our two hates.","notes":[]},"33":{"play":"I’ll haunt thee like a wicked conscience still,","notes":[]},"34":{"play":"That moldeth goblins swift as frenzy’s thoughts.","notes":[]},"35":{"play":"Strike a free march to Troy! With comfort go.","notes":[]},"36":{"play":"Hope of revenge shall hide our inward woe.","notes":[]},"37":{"play":"[Enter Pandarus.]","notes":[]},"38":{"play":"PANDARUS: But hear you, hear you!","notes":[]},"39":{"play":"TROILUS: Hence, broker, lackey! Ignomy and shame","notes":[]},"40":{"play":"Pursue thy life, and live aye with thy name!","notes":[]},"41":{"play":"[All but Pandarus exit.]","notes":[]},"42":{"play":"PANDARUS: A goodly medicine for my aching bones! O","notes":[]},"43":{"play":"world, world, world! Thus is the poor agent despised.","notes":[]},"44":{"play":"O traitors and bawds, how earnestly are","notes":[]},"45":{"play":"you set a-work, and how ill requited! Why should","notes":[]},"46":{"play":"our endeavor be so loved and the performance so","notes":[]},"47":{"play":"loathed? What verse for it? What instance for it?","notes":[]},"48":{"play":"Let me see:","notes":[]},"49":{"play":"Full merrily the humble-bee doth sing,","notes":[]},"50":{"play":"Till he hath lost his honey and his sting;","notes":[]},"51":{"play":"And being once subdued in armèd tail,","notes":[]},"52":{"play":"Sweet honey and sweet notes together fail.","notes":[]},"53":{"play":"Good traders in the flesh, set this in your painted","notes":[]},"54":{"play":"cloths:","notes":[]},"55":{"play":"As many as be here of panders’ hall,","notes":[]},"56":{"play":"Your eyes, half out, weep out at Pandar’s fall;","notes":[]},"57":{"play":"Or if you cannot weep, yet give some groans,","notes":[]},"58":{"play":"Though not for me, yet for your aching bones.","notes":[]},"59":{"play":"Brethren and sisters of the hold-door trade,","notes":[]},"60":{"play":"Some two months hence my will shall here be made.","notes":[]},"61":{"play":"It should be now, but that my fear is this:","notes":[]},"62":{"play":"Some gallèd goose of Winchester would hiss.","notes":[]},"63":{"play":"Till then I’ll sweat and seek about for eases,","notes":[]},"64":{"play":"And at that time bequeath you my diseases.","notes":[]},"65":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[]}}}